<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-MARLINS-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKS BEAT MARLINS 5-1
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As defending World Series champions, the Florida
Marlins should be the crown jewel of the major leagues this season.
Having squandered their valuables in trades, however, the Marlins
are baseball's gypsies, scrounging for victories and a new identity
as they search for a new and permanent home in South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   But the Marlins almost stole a game from the Yankees Friday
night. Almost. Andy Pettitte allowed just one unearned run and
pitched a complete game, outdueling rookie Joe Fontenot, 5-1,
before 28,085 at Yankee Stadium. After taking their first
interleague game of the season, the Yankees (42-13) have won five
consecutive games.
</P>
<P>
   The score was tied, 1-1, after the Marlins scored in the top of
the seventh. But Darryl Strawberry blasted a high drive over the
wall in left field in the bottom of the inning, and the Yankees
added another run in the seventh and two in the eighth to beat
Fontenot (0-3) and the Marlins, who sport baseball's worst record
at 17-42.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte (7-5), who has struggled lately, Friday night allowed
five hits and only one walk while striking out four in a
complete-game victory that was aided by the Marlins' batters.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that the likes of Gary Sheffield and Moises Alou have
been replaced by bad players as Florida's front office hacked away
at the team's payroll. Most baseball executives believe that the
Marlins' roster is loaded with talent _ very young talent, rookies
cutting their teeth with every major-league at-bat. But the Marlins
are learning on the job, and there was no greater evidence of that
Friday night than the quality of their at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Struggling for command the first two months of this season,
Pettitte has averaged 16.8 pitches per inning, an usually high
number. Ken Kaiser, Friday night's plate umpire, typically calls a
small but consistent strike zone. Given those factors, the Marlins
might have had a chance to drive up Pettitte's pitch count, forcing
him to work and possibly make mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the young and aggressive Marlins swung freely, to
Pettitte's benefit. He needed just six pitches to get through the
first inning, eight pitches to get out of the second, only 34 for
the first four innings. Of the first 14 Florida hitters, only one _
Craig Counsell, in the third inning _ had an at-bat of more than
three pitches.
</P>
<P>
   But Pettitte, looking for a way out of his maze-like slump,
won't care whom he pitched against, how he got them out or how much
they helped him with their reckless at-bats. He needed a boost of
confidence, which arrived in teal packaging Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte allowed seven runs in two and two-thirds innings in his
previous start, pushing his perpetual self-examination into
overdrive. After throwing in the bullpen and, according to others
in the organization, making minor changes in his delivery, Pettitte
backed off, in a sense. He determined that, rather than trying to
make the perfect pitch, he should just concentrate on throwing the
ball over the plate, forcing the hitters to put the ball in play.
He had walked seven in six innings on May 26 and thrown a whopping
70 pitches in the eight-out start on May 31.
</P>
<P>
   But he changed that Friday night against the Marlins. Pettitte
allowed only three hits and a walk in the first six innings, and in
the two situations when Florida had a runner in scoring position,
Pettitte pitched out of trouble. In his previous outing, the Red
Sox were 5-for-7 with runners in scoring position.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Marlins' inexperience meant that the Yankees knew virtually
nothing about Fontenot, who was 2 years old when Tim Raines broke
into the big leagues in 1979. Fontenot, 21, began the season in
Class AA, but after losing on May 16 to Norwich, the Yankees'
Eastern League affiliate, the right-hander was promoted to the
major leagues and lost his first two starts.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, however, Fontenot changed speeds expertly and kept
the ball down in the strike zone. Kaiser often called strikes and
generated stares from the perplexed Yankee hitters, and Kaiser
looked right back at them as if to say: Hey, what can I tell you,
it was a strike.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had two runners in the first inning, another reached
scoring position in the second, and Chuck Knoblauch singled to
start the third. At any time, it seemed, Fontenot would crumble
under an inevitable flood of runs from the Yankees, who are
averaging more than six a game.
</P>
<P>
   But Fontenot shut out the Yankees in the first five innings,
allowing just two hits and striking out two; he struck out two more
to open the sixth, fooling Scott Brosius so badly that Brosius
twice launched bats into the stands on the third-base side as he
flailed away. (It appeared that no fans were injured.)
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Paul O'Neill rapped a single through the middle with
two outs in the sixth, took second on a wild pitch and scored when
Tino Martinez dropped a broken-bat looper into short right. The
Yankees led, 1-0.
</P>
<P>
   The Marlins tied the game in the top of the seventh. With
runners at first and second and one out, Derrek Lee hit a chopper
back to Pettitte, who turned and fired to second, where shortstop
Luis Sojo and Knoblauch appeared confused as to who should take the
throw. Knoblauch stepped in to get the ball and threw wildly to
first, the ball hopping into the stands. Todd Zeile trotted home
with the first unearned run allowed by the Yankees in 89 innings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
