<HEADLINE>
FORMER L.A. MAYOR SAM YORTY DIES AT AGE 88
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Daily News Staff Writer Eric Moses contributed to this story.) 
By DAVID R. BAKER AND RICK ORLOV  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Sam Yorty, Los Angeles' hard-charging mayor during
the turbulent but prosperous 1960s, died Friday morning at his home
in suburban Studio City. He was 88.
</P>
<P>
   The boisterous politician, who relished his reputation as the
``Maverick Mayor,'' died peacefully from complications of a May 24
stroke, family members said.
</P>
<P>
   City flags were lowered to half-staff in his honor, and the City
Council adjourned in his memory.
</P>
<P>
   Yorty presided over a period of rapid growth in Los Angeles
after his election in 1961 and unabashedly took credit for the
city's rise to international prominence.
</P>
<P>
   But his 12-year tenure in office was marred, perhaps doomed, by
the Watts riots of 1965, which left 34 people dead and more than
1,000 injured. Yorty ran two racially tinged campaigns against Tom
Bradley, winning in 1969 before being ousted in 1973, when voters
elected the city's first African-American mayor.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Yorty was remembered as an exuberant man who, in
spite of his reputation for two-fisted politics and sometimes
insensitive remarks, tried to unite the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the type of person who made every effort to bring this
city together,'' said Celes King III, state chairman of the
Congress of Racial Equality and a longtime friend of Yorty's. ``He
was a great mayor.''
</P>
<P>
   City Council President John Ferraro, who knew Yorty for more
than 50 years, called him a colorful man with a love of politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``He lived life and played politics to the fullest,'' Ferraro
said.
</P>
<P>
   Yorty came to the Mayor's Office after a career that included
stints as a California assemblyman and U.S. representative. At
every turn, he defied expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Born in 1909 in Lincoln, Neb., Yorty's fascination with politics
surfaced early.
</P>
<P>
   In a ninth-grade composition, he wrote that his goal was to
become a politician. His teacher told him to concentrate on
becoming a statesman instead.
</P>
<P>
   Yorty moved to Los Angeles after high school and in 1936 won a
seat in the state Assembly. As a young Democratic lawmaker, he
earned the enmity of conservatives by championing pro-union
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Years later, he enraged his own party by backing Richard Nixon's
1960 presidential bid over John F. Kennedy's. Furious Democratic
leaders refused to help Yorty become mayor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a man of contradictions and great complexity,'' said Ed
Edelman, a former councilman and county supervisor who frequently
sparred with Yorty. ``He couldn't be pegged as a liberal or a
conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   Without his party's support, Yorty won the mayor's seat by
railing against what he called a clique of downtown interests that
ruled Los Angeles. That approach struck a chord among San Fernando
Valley residents, African-Americans and Latinos, all of whom felt
excluded from local government.
</P>
<P>
   Once elected, Yorty began increasing the number of minorities in
city government, said King, whom Yorty appointed to a commission on
race relations in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the person who partially opened the door,'' King added.
``Tom (Bradley), of course, pushed it wide open, but if it hadn't
been for Sam, the beginning wouldn't have happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite those efforts, the riots that ripped through Watts in
1965 became one of the most important events in Yorty's tenure.
</P>
<P>
   Federal and state officials complained that he hadn't cooperated
with their plans to prevent such violent disturbances. Yorty
countered that the federal government had raised the hopes and
expectations of African-Americans without providing opportunities
to fulfill them.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley waged two hard-fought campaigns to unseat Yorty. The
incumbent mayor _ who had ushered minorities into his
administration _ responded by countering that African-Americans
usually vote for candidates of their own race. He also warned
voters about a political bloc of ``black-power (advocates),
left-wing radicals, and if you please, identified Communists.''
</P>
<P>
   Several City Council members said Yorty's memory should not be
clouded by the bitterness of his last campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played hardball politics and did what it took to win,''
said Councilman Richard Alatorre, who worked on Bradley's first
campaign against Yorty. ``Although I didn't agree with his later
politics, early on in his career he was fighting for the
workingman. And he served as mayor at a time that would be hard for
anybody with the riots and anti-war demonstrations going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Richard Riordan praised Yorty for trying to bring people
from the suburbs into the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under Mayor Yorty's service, Los Angeles first became known as
the city of the future,'' Riordan said.
</P>
<P>
   Edelman described Yorty as a fair man and skilled administrator
who always had his city's best interests at heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a very colorful person who felt he had something to say
about everything, and that got him into a lot of trouble,'' Edelman
said. ``But underneath, he cared about this city.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
