<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-TRUCKS-CRASHES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRASHES PAINFUL FOR DRIVERS AT TMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JIM PEDLEY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ John Timber was in tears as he quickly
strode through the garage area at Texas Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   They weren't tears of joy.
</P>
<P>
   Timber trotted up to driver Boris Said and a stream of apologies
flowed with the tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry, man. I'm sorry,'' Timber said as he burrowed his
head into Said's shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Said assured Timber more than once that there was no problem and
no need for apologies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel bad for him,'' Said said after Timber wandered off,
mumbling.
</P>
<P>
   The emotional scene was set by a fourth-lap crash during the
Pronto Auto Parts 400K last night.
</P>
<P>
   Said explained what happened and what precipitated Timber's
emotional state. He said a truck or trucks in front of him broke
loose and began to spin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't see a thing,'' Said said. ``My spotter said `Go
low, go low.' I went low and somebody was there.''
</P>
<P>
   Timber was Said's spotter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel bad for him,'' Said said. ``It's hard for a spotter.
I've been a spotter. You've only got a couple of seconds to make a
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Said, who finished second last year at the TMS event, started
the race in the 16th position on the outside of row eight. He said
he had worked his way past five or six trucks and was feeling
pretty good about attaining his goal of finishing in the top 10.
``I think we may have been in the top five by the way (the truck)
felt,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While the crash ended the hopes of Said and his team, it
prolonged an agonizing run of bad luck for Mike Bliss and his team.
</P>
<P>
   Bliss had had a couple of very good days at TMS. He qualified
fifth and was running strong when his night ended on the fourth
lap.
</P>
<P>
   He was also running strong in Portland and Phoenix this year
when engine blew.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is frustrating because of all the bad luck we've had this
year,'' said Jim Smith, owner of Bliss's truck. ``We are a top team
that is down on its luck.''
</P>
<P>
   Bliss' bad luck at TMS is in its second year. In 1997, Bliss won
the pole and led the first 112 laps, but a cut tire handed the race
to Kenny Irwin Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``We dominated,'' Smith said of the 1997 race.
</P>
<P>
   Bliss's bad luck didn't end with a wrecked truck last night. He
also sustained a broken right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said the crash was not entirely caused by bad luck.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we would have turned it around tonight, but a rookie
got in front of us,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   The rookie was Scot Walters.
</P>
<P>
   Said and Smith said Walters started the events when his truck
spun.
</P>
<P>
   A crew member of Walters' was asked whether his driver was
available to talk about the crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, because there he goes,'' the crew member said, nodding
toward an ambulance headed out of the garage area.
</P>
<P>
   Walters had a chin cut and was complaining of neck pain after
the wreck. He was taken to John Peter Smith Hospital in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth-lap accident was the first of the night but not the
last. In all, nine trucks were eliminated from the race by crashes
and there were nine caution periods.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers cited various causes for the accidents _ high speeds,
poor driving, debris on the track _ but nary a suggestion that the
freshly resurfaced track was a cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just so fast out there,'' veteran Winston Cup driver
Jimmy Hensley said. ``A lot of guys just don't have the trucks'' to
go that fast. ``It's pretty fast for a pickup. And there is a lot
of stuff being kicked up out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Hensley crashed on the 58th lap.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
