A7192 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN--Astros-Royals-HN     06-06 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN--Astros-Royals-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Interleague interruption
<TEXT>
<P>
   Astros' winning ends when American League arrives
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JOSEPH DUARTE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
Baseball purists don't care much for interleague play.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, neither do the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City Royals, behind the pitching of righthander Tim
Belcher, resembled an American League version of the Atlanta Braves
in a 3-0 victory over the Astros on Friday night before a crowd of
27,895 at the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   After experiencing one year of ``The Great Interleague
Experiment,'' the Astros are no closer to finding a way to beat an
AL club, even the Royals, who entered the game in the AL Central
cellar with the third-worst record in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros are 4-12 in interleague play since the concept of the
NL and AL playing each other during the regular season was adopted
last season.
</P>
<P>
   So what do the Astros really think of this interleague stuff?
</P>
<P>
   ``Interleague play killed us last year, so if we would have
taken a vote if we were in favor of it this season, everybody would
have said no,'' second baseman Craig Biggio said.
</P>
<P>
   While the novelty of interleague play has worn off, the Astros
couldn't help but notice the ramifications as the Chicago Cubs
pulled into a first-place tie in the NL Central.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you have to score runs to win in either league. And
the Astros didn't, wasting a solid performance by lefthander Pete
Schourek, whose seven-inning outing was his longest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Schourek, who lasted only two innings in his start May 30 at
Colorado, settled down after allowing Dean Palmer's run-scoring
double in the first inning and did not allow a hit over the next
six innings.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, between the first and ninth innings _ the two innings
the Royals pushed across their runs _ Astros pitchers did not allow
a hit.
</P>
<P>
   Schourek (2-4), who did not permit a runner to reach second base
after the first inning, scattered two hits, four walks and eight
strikeouts in seven innings. He struck out the side in the third.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been progressively getting better,'' said Schourek, who
hadn't pitched beyond 5 innings in his first five starts. ``I was
looking for something like this to eventually happen. I feel like I
could have thrown all my pitches at any time and all three were
effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually if I can get out of the first inning, I can settle
down and realize what my best pitch and second-best pitch is from
then on. I was kind of struggling with my command early on
(Friday). That's just the way it goes.''
</P>
<P>
   On any other occasion, he likely would have been good enough to
win. But Belcher was equally impressive. Belcher (5-6) held the
Astros to seven hits and worked out of several jams _ including one
in the third inning when the Astros stranded two runners, including
the potential tying run at third base.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros had at least one runner reach base in eight of the
nine innings but came up empty-handed each time in losing their
second consecutive game. It was their third shutout loss of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher is 10-3 with a 2.68 ERA in 20 career appearances against
the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good veteran pitcher, but if he pitched 10 times
against us, we'd score nine times,'' Astros manager Larry Dierker
said. ``I don't think he could (shut out us out) again.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros have scored only one run in their last 20 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like we have to start swinging the bats a little
better,'' Dierker said. ``We didn't have that many opportunities,
but what opportunities we did have we didn't get any clutch hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of times we hit the ball sharply, but most of the
time we didn't. We're kind of in an offensive funk right now, and I
hope we come out of it soon.''
</P>
<P>
   The Royals, who snapped a four-game losing streak, scored the
only run they needed in the first inning when Palmer lined an RBI
double to the right-field corner that scored Jose Offerman, who had
singled.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros put runners on first and second with one out in the
ninth when Bill Spiers singled and Ricky Gutierrez walked off
Royals reliever Jeff Montgomery.
</P>
<P>
   They appeared to have loaded the bases when Gutierrez seemed to
beat Montgomery's throw to second off Brad Ausmus' grounder to the
mound. But Gutierrez was ruled out, and Montgomery got his 10th
save when pinch hitter Dave Clark grounded out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really couldn't get anything to fall in or get many breaks
going our way,'' Biggio said. ``We had a couple of guys in scoring
position, we hit the ball hard, but tonight wasn't supposed to be
our night.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros had a good scoring shot in the third inning, and
leadoff singles in the fifth, seventh and eighth also failed to
produce any runs.
</P>
<P>
   In the NL or AL, that's the formula for a loss.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
