<HEADER>
A7196 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-BELMONT-SFCHRON &LR;      06-06 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-BELMONT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL QUIET WILL FINISH HIS BLAZE OF GLORY 
BY LARRY STUMES
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Real Quiet is the real deal.
</P>
<P>
   Forget about the injuries that knocked out many of his opponents
along the Triple Crown trail, forget about his early record that
included two defeats at Santa Fe Downs in New Mexico, forget about
his $17,000 purchase price.
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet will win the Belmont Stakes Saturday at Belmont Park
to become the 12th horse to sweep the Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   Detractors will say he isn't deserving of the honor, that he
couldn't have run with the likes of Secretariat, Citation or
Affirmed.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he couldn't have beaten them, but he is beating the horses
they put in the starting gate with him. In 20 years, no one will
remember who Real Quiet ran against; his name will be there with
the other Triple Crown winners.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people criticizing this horse, but he's run well
every time at 1 1/16 miles or longer on a fast track,'' said Mike
Pegram, who bought Real Quiet for $17,000 through trainer Bob
Baffert at a yearling sale in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet has four wins, two seconds and five thirds in 14
starts. But since losing a one-mile maiden race in his sixth start,
the bay colt has four wins, two seconds and a third in seven starts
on a fast track.
</P>
<P>
   Two of Real Quiet's early losses came in the Indian Nations
Futurity Cup and a trial heat at Santa Fe Downs. Both races were
run at seven furlongs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a greedy owner and a foolish trainer,'' Pegram said.
``They were giving away $600,000 (in purse and bonuses), and we
threw him in there. We were asking him to do something he didn't
want to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wouldn't tell Patrick Ewing to shoot nothing but
3-pointers and then say he was a lousy basketball player because he
couldn't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   After Real Quiet broke his maiden going 1 1/16 miles on October
18, he finished a strong third in the Kentucky Jockey Club Stakes
at Churchill Downs and then won the Hollywood Futurity.
</P>
<P>
   ``He ran in a position most young horses don't accept,'' jockey
Kent Desormeaux said. ``He was behind horses getting dirt in his
face. I needed him to go through a hole on the inside, and he
really went through there. I thought then that he was the best
chance I ever had to win the Kentucky Derby.''
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet opened his 1998 campaign by finishing last _ 221/2
lengths behind victorious Clover Hunter _ in the Golden Gate Derby
on January 18 at Golden Gate Fields. Rain poured all that day, and
the track was a quagmire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was up in the director's room, and going into the first turn
I was back sitting down finishing my beer,'' Pegram said. ``It was
obvious he wasn't going to run in that stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet finished second, a head behind Artax, in the San
Felipe Stakes on March 14 at Santa Anita and second again, 21/4
lengths behind stablemate Indian Charlie, in the Santa Anita Derby
on April 4.
</P>
<P>
   Then he broke out, winning the Kentucky Derby by a half-length
over fast-closing Victory Gallop and making an awesome move on the
second turn to take the Preakness by 21/4 lengths over Victory
Gallop.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Derby, I told Kent to move from the three-eighths pole
to the eighth, and he made a huge quarter-mile run,'' Baffert said.
``Then he ran unbelievable in the Preakness.''
</P>
<P>
   The Belmont Stakes distance of 11/2 miles is the longest of the
Triple Crown; the Kentucky Derby is 11/4 miles and the Preakness is
1 3/16 miles.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the most awesome, fluid style,'' Desormeaux said of
Real Quiet. ``He can just snap off those 12-second eighths (of a
mile) so easily. He's really matured. If there's any horse today
that can get 11/2 miles, it would be him.''
</P>
<P>
   Twelve horses will be trying to knock off Real Quiet Saturday.
Look for Yarrow Brae, Victory Gallop, Thomas Jo and Grand Slam to
provide the strongest competition. But that is all they will be,
competition.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
