<HEADLINE>
PAC-10 HAS REAL SURE THING  
 ASU, USC MEET FOR BASEBALL TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OMAHA, Neb. _ Pat Murphy likes to say the Pac-10 schedule is a
perfect tune-up for the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Jeez, he wasn't kidding.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona State traveled hundreds of miles, beat up some of
college baseball's biggest powers and used some of its finest
strategy for this: the opportunity to meet one of its Pac-10
Southern Division brethren.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona State vs. Southern California. For the national title.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone had just said something, we could have settled this
back home,'' Trojans Coach Mike Gillespie joked.
</P>
<P>
   Truth be told, today's game is about more than the College World
Series crown. It is about two of college baseball's most successful
programs going head to head.
</P>
<P>
   USC has won 11 titles, its last coming in 1978. ASU has won
five, but not since 1981. The Trojans advanced by knocking off, on
consecutive days, Louisiana State, a team that has won four
national crowns in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The ghosts of ASU baseball have some scores to settle. In 1972
and '73, USC beat the Sun Devils for the title in one-run games.
</P>
<P>
   If the regular season is any indication, this contest will be
just as close. These teams split their six meetings with home
sweeps.
</P>
<P>
   If there's an advantage, it's that the Sun Devils are
well-rested. They haven't played since Wednesday. The Trojans will
be competing for a third straight day.
</P>
<P>
   ASU will start its ace, Ryan Mills, who said earlier this week
that his arm was dead. Asked how it felt Friday, he said, ``At this
point, it doesn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to be nitro or anything. I'll be able to give
everything I've got. Whatever that is, I don't know. Our whole
bullpen is rested, and I think that's important.''
</P>
<P>
   USC is expected to go with Rik Currier, who was 5-1 during the
regular season with a 5.23 ERA. His last appearance was against
Mississippi State, when he went eight innings and allowed one run
and four hits while striking out 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``They do everything,'' ASU Coach Pat Murphy said. ``They hit
with power, they run, they bunt, they play defense, they pitch
well. They're a solid ballclub all the way around.''
</P>
<P>
   It may say something about college baseball that the two teams
with the least power in the tournament advanced to the final.
</P>
<P>
   Both schools are capable of hitting home runs _ ASU has five in
three Series games _ but both are better known for manufacturing
runs: stealing bases, bunting, turning to the hit and run.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're like us,'' Mills said. ``They do the little stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's really been a case of David vs. Goliath
when we play people,'' shortstop Michael Collins said. ``We can hit
home runs if we have to, but it's just that we can produce runs in
a number of ways. That's how we keep finding ways to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the key for ASU, though, during this series is its
consistent defense. The Sun Devils have made two errors vs. 11 by
their opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Offensively, Willie Bloomquist (.533) has led a charge of five
players hitting better than .400 in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   This title game is a surprising finish to a season that many
thought would have Stanford as the only Pac-10 representative here.
</P>
<P>
   Few expected ASU to be here. At the season's midpoint, the Sun
Devils were only two games better than .500.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils' last national title came in 1981, a 7-4 victory
over Oklahoma State. ASU lost a 1988 championship to another Pac-10
rival, Stanford, 9-4.
</P>
<P>
   But the Sun Devils are here without a roster of big-name players
_ like Barry Bonds _ that often dotted past lineups.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's true, but I think it's just that there's not that many
big names in college baseball anymore,'' Murphy said. ``The pros
take a lot of the great ones. You've got to win with scrappy guys,
but that's one of the more enjoyable things about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You win with a (Mikel) Moreno, a (Rudy) Arguelles, a Richy
Leon. They all make it go, and it's really beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Mills, the biggest name on the team, said he would spend Friday
night on his own, and that he prefers not to talk to too many
people before he pitches.
</P>
<P>
   But he did realize the opportunity that has been presented him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how many kids dream about this, being in Omaha,''
he said. ``This is why I came to college. I feel good about this
game. One thing about this team, we always come through. We have a
lot of heart, a lot of hard-nosed players. That will make the
difference.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
