<HEADLINE>
DEVILS CAN TOUCH TITLE TROPHY TODAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OMAHA _ The College World Series trophy rests inside a display
case in the lobby of Arizona State's downtown hotel. Bathed in soft
light, the Waterford crystal bat and ball sparkle like crushed
diamonds.
</P>
<P>
   ASU players are drawn to the trophy's glow. They view the
elegant object with respectful silence, their eyes wide and
unblinking, like children gazing wishfully into the front window of
a toy store.
</P>
<P>
   They arrived here 10 days ago. They won their first game. Won
their second. Won their third, circling the bases for 14 runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever dreamed we'd be in ``this'' position?'' ASU pitcher
Ryan Mills said. Now only a pane of glass separates these kids from
their prize.
</P>
<P>
   While watching them gaze at the trophy, you thought of the pop
fly drill the Sun Devils performed Friday during their final
practice of this magical season. Head thrown back, eyes to the gray
sky, third baseman Andrew Beinbrick waved other infielders away and
sang out as he lifted his glove, ``Mine! Mine! Mine!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep saying it!'' Coach Pat Murphy demanded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mine!'' Beinbrink shouted. ``MINE!!''
</P>
<P>
   If all goes well, it will be theirs very soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not very big,'' Doug Schreiber, an ASU assistant coach
said, viewing the trophy with a critical eye. No, but what it
represents is huge. If ASU beats Southern California today the Sun
Devils will win their first baseball national championship in 17
years.
</P>
<P>
   Has it been that long?
</P>
<P>
   Hard to believe, but yes. In the 1980s ASU sent four teams to
Omaha. Barry Bonds played in the College World Series. So did
Oddibe McDowell. But in 1983 and '84 and '87 and '88 the Devils
fell short.
</P>
<P>
   Now the school has an opportunity to write more history with a
spirited group of players and a gung-ho coach who had never been
here before.
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen years?
</P>
<P>
   The last time ASU won the College World Series, Jim Brock's
successor was in college. ``Playing at Florida Atlantic
(University),'' Murphy said, grabbing an imaginary bat and striking
a hitter's squinty pose.
</P>
<P>
   In 1981 most of the players Murphy recruited were preschoolers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know what ASU was,'' said Mills, then age 4. Now the
junior left-hander stands 6 feet 5. His final start for his alma
mater will be the biggest game of his college career.
</P>
<P>
   In 1981, the old man on this team, 26-year-old Rudy Arguelles,
was the youngest and smallest player on his Little League club. The
9-year-old second baseman has a picture of himself sitting in the
dugout, his legs dangling off the edge of the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody else,'' Rudy recalled, ``had their feet on the
ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Rooted in fundamentals, this team grew up together this year. A
tough schedule prepared the Devils for the rigors of the NCAA
tournament. Steady pitching and hot bats have carried them to the
championship game, where they will face a familiar opponent. This
season ASU and USC split six games, the Devils taking the last
three. On April 11 _ their last meeting _ the Devils won 24-4,
which means nothing, of course, unless ASU allows itself to go into
the title game feeling overly confident.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing Murphy, he won't allow that. ASU's fourth-year coach has
a team-as-fortress mentality. He preaches about playing each game
one pitch, one inning at a time, while guarding against possible
distractions, for which he coined a name.
</P>
<P>
   ``FUMPS,'' Murphy said.
</P>
<P>
   Fumps?
</P>
<P>
   The coach ticked them off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fans. Umpires. Media. Nothing personal,'' he said, smiling.
``Parents. Scouts.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans should pose more threat to the Devils than the
FUMPS. USC made the title game the hard way, twice beating two-time
defending champion LSU.
</P>
<P>
   But how can you not like ASU's chances? The Devils are hitting
everything. They're rested. And their ace, who throws 95 mph, says
he can't wait.
</P>
<P>
   Murph, is there anybody you'd rather have on the mound than
Mills?
</P>
<P>
   The coach thought a moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob Gibson,'' he replied. &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at david.casstevens(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
