<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-JAZZ-BULLS-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BULLS EVEN SERIES AT 1-1 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ Michael Jordan read the newspapers and watched
television on Thursday. He came upon several stories and statistics
pointing to his eventual doom and decided, enough already.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have inner strength and confidence,'' Jordan said Friday
morning. ``One game does not deteriorate that. One game does not
dictate how this series is going to end. If you want to write us
off, go ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Hold the Bulls' obituary for another day.
</P>
<P>
   Creating artificial motivation as only he can, Jordan led
Chicago past the Utah Jazz in Game 2 of the National Basketball
Association finals Friday night. Before a silenced throng at the
Delta Center, the Bulls evened the four-of-seven-game series with a
93-88 victory and return to Chicago with home-court advantage.
</P>
<P>
   The series shifts to the United Center for Games 3, 4 and 5
beginning on Sunday night, giving the Jazz two days in which not to
tick Jordan off. He was angry during and after Game 1, an 88-85
overtime loss on Wednesday that was supposed to signal the demise
of a dynasty.
</P>
<P>
   But deposing the king was an impossible chore for Karl Malone,
John Stockton and the Jazz in Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan scored 37 points, 23 in he second half, on 14-of-33
shooting and received help from Scottie Pippen and Toni Kukoc, who
combined for 34 points.
</P>
<P>
   Utah was led by Jeff Hornacek's 20 points. Malone had 16 poins
but shot just 5 for 16.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago led at halftime, 50-46, and Jordan, Pippen and Kukoc had
combined for 40 points.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the game, the emergence of Hornacek helped the Jazz,
too. Battling a slew of minor injuries _ from a nagging back to a
strained Achilles' tendon _ the veteran guard sparked Utah in the
third period with his marksmanship and uncanny knack for finding a
way to get around his defender.
</P>
<P>
   With Malone shackled by Dennis Rodman down low, Stockton
consistently found Hornacek running off screens for jump shots.
</P>
<P>
   Utah took a 73-70 lead into the final period, after a wild few
minutes in which the Bulls fell apart on both ends of the court and
surrendered a lead of 61-53.
</P>
<P>
   Stockton and Hornacek directed an 11-0 run to put Utah in
charge. Whether Stockton was taking the ball away from Steve Kerr
and leading the break or Hornacek was making improbable 3-pointers
and lean-in runners with hands in his face, everything was working.
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz went ahead by 64-61 after Stockton drove the length of
the floor and hit a layup underneath Ron Harper.
</P>
<P>
   The run came after the Bulls went up by eight points midway
through the third quarter and seemed to be on the verge of blowing
the Jazz out. But Utah, as it always seems to do in this building,
caught fire.
</P>
<P>
   First, Malone bulled over Rodman, drew a foul and made two free
throws. Then after a missed Jordan layup in heavy traffic, Stockton
found Bryon Russell on the right baseline. He dropped in a
3-pointer to bring Utah within 61-58.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Hornacek converted a 3-pointer on the right wing to
give the Jazz the lead, bedlam consumed the Delta Center.
</P>
<P>
   It was that kind of game from the start.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Shandon Anderson cut the Chicago lead to 85-83 with 2 minutes 12
seconds left, making two free throws. But the Bulls would not
relent.
</P>
<P>
   They rebounded well, especially their own missed shots. With
less than 3 minutes left, 16 of their 31 rebounds had come on the
offensive end. Rodman, after a quick trip to Las Vegas, after a
subpar showing in Game 1, returned with resolve.
</P>
<P>
   Malone picked up his fifth foul for holding Steve Kerr as the
Bulls guard tried to fight through a pick-and-roll with less than 7
minutes left. Then Jordan gave the Bulls the impetus they needed to
close the door, it seemed.
</P>
<P>
   He hit a near-impossible jump shot from the free-throw line,
with Hornacek draped around him. The ball swished. He drew the foul
and made the free throw to put the Bulls in front, 81-74.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jerry Sloan chose an unusual lineup to begin the fourth
quarter: Adam Keefe, Anderson, Antoine Carr, Howard Eisley and
Chris Morris. Within minutes, he reinserted Stockton and Malone.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Jackson countered with Jordan with less than 9 minutes
left.
</P>
<P>
   Points were at a premium the first five minutes of the fourth
quarter, with non-calls on each side leading to several turnovers
and forced shots.
</P>
<P>
   The teams went at each other like prizefighters in the first
half, the Bulls shooting 52.5 percent from the field and the Jazz
hitting 54.3 percent of its shots. The two best-executing teams in
the league were passing, moving without the ball and getting easy
baskets inside. They combined for 54 points in the paint after two
quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Kukoc went on a personal tear, scoring 13 points in the first
half on 6-of-11 shooting. He was posting up Anderson, scoring over
Russell from the outside and making all the right decisions in
Chicago's triple-post offense.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan needed a break, especially after having to take 29 shots
in Game 1. Pippen provided relief, driving to the goal and doing
everything he could to disrupt the Jazz's defense. The Bulls made
several adjustments from Game 1, including making sure Pippen and
Kukoc drove to the basket. Pippen also was matched up against
Malone at times in the post. His reach and quickness disrupted
Malone from making his move inside on several possessions.
</P>
<P>
   And rather than let Kerr take his chances against Stockton,
Coach Phil Jackson employed Harper's athleticism and Kukoc's size
to help quell the playmaker's penetration.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls played as if their season was on the line, with the
same passion and desire they did against the Indiana Pacers in Game
7 of the Eastern Conference finals. The Jazz seemed to feed off of
that intensity, repelling every Bull run with one of its own.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the classic playoff games in recent memory, neither
team would budge. And when it was over, the series was all even.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
