<HEADER>
A7203 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-TRUCKS-TEX     06-06 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-TRUCKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAINES TOPS ROOKIE TO WIN TRUCK RACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Texas Motor Speedway is good to rookies
driving trucks, but there's something to be said for a little bit
of experience.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Houston made a bid to become the second rookie to win a
NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series race at TMS, but second-year driver
Tony Raines was able to hold him off.
</P>
<P>
   Raines took the checkered flag at the Pronto Auto Parts 400K
last night at TMS, finishing 0.241 seconds ahead of Houston. It was
the second victory on the circuit this season for the driver of the
No. 19 Pennzoil Ford, and the third in his two seasons racing the
trucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is awesome,'' Raines said. ``This is really neat. I like
Texas. It's a big state, a big racetrack and it pays a lot of
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Raines won $56,400 for the victory before an estimated crowd of
60,000, the largest in the four-year history of the series.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Irwin Jr., also a rookie, won the inaugural truck race at
TMS last year. Instead of joining him, Houston settled for the best
finish of his brief career. The previous best for the 27-year-old
driver of the No. 60 Addington Racing Chevrolet was a fourth in the
third race of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony had me beat there at the end of the race,'' Houston said.
``But we hung in there all night, and it was a good run. You're
never satisfied running second, but we stayed out of trouble all
night. We were a little tight in the end or we might have been able
to pull it out.''
</P>
<P>
   The duel for the victory was set up an incident involving
another couple of first-year drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Raines passed rookie Wayne Anderson for the lead with 21 laps
remaining, and fellow rookies Houston and Greg Biffle also closed
in.
</P>
<P>
   Houston went low and Biffle went high, giving the track a brief
taste of three-wide racing. But it didn't last long. Anderson and
Biffle made contact, and Biffle went sideways.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just pushed up into my door and turned me,'' Biffle said.
``I'm sure he didn't mean to do it. It was unintentional contact.
We're both rookies.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston got through before the contact, and the caution flag
allowed him to close up on Raines.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like (Biffle) spun, and I was lucky to get out of
the way of it,'' Houston said. ``It was a hairy moment, but it all
worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   When the green flag dropped after the caution with 12 laps to
go, it quickly became a two-truck duel.
</P>
<P>
   Raines and Houston broke away from the pack on the restart with
Houston all over Raines' rear spoiler.
</P>
<P>
   The rookie took a look inside but couldn't find any room. He
took a look to the outside, but Raines wouldn't let him by. Houston
was stuck, a couple of feet behind Raines when the checkered flag
dropped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Andy was getting too close and would be able to
draft,'' Raines said. ``But I was able to hold him off.''
</P>
<P>
   Veteran driver Joe Ruttman finished third after starting 31st.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just thrilled to death,'' Ruttman said. ``When we
started, I felt like we locked in a traffic jam in Dallas. That's
how far back we were.''
</P>
<P>
   Arlington-based racer David Starr, driving the Reher-Morrison
Chevrolet, finished a career-best 18th.
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of the race belonged to the favorite, Jack Sprague. He
led with 32 laps remaining but was bumped from behind by Biffle and
narrowly avoided a horrendous wreck. He went onto the infield grass
and almost went airborne when two wheels lifted, but he was able to
keep it on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   That incident brought out one of the nine cautions for assorted
wrecks and debris on the track. But unlike the two crash-marred
Winston Cup races at TMS, nobody blamed the reconfigured track.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it might have been that the new track was too good. The
trucks went faster than ever before, making aerodynamics a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Other than that, the trucks appeared to like the repaved race
track. They were able to race, and the lead changed hands 13 times.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
