<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-06 01:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7204 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UTAH-POLICE-SLAYING-A     06-06 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UTAH-POLICE-SLAYING-ART-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO MEN SOUGHT IN KILLING ELUDE AN ARMY OF POLICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(lh) 
 By JO THOMAS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLANDING, Utah _ As hundreds of law-enforcement officers combed
miles of desert canyon near here for two armed men wanted in the
killing of a Colorado police officer, officials conceded Friday
that the pair seemed to have vanished as completely as the mirages
on the blacktop highways.
</P>
<P>
   Law-enforcement officials had thought that the suspects, Alan
Pilon, 30, of Dove Creek, Colo., and Jason Wayne McVean, 26, of
Durango, Colo., whom officials described as survivalists, were
trapped in a seven-by-two-mile area of brush and woods near the San
Juan River. Officials zeroed in on the area after a San Juan County
sheriff's deputy was shot on Thursday by a man in camouflage
clothing near the town of Bluff.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the shooting, the body of a man believed to be an
accomplice of the two, Robert Matthew Mason, 26, of Durango, was
found at a campsite along the river, about five miles east of
Bluff. The police believe he shot himself to death.
</P>
<P>
   Police found pipe bombs near the body of Mason, who was wearing
camouflage clothing and a ski mask.
</P>
<P>
   With the shooting of the Utah deputy, 200 National Guardsmen and
300 local, state and federal officers converged on the area, set up
roadblocks, searched with helicopters and evacuated 230 residents
of Bluff. At the middle school here where they spent their day
until being told they could return home Friday night, residents
wondered how they would feel when they got back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm scared,'' said Charlotte Gray, 31, as she sat with her
6-year-old daughter, Authia, on the front lawn of the school. Mrs.
Gray was at work at the Kokopelli Inn in Bluff when someone ran
past her on Thursday shouting, ``Lock your doors! The killers are
here!'' Then she heard sirens and helicopters, she said.
</P>
<P>
   With help from her brother, she retrieved her three children,
only to abandon the family truck, with its engine running, when
another panicked resident warned, ``Everybody get back inside,
they're just around the corner.'' Eventually, she said, a friend
brought them to Blanding, where they spent the night at the school.
</P>
<P>
   David Florence, the manager of the Red Cross field office in
southeastern Utah, said he had an hour to prepare the middle school
gymnasium for the residents. But residents and churches brought
food and toys and opened their homes, and 150 people stayed at the
gymnasium on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Dennison Bellson, a carpenter, said he was building a house when
a neighbor told him shots had been fired. He climbed to the roof
and saw helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   He and his wife came to Blanding, but worried all night about
their three children, who were staying at their grandparents' home
about 15 miles south of Bluff, on the Navajo Nation Reservation.
Friday morning, he said, they went to get them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were out playing and running around in the sun,'' he
said, smiling with relief. ``And I saw three Navajos out on their
lawn chairs, watching the helicopters go by.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The search area Friday included hundreds of thousands of acres
in southern Utah and 22 miles of river between Bluff and Mexican
Hat.
</P>
<P>
   By late afternoon, Sheriff Mike Lacy of San Juan County warned,
``We may be here a couple more days at least. It's hard to say.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have nothing to go on at this particular time,'' he added.
``We are not 100 percent sure that they are out of the area or
still in the area.''
</P>
<P>
   All four roads to Bluff were closed Friday, and disappointed
tourists and boaters were turned away. On the 11 miles of road
north of Bluff, only crows and helicopters moved in the still
desert landscape.
</P>
<P>
   The manhunt, which now includes hundreds of police and National
Guardsmen began May 29 after police officer Dale Claxton, 45, was
shot to death in Cortez, Colo., by three gunmen armed with machine
guns and dressed in camouflage.
</P>
<P>
   Two Montezuma County sheriff's deputies were wounded in the
ensuing chase and gun battle. The gunmen fled on foot and
disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press reported that in a statement obtained by
KUSA-TV in Denver, Mason's brother Gary Charles Mason, 27, of
Aurora, told the La Plata County Sheriff's Department in Colorado
that he believed his brother was involved in the shootings and had
``a lengthy background in anti-government feelings and anti
law-enforcement statements.'' He said his brother was heavily
armed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that his friends have the same type of thinking that he
does,'' Gary Mason said. ``They sort of feed off each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Mark Potok, a spokesman for the Southern Poverty Law
Center, said that at least one of the gunmen, Pilon, has been
associated with the Four Corners Patriot Militia, which he
described as a ``shadowy, paramilitary organization'' that has been
active for at least three years, has about 25 members, and has no
official headquarters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
