<HEADER>
A7207 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-STARS-WINGS-TEX     06-06 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-WINGS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED WINGS ELIMINATE STARS WITH 2-0 VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ A littany of banners hangs above the ice at Joe Louis
Arena:
</P>
<P>
   Central Division Champions, 1993-94.
</P>
<P>
   Western Conference Regular-Season Champions 1994-95.
</P>
<P>
   Presidents' Trophy Champions 1995.
</P>
<P>
   But not until last season did the modern era Red Wings raise the
Stanley Cup championship banner _ their first since 1955.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars took a look at those banners last night as they walked
from the building that has been their Waterloo. After a 2-0 Game 6
loss in the Western Conference finals that ended the Stars' season
and sent the Red Wings to their third Stanley Cup Finals in the
past four seasons, the Stars said they learned a lesson from the
masters.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have learned what others like us are trying to learn,
that there's an awful high price to pay to win at this level,''
Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``I think what impresses me most
about (the Red Wings) is their resolve. They got pushed to the
limit _ they knew it, we knew it _ but they responded.''
</P>
<P>
   Led by goalie Chris Osgood, who bounced back from a horrendous
overtime gaffe in Game 5 when he allowed an 80-foot goal to create
the need for a Game 6, the Red Wings closed out the series 4-2 and
gave themselves a few days off before facing the Washington
Capitals on Tuesday in Detroit. Osgood had 26 saves and collected
his second shutout of the series. They were bookends in games 1 and
6, and they showed just how much the Wings understand the pressure
of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the series was decided, it's strange to say, when we
were able to win in Dallas,'' Wings coach Scotty Bowman said.
</P>
<P>
   After taking Game 1, the Wings then simply held service on home
ice, running the Stars' desperation at Joe Louis Arena to 1-17-2 in
their past 20 visits _ including 0-6 in the playoffs. Had the Stars
been able to pull off an upset in The Joe just once, they would be
back at Reunion Arena for Game 7 tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   But maybes don't win Stanley Cups.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were close, but close isn't good enough,'' veteran Stars
center Bob Bassen said. ``Tonight, they were the better team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Wings left no doubt about that last night. All the talk
of lucky bounces and bad penalties and fluky goals was put aside.
The Red Wings dominated early, took a lead and never backed off.
They received controlled play from their stars and their role
players. They simply did not yield anything to a Stars team that
Bowman called ``the toughest we have played in the past two
(playoff) seasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock returned the compliment to the Wings.
</P>
<P>
   ``They played their best game of the series, and they played it
when they needed it most,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, there was still room for controversy. Wings defenseman
Larry Murphy scored the key first goal _ the team scoring first won
every game in the series _ on a shorthanded rush when he magically
jumped off the bench and into wide open ice. The Stars said there
was no one within 20-feet when Murphy, a defenseman, slipped out
the forward door _ a transgression, if true, was cause for a
penalty on the Wings. Detroit players claimed defenseman Bob Rouse
was coming off and clearly on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Stars defenseman Craig Ludwig had the best theory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that's (the play) we're going to look back on or
blame the game on,'' Ludwig said. ``We've got to score a couple of
goals.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars didn't, and maybe couldn't. With a hobbled defense,
they often struggled to move the puck out of the defensive zone.
With a frustrated offense, they couldn't break through against a
Red Wings team that has been one of the best at defensive hockey
for the past four seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars scored 11 goals in the six-game series, just slightly
below the 2.3 goals-per-game average they had for the playoffs. No
team has advanced to the conference finals scoring that few goals
since 1968.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed to score more goals,'' Hitchcock said. ``You can't
go along thinking your goalie can be the first star every night of
the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   And, in the end, Stars goalie Ed Belfour certainly was not. He
let in a soft goal from Wings center Sergei Fedorov at the 1:48
mark of the second period and that started the death knell.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the Stars had come back from a 2-0 deficit before. But
this Stars team was tired. This team was injured, this team didn't
have the same experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very close, I don't think anyone is going out of here
thinking we were clearly outplayed,'' defenseman Darryl Sydor said.
``We played hard, we really thought we could win.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet they didn't. Maybe, they couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until you've had your heart broken in this game, you really
don't know what you're missing out,'' said center Mike Modano, who
stood with his chin on his stick while his teammates were lining up
for the final handshake. ``You can talk to guys who have won it and
been there until in you're blue in the face. But until you
experience it yourself, it's hard to understand the words. You need
experience to learn and be better from it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've come a long way,'' he added. ``But we've got a long way
to go.''
</P>
<P>
   As they walked out, the banners called to the Stars, telling
them to look ahead, not look back.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a huge price to pay, mentally, physically and
emotionally,'' Hitchcock said. ``And you can stand there and talk
about it and you can beat on it all you want. But until; you
experience it, until you understand the level of commitment that is
necessary, until you go through it, then all the talk really
doesn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Last night, the Stars stopped talking, and started living.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-06-98 0104EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
