<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-06 01:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7208 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-T     06-06 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEST WISHES FLUTTER UPON DYING STARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ When you wish upon a Star, alas, you have to take the
whole Star.
</P>
<P>
   The paucity of firepower. The ailing defensemen. The
suddenly-turned-sour power play. The goaltender who picked the
worst of times to blink.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars will not live happily ever after, we discovered last
night. The Detroit Red Wings, the reigning kings, playing like
kings, snuffed the Stars' every precocious whim.
</P>
<P>
   For 12 months the Red Wings have carried the load of the Stanley
Cup on their shoulders. But in this series, abruptly concluded last
night with a 2-0 Wings victory, they wore it well.
</P>
<P>
   What a hockey team. What a deep and talented hockey team. What a
poised and well-coached hockey team.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars can take solace that they lost only by the misfortune
of a disputed goal and another that goalie Eddie Belfour should
have clutched, but didn't.
</P>
<P>
   But that's hockey. That's the playoffs. That's Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   If you're scoring along at home, that now makes eight teams in
the past nine seasons who have posted the league's best
regular-season record and then failed to win Lord Stanley's Cup.
</P>
<P>
   You can't sip champagne from the Presidents' Trophy. But maybe
in its reflection, the Stars will see themselves.
</P>
<P>
   A good team. At times, an outstanding one. And a short-handed
one, to be sure, for these past six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike the self-assured Red Wings, the Stars are a team that
still has to get over a hump _ the final hump.
</P>
<P>
   They missed leading scorer Joe Nieuwendyk dearly. But a Stanley
Cup wannabe can't point to ifs and buts until it figures a way to
win more than one of its last 20 games on its chief rival's ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the kind of adversity _ injuries _ that we've been
dealing with all year long,'' defenseman Richard Matvichuk said.
``We lost Joe, and we had the best power play in the league during
the regular season.''
</P>
<P>
   But as Matvichuk's partner on defense, Derian Hatcher, said in
the quiet locker room, ``It doesn't really matter much now.''
</P>
<P>
   Around Hatcher, trunks were being packed for the final ride
home. When the end comes for a hockey team, it comes suddenly. When
it comes like it did last night, in front of 19,983 at Joe Louis
Arena, it leaves little but a loud ringing in the losers' ears.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars didn't even feel the urge to wring their hands over
the two goals that were scored. The first resembled a David
Copperfield trick, with Detroit's Larry Murphy suddenly
materializing _ when? From where? _ to take Darren McCarty's pass
for the score.
</P>
<P>
   ``That happens all year long,'' defenseman Craig Ludwig said.
``I don't think any of us in here are going to dwell on that.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've still got to score a couple of goals to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The second Detroit goal allowed the Red Wings to blanket the
neutral zone and ride the clock to the end. More than anything,
though, it underscored the difference between the two goaltenders
in this conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   Without Belfour, the Stars would have never seen Joe Louis Arena
in these playoffs. With him, they saw it only long enough to earn a
trip home.
</P>
<P>
   In the most vital Stars game of the postseason, Belfour was
roundly outperformed by counterpart Chris Osgood. The Wings goalie
incurred the wrath of the headline writers and the home fans for
the long-distance goal he allowed in overtime Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   But, in truth, he outplayed Belfour in the series. The one game
that coach Ken Hitchcock thought Eddie could steal for the Stars
never came.
</P>
<P>
   As the clock ticked down to the final six minutes, the crowd at
``The Joe'' came to its feet, chanting, ``Oz-zie! Oz-zie!''
</P>
<P>
   You got the feeling that the Stars could have stayed here
another 60 minutes and still not scored.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Washington has got its hands full,'' the Stars' Mike
Modano predicted. ``I think these two teams were the best in the
league. Washington is pretty much going to be a whipping boy for
them, I think.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the Stars locker room carpeted in whispers, Red Wings
fans still howled and cheered. The Wings won all three games played
here during this conference final series.
</P>
<P>
   The message is obvious: Until the Stars say otherwise, the road
to any Stanley Cup has to pass through The Joe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The funny thing is, until this series they were .500 at home
in the playoffs,'' Modano said. ``But if you expect to win a
Stanley Cup, you have to be good on the road. We have to win
here.''
</P>
<P>
   But like the power play that went sour and the goaltender that
flinched, those are questions that the Stars would pack in the
trunk and fly home with.
</P>
<P>
   Six months of glory ended with a thud. When you wish upon a
Star, you'll have to live with that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-06-98 0106EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
