<DOCNO> NYT19980606.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-06 01:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7209 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-PADRES-RANGERS-TE     06-06 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-PADRES-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS DOWN PADRES, 8-7
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The results of a precautionary examination
Rangers closer John Wetteland underwent yesterday afternoon will be
known today.
</P>
<P>
   But the naked eye revealed what the Rangers already suspected.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt great,'' said Wetteland, who converted the 15th of 16
save opportunities this season in an 8-7 victory against the San
Diego Padres last night at The Ballpark in Arlington. ``There were
no problems. I wasn't even thinking about it in the bullpen
beforehand. I was just thinking about getting a good night's
sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland and the Rangers may rest easy, but the Padres made it
uneasy in the ninth inning. Center fielder Steve Finley and pinch
hitter Mark Sweeney produced consecutive one-out singles against
the hard-throwing right-hander, and each advanced 90 feet on a
groundout by catcher Carlos Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   That brought shortstop Chris Gomez to the plate with two outs,
the potential tying run at third and the potential game-winning run
at second. Gomez, though, entered the confrontation against
Wetteland 0-for-3 with two strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   Make that 0-for-4 with three strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland required only four pitches to retire Gomez and to send
the Padres into a first-place tie with the San Francisco Giants.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fun to face a few hitters and compete,'' said
Wetteland, who combined for two innings of scoreless relief with
left-hander Scott Bailes and right-hander Danny Patterson. ``It's
been a while since everything was flowing. I wasn't locating my
fastball at all, but that's not abnormal for me. I didn't put the
pitches where I wanted, but my slider worked well for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangers left-hander Darren Oliver took his best stuff to the
mound, but it is difficult to explain his performance. Oliver
matched his career-best with 10 strikeouts in pitching 62/3
innings, but he surrendered six runs on nine hits and one walk and
hit three Padres batters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oliver had his best stuff all season,'' Rangers manager Johnny
Oates said. ``When I went to take him out, I looked at the
scoreboard and couldn't figure out how he allowed six runs. His
velocity, his movement and his location were the best they've been
all year, and his curveball was the best since the Yankees playoff
game in '96.''
</P>
<P>
   Oliver, who received no decision, was also at a loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt great, the best since the day game in Boston,'' said
Oliver, who surrendered only two runs in a complete-game effort May
3 in the Rangers' 2-1 defeat at Fenway Park. ``It's funny, though.
As good as I felt, I still gave up six runs. But when I wake up in
the morning, I'll be able to look in the mirror and know that I
pitched my best.''
</P>
<P>
   The infielder who drove in what proved to be the game-winning
run told all how well the Rangers and Padres played their first
interleague game of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Fernando Tatis, whose seventh-inning single off
Padres right-hander Donne Wall (2-2) scored shortstop Domingo
Cedeno with the winning run, promptly found himself the target of a
successful pickoff throw by Padres Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers received low marks for artistic value, but it proved
to be enough to beat the best the National League West could offer.
</P>
<P>
   The game included 28 hits, two errors, three batters hit by
pitch and a couple of mistakes on the bases.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came out on top of it,'' said Rangers first baseman Will
Clark, who went 2-for-5 and drove in the Rangers' first run with a
two-out, run-scoring single against Padres right-hander Kevin
Brown. ``That's all anybody cares about in here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers chased Brown, who entered the game with the National
League's eighth-best earned-run average at 2.27, after the fifth
inning. Brown, who also received no decision, allowed six runs on
11 hits and four walks. Every member of the Rangers' offensive
lineup collected at least one hit against Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Offensively, everyone contributed,'' Oates said. ``We were
patient against Kevin, and scored a few runs early. If you don't
score early against Kevin, you're not going to score at all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
