<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-ALLISON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUGH GOING FOR A TRUE CHAMPION  
 LOTS OF BAD BREAKS FOR BOBBY ALLISON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bobby Allison has wept more than one father should be allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Four years after a violent crash in a 1988 race at Pocono
International Raceway ended his career and nearly his life, Allison
buried son Clifford Allison, who was killed Aug. 13, 1992, in a
crash at Michigan International Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   The next summer, NASCAR Winston Cup star Davey Allison, Bobby's
oldest son, died from injuries suffered when the helicopter he was
piloting crashed on takeoff from the infield at Talladega (Ala.)
Superspeedway.
</P>
<P>
   Two sons. Two tragedies.
</P>
<P>
   More followed.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the Allisons (Bobby and wife Judy) auctioned off
much of their personal property to help pay for Bobby's mounting
medical bills. Bobby Allison, who suffered a broken leg and a
concussion that left him mostly unconscious for two months, still
can't recall winning the 1988 Daytona 500 and also suffers from
additional memory loss.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the financial strain and the mental anguish of
losing two sons had an immeasurable impact on the elder Allisons'
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby and Judy separated in 1996 and no longer live in the same
state.
</P>
<P>
   The Allison saga has affected many, including Phoenix
International Raceway officials, who earlier this week announced a
new 5,000-seat grandstand being constructed in Turn 2 will bear
Bobby Allison's name.
</P>
<P>
   Four other grandstand sections are named after Richard Petty,
A.J. Foyt and Jimmy Bryan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby Allison is one of the classiest people I've ever met,''
said Dennis Wood, who formerly owned Phoenix International Raceway
and now is director of special projects. ``We could never do enough
to repay him for what he's meant to PIR. This is just one small way
of trying to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Allison clearly was moved by the gesture, readily approved by
International Speedway Corp., which purchased PIR from PIR
President Buddy Jobe last summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's overwhelming,'' Allison said.
</P>
<P>
   Wood only wished more could be done for one of stock car
racing's greatest drivers. Allison, who has 83 career wins and is a
member of racing's International Hall of Fame, was instrumental in
helping build PIR's popular Copper World Classic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best story I have of Bobby Allison is one that really says
a lot about who this man is,'' Wood said. ``I think it was 1982 and
Bobby called me from Hueytown (Ala.) and said they were having a
big ice storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `I'm the only one in Hueytown with electricity,
there's 45 people living in my house and Judy's trying to make an
upside-down cake in the fireplace. Can I come to the Copper World
Classic?'
</P>
<P>
   ``Now this is from someone who's already won one Daytona 500 and
he wants my permission to come out and race. He didn't want any
appearance money. He said, `I'll fly my airplane out there and have
my car towed.''
</P>
<P>
   Allison thought he would be returning home almost as soon as he
arrived, after suffering a blown motor in qualifying. Then, in a
last-chance race in an attempt to crack the starting grid, Allison
started last and was up to third when another car put him into the
wall and out of the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thinking, `I can't believe this,' '' Wood recalled. `We
have the great Bobby Allison and he's not in the race. What am I
going to do?'
</P>
<P>
   ``But Bobby didn't want to be treated any differently than
anyone else. He was willing to go home, because in those days we
didn't have promoter's options. But we went to the drivers' meeting
and I asked them if Bobby could start last. I said, `If the vote
isn't 30-0 to let him in _ and Bobby agreed _ we won't allow it.'
</P>
<P>
   ``The drivers let him in and Bobby personally thanked each one
of them. He's a great man.''
</P>
<P>
   Jobe already knows that.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have all those problems heaped on him, he's a lot better
man than I am,'' Jobe said. ``I don't know if I could have handled
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even now, Allison blames no one.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if life has been fair, Allison said, ``I don't think life
has to be fair. And I don't think life is fair to a lot of people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have had lots of good times. And I've had some bad times. At
least, I've had those good times and I have had an opportunity to
have those good times.
</P>
<P>
   ``And so I have to appreciate that rather than worry about
whether life has been fair to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Spoken like a true champion. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
