<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-ARMIJO-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROUD DAD CHEEVER RIDING HIGH  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   E &UR; ddie Cheever was in Rome at the moment another  &UR; Eddie Cheever
was crossing the finish line at the Indianapolis 500. They didn't
know it, but each raised a clenched fist into the air.
</P>
<P>
   Like father, like son.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't surprise me he won,'' said the elder Cheever, the
younger Cheever's 70-year-old father. ``I thought he could have won
a couple of years ago, but someone took him out in a crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it. Indy is a lottery. Anything can happen. But
when (Eddie Jr.) finally won, it made me very, very proud.''
</P>
<P>
   The win also allowed Cheever Jr., a 40-year-old Phoenix native,
to fulfill a father's wish 25 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eddie wanted to quit high school when he was 15 or 16 to go
racing full-time,'' said Cheever Sr., reached by telephone Tuesday
in Rome. ``I didn't really object because he wasn't really getting
anything out of it. But I told him if he was going to win one race
in his life, win the Indy 500.''
</P>
<P>
   Mission accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   The road to Indy actually began about 30 years ago in Rome, when
the Cheever matriarch purchased matching go-carts for her husband
and son.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the first time either of us raced,'' Cheever Sr. said.
``Eddie became very good very quick. I crashed, hurt my shoulder
and that was the end of me.''
</P>
<P>
   About 10 years earlier the Cheevers still were living in
Phoenix. At the time, Cheever Sr., a former champion weightlifter
who was born in Globe and crowned Mr. Arizona in 1955, was managing
a string of health clubs.
</P>
<P>
   But the company went bankrupt in 1959, and the elder Cheever
decided to move the family to Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Myself and four partners borrowed $25,000 and opened some
health clubs in Sydney,'' Cheever Sr. said. ``It was all new back
then. We were the pioneers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, we moved to Italy when Eddie was about 4 and opened more
health clubs. I had one in Berlin and London, four in Milan, two in
Turin and one in Naples. They were all great locations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I have just two, but they're beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheever Sr., however, never was too busy to keep up with his
oldest son's racing prowess.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember when we was just starting out, some important
person in the Italian racing business complimented Eddie one time
after a race,'' Cheever Sr. said. ``He said, `That kid knows what
he's doing.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty soon, Eddie was on the Italian Racing Team driving with
Ricardo Patrese.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Cheever Jr. became so proficient he was offered a
full-time Formula One ride with Osella Ford in 1980. In 1983,
Cheever Jr. drove for Renault, and his teammate was the great
French driver Alain Prost.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt bad for Eddie because the Renault team never let him
set the car up,'' Cheever Sr. said. ``They never let him take part
in the debriefing. I remember one time he passed Prost at Monte
Carlo and the crew held up a sign saying to let Prost go around
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Tired of the Formula One grind, where he didn't win in 132
career starts, Cheever Jr. returned to the United States in 1990 to
pursue an Indy car career. He remained winless until last year,
when he won at Walt Disney World Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   In that race, Cheever Jr. never led a green flag lap.
</P>
<P>
   At Indy two weeks ago, Cheever Jr. led more laps (76) than any
driver in the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I almost couldn't watch the race those last few laps,''
Cheever Sr. said. ``I kept thinking something bad was going to
happen.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
One cup sugar, please &QL; 
 &QL; 
Car owner  &UR; Jonathan Byrd of Litchfield Park has replaced Indy
Racing League driver  &UR; Mike Groff with  &UR; John Paul Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just wasn't working,'' Byrd said. ``Sometimes, you have to
change the recipe.''
</P>
<P>
   Groff finished 14th last season and had his year interrupted
after suffering a broken leg in a crash at Texas Motor Speedway,
the site of tonight's race.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
Double duty &QL; 
 &QL; 
Rookie IRL driver  &UR; J.J. Yeley of Phoenix is staying busy.
</P>
<P>
   He's in Memphis today to qualify for a U.S. Silver Crown race,
then returns to Texas for tonight's IRL race. Yeley is back in
Memphis on Sunday for the USAC race, then returns to Fort Worth,
where he will test for IRL car owner John Menard. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mark Armijo can be reached at mark.armijo(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
