<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-JAZZ-ANDERSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANDERSON SHOWS WHAT HE CAN DO 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ It was one year ago, just before Game 2, when a
telephone ring jolted Shandon Anderson from the surreal world of
playing in the finals. Reality crashed down on him the moment he
was told that his father, Willie, had lost his six-year struggle
against cancer.
</P>
<P>
   While the Jazz played on and lost to the Bulls in Game 2,
Anderson dashed home to his family in Atlanta, Ga. He mourned and
cried and wondered why could not he have just a little more time
with his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in the finals, and that was supposed to be this great
time in your career,'' Anderson said before the Jazz fell to the
Bulls, 93-88, in Game 2 of the National Basketball Association
finals Friday night at the Delta Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a really tough time. As difficult as it was last year,
there's some comfort now. I know he's watching me.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson was very visible Friday night. He was part of a bench
that went hand-in-hand with a supporting group of starters that
were ready to help their stars, Karl Malone and John Stockton, get
through Game 2. The Bulls' duo of Michael Jordan and Scottie Pippen
were searching for a hand as well. Jordan and Pippen scored 54 of
their team's 85 points in Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a two-man game in some respects,'' Jordan said. ``It
should have been more than that.''
</P>
<P>
   That was a plea for help. And in the end, it was Steve Kerr who
came through. Kerr took an off-balance 3-point, missed but was not
blocked out. He got his own rebound, handed it to Jordan
underneath. He made the layup, was fouled, and hit the free throw
with 47 second left to give the Bulls an 88-86 lead.
</P>
<P>
   At first Toni Kukoc, who was a quiet starter in Game 1 with 9
points, came through for 13 first-half points. Kukoc cooled, but it
was the oddball Dennis Rodman who came through in the fourth. He
put down a rare jumper to tie the score at 74 to with 7 minutes 40
seconds left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   That basket seemed to push the Bulls, who took a seven-point
lead. While Malone was flustered by Rodman's presence and was in
foul trouble, it was Bryon Russell who came into hit a 3-pointer to
score the first basket for the Jazz in 7 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   It was a back-and-forth to see which auxiliary player could
provide the game-turning support in this game. After the Bulls took
a six-point lead, Anderson came in for a layup and a foul as he
barged inside with 3 minutes left. But he missed the free throw,
and the Jazz were down by four points. Anderson then drew the sixth
foul on Luc Longley with 2 minutes left. Anderson stood at the
free-throw line and hit both to pull the Jazz to within two points.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, Anderson, joined by Howard Eisley on the floor,
quickly took advantage of the Bulls underneath in the first half.
Anderson muscled around whomever the Bulls could throw at him in
the second quarter and scored six consecutive points in the post.
</P>
<P>
   He kept the Jazz close to a Bulls' team that was getting much
more help from its supporting group as well. At least from Kukoc.
Malone and Stockton, have had much more aid from their auxiliary
players than the Bulls. That was evident in the third quarter, when
the Jazz went on a 11-0 run. There was Bryon Russell putting down a
3-pointer, and a limping Jeff Hornacek delivering runners.
</P>
<P>
   Just before the fourth quarter, Eisley, who was giving Stockton
a breather, sank a 3-pointer with 8 seconds left in the third to
give the Jazz a 73-70 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Every point was going to have an impact. And no one knew this as
much as Anderson. Last year, when he returned to the team for Games
5 and 6 last year, he was a bit bleary-eyed and distracted. In the
deciding Game 6, Anderson was on the floor in the closing minutes
of the close game. He was a rookie under pressure. And pressure can
make something as simple as one plus one turn into long division.
</P>
<P>
   He had an open layup. And he missed it. A few possessions later,
with the Jazz having an opportunity to take the lead, Anderson
caught a crafty pass from John Stockton in the paint. With Scottie
Pippen dashing in to block him, Anderson maneuvered around and was
in position for another layup. Another miss.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try not to make it a personal thing, but I really want to
have a good finals this year,'' Anderson said. ``You go through
hard things, and there is a lot of hurt. But then you have some
peace of mind. Last year is over. I know that now I have a second
chance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
