<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXERMOM-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOM PACKS MEAN PUNCH  
 TUCSON BOXER MIXES FAMILY, WORK, SPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The teacher called the student's home because she didn't believe
the third-grader. Lionel Salazar was telling stories about his mom.
Said Mom was a boxer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I am,'' said Lailani Salazar.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, and the teacher once knocked out Muhammad Ali.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the teacher my son wasn't lying, that I really was a
fighter,'' Salazar said. ``But nobody would believe me, so I had to
go to the school and show the kids some of my videotapes.''
</P>
<P>
   Show-and-tell proved to be a huge victory for Salazar. That's no
surprise to anybody who knows her. Effective combinations of the
unlikely are her speciality.
</P>
<P>
   Although no longer a novelty, a woman in the traditionally male
domain of professional boxing is still unusual, especially if the
woman is a mother of three with cake decoration as a trade and a
background that is equal parts Polynesian and desert-Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   Lailani Salazar of Tucson is that woman.
</P>
<P>
   She is half-Hawaiian. She was born in Tucson, where her father
was stationed with the Air Force. She sometimes works as a model.
She has appeared in at least one televised ad.
</P>
<P>
   She and her husband also run a business that specializes in
weddings. She decorates the cakes, which her opponents probably
wish she threw in their faces instead of punches. She is as precise
and disciplined in the ring as she is diverse out of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really love boxing,'' said Salazar, 24, who was scheduled to
fight Saturday night at Las Vegas. ``I enjoy the physical contact.
It's hard to explain, I guess. For me it's a stress reliever. But
it's also something I like more and more as I do it. It's like
giving a child some ice cream for the first time. One taste, and
they want more and more.''
</P>
<P>
   The 119-pound Salazar, winner of her first two pro bouts by
knockout at the Valley's Midnight Rodeo, represents the latest wave
of young women to attempt pro boxing. During the couple of years
since Christy Martin landed on the cover of`` Sports Illustrated''
after a bout on the undercard of a Mike Tyson victory, women in the
pro ring have become as regular a sight as blood and bruises.
</P>
<P>
   The circus aspect is beginning to vanish, although skepticism
re-emerged in New York a few days ago when a Martin opponent, Maria
de las Nievas-Garcia of Mexico, was disqualified because she was 21
weeks pregnant, a first in ringside medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, there are heightened expectations for proficient
skills in an often brutal pursuit. In many ways, Salazar reflects
the new businesslike approach. First and foremost, she's a fighter.
Smart girl. Punches know no gender.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing it simply because I love it,'' said Salazar, who
follows Yvonne Trevino of Peoria as the second woman from Arizona
to try pro boxing. ``A lot of women look at it as a man's sport but
that, `Hey, you can do it. Hooray for you.' But I really don't look
at it that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Salazar said there was some skepticism, if not
resistence, a couple of years ago when she decided to give-up
kick-boxing for the more traditional style, which she favors
because she says it demands more athletic skill.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, my husband (Lionel Sr.) said, `You're crazy. You
can't do that,'' said Salazar, who last year emerged as one of the
nation's best female amateurs while training in Tucson for Hank
McCadden, a former New York welterweight. ``But I told him, `Oh
yeah. Well, you watch me.' He still worries. But now he supports me
in every way because he knows how stubborn I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, she's stubborn.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father figures I can make it in boxing, and he always says
it's because of the Hawaiian in me,'' said Salazar, who started in
karate and other martial arts when she was at Sunnyside High
School. ``A lot of people always say, `Oh, you're going to ruin
your face.' Stuff like that. But my father says, `No, not if it's
really in your heart.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Salazar has a nickname, ``Kekoa.'' What does it mean?
</P>
<P>
   ``Woman warrior,'' said the Arizona-born fighter with
combinations that have convinced at least two professional
opponents and a class of third graders. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-06-98 0114EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
