r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COYOTES_TICKETS-A     06-06 0409
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES_TICKETS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COYOTES WON'T RAISE TICKET PRICES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENT SOMERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Phoenix Coyotes confirmed Friday they will not raise ticket
prices for the 1998-99 season, their third in Arizona, but that
doesn't mean the team is content with its financial situation.
</P>
<P>
   Coyotes officials said they can't make money under their current
lease at America West Arena, which runs for three more seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The team raised ticket prices an average of almost 9 percent
last season, but owner Richard Burke and team President Shawn
Hunter said it's unfair to continue to ask the fans to pay more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our most valuable asset as an organization is our fans,''
Hunter said. ``In just a very short time, Coyotes fans have
demonstrated an unequaled level of passion and enthusiasm for their
team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes are unhappy with their lease at America West Arena
and the 4,300 obstructed-view hockey seats in the facility. Because
those seats have to be sold at a discount, Burke said, the cost of
other seats is higher than it normally should be.
</P>
<P>
   The average price of a Coyotes ticket will be $36, which is less
than the 1997-98 NHL average of about $41. Ticket prices will range
from $9.50 to $200.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the Coyotes, the City of Phoenix and the arena
are studying a plan to renovate the arena. It would involve moving
the ice, knocking out a wall of the lower bowl and installing an
innovative seat design, which could be changed to accommodate
basketball and hockey.
</P>
<P>
   The design would eliminate the obstructed-view seats. If that
happens, Burke has said, it's possible the price of some of the
other hockey seats could be reduced.
</P>
<P>
   But the renovation plans are far from being approved. No one is
sure how much it would cost, although the price tag figures to be
at least $20 million. No one is sure how to pay for it, and no one
is sure how long the arena would have to be shut down during
construction.
</P>
<P>
   The renovation could take parts of at least two summers to
complete, but construction likely would interfere with the arena's
summer tenants, the Rattlers of the Arena Football League and the
Mercury of the WNBA. It also could disrupt other events, such as
concerts.
</P>
<P>
   Officials hope to settle on a renovation plan by the end of this
summer and then spend the coming months figuring out the costs and
how to pay for it. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
