<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SCHOENFELD-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDINALS WILL BENEFIT IF CHARGERS FALTER AGAIN  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nobody in the Cardinals organization will come right out and say
it, but officials are hoping the Bolts turn out to be dolts this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Each loss by the San Diego Chargers will be cheered because the
Cardinals own the Chargers' first-round draft pick for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   With a rookie quarterback (Ryan Leaf), the Chargers, 4-12 last
season, are expected to struggle and finish last again in the AFC
West. But the Chargers could be worse than imagined _ it's not
possible they could have the top pick in the draft next year, is
it? _ after trading their best offensive player of a year ago, wide
receiver Tony Martin, to Atlanta last Wednesday for a second-round
draft choice.
</P>
<P>
   Can you name the five Chargers wide receivers?
</P>
<P>
   Here's a hint: three of them weren't in the NFL last year.
</P>
<P>
   The three in question are Webster Slaughter, Tyrone Brown and
rookie Mikhael Ricks. The others are Brian Still and Charlie Jones,
who combined for one touchdown a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Take away Slaughter, who was out of football last season, and
the Chargers have a combined career total of five scoring grabs.
General Manager Bobby Beathard, who has traded away his '99 and
2000 first-round picks, acknowledges he has taken a big risk by
trading away Martin, who had 14 touchdown receptions in 1996.
(Martin didn't endear himself to Kevin Gilbride when he criticized
the rookie head coach last year).
</P>
<P>
   So now the Chargers are left with their motley receiving corps,
and until Leaf is ready to start, they could line up with Craig
Whelihan at quarterback. Super Bowl champion Denver must be scared.
Kansas City coaches, who have possibly the best defense in the NFL,
are going to stay up late worrying about how to stop the Chargers'
attack.
</P>
<P>
   But the big winners could be the Cardinals, who could have
another top-five pick, if the Chargers are as bad as they appear on
paper.
</P>
<P>
   Who would you want?
</P>
<P>
   Texas running back Ricky Williams, Ohio State linebacker Andy
Katzenmoyer or Wisconsin offensive tackle Aaron Gibson, a
380-pounder? Imagine this scenario: Quarterbacks Brock Huard of
Washington, Tim Couch of Kentucky or Daunte Culpepper of Central
Florida are available when the Cardinals/Chargers are to pick.
</P>
<P>
   Sound familiar? How about trading down for a second-round 1999
pick, a first-rounder in 2000 and two players? &QL; 
 &QL; 
Slim pickings &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The June 1 date has come and gone without much talent set free.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Vinny Testaverde, released by the Baltimore Ravens,
is the best available free agent and likely will end up in
Cincinnati or Oakland. Offensive tackle Greg Skrepenak, cut loose
by Carolina, is an intriguing prospect who could help the
Cardinals, but he has priced himself out of the market. If you like
players with heavy baggage, middle linebackers Bryan Cox and Robert
Jones are available.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are cornerbacks Larry Brown, a bust with the Raiders
after being the Most Valuable Player in Super Bowl XXX at Sun Devil
Stadium, and Donnell Woolford, whose game has slipped.
</P>
<P>
   There still could be some good players cut _ linebackers Eddie
Robinson and Terry Wooden, wide receivers Horace Copeland and
Willie Green and cornerback Terry McDaniel. But those who predicted
a bonanza of talent to become free in June were wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Teams haven't had to dump players because few are having
salary-cap problems, with the cap having gone up to $54.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals, for instance, still are $7.612 million under the
cap, but $4.3 million of that is to sign draft picks. Only one
other team, Cincinnati, at $9.345 million, has more money
available. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Nice and slow &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers won't let future Hall of Fame receiver Jerry Rice make
the same mistake.
</P>
<P>
   He tried to come back from knee surgery in 3{ months last
December but reinjured the knee and missed the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Six months later, Rice showed up at minicamp last week but was
held out of most drills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to do a little more, but Steve (Coach Steve
Mariucci) is being very cautious, and he's really driving me crazy,
too, because I believe in practicing and getting yourself ready,''
Rice said. ``I have no choice. Steve's controlling everything. If
it was left up to me, I would probably take the same approach (as
the last time).''
</P>
<P>
   He is expected to by 100 percent by the start of the regular
season in September. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Cracks in the foundation &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Maybe America has grown tired of the team from the Dairyland,
the Green Bay Packers.
</P>
<P>
   Only 5,000 fans in Jackson, Miss., bought tickets for an August
preseason game against the New Orleans Saints, so the game is being
moved to another location in the South. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Facing reality &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With Broncos quarterback John Elway returning for his 15th
season, third-year pro Jeff Lewis is accepting the possibility he
might spend the entire season on injured reserve or the first six
weeks on the physically unable to perform list.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, the Horizon High School and Northern Arizona product,
suffered a torn anterior cruciate ligament in a pickup basketball
game last February in Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos don't need him this season. They have Bubby Brister,
Doug Nussmeier and rookie Brian Griese to back up Elway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a lot of time to think about this,'' Lewis said.
``The bottom line is I want to be here this year. If it comes down
to competing for a job (in 1999), then that's fine. You'd get a
year to come back, and then I'd come back bigger, faster and
stronger.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Short shots &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone at Towson (Md.) State was pleased that Baltimore
owner Art Modell was the speaker for the school's commencement
exercises. Wrote Todd Jacobson, sports editor of the school paper:
``Are jealousy and greed the characteristics Towson has tried to
instill in its graduates? No, but their last act at Towson will be
hearing a man with no conscience lecture them on what it is like to
be in the real world.''
</P>
<P>
   When the bumbling Ravens cut Testaverde, they sent him a letter
they incorrectly dated May 5, 1997. He received the letter on May
31, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Morris Bradshaw, Raiders director of marketing, is tired of the
bad publicity the team gets because of gangs wearing the team's
gear. ``I get really sick of turning on ``America's Most Wanted''
or ``Cops'' and seeing someone wearing our stuff being busted.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Steve Schoenfeld can be reached at steve.schoenfeld(at)pni.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
