<HEADER>
A7220 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYC-FIRE-500&AMP;ADD-NYT &LR;      06-06 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYC-FIRE-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIREFIGHTER IS KILLED BATTLING BLAZE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CHARLIE LeDUFF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One firefighter was killed, another critically
injured and at least four others hurt Friday night in a five-alarm
fire that consumed a city-owned apartment building in Brooklyn, the
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The fire began at 8:20 p.m. in the back of the wood-frame
structure at 2530 Atlantic Ave. at the corner of Hinsdale Street in
the East New York section, fire officials said Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said they could not yet determine the cause of the
fire, but residents said that workers had been at the house earlier
in the day to repair a gas boiler. While it was unclear Friday
night whether the work was linked to the fire, residents said the
fire started in the basement.
</P>
<P>
   None of the firefighters' names were released Friday night, as
family members and city officials, including Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani, gathered at the three hospitals where the firefighters
were being treated.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Brian Dixon said early Friday that a firefighter who had
been taken to Brookdale Hospital in Brooklyn had died.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters on the scene reported immense flames leaping out
the windows of the three-story building.
</P>
<P>
   The first crew entered with hose and nozzle when firefighters
outside witnessed a flash. They were uncertain whether it was a gas
explosion, a ceiling collapse that spewed embers or some other
calamity.
</P>
<P>
   Within seconds, firefighters were dragging out injured men, some
with severe burns, others with lungs laced with smoke and still
others with head and neck damage.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Richard Pagona of the Fire Department said that four other
attached buildings had been damaged by the fire and that the
ceiling and top floors had collapsed in the building where the
firefighters were injured.
</P>
<P>
   The blaze quickly leapt to the neighboring wood-frame row
houses, and within minutes, 225 firefighters using 52 ladder
trucks, engines and ambulances were battling the flames from the
exterior.
</P>
<P>
   The flames were extinguished by 10:45 p.m., fire officials said.
But not before they exacted a high toll.
</P>
<P>
   The six firefighters were injured inside the building while
fighting the blaze. Besides Brookdale Hospital, the injured were
taken to New York Hospital-Cornell Medical Center in Manhattan and
Jacobi Medical Center in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   At Cornell, one firefighter was in critical condition with burns
to his face, hands and legs; another was listed in stable condition
with burns to his face, a spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   Another firefighter, also in critical condition, was taken to
Jacobi to be put in a hyperbaric chamber, which is used to treat
victims of severe smoke inhalation.
</P>
<P>
   At Cornell Medical Center Friday night, officials said the
firefighters' bunker gear, heavy protective suits designed to
shield firefighters from flame and severe heat, had remained
intact.
</P>
<P>
   But they said that the heat may have been so intense that
firefighters were burned by their own perspiration, boiling inside
the suits.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Of the other firefighters at Brookdale Hospital, said Ruth L.
Richman, a spokeswoman for the hospital, one man suffered head and
neck injuries when a ceiling partially collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   He was in stable condition, Ms. Richman said, but he could not
be moved because of the nature of spinal injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The building, two blocks south of the sprawling Cemetery of the
Evergreens, is city-owned, said Lizzy Pearl Warren, who has lived
there for 27 years.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Warren lives on the third floor with her adult children, and
her daughter Casandra lives on the second floor with two young
sons. The first floor is a vacant restaurant space.
</P>
<P>
   Evelyn Hester, 31, a friend of the family who lives nearby, said
that the city had recently renovated the house, installing new
stairs, doors, windows and walls.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the boiler had been acting up. ``The gas company
was here all day,'' Ms. Hester said. ``They left and the building
caught on fire.''
</P>
<P>
   That is when the injuries occurred, the firefighters said,
asking that their names not be used.
</P>
<P>
   There were no fire doors, and the walls did not appear to retard
the fire, firefighters said. They questioned whether the city-owned
building was up to fire code.
</P>
<P>
   The family members escaped unharmed, and as investigators picked
through the rubble Friday night, orange embers could still be seen
burning along the roof line and the smell of charcoal hung in the
air.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Warren was asleep when the fire broke out, but by the
time firefighters from Engine Company 233 and Ladder 103 arrived on
the scene just minutes later, the wood-fed flames were roaring out
of the windows and the heat warped the air like a fun-house mirror,
witnesses reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother called me out,'' Warren said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, another nine firefighters suffered minor
injuries in a blaze at a waste transfer station at 123 Varick St.
</P>
<P>
   The flames were noticed at 6:15 p.m., Cillo said. The
firefighters were taken to Brookdale Hospital with minor injuries.
The fire was pronounced under control but was still being
extinguished late Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Raymond Nakovics, 49, a firefighter for 27 years, died
after having a heart attack at the scene of a fire at a Manhattan
apartment house.
</P>
<P>
   In February 1996, Louis Valentino, 37, was killed when the roof
of an auto body shop in Brooklyn collapsed on him as he searched
for people inside the building.
</P>
<P>
   His death was the third in a six-week period in 1996. The
unusual string of on-duty deaths in the Fire Department began when
a firefighter fell through the floor of an abandoned house in
Queens that the police said was being used by squatters and drug
addicts.
</P>
<P>
   A week later, another firefighter died in an apartment fire,
also in Queens.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
