<P>
   RUSSIA-SOLZHENITSYN (Moscow) _ By the time the first copies of
Alexander Solzhenitsyn's latest book landed at a Moscow bookstore
on Thursday, its arrival had been heralded far and wide. But for
all the advance publicity, the publication of ``Russia in
Collapse'' begs a question that has dogged its 79-year-old author
since his return from exile four years ago: Who in Russia today is
prepared to read what Solzhenitsyn has to say? By Celestine Bohlen.
(With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS DAY
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `f' category)
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ The economy added more jobs than
expected in May, and the unemployment rate was unchanged at a
28-year low of 4.3 percent. Payrolls expanded by 296,000 people
last month, exceeding forecasts of a gain of about 220,000. April's
employment gain was revised upward to 302,000 from the initial
estimate of 262,000. By Sylvia Nasar. (With graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ The stock market roared back to life Friday
after the government said that economic growth remains robust. By
David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   GOLDMAN-WORTH (New York) _ Goldman, Sachs has taken many
companies to market, putting its imprimatur on the value of
thousands of public offerings of shares. So what value would it put
on itself? The answer, as might be expected with a franchise as
envied as Goldman, is not clear-cut, and estimates range from as
low as $15 billion to as high as $35 billion. By Peter Truell.
(With graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-FCC (Washington) _ The FCC is considering whether to
halt the collection of money from telecommunications companies to
finance the wiring of schools and libraries to the Internet. By
Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-U.S. _ The Clinton administration renounced the last
vestige of control by the U.S. government over the Internet's basic
structure on Friday, acknowledging that the computer network had
grown too big, too global and too commercial to be overseen by any
one nation. By Amy Harmon.
