<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS SHUT OUT IN SEATTLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Dodgers talked to the Seattle Mariners all week,
but when it finally came time to meet, they never showed.
</P>
<P>
   Their 4-0 loss to the Mariners in front of 39,053 on Friday
night at the Kingdome was less about their failed attempt to
acquire left-hander Randy Johnson than it was a miserable showing
after one of their most inspired victories of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Against Billy Swift and particularly reliever Mike Timlin, the
Dodgers got just two batters to third base. On Thursday, they left
home after coming from behind to defeat St. Louis and thought all
the distractions were over.
</P>
<P>
   Now, they can only hope it doesn't happen today when the two
teams play again in front of a national TV audience.
</P>
<P>
   This is supposed to be one of the marquee interleague matchups
in baseball. Instead, the Mariners raised their record to 3-0
against the Dodgers at home.
</P>
<P>
   A big reason was the Mariners' bullpen, which like the Dodgers,
is the club's weak spot. But after Timlin took over for Swit (5-3)
with one in the seventh, he worked out of a bases-loaded situation
then retired the Dodgers in order in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Heathcliff Slocumb pitched a perfect ninth as the Dodgers fell
to 29-31, 7{ games behind San Diego and now San Francisco, which
moved into a tie for first place.
</P>
<P>
   Swift breezed through the first six innings, but allowed a
single to Jim Eisenreich to open the seventh. Charles Johnson
followed with a base hit to left, putting runners at first and
second. After left-fielder Thomas Howard struck out, Eric Young
singled to center, but Eisenreich was held at third.
</P>
<P>
   In came Timlin, who had blown four of five save opportunities
and retired just 16 of the 28 first batters he has faced. This was
the guy who the Mariners got for top prospect Jose Cruz, Jr. last
season and there were quite a few boos when he entered the game.
</P>
<P>
   But he struck out Jose Vizcaino then retired Gary Sheffield on a
grounder to third to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield, who had a single and a double, was ahead in the count
3-1 and thought he had a walk on a Timlin breaking ball up. As
Sheffield walked to first, home plate umpire Marty Foster called
the pitch a strike.
</P>
<P>
   Two pitches later, the Mariners were out of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers starter Ismael Valdes (4-7) lost, but didn't have much
support. The middle of the order, Eric Karros, Raul Mondesi and
Bobby Bonilla were a combined 0 for 11.
</P>
<P>
   Karros, who moved from first base to designated hitter in the
American League park, had a chance to give the Dodgers an early
lead when he came up with runners and first and third and one out
in the first.
</P>
<P>
   Karros had six RBI in his previous two games, but he popped out
to second, setting the tone for the rest of the night. His
nine-game hitting streak ended.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes, who lost here 8-2 last June to Sunday's starter Jamie
Moyer, went 71/3 innings, allowing nine hits and three earned runs,
three walks and four strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers came into the Kingdome after a zany week of trades,
non trades, and general mayhem.
</P>
<P>
   They thought a chance to get out of town would help, especially
after scoring all three of their runs against St. Louis with two
outs.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, going on the road was probably the best thing right
now,'' manager Bill Russell said. ``We had a good win on Thursday
and we're confident that it will continue.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't start that way on this night as the Dodgers fell
behind 2-0 in the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   David Segui opened by reaching on a fielding error by Bobby
Bonilla at third and later scored on a single to left by Glenallen
Hill. Rob Ducey, who reached on a fielder's choice, scored on a
base hit by catcher Dan Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes settled down until the fifth when Joey Cora opened with a
triple and later scored on a single by Ken Griffey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes quickly got in trouble in the sixth when Ducey opened
with a double to the gap in right-center and moved to third on
Hill's fly ball to right.
</P>
<P>
   With Ducey breaking for home on the pitch, Wilson squeezed a
bunt in the air toward the third base line. Valdes dove for the
ball but dropped it as Ducey scored.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
