<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: FIREFIGHTERS' BRAWL
</HEADLINE>
 (EDS: Changes number in graf 3 and wording in graf 4)  
 (js)  
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Saturday, June 6:
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago New York City police officers attending a
convention in Washington brought shame on their city when they
trashed their hotels, harassed other guests and cavorted, drunk and
naked, in public. Now New York firefighters have replicated this
behavior at home, staging a rampage at a restaurant in midtown
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The outrageous behavior occurred on Wednesday night at the
Bryant Park Grill behind the New York Public Library. The day had
begun as a celebration of heroism in which Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
praised the firefighters as ``greater heroes than the Yankees'' and
cited two officers for valor in the line of duty.
</P>
<P>
   Between 50 and 100 firefighters ended up afterward at the Bryant
Park restaurant, where many of them drank heavily for hours, their
moods growing uglier as the evening advanced. The firemen urinated
publicly, exposed themselves, ran through a women's restroom and
bloodied each other in violent fights. Patrons ran for cover, and
the restaurant's managers stood by terrified, fearful of being
harmed if they intervened.
</P>
<P>
   The firefighters were in uniform, leaving no question about
their identity. But althought there were several witnesses to this
behavior, the only person immediately arrested was the restaurant's
bouncer.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation into the police officers' brawl in Washington
was slow off the mark and took almost a year to run its course.
Giuliani and Fire Commissioner Thomas Von Essen will need to do
better than that to quell public outrage. The firefighters who
participated in this latest brawl need to learn swiftly that
drunken hooliganism is a career-ending offense.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
