<HEADER>
A7229 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN--FINALS-HNS &LR;      06-06 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN--FINALS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Jordan &AMP; Co. ratchet up heat 
as Jazz goes cold in 4th period
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By EDDIE SEFKO &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SALT LAKE CITY _ The mystique. The magic. The Michael. They were
all back in force for the Chicago Bulls on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Swatting away speculation they have lost their reputation as
crunch-time kings, the Bulls leveled the NBA Finals at a win apiece
as Michael Jordan scored 37 points to anchor a 93-88 victory over
the Utah Jazz at the Delta Center.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan converted a go-ahead three-point play with 47.9 seconds
left, saving the Bulls from falling into a 2-0 hole, something they
never have faced in a Finals series.
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz, which went seven minutes at the start of the fourth
quarter without a basket, shot just 4-for-15 in the final period,
had seven turnovers and surrendered six crucial offensive rebounds
to the Bulls, which they turned into eight key points.
</P>
<P>
   None was bigger than Steve Kerr's retrieval of his missed
3-pointer with 49 seconds left, his first rebound of the series.
Kerr then quickly shoveled the ball to Jordan, who scored from
point-blank range and was fouled by John Stockton.
</P>
<P>
   The free throw put Chicago up 88-86, and after Karl Malone
missed from 20 feet, Kerr hit two free throws with 14.5 seconds
left to clinch it.
</P>
<P>
   With the win, the Bulls served notice their dynasty, while
wobbling, is far from crumbling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always felt that way,'' Jordan said. ``People talk about
our age or whatever, but we're here. I've always believed in what
we can accomplish. You don't become champs five times without
having some type of mental advantage. We certainly are mentally
strong to defend what we have.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz knew it could put itself in a commanding position with
a win. But Utah allowed the Bulls to grab control of the game
early, and its fourth-quarter problems doomed the Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we got outhustled,'' said Utah's Jeff Hornacek, who
had a team-high 20 points. ``They're still the champs until
somebody beats them. We knew they'd come out not wanting to go down
2-0. We didn't respond to that challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls' trademark moxie had been questioned after their loss
in Game 1, but they came back with a vengeance, making all the
crucial plays down the stretch, particularly on defense and in the
rebounding department.
</P>
<P>
   Utah was awful in the first seven minutes of the fourth quarter.
The Jazz scored just one point on its first nine possessions of the
period.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, it had trouble getting the ball. Chicago grabbed four
offensive rebounds in the first nine minutes of the fourth and
turned those extra possessions into six crucial points.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Rodman, who did a superb job of battling Malone all
night, got a pair of offensive boards, and Toni Kukoc got two.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls weren't exactly lighting up the scoreboard, but they
did outscore the Jazz 11-1 to go up 81-74 with 5:10 to play. Utah
finally got its first basket of the quarter when Bryon Russell
canned a 3-pointer with five minutes left.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago kept the lead at four or six points until Jordan
uncharacteristically missed consecutive shots as he tried to work
his magic. After he missed a fadeaway, the ensuing fast break led
to two free throws by Shandon Anderson, which cut the lead to
85-83.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan then missed a post-up from 12 feet, and the Jazz took the
lead with Hornacek's 3-pointer with 1:46 left.
</P>
<P>
   By then, the crowd was at an eardrum-breaking level.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls opened the door further when Kukoc and Scottie Pippen
missed, but Stockton threw away the ball with just more than a
minute left.
</P>
<P>
   That set up the heroics by Jordan and Kerr, who combined to
score Chicago's final eight points.
</P>
<P>
   After Jordan's three-point play, Utah couldn't get a good shot
and Malone had to fling up a 20-foot prayer that had no chance of
going in. Rodman rebounded and called time out with 23.4 seconds
left. Kerr's free throws clinched it with 14.5 ticks to go.
</P>
<P>
   Utah knew this would not be a repeat of Game 1, when it got away
with some crummy basketball and still managed to go up 1-0 in the
series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know,'' Stockton said after that game, ``that we're going
to have to play a whole lot better to beat this team in Game 2.''
</P>
<P>
   Stockton couldn't have known how right he would be.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls came out with a tenacity on their offensive end that
made them look like a different team than the one that shot 41.5
percent in Game 1, including 3-for-16 (18.8 percent) from 3-point
range.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen was getting into the paint whenever he wanted, and Jordan
was his usual self.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bulls were better because of people such as Kukoc and
Luc Longley, who had lively stretches, particularly during the
first half. A pair of Longley baskets sandwiched around a 3-pointer
by Scott Burrell put Chicago in front 36-30.
</P>
<P>
   On Utah's end, things were out of sync. Chris Morris missed an
uncontested layup after Antoine Carr made perhaps the best pass he
can make, over the shoulder to the cutting Morris.
</P>
<P>
   Plays like that tend to haunt a team. And the Jazz stammered
along throughout the first half, which ended with Chicago up 50-46.
</P>
<P>
   If not for some spirited play by Greg Ostertag, who had seven
points and three rebounds in just six second-quarter minutes, the
Jazz might have been worse off than it was.
</P>
<P>
   To that point, the Delta Center crowd was sitting on its hands,
fearing _ expecting, perhaps _ a letdown by the Jazz after the Game
1 win.
</P>
<P>
   When Jordan slammed with 6:30 left in the third quarter, Utah
was in a 61-53 hole, the Bulls' biggest lead of the game. Utah
looked to be cooked.
</P>
<P>
   But things changed. In a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   Longley had picked up his fourth and fifth fouls early in the
third period, and, though it took awhile, the Jazz took advantage,
starting with a pair of Malone free throws with 5:42 left in the
third after Rodman fouled him.
</P>
<P>
   It was the start of an 11-0 blitz by the Jazz. After Malone's
free throws, Russell knocked in a wide-open 3-pointer from the
right corner. Suddenly, the crowd came alive.
</P>
<P>
   After Stockton stripped Kerr, Hornacek buried a trey in
transition. The Bulls were busy missing three shots and committing
two turnovers, which was enough of an opening to put Utah up 64-61
with less than four minutes left in the third frame.
</P>
<P>
   Hornacek had his best quarter in at least two playoff series,
hitting four of five shots in the third for 10 points. And Howard
Eisley saw to it the Jazz finished off the period strong. He scored
the Jazz's last seven points, including a 3-pointer with 8.9
showing on the clock that sent Utah into the fourth quarter up
73-70. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-06-98 0148EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
