<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-06 02:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7230 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-HNS &LR;      06-06 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Kerr's late heroics provide 
atonement for Game 1 sins
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By FRAN BLINEBURY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SALT LAKE CITY _ For the better part of two days, Steve Kerr had
gotten more air time than the cast of Seinfeld. He showed up in
every replay of John Stockton's triumphant runner at the end of
Game 1. He had the very best view in the house.
</P>
<P>
   Kerr was the poor sap with the desperately flailing arms up in
the air and the hopeless look painted all over his face.
</P>
<P>
   So, of course, as the clock again ticked down inside the final
minute Friday night, the game _ and maybe the balance of the NBA
Finals _ wound up once more staring Kerr in the eyes.
</P>
<P>
   This is how it is in sports. At the most hurtful times, the
spotlight will always manage to find you.
</P>
<P>
   But things change in the space of a heartbeat.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 2, Kerr was the defibrillator who brought the Bulls back
to life. He didn't score a field goal in the fourth quarter. He
merely saved the game.
</P>
<P>
   First, Kerr climbed right back on the horse who was Stockton,
practically getting inside his skin as Utah tried to protect a
one-point lead in the final minute. He got nose-to-nose,
chin-to-chin on defense and eventually forced an uncharacteristic
turnover from Stockton as Toni Kukoc picked off a pass.
</P>
<P>
   Kerr then raced across midcourt and received the ball. He
fearlessly pulled up on the fast break and fired up a 3-pointer. It
missed. But then, Kerr did what every kid who ever played the game
is always told to do by every coach from the first time he walks
onto the floor. He followed his own shot.
</P>
<P>
   Kerr grabbed the offensive rebound _ his only rebound of these
first two games _ and then slipped a pass inside to Michael Jordan
for a layup and a three-point play with 48 seconds to go that put
the Bulls in front for good.
</P>
<P>
   It was instant atonement. A turnaround that hit with the
swiftness of a lightning bolt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve Kerr's play killed us,'' Utah's Jeff Hornacek said.
``Just killed us.''
</P>
<P>
   And so what could have been a difficult uphill battle for the
Bulls going back to Chicago turned into a 93-88 Bulls victory and a
1-1 split in the series.
</P>
<P>
   That's how it so often turns out for playoff teams that have to
face the Bulls. They spend so much time and so much effort and so
much energy trying to throw a rope around Jordan and Scottie Pippen
that one of the other guys slips through the cracks to make the big
play.
</P>
<P>
   Kerr did it a year ago in the Bulls' title-clinching Game 6
victory over the Jazz, stepping outside to hit the winning basket
on a pass from Jordan. Way back in 1991, at the beginning of the
Chicago championship run, John Paxson hit the big jumpers that
wrapped up the Bulls' first title over the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have faith in Steve Kerr,'' Jordan said. ``We have faith in
all of the guys that we put out there on the floor. You have to
deal with all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan finished with 37 points, but it took him 33 shots to get
there. Pippen finished with 21 points but was quiet for most of the
second half.
</P>
<P>
   On a night when the Jazz let the home-court advantage slip away,
it was Kerr and another supporting cast member by the name of
Dennis Rodman who turned the whole thing around for the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   While Kerr's Game 1 nightmare was being replayed on TVs all
around Salt Lake City, Rodman was drawing attention and criticism
for his late-night jaunt to Las Vegas after the loss. His
Weirdness' escapades at the Hard Rock Hotel Casino, where he played
with $1,000 chips into the wee hours, were detailed. Here were the
Finals, and here was Rodman being a distraction again.
</P>
<P>
   That is, until the second half, when he grabbed all of his nine
rebounds, tossed in a key jumper from the top of the key and tied
up Karl Malone in knots with his active defense. The Mailman spent
another night in the dead-letter office, shooting only 5-for-16
from the field. Malone has shot 14-for-41 and scored a total of 37
points in two games, and now the Jazz goes to Chicago with the
situation turned around.
</P>
<P>
   Kerr knows all about that. He had to deal with the images left
over from Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, John Stockton is one of the greatest point guards ever to
play the game,'' he said. ``I didn't lose any sleep over that play.
I made him take a tough shot, and he made it. I went home and slept
fine. And I'll sleep fine again tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``On that 3-point shot, I knew Karl Malone was in front of me
and that he didn't really want to come out that far and guard me.
Taking 3s is my main job, so I took the shot. It felt good. I
thought it was in. But when it didn't, I went to the boards and
grabbed the rebound. As soon as I got it, I saw Michael underneath.
Actually, it was a very easy play. It felt good.''
</P>
<P>
   Atonement usually does.
</P>
<P>
   Listen to Fran Blinebury on the Chronicle's Sports Page radio
show on KPRC (950 AM) from 5-7 p.m. weekdays.
</P>
</TEXT>
