A7251 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-COLUMN-THIEL-SPI &LR;      06-06 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-COLUMN-THIEL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BULLS YANK UTAH BACK TO EARTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ After beating the Los Angeles Lakers four
straight games, then opening the NBA Finals with a win over the
Chicago Bulls _ making for a 3-0 record this season against the
champs _ the Utah Jazz were flying at sufficient altitude to be
offered headsets to watch the movie.
</P>
<P>
   But after one brief moment of turbulence Friday night, the Jazz
and their fans are pinned to the ceiling, screaming.
</P>
<P>
   This is how it works in the NBA playoffs. Please stay buckled
up. You never know.
</P>
<P>
   From a fourth quarter in which they missed 11 of 15 shots and
committed seven turnovers, the Jazz not only lost Game 2, 93-88,
but all the supposed advantages that created the best chance in
years for a Western foe to finally topple the Bulls' empire.
</P>
<P>
   The series goes back to Chicago 1-1 with an opportunity for the
reinvigorated Bulls, despite all of their fatigue, controversies,
suspicions, age and hair colors, to do in the Jazz without a return
to the Delta Center earache salon.
</P>
<P>
   While that might not be possible, the odds do go in the Bulls'
favor if the Jazz cannot convince their star, Karl Malone, to
remove his ballerina outfit and slap on the tool belt and hard hat.
</P>
<P>
   Malone had a second straight game of uncharacteristic delicacy,
missing 11 of 16 shots, nearly all of the errant tosses from
outside. He missed all four field-goal attempts in the mess the
Jazz made of the fourth quarter, never once taking his mammoth self
hard to the hole where he would draw fouls and create mayhem.
</P>
<P>
   After a mediocre first game, Malone continues to squander the
Jazz's great opportunity. He is the first to admit it, more manful
in his post-game discourse than he was against the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any excuses,'' he said after a 16-point night
that was a dozen below his average. ``There's a lot of things I
could have done. I take responsibility for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's on these shoulders, and when I don't do it, I face the
firing squad, which is you guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it isn't merely reporters lining up with shots. If
Malone continues his timidity, it will evoke images of his mediocre
Finals of a year ago, as well as his shortcomings against the
Sonics in the 1996 Western finals.
</P>
<P>
   The mail simply isn't getting delivered in June, which would be
a wretched legacy for an otherwise remarkable career.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Utah can win with Malone playing this way, Malone owned
up: ``No. Point-blank, no. We will not win this series if I don't
play better.''
</P>
<P>
   This sort of certitude would be even more impressive if it came
while he was in shorts instead of street clothes.
</P>
<P>
   There was more at work Friday night than Malone's shortcomings,
principally a tepid first quarter for Utah that restored the Bulls'
resolve after four consecutive road losses in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game was decided in the first part,'' said Utah coach
Jerry Sloan. ``When (Toni) Kukoc drove around us and went to the
basket, that tells you we weren't ready to compete. I don't like
losing, but I hate to see guys not competing. We came out very
soft, and they were the aggressors.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere was that contrast more evident than the fourth-quarter
disposition of the club's stars. While Malone, burdened with fouls,
was passive, Michael Jordan demanded the ball and slashed to the
basket, sometimes recklessly but always knowing he would create
something.
</P>
<P>
   He scored seven consecutive points for an 83-77 Chicago lead
with four minutes remaining. Even though he forced up bricks on two
straight possessions that allowed the Jazz to take a temporary
lead, his continued pressure forced the Jazz to make all sorts of
compensations. Meanwhile, the Bulls could leave Dennis Rodman alone
on Malone, without repercussions because the big guy was content
with jump shots that have deserted him this week.
</P>
<P>
   The decisive moment came just inside one minute, when
fast-breaking Bulls reserve guard Steve Kerr missed a pull-up trey
over Malone, then scooted around him for the rebound, which he
dished to Jordan for a lay-in and free throw that made for an 88-86
lead that was good to go to Chi-town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had Karl in front of me, and I didn't think he wanted to
come out to me,'' said Kerr, admittedly surprised to find himself
in the game's pivot point. ``The rebound happened to bounce my way.
I don't think Karl expected me there.''
</P>
<P>
   Many things were unexpected in that fourth quarter, mostly
because the Jazz had won 60 consecutive games in which they led
entering the final period. They showed in Game 1 they have
sufficient moxie to match the Bulls clutch for clutch. But they
went the first seven minutes without a field goal, a profound
drought against a club as resourceful as the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   Malone's semi-stupor was partly attributable to Rodman, who
shook off his own Vegas-induced daze in the first half to come up
with nine boards in the second half as well as push Malone to the
perimeter and the Jazz to their discomfort zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I'm content with the perimeter,'' said Malone.
``All year I make those jump shots. (Missing them) comes at a
(expletive) time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could make a lot of excuses, but I can't. I didn't
play well the first two games. We got away with the first one,
tonight we didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere in the salt flats there sits a big pile of mail,
undelivered.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
