<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-06 02:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7252 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      06-06 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS' VALDES PROVES SKID-STOPPER FOR MARINERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Never mind.
</P>
<P>
   For a few brief hours on Tuesday, Ismael Valdes was a Mariner in
somebody's fantasy league. Friday night, he was an unwelcome
Kingdome guest, shoved out the door with a 4-0 defeat.
</P>
<P>
   He got the Seattle club turned around, and didn't have to switch
uniforms. He simply served up run-scoring hits to Glenallen Hill
and Dan Wilson (twice) and came in second-best on the mound to
Billy Swift.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome helped ease the strain for the Mariners, ending
their four-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of our better games of the year, if not the
best,'' Mariner manager Lou Piniella concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes, allegedly the focal part of a Dodger trade package for
Randy Johnson that was widely splashed across the Internet but left
on the table, probably doesn't know what to believe anymore. He
didn't relocate to the Pacific Northwest. And Friday, there was a
rare Mariner bullpen sighting.
</P>
<P>
   Protecting Swift's handiwork, Mike Timlin pulled his team out of
a one-out, bases-loaded jam in the seventh with nary a drop of
blood spilled. Timlin also pitched a 1-2-3 eighth. Heathcliff
Slocumb, a surprise closer, went three-up and three-down in the
ninth. No giveaways on this night for the crowd of 39,053.
</P>
<P>
   Slocumb replaces Bobby Ayala, assuming a post he hasn't held for
two months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him after the way he threw the ball in the Baltimore
series, we were going to use him in that role,'' Piniella said.
``He's had three or four real nice appearances.''
</P>
<P>
   Piniella also made a bullpen move after the game, sending rookie
Steve Gajkowski back to Class AAA Tacoma and recalling outfielder
Charles Gipson. That leaves the Mariners with an 11-man pitching
staff.
</P>
<P>
   The manager has had few worries lately with the tail end of his
rotation. In 61/3 innings, Swift (5-3) spaced nine hits, walked one
and did just enough to keep the Dodgers off balance.
</P>
<P>
   Tied with Johnson and Jeff Fassero for the team lead in wins,
the 36-year-old right-hander was his usual annoying self, using his
trademark sinker. He retired Los Angeles on three popups in the
first, three grounders in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can stay healthy, I can do the job,'' Swift said. ``I'm
in a good groove right now.''
</P>
<P>
   His approach apparently is catching.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told myself to throw the ball like Billy was doing, with the
sinker and slider,'' Timlin said. ``It was working. If I can throw
the ball like him, I might make some money.''
</P>
<P>
   Swift was backed by superlative defense, something missing for
the Mariners in recent weeks. Rob Ducey made a lunging third-inning
grab in right. In the same inning, first baseman David Segui
started and finished a slick double play, flagging down a
bullet-like grounder. Alex Rodriguez leaped high to stab a liner at
short in the fifth. And Joey Cora made a sliding stop on a grounder
to second to end the sixth inning, leaving runners at first and
third.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes had no such luck, or support. Certainly not the comfort
zone he would have preferred.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a very weird week,'' said the right-hander, a
24-year-old from Mexico. ``There's always going to be rumors, but
you're never going to believe it until it happens. It takes away
from your concentration.''
</P>
<P>
   Valdes (4-7) got stung in the second inning for two runs. Bobby
Bonilla's lack of concentration, not the pitcher's, was
responsible. The Dodger third baseman booted a ball by Segui to
open the inning. After a walk and fielder's choice, Hill singled
home the only run the Mariners would need and Wilson plated
another.
</P>
<P>
   A triple by Cora and a Rodriguez groundout made it 3-0 in the
fifth, and Wilson's squeeze bunt accounted for the final run in the
sixth. The Mariner catcher dinked a popup near the third-base line
that a diving Valdes got a glove on but couldn't hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I got the sign, I realized it was a good situation right
then,'' Wilson said. ``I don't think they expected it.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Valdes: ``I almost got it. I did my best effort. I thought
I had it for a moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Piniella marveled at the pitcher's athleticism and almost
sounded as if he wished he'd snapped up Valdes in a trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to get involved in that, but Valdes threw the
ball well,'' Piniella said. ``He spotted his fastball and he had a
pretty good breaking ball.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodger pitcher was lifted in the eighth, completing a
126-pitch outing and a strange 72-hour journey.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
