<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS, BONILLA STRUGGLE IN SEATTLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Without Randy Johnson or Hideo Nomo to worry about,
the Dodgers have shifted their concern to Bobby Bonilla.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't the only problem in Friday's 4-0 loss to the Seattle
Mariners, just the most glaring. Since joining the team three weeks
ago today, Bonilla has provided leadership into the clubhouse, but
not big hits in the Dodgers' long search to right their season.
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla was expected to give the Dodgers a left-handed power
hitter in a lineup top heavy with right-handers but has just one
extra-base hit in his last 11 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby just isn't swinging the bat with authority,'' said
Dodgers manager Bill Russell, who will rest Bonilla in today's
game. ``He just isn't himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla said after going 0 for 4 against Billy Swift and two
relievers that he has been battling the flu for more than a week.
But his problems go back much further.
</P>
<P>
   Since joining the Dodgers in the May 15 blockbuster trade with
Florida, Bonilla is batting .204 (15 for 73). He had game-winning
hits in his first three games at Dodger Stadium, but does not have
a home run since May 16.
</P>
<P>
   Hitting instructor Reggie Smith said Bonilla's problems stem
from wrist and Achilles injuries that forced him to miss most of
spring training and early April.
</P>
<P>
   At age 35, Bonilla has a daily ritual of lengthy ice treatment
and rehabilitation. The wrist still is tender from offseason
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   To his credit, Bonilla has started all but one game at third
base. But with the Dodgers facing left-handers the next two days,
the switch-hitting Bonilla could be sitting for the rest of the
series.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you miss spring training they way he did, this becomes
your spring training,'' Smith said. ``His timing is off and he
doesn't have the bat speed he usually does. I think he'll be okay,
but he's been through a lot already this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Eric Young and Gary Sheffield had two hits apiece
Friday, the heart of the Dodgers order _ Eric Karros, Raul Mondesi
and Bonilla _ were a combined 0 for 11.
</P>
<P>
   Karros, who moved from first base to designated hitter in the
American League park, has moved into the cleanup spot during
Bonilla's slump.
</P>
<P>
   With Friday's game still close in the sixth inning, Bonilla had
a chance to get something going with runners at first and third
with two outs. He appeared to have a base hit between first and
second, but Joey Cora made a diving stop and threw out the
slow-footed Bonilla to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will come around,'' Bonilla said. ``I'm not going to get
down.''
</P>
<P>
   If not for Bonilla, the attention might have shifted to starter
Ismael Valdes, who was offered to Seattle for Johnson earlier this
week. He allowed three earned runs in 71/3 innings, but made bad
pitches in the second when the Mariners scored twice.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes (4-7) wasn't helped when Bonilla started the second by
making an error. But the Mariners' seventh and eighth hitter,
Glenallen Hill and Dan Wilson, had RBI singles and Valdes then
walked the next two hitters.
</P>
<P>
   All of that could have been overcome with a little timely
hitting. Against Swift and particularly relievers Mike Timlin and
Heathcliff Slocumb, the Dodgers got just two runners to third base.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the shutdown was the Mariners bullpen, which is
the club's weak spot. But Timlin took over for Swift (5-3) with one
in the seventh, worked out of a bases-loaded situation then retired
the Dodgers in order in the eighth. Slocumb pitched a perfect
ninth.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers fell to 29-31, 7{ games behind San Diego and San
Francisco, which moved into a tie for first place Friday with a
victory over St. Louis.
</P>
</TEXT>
