</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-A'S-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATE-INNING MAGIC DOES TRICK FOR A'S 
BY RON KROICHICK
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND _ Kenny Rogers deserved the starring role. He christened
the interleague portion of the A's schedule Friday night,
introducing the Arizona Diamondbacks to his hypnotizing array of
pitches.
</P>
<P>
   And for his effort, Rogers got a hearty pat on the back.
</P>
<P>
   The A's won the game long after Rogers departed. Mike Blowers
knocked home the winning run in Oakland's 2-1 victory at the
Coliseum, with a bases-loaded single in the bottom of the 11th
inning.
</P>
<P>
   The starting pitchers, Rogers and Bob Wolcott of Arizona,
slapped two tidy rows of zeroes on the scoreboard. They each
pitched eight shutout innings, then turned over the game to the
bullpens.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers collected his fourth consecutive no-decision. He's 6-2
with a 3.43 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kenny should be closing in on 10 wins, the way he's been
pitching,'' A's manager Art Howe said.
</P>
<P>
   The A's had help in putting together their decisive rally. Scott
Spiezio led off the 11th with a walk _ after Diamondbacks catcher
Damian Miller dropped Spiezio's foul popup for an error.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Grieve followed with a rocket-like single to left-center off
Russ Springer, moving Spiezio to third. Springer intentionally
walked Matt Stairs, loading the bases for Blowers.
</P>
<P>
   He promptly launched an 0-2 pitch over left fielder David
Dellucci's head to end the game. Dellucci was drawn in on the play,
as was the rest of Arizona's defense.
</P>
<P>
   Blowers is making a strong case to remain the starting third
baseman, even when Dave Magadan (sprained hand) returns from the
disabled list. Blowers is hitting .279 and ranks third on the A's
with 33 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever since he's gotten the opportunity, Mike's made the most
of it,'' Howe said. ``He's had a lot of big hits for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Fetters replaced Rogers in the ninth; Rogers had thrown 121
pitches and his back was stiff. Fetters relinquished a two-out
infield single to Matt Williams, when the ball glanced off Blowers'
outstretched glove.
</P>
<P>
   Travis Lee followed with a single to left field, sending
Williams to second. He scored on Jay Bell's single, putting the
Diamondbacks ahead 1-0.
</P>
<P>
   The A's tied the score in their half of the ninth, against
Arizona closer Gregg Olson. Rickey Henderson walked _ he's Rickey,
after all _ and moved to second on Spiezio's sacrifice bunt.
</P>
<P>
   Olson walked Grieve on a 3-2 pitch, putting the winning run on
base. Stairs then struck out looking, leaving the A's on the verge
of wasting their last chance.
</P>
<P>
   They came perilously close, when Blowers barely checked his
swing on a 1-2 pitch from Olson. First-base umpire Mike Reilly
ruled in Blowers' favor _ and he promptly blooped a single into
right field on the next pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona manager Buck Showalter was furious about Reilly's
non-call. Showalter said Blowers ``obviously'' did not check his
swing in time; the Diamondbacks could have secured the victory
right there.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson, who had stolen third base during Blowers' at-bat,
instead strolled home to tie the score. The run was the 1,949th of
Henderson's career, tying him with Stan Musial for sixth place on
the all-time list.
</P>
<P>
   Willie Mays is fifth at 2,062. Henderson holds out remote hope
of playing long enough to catch Ty Cobb, the all-time leader at
2,246.
</P>
<P>
   ``The runs record is probably more important than the
stolen-base record,'' Henderson said. ``That's your job as a
leadoff hitter _ to get on base and score runs.''
</P>
<P>
   The A's nearly won the game when the next batter, Jason Giambi,
smoked an Olson pitch to deep center field. Arizona's Devon White
raced back and made a nice, staggering catch near the warning
track.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
