<HEADER>
A7258 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BULLS-SFCHRON &LR;      06-06 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BULLS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BULLS ARE BACK EVEN WITH JAZZ 
BY DAVID STEELE
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ After the Utah Jazz took a harrowing 88-85
victory over the Chicago Bulls in Game 1 of the NBA Finals on
Wednesday, a Salt Lake City columnist declared the series ``over
... Done. Finished.'' With 1:46 remaining in Friday night's second
game, the columnist looked like a prophet.
</P>
<P>
   At the final buzzer, however, it was the Delta Center that
resembled a mausoleum, while the five-time champion Bulls looked
very much alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that's what they consider being dead,'' said the Bulls'
Michael Jordan, ``then I wouldn't mind being dead for a little
while longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's Bulls dominated the final stretch, especially on
defense, and pulled out a 93-88 win that tied the series at one
game apiece and snatched home-court advantage going into the next
three games in Chicago. While Jordan scored 37 points, 13 in the
fourth quarter, it wasn't him who revived the Bulls at the end.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan can thank Steve Kerr for his big rebounding, Dennis
Rodman for his timely scoring, and a swarming defense that made
Karl Malone invisible and John Stockton error-prone. Once again,
the world's most photogenic team won a big game in a most
unglamorous way.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a long playoff, I can see it in the making,'' said
Bulls coach Phil Jackson. ``It's going to be one of those playoffs
that's going to be very difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   It was difficult for the Bulls, even as Jordan exploded again,
and as Toni Kukoc came out of the gate by scoring all 13 of his
points in the first half, and with Scottie Pippen again doing a
little of everything with 21 points, six rebounds and four assists.
With three minutes to go, they led 85-79 and seemed completely in
control; Jordan had a hand in the last nine Bulls points, scoring
seven of them and dishing to Pippen out of yet another double-team
for a jumper.
</P>
<P>
   Then all of a sudden, the Jazz found all kinds of ways to
compensate for another awful Malone performance _ 5-for-16 shooting
overall, 6-for-9 free-throw shooting, five fouls and 16 meek
points. (Malone correctly pointed out afterward, ``We will not win
this series if I don't play better. That's a fact.'')
</P>
<P>
   Shandon Anderson scored off a clever Bryon Russell pass in
traffic, Jordan missed a jumper, Anderson drained two free throws
on Luc Longley's sixth and final foul, and following another Jordan
miss in the lane, Jeff Hornacek buried a 3-pointer from the right
wing that put the Jazz up 86-85 with 1:46 to go.
</P>
<P>
   On their home court, the Jazz seemed in perfect position to take
control and take a 2-0 lead to Chicago. But, as several Bulls
mentioned, the champs have been there before. ``I think we went
back to the huddle, and everybody was quiet and focused, and we
came back out and took control,'' Kerr said. ``Everybody was very
confident.''
</P>
<P>
   Confident enough to completely shut the Jazz down; they didn't
score again until a virtually meaningless basket with three seconds
left. Rodman _ who played as well against Malone as he ever has _
beat the Mailman to a Kukoc miss to save a possession. Kukoc halted
a Jazz break by intercepting a Stockton pass intended for an open
Russell beyond the three-point line.
</P>
<P>
   And when the ball went the other way, Kerr measured a 3-pointer
from the right wing. He was short, but he drove between Malone and
Stockton, grabbed the rebound on the baseline, dribbled once and
fed Jordan underneath for a layup, a foul and a three-point play.
Jordan hit the free throw and, with 47.9 seconds left, the Bulls
were up for good, 88-86.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve strictly made a hustle play,'' Jordan said. ``He had an
opportunity to make the three, and I guess he had a feel in terms
of the shot not going in, and he chased the rebound. I'm sure Karl
was surprised, but that's true desire, to get those loose balls and
offensive rebounds.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was maybe my first rebound of the series,
probably,'' Kerr added. He was right; it was also only his 15th of
the entire postseason. Kerr called it ``ironic,'' but it wasn't any
more so than Rodman's turnaround jumper from the key with the shot
clock winding down that had tied the game at 74 midway through the
fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Rodman was much more potent on the glass, with five offensive
rebounds and nine overall (the Bulls beat the Jazz 18-9 on the
offensive glass), and on defense, where he made Malone shrink on
every possession. Malone took two shots in the fourth quarter and
scored exactly one point. He also played the last 6:20 after
picking up a silly fifth foul, raising an elbow into Kerr on a
pick-and-roll. On the ensuing possession after Jordan's three-point
play, Malone all but avoided the ball as Stockton kept working the
ball all around; Malone finally settled for a one-legged fallaway
18-footer with the shot clock winding down that clanked harmlessly
away with 23.4 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls commenced to hit five of eight free throws from then
on, and the Jazz were done.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
