r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JENKINS-JENKINS-SFCHR     06-06 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JENKINS-JENKINS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RODMAN'S FIERY COLOR COMES OUT AGAIN 
BY BRUCE JENKINS
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ Many of them stuck around the Delta Center,
helpless now without their exploding fireworks, out-of-context
music and preposterous mascot, with nothing to watch but Dennis
Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   He was standing around midcourt after the Chicago Bulls'
victory, soaking it all in with a couple of interviews. Here was
the man who went to Vegas, who ridiculed all things Mormon, who
outplayed Karl Malone. They tried a little sarcasm earlier; one
sign read, ``Welcome Back, Brother Rodman,'' but now the Utah fans
were plainly baffled. They observed Rodman as if he had just
stepped off a space ship in their own back yard.
</P>
<P>
   He was wearing a purple towel over his head: Jazz colors. The
shoes were gone. Socks only. He wore a look that only Rodman
understands, the kind of serenity this man derives from a 6 a.m.
gambling mission in another state on the morning of a team practice
with a woman on each arm. Dennis Rodman brought his world to Salt
Lake City last night, and Karl Malone was just another face in the
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't Rodman's game specifically; not by any means.
Michael Jordan scored 37 points, Scottie Pippen had 21 and Steve
Kerr had some fine, brazen moments near the end. But Rodman
symbolized how it all went wrong for the Jazz in a loss they
couldn't afford. If Malone is going into a shell, the Bulls put
Pippen on John Stockton and Rodman is standing there with a
gigantic smile on his face, Utah can't feel too great about playing
the next three games in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Utah coach Jerry Sloan was clearly disgusted afterward, although
he pointed no fingers. He just said this: ``When Toni Kukoc comes
out of the gate and goes right around everybody, like there's
nobody else on the floor, that tells you we're not ready to
compete. We came out soft. Simple as that.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact about Malone is that he's had a number of
disappearances in big games, particularly in last year's Finals.
He's a Hall of Famer and maybe the greatest power forward of all
time, but in situations like this, he is neither. There's too much
evidence to the contrary. He doesn't act the way great players act.
You've got numbers if you want 'em: Malone is shooting 34 percent
in the series, and he was 0-for-2 from the floor in the fourth
quarter Friday night, but it's more than that.
</P>
<P>
   As the stretch drive unfolded, Malone got into a pattern of
silly fouls, to the point where he had five and could no longer be
a defensive force underneath the basket. These weren't necessary
fouls on Pippen or Luc Longley inside, but inexplicable bumps and
elbows on people like Kerr, far from the basket.
</P>
<P>
   There had been a stunning sequence with 48 seconds left when
Kerr, after missing a pull-up 3-pointer, got his own offensive
rebound between Stockton and Malone. What an image. The skinny
red-haired kid, well past his prime, stepping right into the heart
of Utah lore. Kerr got the ball to Jordan, who cashed in a
three-point play for an 88-86 Chicago lead.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end, Stockton had the ball. It wasn't Kerr guarding
him (like Game 1), or even the long-armed Ron Harper, but Pippen,
one of the best defensive players in league history. It was a
brilliant move by Bulls coach Phil Jackson, and it meant just one
thing: Malone had to step up.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't. Malone was shifting idly inside, looking for a pick
to set, until the clock got to Stockton and he kicked the ball out.
Malone had an outside shot, the type he has consistently missed
through the first two games, and it kicked off the rim. The Jazz's
chances went right along with it.
</P>
<P>
   Early in his career, such as the Warriors' playoff upset over
Utah in '89, Malone was sullen and arrogant after a big loss. He's
learned a lot since then. He's mature and gentlemanly, and the
first thing he said when he entered the interview room last night
was, ``Sorry for making you guys wait.''
</P>
<P>
   He then proceeded to tell it straight, the only way he knows
how. ``I'm not playin' well right now, and it's an unfortunate
time. We will not win this series if I don't play well that's a
fact. I don't have any excuses. There's a lot of things I coulda
did. But I didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``All year,'' he went on, ``I make those shots. Right now I'm
missing 'em. Comes at a really (crummy) time, too (laughter). But I
don't shy away from the responsibility. When you don't do it, you
gotta face the firing squad. That's you guys.''
</P>
<P>
   And then Malone went back to the locker room. Somewhere nearby,
Rodman was dressing hurriedly. You never know with this man, but he
was probably getting ready for another Vegas run. With any luck
he'd be there by 2 a.m., his mind just right. There would be
wisecracks and revelry, and undoubtedly talk of that improbable
17-foot shot he buried with about eight minutes left in last
night's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a 37-year-old man now, I don't run up and down the court
like an antelope any more,'' Rodman said with a smile. ``You know
how it goes. If I miss that shot, it's all my fault. If it goes in,
it was Michael's game. I can't win.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, but you can, Dennis. You just did.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
