</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-GIANTS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS CONTAIN CARDS _ 7TH STRAIGHT VICTORY 
BY MARK CAMPS
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Mark McGwire's pursuit of the single-season home run
record resumed with a bang Friday night, but he'd probably trade
every one of those long balls for something the Giants attained: a
share of first place.
</P>
<P>
   While McGwire's Cardinals continue to sputter, the Giants
continue to surge. Backed by strong pitching from Orel Hershiser
and another remarkable job by the bullpen, the Giants won their
seventh in a row, 3-2 at Busch Stadium. The victory, coupled with
the Padres' 8-7 loss at Texas, gave the Giants a share of the top
spot in the West for the first time since April 7.
</P>
<P>
   Robb Nen, who in the Giants' last game here gave up a game-tying
home run to McGwire, this time blew him away on strikes in the
ninth inning. Nen then did the same to Brian Jordan to end the game
and record his league-leading 17th save.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was Nen's night tonight. It was McGwire's last time,'' said
Giants manager Dusty Baker, whose team is a season-high 13 games
over .500. ``Finally we won a close, one-run game in this ballpark.
Usually it goes the other way.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday night's victory was the Giants' second in a row in St.
Louis, their first two-game win streak at Busch since August 1996.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire, who was coming off a three-game layoff because of back
spasms, did not take long to show the baseball community he is just
fine. In the first inning, on a 1-2 sinking fastball, McGwire
launched a low line drive that carried well over the wall in
straightaway center that gave the Cardinals a short-lived 2-0 lead.
It was McGwire's 28th home run of the year, putting him on pace for
75.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good pitch to a great hitter,'' Hershiser said. ``I
got a little too arrogant thinking I could get him out, and I went
right after him.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the only serious mistake made by Hershiser, who has now
won six consecutive starts. He walked five batters in his six
innings, at times looking like he was one batter away from getting
pulled, but the reigning pitcher of the month would not give in. In
the sixth, after the first two St. Louis batters were retired, the
Cardinals loaded the bases on a double by Royce Clayton and two
walks. Hershiser got out of the jam by striking out Delino
DeShields.
</P>
<P>
   ``Orel had a real gutsy performance,'' Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants did all their scoring in the third inning. A two-run
single by Jeff Kent and a run-scoring grounder by J.T. Snow
accounted for all the runs.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, Baker said his goal was to get into the
Cardinals' overworked bullpen _ 10 innings from the relievers in
their past two games. To make matters worse for St. Louis, injuries
to starters Donovan Osborne, Alan Benes and Matt Morris have forced
manager Tony La Russa to use relievers as starters on several
occasions. Kent Bottenfield, who went the first three innings, was
making his first big-league start since June 1994.
</P>
<P>
   By knocking out Bottenfield early, Baker's objective was
achieved, and the Cardinals' soft, white underbelly was exposed.
And although the Giants had numerous chances _ they put runners in
scoring position in the fourth, sixth (bases loaded) and seventh _
they failed to pad their 3-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   But with the pitching of Hershiser and relievers Jim Poole,
Steve Reed, Rich Rodriguez and, finally, Nen, the Giants' bullpen
was just as resilient. The Giants' seven-game winning streak is the
longest since winning nine in a row early last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't seem like a seven-game win streak,'' said Baker.
``It just seems like we're playing like we're supposed to.
Hopefully it can go on and on.''
</P>
