<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 The Week in Review  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   An AIDS Vaccine Gets A Go-Ahead for Testing  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration gave Vaxgen Inc. of South San
Francisco the green light to test its AIDS vaccine among 5,000
uninfected volunteers in this country. The same vaccine is expected
to be tested among 2,500 volunteers in Thailand later this year.
Health officials say a vaccine is desperately needed to stem the
AIDS epidemic. But results of these trials will not be known for
four years. _
</P>
<P>
   _ By LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN
</P>
<P>
   A Plea to Ease Sanctions  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   South Korean President Kim Dae-jung begins a nine-day state
visit to the United States this weekend, and a few days before
leaving he called on Washington to ease sanctions against North
Korea. It was an unusual spectacle for the South Korean president
to ask his allies to lift sanctions against his mortal enemy, but
Kim said engagement with North Korea was more likely to open it up
and moderate its behavior.
</P>
<P>
   _ By NICHOLAS D. KRISTOF
</P>
<P>
   Merger Mania, Cont'd  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a deal that raised eyebrows on Wall Street, American Home
Products announced it would acquire Monsanto Co. for $34.4 billion
in stock.
</P>
<P>
   The combined company will be the nation's largest seller of
prescription drugs _ and perhaps also the site of the biggest
boardroom brawl to come along in years.
</P>
<P>
   The two bosses _ John Stafford from American Home Products and
Robert Shapiro at Monsanto _ will share the chairman's duties but
probably not for long. A clause in the deal enables the company's
new board to reexamine the partnership after the first year.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID J. MORROW
</P>
<P>
   Seriously Settling  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nearly four years after Orange County, Calif., filed for
bankruptcy after losing $1.6 billion on a wrong-way bet on interest
rates, the affluent county is about to get a big check. It
announced a $400 million settlement with Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., the
brokerage firm that sold the county speculative securities that
went sour.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement, a record for municipal finance, heads off a
scheduled September trial in a $2 billion lawsuit the county
brought against the firm.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Orange County says it shares some responsibility. ``The
county was not blameless in these losses,'' said Thomas Hayes, the
state official heading the county's litigation effort.
</P>
<P>
   _ By LESLIE WAYNE
</P>
<P>
   A Bishop Resigns  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After 40 years of priesthood, the Roman Catholic bishop of Palm
Beach, Fla., Joseph Keith Symons, resigned after admitting he
sexually molested five boys more than 25 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   When the bishop confessed the abuse to another priest years ago,
he was told to abstain from alcohol and be chaste. This time,
prompted by a report from one of his victims, the 65-year-old
cleric left for medical treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The Diocese of Palm Beach that he led for eight years was
stunned. Victims' groups said the case of Symons, the first
American bishop to resign for molesting minors, underscored the
depth of a widespread problem.
</P>
<P>
   _ By MIREYA NAVARRO
</P>
<P>
   Derailing at 125 Mph  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was Europe's worst rail crash in more than 20 years. A
high-speed express train hurtling through northern Germany at 125
miles per hour piled into the concrete support of an overpass,
killing at least 95 people. Officials said it was most likely a
broken wheel that derailed Inter-City-Express 884, a rare example
of mechanical failure in a land that prides itself on its
engineering prowess.
</P>
<P>
   Germans associate technological advance with safety, and the
crash shook the nation. As if to acknowledge widespread fears,
German Rail withdrew 60 of its 104 high-speed trains for
inspection, causing widespread disruption of its service.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ALAN COWELL
</P>
<P>
   Switzerland and Company  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even when the news about Nazi gold is good for the Swiss, it's
not so good for the Swiss.
</P>
<P>
   The United States State Department turned out a final report
detailing how other countries that remained neutral during World
War II _ Argentina, Portugal, Spain, Sweden and Turkey _ took
looted gold in return for providing Hitler with much-needed war
materiel, including the ores that were used in making
armor-piercing shells. Their actions likely prolonged the war.
</P>
<P>
   But the report, like a Swiss commission that issued its findings
in May, found that more gold was stolen from the victims of the
Holocaust than previously believed. And much of it went first to
Switzerland, chiefly the Swiss National Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in New York, the three major Swiss commercial banks,
which have been charged with obstructing Holocaust survivors and
their heirs from recovering their accounts, reportedly offered to
settle a series of suits for more than $1 billion. Negotiations are
continuing.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID E. SANGER
</P>
<P>
   Hold That Toast  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A well-known Bordeaux wine chateau, Giscours, was charged by the
French government with fraudulent winemaking practices. According
to indictments handed down in Bordeaux, Giscours' winemakers
stretched their good stuff by using wine from a lesser region,
mixing one year's wine with another's, adding sugar to boost
alcoholic content and soaking wood chips in the vats to simulate
aging in a barrel.
</P>
<P>
   What worried Bordeaux was not Giscours troubles but the
possibility that wine buyers around the world, fed up with the
staggeringly high prices of Bordeaux wines, would use the scandal
as an excuse to take their business elsewhere _ perhaps someplace
like the Napa Valley.
</P>
<P>
   _ By FRANK J. PRIAL
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ingles, Please  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   California voters delivered a decisive blow to three decades of
bilingual instruction in their public schools, voting by a 60-to-40
margin in favor of a ballot measure that said, essentially, ``No
mas!'' The measure would limit instruction for non-English speakers
to one year of intensive immersion. Hispanic voters opposed it by
almost the opposite margin.
</P>
<P>
   _ By TODD S. PURDUM
</P>
<P>
   An Appeal Denied  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In his first legal setback in the Monica Lewinsky investigation
in months, independent counsel Kenneth Starr was resoundingly
rebuffed by the Supreme Court, which refused to resolve quickly the
claims of privileges that have blocked the testimony of four grand
jury witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   But his appeals prompted President Clinton to drop his executive
privilege claims. Starr must now decide whether to issue an interim
report to Congress in the next few weeks, or wait to write a more
complete report after the November election.
</P>
<P>
   _ By STEPHEN LABATON
</P>
<P>
   A Zambian, Freed  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Kaunda, one of Africa's grand old men, is a free man
again. After keeping the former president in jail or under house
arrest for more than five months, Zambian prosecutors dropped all
charges against him. Their case had always looked weak. Kaunda was
originally accused of plotting a bungled coup attempt last October.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomatic sources said South African President Nelson Mandela
brokered a deal _ free Kaunda, who ruled Zambia from 1964 to 1991,
and he would return to retirement. But probably not quietly.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Einstein's Dangerous Liaison  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Einstein in love? So it appears, according to nine letters
written by the legendary scientist in 1945 and 1946.
</P>
<P>
   The And the object of his affection was Margarita Konenkova, who
may have been a Russian spy.
</P>
<P>
   The heartfelt letters, written by Einstein in German, were found
by a member of Ms. Konenkova's family among her belongings and will
be auctioned by Sotheby's later this month.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Konenkova's assignment was to influence prominent American
scientists while living in Princeton, N.J., according to a recent
book by former Soviet spy master, Pavel Sudoplatov. After Konenkova
returned to Russia with her husband, the sculptor Sergei Konenkov,
she and Einstein corresponded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that you find a happy new life in your old homeland, to
which you are so strongly attached,'' he writes in one note. ``Be
greeted and kissed by your A. Einstein.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By ROBIN POGREBIN
</P>
<P>
   Avast!
</P>
<P>
   One joy of working at The New York Times is the interchange with
readers _ smart, well-educated folks who care, a lot, about their
newspaper's standards. But it's an endless revelation to discover
what, precisely, floats their boats.
</P>
<P>
   A picture caption last Sunday about the world's largest cruise
ship incorrectly described its relationship with a nearby sailboat.
The ship was at anchor. It was not edging past the sailboat.
</P>
<P>
   What an uproar ensued! No mistake in years has prompted such an
outpouring. You'd think a photograph of Fidel Castro had been
misidentified as Jesse Helms.
</P>
<P>
   Readers seemed eager to underscore the clarity of it all, with
most letters wielding the word ``clearly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The ship is clearly at anchor,'' one reader wrote. ``The
starboard anchor chain is clearly visible.'' One charitable reader
tempered this to ``possibly,'' while another upped the ante to
``obviously.''
</P>
<P>
   And listen to the condemnation of the errant caption writer:
``Nautically challenged.'' ``Landlubberly.'' ``Are you slipping?''
``Should be assigned extended time at a shore resort.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most instructive was Rear Adm. David C. Brown, who
advised that ``the daytime signal indicating the vessel's anchored
status, a black ball, is clearly visible near the bow.''
</P>
<P>
   The editors got out their magnifying glass and, sure enough,
there it was! They hang their heads in landlubberly shame.
</P>
<P>
   _ By HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
<P>
   The FBI's Most Famous &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mickey Mantle, Thurgood Marshall, Adolf Hitler, John Lennon,
Cardinal Francis Spellman, Paul Robeson and Pablo Picasso are just
some of well-known public figures whose FBI files just appeared on
the agency's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   They join Lucille Ball, Elvis Presley and other celebrities
whose dossiers were previously transferred to the FBI site
(http://www.fbi.gov). These nearly three dozen files are the most
frequently sought out and are open to the public at the J. Edgar
Hoover building.
</P>
<P>
   Also available on the Web site are files on the Hindenburg
explosion, the escape from Alcatraz and the Basque intelligence
service.
</P>
<P>
   Long available to scholars, the files provide little new
historical information but cast an intriguing light on the dark
side of the agency under Hoover, when agents were preoccupied with
leftist activists and chased gossip and scandal as assiduously as
they tracked down criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Spellman's warm correspondence with Hoover is there, along with
background reports on Marshall before he became a Supreme Court
justice. So are reports from informers asserting that Picasso once
said he was a communist, and statements from people who claimed to
have seen Hitler alive long after World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ball, the star of ``I Love Lucy,'' earned a file in the
early 1950s when she was investigated by the House Un-American
Activities because she registered to vote as a communist _ at the
insistence of her grandfather.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI also investigated legitimate extortion attempts and
threats like one against Mickey Mantle, the legendary New York
Yankee, who received a threatening note in 1960 suggesting that he
might be shot during a game. ``I have a gun with a microscopic
sight,'' a man wrote him, ``and I'm going to get you through both
of your knees and it's going to happen soon.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID JOHNSTON
</P>
</TEXT>
