<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
th 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories in sight at this hour from The New
York Times News Service for AMs of Sunday, June 7:
</P>
<P>
   For questions about stories call (212) 556-1927. The supervisor
is Tim Hilchey, followed at 5 p.m. by Henry Warnken.
</P>
<P>
   For technical problems call Peter Trigg at (212) 499-3332.
</P>
<P>
   Please note that news stories and features from The Arizona
Republic, Bloomberg News, The Boston Globe, Cox News Service, Fort
Worth Star-Telegram, Hearst Newspapers, The Kansas City Star, Los
Angeles Daily News, San Francisco Chronicle, Seattle
Post-Intelligencer, States News Service and the New York Times
Regional newspapers are all part of your New York Times News
Service file.
</P>
<P>
   Stories scheduled for Page 1 will be listed in FRONTPAGE-NYT,
which will move by 12:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (These stories will move with an ``i'' category
code)
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-MISSING (Paulpietersburg, South Africa) _ When South
Africa's Truth and Reconciliation Commission began its work more
than two years ago, it first asked apartheid's victims to come
forward and tell their stories. The early days were grim with tales
of beatings, torture and murder. But in the background were other
victims, like the Mahlombe family. They came humbly forward without
any facts, but with requests for information about missing loved
ones and, in particular, for bodies to bury properly. By Suzanne
Daley.
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN-GUNTRADE (Peshawar, Pakistan) _ Peshawar has for
centuries been home to an extraordinary community of gunsmiths.
With skills handed down through generations, they say they are able
to make exact duplicates of any weapon they can lay their hands on.
By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-COUNTERFEIT-FOE (Beijing) _ Wang Hai, 25, a high-school
dropout, has in three years transformed himself into China's first
consumer advocate, and a national hero. By Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-PILOTSTRIKE (Paris) _ Prime Minister Lionel Jospin said
Saturday that the French government was ready to step in and push
Air France pilots and management to settle a strike that has
grounded most of the airline's flights just as hundreds of
thousands of soccer fans began to pour in for the World Cup soccer
tournament. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-HUMAN-RIGHTS (Bogota, Colombia) _ The recent raid on
the Intercongregational Committee for Justice and Peace, a Jesuit
group, appears to be part of a wave of assaults on the chroniclers
of human rights abuses in Latin America. By Diana Jean Schemo.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-DRUG-STRATEGY (United Nations) _ With President Clinton and
other world leaders coming here Monday for a special session of the
General Assembly on the world's drug problems, the United Nations'
top anti-narcotics official has submitted a two-pronged strategy
that moves beyond the conventional approach of intercepting illegal
drugs and arresting traffickers. By Christopher S. Wren.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (These stories will move with an ``a'' category code)
</P>
<P>
   NEB-HAGEL-TRADE (West Point, Neb.) _ At Harry Knobbe's Feed
Yards the other day, Sen. Chuck Hagel, R-Neb., was holding forth on
the global economy, the Asian financial crisis and the
International Monetary Fund with a dozen or so hog and cattle
farmers. Here in Cuming County, one of the largest cattle-producing
counties in the United States, the farmers were hanging on every
word. But getting his fellow senators to focus on international
matters is a lot tougher than holding that discussion with farmers
in a state that exports $1.6 billion worth of farm products to Asia
each year. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-CENSUS (Sacramento, Calif.) _ Since the beginning of
April, temporary Census Bureau employees like Cindy Jumper have
fanned out across Sacramento, interviewing residents in households
that did not return the forms mailed to them in early March. But
the number of households that will be visited is different in
Sacramento than it has been in any previous census. This river city
of about 374,000 is one of three sites where the bureau is
conducting its dress rehearsals for the next census using a method
called statistical sampling, which will be used to estimate the
size and characteristics of its population. By Steven A. Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   PA-DEATHPENALTY-RACISM _ A new study on racial disparities in
death-penalty cases has found that black defendants in murder cases
in Philadelphia are nearly four times more likely than other
defendants to be sentenced to death, even when the circumstances of
killings are the same. By Fox Butterfield.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-DEATHROW-DILEMMA (Houston) _ As long as there is a death
penalty in the United States, perhaps no man would seem so ripe a
candidate for execution as Henry Lee Lucas, a former drifter now on
Death Row for the rape and murder of a hitchhiker 19 years ago.
Lucas is also serving six life terms, two 75-year terms, and one
60-year term for nine other killings. But as his execution date on
June 30 approaches, Texas officials are grappling with an unusual
legal and political problem. While there is virtually no dispute
that Lucas is a vicious murderer, there is considerable doubt about
whether he could have committed the one murder for which he was
sentenced to death. By Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   VA-COUNTY-JOBSDRIVE (Martinsville, Va.) _ Henry County, reeling
from factory closings, has launched a campaign to draw attention to
its underutilized workforce. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL-BRIEFS _ Short items on politics from around the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (These stories will move with a ``w'' category
code)
</P>
<P>
   EPA-POLLUTION-AUDIT (Washington) _ The inspector general of the
Environmental Protection Agency has documented widespread failures
by federal and local officials in several states. By John H.
Cushman Jr.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-STARR (Washington) _ Kenneth Starr's effort to bring
White House aides and Secret Service agents before his grand jury
has provided much of the recent legal drama here. But it is his
pursuit of notes from a lawyer's interview with a man who has been
dead nearly five years that, of all the disputes surrounding the
independent counsel's investigation, could ultimately matter most
to anyone who has ever consulted a lawyer about a potentially
embarrassing problem. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS &LR;  (This story will move with an ``s'' category code)
</P>
<P>
   SOC-MATCH-FIXING (Paris) _ This week, the World Cup, the 32-team
tournament and ultimate championship in the world's most popular
sport, will start, and with it will come celebrations of soccer's
ability to galvanize national pride and transfix the globe. A
cumulative television audience of 37 billion is expected. But in
virtually every corner of that captivated globe, a darker side of
soccer has worsened in recent years _ a dispiriting underside
disfigured by tales of lucrative gambling rings, rigged results and
a pervasive erosion of trust. By Jere Longman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (These stories will move with a ``k'' category code)
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN _ Details to come. By Maureen Dowd.
</P>
<P>
   HERBERT-COLUMN _ Details to come. By Bob Herbert.
</P>
</TEXT>
