r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAGIC-LATE-NIGHT-2tak     06-06 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGIC-LATE-NIGHT-2takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOWTIME RETURNING TO L.A.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Will also move in the ``a'' national and ``e'' entertainment news 
 files.) 
By KEITH MARDER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When he hit Los Angeles in 1979 as a 19-year-old
Laker rookie, his no-look passes and million-watt charisma turned
the game of basketball into Showtime, lighting up the Forum and
luring a slew of stars courtside to catch his magic.
</P>
<P>
   Showtime ended in 1991 when he shocked the world by disclosing
he was infected with the HIV virus. By then Earvin ``Magic''
Johnson was much more than a basketball player. He was an L.A.
institution, his smile as recognizable as the Hollywood sign.
</P>
<P>
   Now Showtime is back _ only on a different court.
</P>
<P>
   This time Magic _ businessman and AIDS activist _ is host of a
new late-night talk show, and he has new teammates. Gone are Kareem
and James. In are Arnold and Harrison. His opponents no longer
Larry and Michael but Dave and Jay.
</P>
<P>
   ``The role I had with the Lakers is the same as I will have as a
talk-show host,'' Johnson said in an interview last week. ``I'll be
setting people up, and making them look good.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has no illusions that ``The Magic Hour,'' which debuts
Monday at 11 p.m. on KTTV (Channel 11), will be an easy win.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get nervous,'' he admits.
</P>
<P>
   But nervous or not you're talking to a man who never gives up.
He led the Lakers to five National Basketball Association
championships, fought back HIV to the point that it is undetectable
in his blood and has brought jobs to the inner city with a national
chain of movie theaters, the first opening in 1995 in L.A.'s
Crenshaw district.
</P>
<P>
   Now his success will be measured in Nielsen Ratings as his show
will enter the contentious late-night war that has seen the demise
of Dennis Miller, Chevy Chase, Pat Sajak, Keenan Ivory Wayans and a
luke-warm reception for Sinbad.
</P>
<P>
   ``God has blessed me with a third career,'' Johnson says.
``Basketball, business and now this. When I first got here I
thought I'd be a businessman, but not like all this. Building up
the inner city is what I am most proud of. I'm sure I'll be very
proud once the show starts on Monday.''
</P>
<P>
   And Magic's charisma is still luring celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   Personal requests have secured opening-night visits from Arnold
Schwarzenegger and Whitney Houston, and get this, neither has
anything to promote.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been an ambassador of good in so many areas because he
knows how to use his charm,'' said executive producer Geovanni
Brewer. ``People know he won't put them in an unflattering light.''
</P>
<P>
   In another unusual turn, Jay Leno invited Johnson on ``The
Tonight Show'' last week to promote his new competition because,
``I like him. He's a good guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrison Ford, Michael Douglas, Gillian Anderson, Kenny G and
Arsenio Hall are also among first-week guests. In fact, Ford was
taping a ``Tonight Show'' appearance in a studio near to the one
that Johnson was taping his pilot when the superstar actor asked if
he could stop by and meet Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was as excited to meet him,'' Johnson said. ``Hopefully the
enthusiasm will come across to the viewers at home.''
</P>
<P>
   After a personal invitation from Johnson, Ford agreed to appear
on the show.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, maybe they heard that Johnson gave out autographed
basketballs to the guests of his pilot episode, a possible
full-time replacement for the obligatory fruit basket many
talk-show guests receive.
</P>
<P>
   ``People just love Magic and want to come on to talk to him,''
said Heather Russell, one of the show's bookers. ``A lot of people
are like, `Wow, Magic, I just want to come on.' They admire him,
not just from his basketball days, but because of his whole
entreprenurial aspect.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who lives in Beverly Hills with his wife, Cookie, and
his two children, has become a spokesman for AIDS awareness, and
his foundation has raised more than $8 million to fight the
disease.
</P>
<P>
   As for his own battle, Johnson says a new combination therapy of
AIDS drugs has cleared HIV from his system, declaring himself
``healed'' _ not cured.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson says he goes to his movie theaters once or twice a week
and that the feedback he gets from patrons make all his efforts
worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   ``We help put people to work,'' he said. ``People cry, and laugh
and smile when you go to the different theaters. They are thankful.
They mob me for hugs and high-fives, and say thank you.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the theaters and a proposed shopping center, Johnson
owns Starbucks and TGI Friday restaurant franchises in the inner
cities of Los Angeles, Houston and Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Johnson also recently partnered with singer Janet Jackson to buy
a bank in South Central Los Angeles and is among those trying to
bring the National Football League back to town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is generally acknowledged that he has established
himself as a force for good,'' said Councilman Mark Ridley Thomas,
``and he continues to do those kinds of things and frankly it is
incumbant upon us all to encourage him in those pursuits.''
</P>
<P>
   So how will Johnson, as one of the few noncomedian talk show
hosts, face his newest challenge? Like he did as an athlete with a
training camp, taking speech and interviewing lessons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked on the pronounciation of my words and learned to
really take my time and speak clearly,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He will not, however, do a monologue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm a showman, but I'm not a stand-up comic,'' Johnson
says.
</P>
<P>
   But he will be involved in some comedy bits. For instance, he
will do things in public to see people's reactions, Brewer said,
such as serving java in a local coffee shop.
</P>
<P>
   Comic Craig Shoemaker will be Johnson's sidekick and
singer/percussionist Sheila E. will be the bandleader.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not deep; it's about entertainment,'' Brewer said.
``He wants people to go to sleep with a smile on their face. That's
what the agenda of the show is.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson says he realizes that Leno is television's No. 1 host,
and he has no illusions of upending him. Throughout the process of
putting this show on its feet, Johnson says he has learned that
Leno and other hosts have worked hard to make it look easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if the show doesn't last a year from now,'' Johnson said,
``I'll still be a better person and a better man for having
prepared for it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
