<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-06 12:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7309 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCOTUS-STARR-690&AMP;ADD-     06-06 1281
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-STARR-690&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYER-CLIENT PRIVILEGE FACES A CRITICAL TEST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (lb) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Kenneth Starr's effort to bring White House aides
and Secret Service agents before his grand jury has provided much
of the recent legal drama here. But it is his pursuit of notes from
a lawyer's interview with a man who has been dead nearly five years
that, of all the disputes surrounding the independent counsel's
investigation, could ultimately matter most to anyone who has ever
consulted a lawyer about a potentially embarrassing problem.
</P>
<P>
   The question, which will be argued before the Supreme Court on
Monday, is whether the age-old attorney-client privilege survives
the client's death. The privilege is the basis for lawyers'
relationships with their clients on the one hand, and with the rest
of the world on the other.
</P>
<P>
   The client in this case was Vincent Foster, the deputy White
House counsel who killed himself nine days after seeking advice
from James Hamilton, a prominent Washington lawyer who took three
pages of notes during the two-hour meeting. Starr is seeking the
notes as part of his investigation into whether presidential aides
lied about any role Hillary Rodham Clinton might have had in the
dismissal of seven employees of the White House travel office.
</P>
<P>
   But the particular facts and political context are nearly
irrelevant to lawyers across the United States, as well as
organizations speaking for the terminally ill and for the nation's
psychiatrists, whose attention has been riveted on the opinion
issued last year in the case by the U.S. appeals court here.
</P>
<P>
   A privilege long assumed to be one of life's absolutes suddenly
turned out to be, at the end of life, porous and unreliable.
</P>
<P>
   Foster had requested, and Hamilton confidently gave, an explicit
promise of confidentiality at the start of their interview on July
11, 1993. But the District of Columbia U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals ruled that Starr could have the lawyer's notes as long as
he could persuade a U.S. District Court that he needed them.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the context of disputed wills, where different rules
apply to enable lawyers to make known the wishes of their deceased
clients, this was the first federal ruling to lower the absolute
shield of the privilege. Lawyers say that unless the Supreme Court
overturns the decision, they will have to modify the assurances
they now give their clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the fundamental aspects of the lawyer-client
relationship is that the duty of confidentiality lasts forever,''
Steven Krane, a New York lawyer who has served on several
professional ethics committees, said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``You take your client's secrets to your grave,'' Krane, a
partner in the firm of Proskauer Rose, said he had taught his
students at Columbia Law School. ``Now, if a client leaves my
office and is hit by a bus, suddenly everything is potentially
available.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the appeals court's decision is binding only in the
federal courts here, the case, Swidler &AMP; Berlin vs. United States,
has been the talk of the legal profession. The cover story in the
current issue of The American Lawyer, a monthly magazine, describes
the case as ``one of transcendent importance to lawyers throughout
the country.''
</P>
<P>
   The American Bar Association and three other national lawyers
organizations have filed briefs urging the justices to overturn the
decision.
</P>
<P>
   One of those briefs was also signed by the National Hospice
Organization, representing 48 state hospice organizations, and the
American Psychiatric Association, which successfully urged the
court two years ago to recognize a psychotherapist-patient
privilege. Society as a whole benefits from a high level of trust
between lawyers and clients, the briefs all maintain.
</P>
<P>
   The American Bar Association said there were ``hundreds of
thousands if not millions of Americans'' contemplating the likely
imminence of their own deaths. ``Many of these people undoubtedly
have secrets and confidences that, if revealed, would be at the
least highly embarrassing to themselves or their friends and loved
ones,'' but they might want to turn to a lawyer to help sort such
matters out while there is still time, the brief said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Disclosure of sensitive material after death ``can be
devastating to survivors,'' the National Association of Criminal
Defense Lawyers said in a brief that the hospice and psychiatric
organizations also signed.
</P>
<P>
   If upheld by the Supreme Court, the brief said, the appeals
court's decision ``will come to bear every time a lawyer counsels a
client'' and a client must decide ``whether to make a full and
candid disclosure to his lawyer of the most highly incriminating,
embarrassing, or otherwise sensitive facts the client possesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Although no organizations have filed briefs on Starr's side, the
argument is not quite as lopsided as that fact might indicate. A
number of prominent legal scholars over the years have called for a
relaxation of the absolute privilege after the client's death, in
cases of ``exceptional need,'' as the American Law Institute, a
group of scholars and bar leaders, urged in a policy statement
adopted last month.
</P>
<P>
   Those who argue for a flexible privilege are troubled by the
occasional cases in which the truth has quite obviously been
sacrificed for the sake of a dead person's privilege. In a famous
case from Arizona, in 1976, a judge invoked the state law requiring
an absolute attorney-client privilege, to prevent two lawyers from
testifying that a deceased client had confessed to a double murder
for which another man was on trial.
</P>
<P>
   In the notorious Charles Stuart case in Boston in 1990, the
Massachusetts Supreme Judicial Court refused to permit prosecutors
to question the lawyer for a man who had first accused an
unidentified _ and nonexistent _ black gunman of killing his wife,
and who then, as suspicion shifted to himself, jumped from a bridge
to his death a day after consulting the lawyer. The Massachusetts
court cited one of its own precedents, from 1833, insisting that
``the mouth of the attorney shall be forever sealed.''
</P>
<P>
   In the current case, the appeals court limited its holding to
criminal investigations, concluding that because clients face no
criminal liability after their death, the prospect of posthumous
disclosure would not be particularly troublesome. The 2-to-1
majority said it expected ``the chilling effect to fall somewhere
between modest and nil.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr's brief asserts that because people can be required to
testify in criminal investigations while they are alive, the only
clients who have anything to fear from the ruling are those who
perjure themselves and fear betrayal by their lawyers after they
die. The other side's ``entire theory is acrid with the odor of
presumed perjury,'' his brief says.
</P>
<P>
   Simon Frankel, a San Francisco lawyer whose 1992 law review
article on the subject has been cited by both sides, said in an
interview that at the heart of the dispute were ``different
visions'' of how a rule permitting posthumous disclosure would
affect the behavior of living people.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's true that once you're dead, you don't care, but you do
care while you're alive,'' said Frankel, who advocates retaining an
absolute privilege. The problem, he said, is that it is ``in the
precise case where the information is juiciest'' that the
prosecutor is likely to assert the greatest need for disclosure,
even as the client is staking everything on the expectation of
confidentiality.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-06-98 1224EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
