   A. FALSE. Dogs have keen senses; under these conditions, you
would probably startle the dog and increase the possibility of an
attack. The right procedure? Make a soft noise, such as a low
whistle, so the dog won't be surprised. Keep your eye on the dog,
and if you must withdraw, back up slowly and carefully to avoid a
fall.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Turning away and retreating quickly from a dog will probably
prevent you from being bitten. True or false?
</P>
<P>
   A. FALSE. Turning and running often increases the dog's
excitement and provides an opportunity for it to bite while your
back is turned. The proper procedure? Stand your ground initially;
face the dog; use a purse, briefcase, book, coat or jacket as a
shield between you and the dog; and back away slowly.
</P>
<P>
   Q. It's a good idea to carry biscuits to make friends with dogs.
True or false?
</P>
<P>
   A. FALSE. Too often the dog will accept the treat, but still not
accept you. . . .
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)But even the Postal Service isn't completely
grim about dog bites, maybe since it has managed to reduce attacks
on its carriers through a variety of precautions. In an address in
Washington to kick off Dog Bite Prevention Week, Michael J. Shinay,
vice president of the Postal Service, noted that when it comes to
dog-bite humor, postal workers have heard it all:(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   That brings to mind a classic scene from the movie ``The Pink
Panther Strikes Again'' (1976). Inspector Clouseau is standing at
the front desk of an inn, talking to the innkeeper. A dog lies at
his feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does your dog bite?'' he asked the innkeeper.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' the innkeeper replies.
</P>
<P>
   The inspector reaches down to pet the pup, which promptly sinks
his canines into Clouseau's hand.
</P>
<P>
   Clouseau angrily turns to the innkeeper and says, ``I thought
you said your dog does not bite!''
</P>
<P>
   With a shrug, the innkeeper replies, ``That's not my dog.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
