<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-MISSING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VICTIMS' GRAVES TELL GRIM STORIES OF APARTHEID 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SUZANNE DALEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PAULPIETERSBURG, South Africa _ Before going to the cemetery,
Bafana Mahlombe's family gathered in front of the police station
here, laughing and joking about the 22-year-old they remembered. He
had been short and muscular. He hadn't talked much.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had crossed teeth in front, like my mother,'' said his
sister Magdeline, a librarian in Durban. ``He had her whole face,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   When he went off to fight apartheid in the armed wing of the
African National Congress, he promised that he would go down
fighting.
</P>
<P>
   That was 15 years ago, and his family never saw him again. Rumor
had it that he died three years later in this town at the hands of
the security police. But the Mahlombe family never got official
word. All those years, they wondered what had really happened to
him and worried that his spirit was not at rest.
</P>
<P>
   Now they were here to watch the exhumation of a pauper's grave,
No. 281, which according to local morgue records was where Bafana
Mahlombe had been since 1986. It was time to take him home, they
said. Time to put him in a grave next to his mother's.
</P>
<P>
   When South Africa's Truth and Reconciliation Commission began
its work more than two years ago, it first asked apartheid's
victims to come forward and tell their stories. The early days were
grim with tales of beatings, torture and murder.
</P>
<P>
   But in the background were other victims, like the Mahlombe
family. They came humbly forward without any facts, but with
requests for information about missing loved ones and, in
particular, for bodies to bury properly.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the commission has exhumed more than 50 bodies, some on
the edges of rivers or in isolated farm areas where the victims
were brutalized and killed. Many have been found because security
officials confessed to killing them to get amnesty from the
commission.
</P>
<P>
   But sometimes the graves themselves do the talking. In one case,
investigators digging for three bodies found 12. In another,
amnesty applicants said one victim had died of a heart attack
during a torture session. But when her body was unearthed there was
a bullet in the head.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bodies tell us a lot,'' said Gail Wannenburg, the
investigating officer supervising the Mahlombe case. ``If a police
officer is claiming that someone was shot because he was holding a
grenade, then the body should show signs of that, assuming the
grenade went off. We can also see broken bones and what kind of
condition they were in when they died. There is a lot of
information there.''
</P>
<P>
   Escorting the family to the grave, Ms. Wannenburg said she
believed she had all the facts in this case. Most police records
were illegally destroyed in the last days of apartheid rule, but
local morgue records remained. Bafana Mahlombe's death was recorded
there, along with those of four other guerrillas who probably
sabotaged local power stations and oil refineries.
</P>
<P>
   The records said he had been shot by police officers hunting him
down by helicopter as he ran through the fields nearby. His body
had been stripped and buried in black plastic.
</P>
<P>
   The stripping was unusual, Ms. Wannenburg said. But in the
record, at least, there was nothing else indicating that his
killing was more than a routine act of the police department, whose
tactics during the low-level guerrilla war of the 1980s shifted
from pursue-and-arrest to a more military style search-and-destroy.
</P>
<P>
   At the grave in the rundown cemetery in the black section of
town, the mood was somber. Nelson Mahlombe knelt among the tiny
enamel markers, talking softly to his brother before the digging
began.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are here now to take you home,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the exhumations have been huge press events and showcase
gatherings of African National Congress leaders. But Bafana
Mahlombe was just a young soldier. Still, local congress officials
were out in numbers, and members of the congress' Women's League
gathered to sing traditional songs and help the family through the
hourlong wait before the body was found.
</P>
<P>
   When the family said they were ready, the grave diggers lifted
the black plastic sheeting, laid it on the ground and unwrapped the
bones.
</P>
<P>
   After staring in silence for a minute, Magdeline and Nelson
Mahlombe asked to see the teeth so they might be sure the body was
their brother's.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Fanie Molapo, who heads the commission exhumation team,
obliged, rummaging through the bones for the jaw. He found broken
pieces of skull that suggested Bafana Mahlombe had suffered massive
head injuries, he said. Inside the bag, too, were knotted ropes
indicating that he had been tied up when he died. The family
members argued over the teeth that could be found, with the older
members finally convincing the younger ones that they were indeed
Bafana's.
</P>
<P>
   Before the afternoon was over there was evidence that all five
of the people buried here had probably been shot at close range,
most of them through the forehead.
</P>
<P>
   The Truth Commission, which was created to help this country put
its brutal past to rest without the cost of expensive and
politically divisive trials, is supposed to finish most of its work
by the end of July and publish its report. But with limited money
it is unlikely to resolve all the mysteries of the era, and family
members doubt they will ever know exactly what happened to Bafana
Mahlombe.
</P>
<P>
   The commission does pay for the exhumation, however, and $500
toward the cost of reburial.
</P>
<P>
   In the late afternoon, when the bones had been placed in a
proper coffin, the Mahlombe family said they were finally
satisfied. Like many Zulus, they believe that a spirit not put to
rest will haunt the family.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, for many years now we have had a lot of trouble in
our family,'' said Magdeline Mahlombe. ``Now, I think it will be
better. How could he be at peace buried like that and with his
hands and legs tied?
</P>
<P>
   ``He will lie better now, and we will be a bit relieved. But we
won't be happy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
