<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-06 13:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7372 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-MATCH-FIXING-2TAK     06-06 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-MATCH-FIXING-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEEPING THE DARK SIDE OF SOCCER AWAY FROM THE CITY OF LIGHT
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By JERE LONGMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ As the United States prepared for a World Cup soccer
qualifying match against El Salvador in November, John Harkes and
Roy Wegerle, two of the team's top players, received an alarming
telephone call at the team hotel in Providence, R.I. The caller
suggested that the players could make money by throwing their game
against El Salvador.
</P>
<P>
   The American players reported the anonymous call to Coach Steve
Sampson, but they never determined whether it was a serious attempt
at a bribe or a prank. While the Americans were disturbed, they
were not entirely surprised. Nor was anyone else involved in
international soccer.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is enough proof in the past, not necessarily at the
World Cup, but at the club level, that these things have taken
place,'' Sampson said. ``Referees have been bribed and players have
been given incentives to throw matches.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, the World Cup, the 32-team tournament and ultimate
championship in the world's most popular sport, will start, and
with it will come celebrations of soccer's ability to galvanize
national pride and transfix the globe.
</P>
<P>
   But in virtually every corner of that captivated globe, a darker
side of soccer has worsened in recent years _ a dispiriting
underside disfigured by tales of lucrative gambling rings, rigged
results and a pervasive erosion of trust. In the last year alone,
allegations of fixed matches in domestic club leagues have been
investigated in Russia, China, Greece, Israel, Belgium and Vietnam,
all coming as the economy of soccer _ experts estimate it as a $400
billion-a-year industry _ grows more enormous.
</P>
<P>
   In Bulgaria, the government announced last month that it was
assuming control of the national soccer federation because of
widespread corruption and incompetence. In November in Greece, 123
members of Parliament backed a public statement concluding that
``championships in all divisions and team standings'' were being
``cooked up in backstage deals.'' Two months ago in Russia, Pavel
Sadyrin, who coached the country's 1994 World Cup team, told the
national soccer federation that ``there were, still are, and, alas,
always will be, rigged matches as long as the country does not
follow the rule of law.''
</P>
<P>
   And in Vietnam, soccer fans are infuriated over concerns that
bookmakers, through bribes to players and referees, are fixing the
results of club league games. In fact, the Vietnamese soccer
federation recently refused to validate the score of a match
between teams from Hanoi and Haiphong because of widespread
suspicions of rigging. ``Our players have to relearn the spirit of
sport and understand that we don't play matches using deceit,''
Nguyen Tai Ngo, a member of Vietnam's committee for sports and
gymnastics, said in an Agence France-Presse report.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are merely reflections of the vastly increasing richness
of the game,'' Paul Gardner, a columnist for the magazine Soccer
America and one of the foremost authorities on the sport in the
United States, said of the spread of game-fixing scandals. ``There
is an obscene amount of money in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   While there has never been a confirmed fixing scandal in the
World Cup, the rash of recent investigations has prompted FIFA, the
French initials used to identify soccer's world governing body, to
install safeguards before the start of the tournament on Wednesday.
For example, teams and the 67 referees involved in the tournament
will stay in secure hotels or on isolated floors of hotels,
theoretically apart from danger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course this is a matter of concern, but we are not
expecting serious problems,'' Michel Zen-Ruffinen, FIFA's deputy
executive director, said of the prospect of a scandal. ``There
would be serious sanctions taken. We expect people to be aware that
it is not worth destroying a career to accept money. We believe the
pride of playing for a country is stronger than the desire to
receive money.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, though, the World Cup has not been immune from
problems _ both real bribe attempts and suspicious matches.
</P>
<P>
   A Costa Rican referee, Rodrigo Badilla, was suspended from the
1998 World Cup, Zen-Ruffinen said, for failing to sufficiently
report a $50,000 bribe attempt aimed at him to fix a qualifying
match in October between Japan and the United Arab Emirates.
Badilla, who refereed the 1994 World Cup in the United States, hung
up on the caller who mentioned the bribe, and he was not suspected
of having tainted the match, Zen-Ruffinen said. However, Badilla
reported the matter only to another referee and not to FIFA
officials, Zen-Ruffinen said.
</P>
<P>
   This was the only reported case of attempting to bribe a referee
in 700 qualifying matches for the 1998 World Cup, Zen-Ruffinen
said.
</P>
<P>
   FIFA officials are particularly sensitive to attempts to
compromise the game officials because they wield enormous control
in such a low-scoring sport with the right to call, or not call,
penalties. Some soccer experts say they believe referees are
vulnerable because their salaries have not kept up with the
millions paid to top players.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Another top referee, Kurt Rothlisberger of Switzerland, who
worked the 1994 World Cup and was removed after a controversial
no-call on an apparent penalty during a Belgium-Germany match, was
banned for life last year for allegedly demanding $60,000 to help
fix a 1996 European Champion League match.
</P>
<P>
   Just as worrisome to FIFA is the mere perception of rigged
games. During qualifying for the 1998 World Cup, the coach of El
Salvador, Milovan Djoric, was twice suspended for contending that
the referees had helped Mexico in its matches with El Salvador.
Horace Burrell, the president of the Jamaican soccer federation,
threatened last fall to sue the Salvadoran federation over its
suggestions that Jamaica may have offered bribes to the Salvadorans
to throw a qualifying match against Jamaica in November. The
Salvadorans later apologized and admitted the Jamaicans were
guiltless.
</P>
<P>
   A particularly disquieting incident took place in Qatar at the
1995 World Cup for players under 17 years of age. According to
Zen-Ruffinen, some players had been offered gifts by men thought to
be part of a Malaysian betting syndicate, three of whom were
arrested.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were not asking the players to do something in
exchange,'' Zen-Ruffinen said, adding that the players had allowed
the men to take photographs. ``The idea, most surely, was to use
the pictures at a later stage when these players became famous,
presumably in a case of extortion or something like that,''
Zen-Ruffinen said.
</P>
<P>
   In one preventive measure, match assignments for referees at
this World Cup will be handed out with little advance notice, and
referees traveling to matches will be accompanied by security
guards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never been approached,'' said Esse Baharmast, the lone
American referee assigned to this World Cup. ``If there is a
strange phone call coming in, the first thing I would do is go to
the authorities and tell them what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampson, the American coach, said he understood the need for the
precautions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not really concerned about it, but I don't want to be
naive,'' he said. ``When so much is at stake financially for
individuals and for countries, when literally the image of an
entire nation is resting on the results of how a team fares in the
World Cup, there is bound to be at least the perception that there
will be those kind of incidents.''
</P>
<P>
   Soccer experts say that there is nothing inherently corrupt
about the game, but rather that corruption in soccer is reflective
of the money and popularity of the sport and consistent with the
corruption found at many levels in many countries.
</P>
<P>
   With widespread television exposure, soccer also has become
hugely popular for bettors. In Thailand, where two men were given
three-month sentences in May for operating an illegal soccer
betting racket, a research center estimated that $1 billion would
be bet in that country alone during the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   In January, 12 of China's top clubs admitted in a newspaper
survey that they had offered cash bribes to referees, some of whom
had accepted. In April, two soccer players were arrested in Vietnam
for fixing league matches last year, and published reports said up
to 74 players and team officials were suspected of rigging games.
And the Italian Parliament was suspended on April 29 when a scuffle
broke out among elected officials over the credibility of the
refereeing in a match that had significant implications for the
Italian season.
</P>
<P>
   A match-fixing scandal at the 1998 World Cup would be a painful
embarrassment for the French, who suffered through the most
notorious example of match-fixing in recent years. Bernard Tapie,
the former French urban affairs minister, was sentenced to a year
in prison in 1995 for fixing a 1993 match involving the team he
owned, Olympic Marseilles.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two decades, two World Cup matches have aroused
suspicion of rigging. In 1978, Argentina needed a four-goal victory
over Peru to advance ahead of Brazil _ total goals counted in the
formula for advancement _ and into the final against Holland. When
Argentina won, 6-0, Brazilian reporters pointed out that the
Peruvian goalkeeper, Ramon Quiroga, was a native of Argentina.
Quiroga has continued to deny any foul play. FIFA has since changed
the tournament format to single elimination after the first round.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1982 World Cup, a 1-0 victory by West Germany over
Austria sent those two teams to the second round on goal
differential ahead of Algeria. West Germany scored early, and
neither team made any real effort to score again. To avoid this
situation again, FIFA now schedules all final games in the first
round at the same time, so teams cannot know in advance how many
goals will get them to the next round.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Rothenberg, president of the United States Soccer
Federation, said he doubted games would be thrown at the 1998 World
Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I'm the classic, naive American,'' he said, ``but I
believe when players step on the field, they play hard and want to
win.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-06-98 1325EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980606.0097 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-06 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7374 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-DEATHROW-DILEMM     06-06 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-DEATHROW-DILEMMA-845(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN WHO DESERVES TO DIE MAY NOT DESERVE EXECUTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)  (lb) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ As long as there is a death penalty in the United
States, perhaps no man would seem so ripe a candidate for execution
as Henry Lee Lucas, a former drifter now on death row for the rape
and murder of a hitchhiker 19 years ago. The victim, never
identified, was known as ``Orange Socks,'' a reference to the only
items of clothing left on her body when it was discovered in a
culvert off a Texas freeway.
</P>
<P>
   The notorious Lucas is also serving six life terms, two 75-year
terms, and one 60-year term for nine other killings, and in the
1980s he claimed to have committed up to 600 murders across the
United States. ``I filleted some of them like fish,'' was his
gruesome boast.
</P>
<P>
   But as his execution date on June 30 approaches, Texas officials
are grappling with an unusual legal and political problem. While
there is virtually no dispute that the 62-year-old Lucas is a
vicious murderer, there is considerable doubt about whether he
could have committed the one murder for which he was sentenced to
death.
</P>
<P>
   ``My concern is not for Henry Lee Lucas, but for our system of
criminal justice,'' said the state's former attorney general, Jim
Mattox, who reviewed Lucas' case and concluded that signed work
records, interviews with neighbors and a cashed check all offered
compelling evidence that Lucas was in Florida when the Orange Socks
murder occurred.
</P>
<P>
   No physical evidence ever linked Lucas to the scene, and his
conviction was based virtually entirely on his confession, later
recanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Lucas is, of course, a totally unsympathetic individual,''
said Mattox, who is a staunch supporter of the death penalty and
says Lucas may well have deserved death for other crimes. ``But the
question is whether or not the state of Texas should execute
someone they know, in all probability, is not guilty of this
crime.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the attorney general, Dan Morales, told The
Houston Chronicle recently that it was ``not impossible, but highly
improbable'' that Lucas committed the Orange Socks murder.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the questions swirling around Lucas' death sentence,
there has been virtually no groundswell of public support for
stopping Lucas' execution, and Morales himself recently issued a
statement saying it was inappropriate for his office to
``second-guess the jury's determination.''
</P>
<P>
   With Texas leading the nation by far in executions and with many
in the public clamoring for the pace of capital punishment to be
stepped up, some death-penalty experts say they are not surprised
by the lack of attention to Lucas' case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one reason is that the public, in general, tends to be
not all that worried about executing even someone who's innocent,''
said David Dow, a law professor at the University of Houston and an
opponent of the death penalty. ``That phenomenon is magnified to
the nth degree when that person might be innocent of this
particular crime but is not, in the broader moral sense, an
innocent human being.''
</P>
<P>
   While Lucas briefly gained fame as apparently the worst serial
killer in the nation's history, freely offering confessions that
led investigators in more than 20 states to close out unsolved
murders, he later garnered yet more notoriety when he was revealed
to be the perpetrator of an astonishing hoax.
</P>
<P>
   He recanted every single confession except the 1960 slaying of
his 74-year-old mother, Viola. ``I have killed Mother, and that is
the only one,'' he told reporters in 1985. He served 10 years in a
prison and mental institution for the killing.
</P>
<P>
   After an exhaustive review involving state officials around the
country, investigators concluded that Lucas had indeed committed
other murders, but nowhere near the number to which he originally
confessed.
</P>
<P>
   The question now is whether he committed the Orange Socks
killing. No physical evidence or witnesses ever linked him to the
scene, and work records indicate that he was on the job as a roofer
in Florida on the day the murder occurred in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyers argue now that no group of jurors would ever have
convicted him if they had known how discredited many of his
confessions would later come to be, but state and federal courts
have consistently ruled that he received a proper trial at the time
and has no grounds for appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The two prosecutors in Williamson County who put Lucas on death
row say they remain confident that Lucas committed the crime and
was fairly sentenced to death. And they question the political
motives of Mattox, the former attorney general who is currently
running to get his old job back, though it is not immediately clear
how Mattox might gain by sticking up for one of the state's most
nefarious killers in a staunchly pro-death-penalty state.
</P>
<P>
   They say that the work records were forged by the foreman as
part of an elaborate, no-show kickback scheme, and that Lucas had
plenty of time after the murder to drive back to Florida and pick
up his paycheck, which he cashed either one or two days after the
murder occurred, according to bank records.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``He either confessed to a crime that he indeed committed, or
you would have a sheriff who made up the whole thing so that an
innocent man could be executed,'' said Ken Anderson, the county's
district attorney who was an assistant district attorney when he
prosecuted the case. He was referring to the sheriff at the time,
Jim Boutwell, who died several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Walsh, the district attorney who was the chief prosecutor,
said he simply refused to believe that the sheriff coerced a false
confession. ``In my mind, this has always gotten back to Jim
Boutwell,'' said Walsh, who is now in private practice in Round
Rock. ``My opinion of him was very high. I just don't think he
would have ever done something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   In his confession to Boutwell, Lucas said at one point: ``I know
that circumstances show that I didn't do it, but I'm still the
guilty person, regardless of what the circumstances show.''
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging that Lucas had made dozens of false
confessions, Anderson noted that the Orange Socks killing was one
of the first and most detailed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was early on,'' he said. ``Before there was any going to
Dairy Queen and getting hamburgers'' _ a request Lucas sometimes
made to accommodating prosecutors before confessing to their
unsolved murders _ ``there was a confession to this crime.''
</P>
<P>
   With courts having consistently ruled against Lucas, lawyers on
both sides of his case agree that his best hope to be spared
execution lies with the state's clemency process, though any
recommendation for a commutation by the state's Board of Pardons
and Paroles would present a delicate political question for the
state's governor, George W. Bush, who would have the final say on
the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who is running for re-election, has yet to grant clemency
or a pardon to anyone on death row, including Karla Faye Tucker,
who this year became the first woman executed in Texas since the
Civil War and whose case attracted extraordinary attention from
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has made no specific comment on the Lucas case and is
unlikely to do so until the board acts. Linda Edwards, a
spokeswoman for the governor said: ``He first asks is there any
question about the guilt of the individual, and if there is any
question, he'll want to look at the evidence carefully and make
sure the courts have had adequate opportunity to review all the
legal issues involved.''
</P>
<P>
   In its ruling turning down Lucas' appeal in January, the 5th
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in New Orleans said, ``Much of the
evidence alleged by Lucas to be newly discovered is neither new nor
newly discovered, but in its essence and character, was presented
or available to present to the jury.''
</P>
<P>
   Dow, at the University of Houston, said that Lucas ``doesn't
have any chance of generating public sympathy,'' and noted that
even some staunch opponents of capital punishment had not seized on
his case. ``They would have a really tricky time politically,'' he
said, ``trying to use Henry Lee Lucas as a poster boy.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-06-98 1326EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980606.0099 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-06 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7376 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-ROCKEFELLER-CENTER     06-06 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ROCKEFELLER-CENTER-ART-1,000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING A FAMOUS ADDRESS REFLECT THE NEWEST NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-1243 or 1927. A graphic is being sent to NYT graphics
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(mk) 
 By GLENN COLLINS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There are more than 60 empty storefronts at
Rockefeller Center these days, and the 65,000 people who work there
have certainly noticed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right over there, in a little store, that's where I used to
buy my ties,'' said Chuck Riley, a financial planner who works in
an office high above the statue of Atlas on Fifth Avenue. ``One
day, poof, the tie store is gone. The space is still empty, so they
must be losing a bundle. The question is, what do they think they
are doing here?''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Speyer, the man best qualified to answer that question,
says the stores are empty by design, ``just a part of the process''
of resuscitating ``the world's most famous address.''
</P>
<P>
   Only two years ago, this great architectural icon of the 20th
century, a national symbol of New York City's might and swank, was
a limestone-and-glass monument to the humiliation of bankruptcy.
The collapse of office rental rates early in the decade made it
impossible for its former Japanese owner, Mitsubishi Estate Co., to
keep up the mortgage, and it absorbed a $1 billion loss after
filing for Chapter 11 bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Now Speyer, the center's manager and part owner, is trying to
reinvent it as an ornament of the newest of New Yorks, the city of
the great bull market. And he has been pretty busy lately.
</P>
<P>
   As signals of his boom-time ambition, he has asked the
protectors of the city's landmarks for permission to make some
retail-friendly alterations, and he has placed the Rainbow Room,
one of the center's jewels, up for grabs _ to the restaurateur
willing to pay rent of $4 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   He has persuaded Christie's to abandon Madison Avenue for 49th
Street and Cablevision to take up residence at the Radio City Music
Hall, with ambitious plans for restoration, television production
and a lot more. And he has brought office occupancy to 96 percent,
from 86 percent in 1996, and spent $20 million of a promised $100
million refurbishing the 12-building core of the complex.
</P>
<P>
   But the sum of his grand vision is this: to turn Rockefeller
Center into a year-round magnet for high-end shoppers as well as
tourists and office workers, a destination for restaurant- and
entertainment-seekers that is also a power center of video-industry
production. At night, the city-within-a-city will be driven, he
says, by the busiest theater in the world, the grandly spruced up
and polished Radio City.
</P>
<P>
   So compelling will be its glitzy gravity, he contends, that the
new center will upgrade Manhattan's retailing milieu southward on
Fifth Avenue and westward all the way to Times Square, just as
Lincoln Center transformed the Upper West Side of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   But, the critics wonder, can he do it?
</P>
<P>
   Can the realities of Rockefeller Center square with Speyer's
vision of a palace of affluence? Will tourists and tourist-wary New
Yorkers really mix? Given the revival of nearby Times Square, is
there enough boom to go around? And what will happen if the stock
market heads south?
</P>
<P>
   Owners Say Vacancies Foretell Future Deals
</P>
<P>
   If the empty shops suggest a slow transition to the new
Rockefeller Center, the owners are whistling a happy tune. ``You
see vacancies, but we see excitement, activity and deals,'' said
Daniel Neidich, a partner of Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., the center's
principal owner, along with Tishman Speyer, David Rockefeller and
members of the Agnelli and Niarchos families. ``Right now our
biggest worry is not that we have vacancies but that we will run
out of space.''
</P>
<P>
   Very expensive space: The prime leases on Fifth Avenue and the
Channel Garden used to go for a top price of $300 per square foot,
but recently Tishman Speyer, the company that the 57-year-old
Speyer heads, has been asking $500.
</P>
<P>
   Some brokers say they can get it, because large retail blocks in
midtown Manhattan are rarities. ``I think there are more potential
tenants than they have space,'' said Faith Hope Consolo, a senior
managing director of Garrick-Aug Worldwide Ltd. ``People just want
to kill to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Ann Tighe, a broker at Insignia/Edward S. Gordon Co., said
that Tishman Speyer had already rejected some prospective stores
that do not attract ``all day'' crowds ``because they don't want
tenants that create a dead spot for part of the day,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In promoting the center, Tishman Speyer has assets that do not
meet the eye. Roadways, loading docks and storage rooms under the
center were carved deeply into the bedrock in the 1930s and can
save retailers money ``because so much of the backstage work can be
done without worrying about loading or unloading in traffic,'' Ms.
Tighe said.
</P>
<P>
   But other brokers are less sanguine. ``The place is neither fish
nor fowl,'' said one who insisted upon anonymity. She said the
center ``still has a musty feel'' thanks to its traditional
hodgepodge of bargain stores and tourist emporiums. And she
questioned whether affluent shoppers can ever find it truly chic as
they jostle with hordes of fanny-packed tourists in shorts.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, prospective tenants for the center's 510,000 square
feet of retail space include not Cartier, Ferragamo or Hermes, but
rather Banana Republic _ which already has a flagship store two
blocks away _ and Sephora, the European cosmetics chain.
</P>
<P>
   And next month NBC is expected to announce its expansion into a
vacant two-and-a-half-level former bank branch in 30 Rockefeller
Plaza, across 49th Street from the studio home of the ``Today''
show.
</P>
<P>
   To be called ``The NBC Experience at Rockefeller Center,'' it
will offer a 3-D theater, a cybercafe and displays of NBC
memorabilia, while serving as a staging area for studio tours and a
venue for merchandising T-shirts, hats and Peacockiana.
</P>
<P>
   Brokers say other interested retailers include Old Navy, T.J.
Maxx and a possible Saks Fifth Avenue satellite. The strategy,
brokers and Rockefeller Center officials say, is to sell large
blocks of retail space to at least five blue-chip retailing names,
establishing anchor sites. All Speyer would say is that ``it's like
working on a mosaic.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Objections to Changing a Building's Experience
</P>
<P>
   The final roster of retail tenants is hanging fire, waiting for
the Landmarks Preservation Commission to consider Rockefeller
Center's grand plan. The center's owners want to accommodate
merchants' penchant for multilevel stores by enlarging the center's
one-story Fifth Avenue storefronts to two-story glass bays. And
they hope to create new entrances to the underground shopping
concourse from the Lower Plaza by encroaching on the
granite-backdrop-and-basin setting of the center's cynosure, the
gilt statue of Prometheus.
</P>
<P>
   The commission will vote on the proposal this month.
</P>
<P>
   Some preservationists have opposed such alterations to what they
call an esthetic masterpiece. The proposed bays ``seem like a small
thing, but can make a major change in the experience of the
building,'' Eric Allison, president of the Historic Districts
Council, said.
</P>
<P>
   David Rockefeller, however, sees things differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the bays change the basic character in any
way,'' said Rockefeller, the patriarch of the clan that gave the
center its name and currently owns 5 percent of it.
</P>
<P>
   Speyer, he said, ``is showing great imagination'' in managing
the Art Deco complex, built in the 1930s at a cost of $125 million.
</P>
<P>
   Speyer would not comment on the preservationists' objections,
save to say, ``We will not be bringing chrome to Rockefeller
Center, I promise you.''
</P>
<P>
   He made it clear that he would not tamper with the center's
classic elements: its ice rink, Channel Gardens and annual
Christmas tree festivities.
</P>
<P>
   Center's Manager Sees a New Urban Square
</P>
<P>
   To Speyer, Rockefeller Center is nothing less than ``the hub of
the wheel.'' ``It is the epicenter of New York City, the link
between upper Fifth and lower Fifth. If we are successful, we can
bring Fifth Avenue back, right down to Lord &AMP; Taylor, and all the
way to the Empire State Building. And that would be quite an
achievement.''
</P>
<P>
   Speyer's impulse harks back to the center's original purpose, to
create an urban square ``that will make the immediate surroundings
the most valuable shopping district in the world,'' according to
1928 Rockefeller family documents.
</P>
<P>
   But Speyer's detractors insist that rather than some grand plan
to save a stretch of Fifth Avenue, he is driven primarily by an
urgent financial imperative: High rents are needed to pay interest
on the owners' loans and earn the investors a sought-after 20
percent return on their $306 million purchase price. Speyer
counters that he is creating ``the right mix'' after years of
dogged preliminary moves.
</P>
<P>
   Speyer has won high marks even from critics for two key deals:
landing Christie's and finding a tenant for Radio City. By early
1999, Christie's will consolidate its offices and auction space on
49th Street between Fifth Avenue and the Avenue of the Americas.
</P>
<P>
   Speyer is giving both new tenants extraordinary latitude. For
example, Christie's has the right to close Rockefeller Plaza at
night ``and to treat it as a private street for dropping off
customers'' at major evening sales, said Patricia Hambrecht,
president of Christie's in North and South America.
</P>
<P>
   Christie's may also collaborate with Cablevision Systems Corp.,
which has leased Radio City Music Hall for $13 million per year.
Cablevision plans to spend more than $25 million renovating the
65-year-old concert hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be far and away the busiest theater in the world when
we're done,'' said Dave Checketts, president and chief executive of
Madison Square Garden, a subsidiary of Cablevision.
</P>
<P>
   He said Radio City would also become the new headquarters of
American Movie Classics, one of Cablevision's cable channels.
Cablevision also plans to build a television production facility in
Radio City space, and will use the hall's stage for productions.
</P>
<P>
   Many Merchants Are Facing Uncertainty
</P>
<P>
   But banished from this hive of worker bees is a horde of
dispossessed merchants. ``My father and I spent our lives there; we
really felt part of the Rockefeller Center family,'' said Arthur
Sogno, a jeweler, whose father was one of the first retail tenants.
The center's management did not renew his lease, forcing him to
leave more than a year ago. The store is still vacant.
</P>
<P>
   Many remaining tenants have been given their walking papers.
``They are saying I could be out by September,'' said Jerolim
Vukich, the owner of a bustling nine-chair barbershop on the
concourse level, who may be offered a more expensive space in a
less-trafficked area. ``I hope my customers will still need their
Jerry.''
</P>
<P>
   The center has its own uncertainties to face. It will continue
to require costly improvements and has high operating costs.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, restaurant veterans wonder whether the owners can
have a successful late-night restaurant-and-retail operation where
there is no residential base.
</P>
<P>
   The owners are negotiating with Restaurant Associates to create
new dining concepts in the center. And to enhance the profitability
of the Rainbow Room, the owners will eject the current operators,
who balked at paying a huge increase in their $2.8 million annual
rent.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rockefeller Center neighborhood, dominated at night by
the shuttered Saks, St. Patrick's Cathedral and a stand of ghostly
office buildings, is ``one of the few places in Manhattan where the
sidewalk rolls up at night,'' said one neighborhood merchant who
spoke on the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   In the coming months, no formal Rockefeller Center master plan
is likely to be trumpeted, ``but we have a clear vision that is
evolving,'' Speyer said. Successful or not, that vision will try to
capitalize on Rockefeller Center's special status.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the Empire State Building or Wall Street,'' Barry
Bull, a tourist from Brisbane, Australia, said on a recent
afternoon. ``If you haven't seen Rockefeller Center, you haven't
seen New York.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
