<HEADER>
A7386 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-U.S.-ANTHRAX-NYT     06-06 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-U.S.-ANTHRAX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRAQIS' IMMUNITY TO ANTHRAX RAISED U.S. FEARS, BOOK SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EXCLUSIVE; 4 p.m. ET EMBARGO for print media; 7 p.m. ET EMBARGO
for electronic media.) 
(mk) 
 By WILLIAM J. BROAD    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just before the 1991 Persian Gulf War, the American military
discovered that Iraqi soldiers captured in a covert operation had
immunity to deadly anthrax, heightening fears in Washington that
Baghdad was preparing to wage germ warfare, a new book says.
</P>
<P>
   The book, ``Against All Enemies: Gulf War Syndrome: The War
Between America's Ailing Veterans and Their Government''
(Ballantine) by Seymour Hersh, says the secret finding of Iraqi
immunity played a role in accelerating the Pentagon's crash program
to vaccinate American troops against anthrax before the war.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, some 150,000 coalition soldiers were immunized
against the disease. Anthrax normally afflicts animals like cattle
and sheep, but it can kill humans.
</P>
<P>
   The death rate for untreated pulmonary anthrax is more than 90
percent. Pentagon officials feared an Iraqi germ attack could kill
up to 200,000 American troops, the book says.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq invaded Kuwait in August 1990, setting off an international
crisis. In February 1991, an American-led coalition expelled Iraqi
troops in a ground war that saw no known use of biological weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Hersh, an investigative journalist, says in the book that an
elite American team penetrated deep into Iraq before the war and
kidnapped several Iraqi soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews, a retired American military official and a gulf
war veteran both affirmed that a secret abduction had taken place.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty well known, but not the specifics,'' said Jim
Brown, an Army veteran who lives in Hannibal, Mo., and is director
of Gulf Watch, a veterans advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was actively going on behind Iraqi lines,'' said the
retired military official, who held a senior post during the war
and spoke on the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   In the book, Hersh says blood samples drawn from the captured
Iraqi troops showed ``they had recently built up an immunity to
anthrax,'' one of the deadliest agents for biological warfare.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon was uncertain, he added, whether the Iraqis had
been inoculated with anthrax vaccine or had developed a natural
immunity to the disease, which occurs in animal populations in
parts of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   ``Military planning had to assume the worst-case scenario _ that
the Iraqis would not be affected by a biological attack,'' he
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   A formerly secret document declassified in 1996 by the Army, a
chronology of germ actions and analyses during the gulf war,
suggests that Pentagon officials were deeply interested in Iraqi
blood samples and what they might reveal about Baghdad's
preparations for germ warfare. The document was recently obtained
by The New York Times from Veterans for Integrity in government, a
group based in Centreville, Va.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defectors from Iraqi Republican Guards still in custody of
Saudis,'' the document says in a note dated Nov. 21, 1990 _ before
the war. ``Blood would reveal types and strains of BW agents they
have been protected against,'' the ``BW'' referring to biological
warfare.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1980s, American military and intelligence officials
gathered much circumstantial evidence that Iraq had embarked on a
large program to make germ weapons, but the intelligence was
generally vague.
</P>
<P>
   In the months before the gulf war, American officials were
unsure whether Iraq was ready and willing to use germ weapons.
Thus, at least in theory, the blood samples offered key evidence of
Iraq's intentions. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-06-98 1358EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980606.0103 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-06 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7387 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-PREACHERS-645     06-06 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PREACHERS-645&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORALITY MISSION FACES CAPITAL REALITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Calif., Ohio)  (lb) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Soon after an opening riff of Scripture resounded
down the stony corridors of power this week, the gathering of
preachers _ all fired up to lobby on the themes of social morality
and the poor _ sadly confronted the Monica Monomania that grips the
national capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``The moral whirligig!'' one visiting minister snarled
dismissively. He was taking the spiritual measure of a city now
peddling ``White House Intern'' souvenir T-shirts, smutty
Bill-and-Monica greeting cards and various other anecdotal evidence
that the dissing of President Clinton is trying to quietly steal
into place as his long-sought legacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``God is calling us to talk about morality, not the morality of
the president,'' thundered one minister, the Rev. Yvonne Delk of
Chicago, pulpit-thumping in a Capitol office on behalf of poor
families now being ushered from welfare rolls across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Only one member of Congress stopped in during a daylong
preach-in by dozens of visiting ministers as the ceaseless
investigation into accusations about sex and mendacity at the White
House maintained its grip on the political capital.
</P>
<P>
   Attention was being paid elsewhere: Fresh lawyers were being
celebrated as they entered the fray like reinforcements for George
Orwell's armies that endlessly tugged back and forth on television
in his ``1984'' vision of a transfixed state.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd gathered on Connecticut Avenue to gape at a live
sighting of Monica Lewinsky, the former White House intern, now
ending her fifth month of enigmatic smiles before the nation. Fresh
strategies were afoot as the independent counsel stalked the
president. The photo-op comings and goings at the grand jury
continued apace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to figure out whether or not Americans really do
give a damn about public morality,'' boomed the Rev. William
Pannell of Fuller Theological Seminary in Pasadena, Calif.,
despairing of the ``whirligig'' he finds here.
</P>
<P>
   Official Washington showed the ministers no mercy as they
preached and sang, since disrespecting the president seems a
capital subtheme taken for granted now as the months of
investigation roll forward.
</P>
<P>
   A recent advertisement by the Washington Sports Clubs was
headlined ``Attention Bill Clinton: We too have a no-commitment
policy.'' Plastic place mats have appeared of a news photograph of
a parade float in Germany that depicted a papier-mache Clinton
groping an offended Miss Liberty. In idle moments, Washingtonians
can vie with the rest of Internet America in a rude limerick
competition rhyming Lewinsky and Kaczynski, the intern and the
Unabomber, at Clinton's expense.
</P>
<P>
   A country singer felt emboldened enough at a recent luncheon
honoring Hillary Rodham Clinton to serenade the first lady with
such songs as ``You Ain't Woman Enough to Take My Man'' and ``Is
This the Thanks I Get After All I've Done for You?'' A local
editorial cartoonist has refined his image of the president down to
a merry raincoat-clad exhibitionist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton's completely out of the game,'' said the Rev. Jim
Wallis, one of the hosts of the preach-in, regretfully insisting
the president had lost his edge on moral issues under the weight of
all the accusations, investigations and shameful mockeries.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is this paralysis here in the political process, a civic
poverty,'' said Wallis, who knows Washington well as the editor
here of ``Sojourners,'' a religious magazine, and as the organizer
of Call to Renewal, a broad array of churches fighting poverty and
racism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Clinton could have taken us to a different level on so
many things, the issue of race, for example, but nothing's come of
it,'' Wallis said. ``The great shame is that all our so-called
moral attention is focused on alleged White House sex scandals and
not on tremendous tasks like integrating the poorest families into
our midst.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   By the end of their preach-in, ministers were pronouncing
capital politicians oblivious to the warning that there is growing
evidence of poor families' suffering inordinately from the 1996
overhauling of the federal welfare system.
</P>
<P>
   Sheaves of press releases citing statistics about the dearth of
jobs for postwelfare recipients went unread. The antennas of news
television stayed resolutely elsewhere, staking out the Lewinsky
case. They rose delicately toward the heavens above the grand jury,
as if in search of intelligent life elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Not all the preach-in participants found Clinton a singular
drain on the moral agenda. ``You can't just point the finger at the
president,'' said the lone member of Congress who showed up, Tony
Hall, D-Ohio, just back from a tour of poverty in Africa. ``It's a
number of factors, including both parties' losing their edge in
their ability to even talk about the poor.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall said the change in the welfare law let politicians off the
moral hook so they could ignore poverty in the rest of the country
while the scandal hunts go forward in the capital. ``I recently
toured rural Appalachia and saw 1,200 people lined up at a
food-bank soup kitchen,'' he said. ``I was shocked; 1,200 working
poor, not welfare cases. And my colleagues refuse to believe me
when I try and tell them.''
</P>
<P>
   Lately, utterances of despair about the capital's monomania can
even be heard from principals participating in television's nightly
verbal slugfests over the Lewinsky investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The connect-the-dot story inches forward,'' said Lanny Davis,
a former White House special counsel who is still addicted, he
admits, to the blandishments of celebrity. ``I go on again with the
pundit gang, and you know what? We'll walk out after the show, look
at each other, and say, `Don't you feel unclean?''' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-06-98 1400EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980606.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-06 14:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7388 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEB-HAGEL-TRADE-ART-N     06-06 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEB-HAGEL-TRADE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZEALOUS FRESHMAN SEES SENATE THINKING GLOBAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Neb., Miss., W.Va., Ill., Alaska)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(bl) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST POINT, Neb. _ At Harry Knobbe's Feed Yards the other day,
Sen. Chuck Hagel was holding forth on the global economy, the Asian
financial crisis and the International Monetary Fund with a dozen
or so hog and cattle farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Cuming County, one of the largest cattle-producing
counties in the United States, the farmers were hanging on every
word.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the markets go down in Asia, it's not good for the United
States and it's not good for Nebraska,'' Hagel said over sodas and
sugar cookies, drawing approving nods and murmurs. ``They can't buy
your beef, pork and feed grains.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting his fellow senators to focus on international matters is
a lot tougher than holding that discussion with farmers in a state
that exports $1.6 billion worth of farm products to Asia each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of my colleagues don't understand foreign affairs, they
don't travel, they don't get out,'' Hagel said later. ``They're
scared of taking trips that will be labeled political junkets. They
don't have much interest, and they don't see the relevancy.''
</P>
<P>
   Translating the lexicon of Washington foreign policy into
nuts-and-bolts realities for constituents and other senators is a
steep challenge for Hagel. But even as the freshman Republican on
the Foreign Relations Committee, ranked 98th in seniority out of
100 senators, he is proving an influential new voice in foreign
affairs.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when the country is looking inward, Hagel, a
51-year-old self-made millionaire, is preaching the virtues of
internationalism to Congress and the public.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting his pro-business conservatism, he told a group of
Omaha mortgage bankers, ``Foreign policy is not some theoretical,
esoteric, Kissinger-esque thing hanging out there. It's foreign
trade.''
</P>
<P>
   As crises from Kosovo to Pakistan threaten stability, Hagel
says, ``now is the time for America to project its leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   In less than 18 months, Hagel has helped broker a deal among his
colleagues for approval of $18 billion in new financing for the
International Monetary Fund. He forged an unusual alliance with
Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., to counter the administration's backing
of a treaty to combat global warming. And Hagel, an Army veteran
twice wounded in Vietnam, has fought against the Pentagon's use of
antipersonnel land mines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I know of any freshman senator since I've been
here who's done better work than he has,'' Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott, a longtime friend of Hagel's, said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Hagel has earned a reputation as a blunt consensus-builder who
is willing to reach out to Democrats to cut a deal. ``He's
conservative,'' said Sen. Richard Durbin, D-Ill., who drafted a
health insurance bill with Hagel. ``But he's not one of the
fire-breathing, steely ideologues.''
</P>
<P>
   Hagel has also shown that he is not afraid to buck fellow
conservatives on international security issues. He was an early
supporter last year of the treaty to ban the use and production of
poison gas, despite stiff opposition from rightist groups.
</P>
<P>
   Lott credits Hagel with influencing his decision to back the
chemical weapons treaty. ``When I was getting really criticized by
some of my own people,'' Lott said, ``Hagel gave me a handwritten
note that said: `Don't let the ankle-biters get you down. Do what's
right, and I'm with you.'''
</P>
<P>
   Hagel has his critics _ particularly environmentalists who
oppose his position on the global warming treaty. ``Hagel seems to
be a new leader of the head-in-the-sand crowd on Capitol Hill who
want to ignore critical environmental problems,'' said Gene
Karpinski, executive director of U.S. Public Interest Research
Group.
</P>
<P>
   The senator started his political career in the early 1970s as
an aide to Rep. John McCollister, R-Neb. There he struck up some
valuable friendships: another young House aide named Trent Lott,
and a young Republican congressman, Thad Cochran, now the senior
senator from Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   During Ronald Reagan's presidency, Hagel served as deputy
administrator of the Veterans Administration and was an influential
backer of the Vietnam Veterans Memorial. Leaving government, he
became a founder of what grew into a large cellular telephone
company, Vanguard Cellular Systems.
</P>
<P>
   In the emerging cell-phone business, and in consulting work
later, Hagel became an outspoken supporter of free trade,
installing cellular systems in Costa Rica, Saudi Arabia and
Britain. He puts his net worth at about $6 million.
</P>
<P>
   A long-shot candidate for the Senate in 1996, he upset the
popular Democratic governor, Ben Nelson. With his military and
overseas-trade background, he took aim at his first committee
choice: Foreign Relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't hard to get,'' said Hagel, who is chairman of the
International Economic Policy, Export and Trade Promotion
Subcommittee. ``No one wanted to be on Foreign Relations.''
</P>
<P>
   From his sometimes lonely bully pulpit on the committee, he has
criticized the Clinton administration and its national security
policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure the president has ever had a philosophy about
foreign policy or thought through what role the United States
should have in the world,'' he said. ``The administration's foreign
policy has been to ricochet from crisis to crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   Hagel's biggest challenge was shepherding the $18 billion
financing for the IMF through a skeptical Senate, a task Lott
assigned him. Hagel learned a lesson in Senate hardball when
opponents of the financing went around him to attach conditions
that would have killed a delicate compromise.
</P>
<P>
   He enlisted a powerful ally, Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska,
chairman of the Appropriations Committee, to restore the original
deal. The financing passed, 84-16, but the House has bottled up the
package.
</P>
<P>
   Back in Nebraska, Hagel finds support for the IMF among big
exporters like Valmont Industries, an irrigation equipment and
lighting pole manufacturer in the town of Valley. For these
executives, the $18 billion for the IMF is not even an issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``If not the IMF, who would do it?'' asked Valmont chairman
Mogens Bay. ``The United States can't do it alone.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
