u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-DILEMMA-N     06-06 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-DILEMMA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREMORS KEEP ROCKING THE DODGERS' CLUBHOUSE AND FRONT OFFICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let the Dodgers' season begin. If you're Fred Claire, you're
saying, ``Please let our season begin.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking the other day, Claire, the Los Angeles Dodgers'
beleaguered general manager, actually said: ``We're starting our
season on the fifth of June. I want to let this club play for a
couple of months. Normally, the first couple of months would be
April and May. Our first two months will be June and July. We have
good talent. I want to give it a chance to settle in.''
</P>
<P>
   Like a city shaken by earthquakes and aftershocks, the Dodgers
hope they can now relax, regroup and recover from the series of
tremors that struck them in the space of three weeks. The
blockbuster trade that sent Mike Piazza away was the big one that
registered high on the Richter scale. The pursuit of Randy Johnson,
the erroneous news reports that emanated from it, other wild and
equally inaccurate reports and the trade of Hideo Nomo were the
aftershocks.
</P>
<P>
   Claire met with the players before their game last Tuesday night
to explain various matters, including his own status, and to tell
them where the team was headed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was letting them know I believe in this team and I felt we
had to give this team a chance to settle down in view of all that
had happened,'' he said. ``No team could go out and play in the
environment we had. We were totally disrupted. I felt like we were
the Yankees.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers began interleague play with a record that was one
game under .500 at 29-30. They haven't been more than one game over
.500 in a month. They experienced a winning spurt after Gary
Sheffield, Bobby Bonilla and Charles Johnson joined their lineup
from the Marlins in place of Piazza and Todd Zeile but quickly
squandered their gain with a four-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   The Piazza trade, while intended to ignite the lethargic,
underachieving Dodgers, created a problem in the team's operations.
Claire, who is in his 12th season as general manager, did not make
the deal. Chase Carey, one of the Fox executives who oversee the
team, put it together in conversations with Don Smiley, the Florida
Marlins' president. Claire was reluctant to discuss the issue, but
felt it was major enough to make it one point in his address to the
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the long run,'' he said in a telephone interview, ``that
will be beneficial for our baseball organization because I think
even the Fox people would acknowledge that could have happened in a
different fashion. In summary of that, if your general manager
isn't being held totally responsible, then that's not a good
situation. I believe in responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Graziano, the Dodgers executive whom Fox named president
when it bought the team from the O'Malley family, acknowledged that
the ``mechanics could have been handled better.'' But, he added,
``We have assured people it was an aberration, a one-time type of
deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Claire was indeed the club official trying to pry Johnson from
the Seattle Mariners. But his efforts led to two television reports
that proved to be 100 percent wrong. The first report had a deal
virtually done in which the Mariners would have got Nomo and
outfielder Todd Hollandsworth.
</P>
<P>
   Claire heard about it when Don Nomura, Nomo's agent, awoke him
at 3 a.m. after he had returned with the team from a road trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a story on a completed trade where we had never
mentioned either player to Seattle at that point in time,'' Claire
said. ``That's a great part of what fanned this fire. There wasn't
a night when there weren't 50 to 100 media people on the field
before the game. If anyone says our team wasn't distracted, just
look down on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Less than a week later, a second report had a Johnson trade
virtually completed for Ismael Valdes and Wilton Guerrero. Except
the report came after the Dodgers' deadline for a trade passed
without response from the Mariners on Claire's proposal.
</P>
<P>
   With Johnson no longer a factor in the Dodgers' plans, Claire
turned his attention to trading Nomo, whose request for a trade and
subsequent designation for assignment threw another bomb into the
team's on-field efforts. After the unhappy pitcher was traded
Thursday night, a newspaper report introduced another element into
the front office situation.
</P>
<P>
   Claire, the report said, had been told to trade Nomo to the Mets
by Peter O'Malley, who remains chairman of the Dodgers. Claire
could not have denied that report more vehemently.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely totally false,'' he said. ``In 12 years as general
manager, right up to today, Peter never one single time ever
instructed me on a player transaction to do anything. He always
gave me full, total, complete responsibility. This idea that he
instructed me to do anything is absolutely false.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet another newspaper report last week triggered a seismic jolt.
It said that Marlins general manager Dave Dombrowski and manager
Jim Leyland would replace Claire and manager Bill Russell.
</P>
<P>
   Claire called the report a nonissue. ``My main concern was to
get Bill Russell settled down,'' he said, ``but it was hard for me
to settle him down when I was in the same story.''
</P>
<P>
   A Fox official and Graziano said there was no basis to the
report. ``With the change in ownership, there's all kinds of
speculation,'' Graziano said, ``just as there was when we were
going through the sale process. We have not contemplated any
changes. It has not been discussed.''
</P>
<P>
   The end of the season, Graziano said, will be a time for
evaluation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always gone through an evaluation at the end of the
year,'' he said. ``Peter O'Malley did it at the end of last year,
an evaluation of how the team ended up and are we positioned
properly for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   First, though, the Dodgers want to concentrate on the rest of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not to say I won't take phone calls,'' Claire said, ``but I'll
guarantee you that trade rumors involving the Dodgers won't stem
from any calls I make in the near future. Give this team a chance
to see what we're all about. It never could happen in the
environment we were in.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
