<HEADLINE>
THE NEXT MIKE PIAZZA?  
 THE AGENT NO ONE WANTS TO DEAL WITH  
 HALL OF FAME AND THE UNION 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Next Mike Piazza?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, Mike Piazza was No. 1,390 in the amateur draft.
Last week, Aaron Alvarez was the 1,390th player drafted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh really? Oh my gosh,'' a stunned Alvarez exclaimed when he
learned that he was Piazza a decade later. ``I'm a catcher, too.
Well, we'll see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez, a high school senior from Duluth, Ga., an Atlanta
suburb, was chosen by the Florida Marlins in the 47th round. He was
hoping the Braves would pick him, but he was excited nonetheless.
``I'm still on Cloud 9,'' he said. ``It's been a dream.''
</P>
<P>
   The 18-year-old Alvarez said he spent the past season working on
his defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't start catching until I was 13,'' he said. ``I
couldn't stand catching. But my rec team didn't pick a catcher for
the team, and I was the biggest one on the team and they asked me
to catch. I said I'd try it for a game, and I loved it and never
quit.''
</P>
<P>
   He plans to spend at least a year at Middle Georgia Junior
College working on his offense. ``The Marlins want to see me get a
little better with my offense,'' he said. ``They drafted me for my
defense. They have me under draft control. If I do good enough next
year, they can still sign me before next year's draft. If I think I
can do better, I'll go back into the draft.''
</P>
<P>
   But then he wouldn't be No. 1,390.
</P>
<P>
   The Agent No One Wants to Deal With  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Scott Boras, the agent whose $10 million demand the past year
sent J.D. Drew through the draft a second time, continues to be the
scourge of the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you do your draft board,'' one general manager said,
``you mark the guys who may play football or go to college. Now you
have to add Boras clients.''
</P>
<P>
   Five players were selected lower than the possible first-round
picks they had been projected to be because clubs thought they were
Boras clients. The two left hanging the longest were Mark Teixeira,
a third baseman, whom Baseball America rated as the 12th-best
position player, and Brian Sager, who was ranked 22nd among
pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Boston took Teixeira in the ninth round as the 265th player
selected, and Arizona drafted Sager No. 403 in the 13th round.
</P>
<P>
   Hall of Fame and the Union  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Hall of Fame has opened an exhibit marking an enlightened
departure from the baseball establishment's usual thinking. It
depicts the labor relationship between owners and players
throughout the game's history and acknowledges the impact made by
Marvin Miller and the Players Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``Workers have a long history of organizing and acting together
to achieve better working conditions and better pay,'' the exhibit
notes. ``The relationship between professional baseball players and
team owners is similar to that of other American workers and
business owners.''
</P>
<P>
   After hearing part of the exhibit text, Miller pronounced it
``pretty fair, pretty accurate.'' After hearing the exhibit's
description of the reserve clause, which before free agency left
players at the mercy of their employers, the retired labor leader
said: ``That's pretty good. That's not bad. At least it says what
it was.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
