<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, June 7, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Early Saturday, the temperature at Amarillo, Texas, dropped to a
record 41 degrees, marking the town's fourth coldest June reading
on record. The trail of record chill extended north along the
western High Plains and the Front Range of the Rockies to Denver
and Casper, Wyo., where the thermometer registered 34 and 30
degrees respectively. The cold dawn was fostered by a seasonably
strong high pressure system with a barometric pressure near 30.21
inches of mercury.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the stalwart high will become a chameleon Sunday as
it drifts toward the Tennessee Valley, pumping warmer, more humid
air northward into areas it chilled less than 24 hours earlier. As
a result, scattered showers and thunderstorms will flare from
western Texas to western Kansas along a boundary that separates dry
air from the Rockies and returning Gulf moisture.
</P>
<P>
   Another area of showers and thunderstorms will develop across
northern Kansas, western Nebraska, northeast Colorado, southern and
western South Dakota and eastern Wyoming as a disturbance racing
ahead of an upper-level low over Nevada lifts returning moisture.
</P>
<P>
   The Nevada low will spark scattered showers and thunderstorms
from California's central Sierra Nevada eastward to parts of Idaho,
western Wyoming and Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a pool of high-altitude cold air will swing east from
the Great Lakes, setting the stage for cool showers across the
Northeast, with snow showers at high elevations in the Adirondacks
of New York. Farther south, isolated thunderstorms will speckle
southern Florida. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: HUMID BUT DRY
</P>
<P>
   In the steamy air that settled over the Texas coast, nighttime
temperatures have been stifling. Friday morning, with the air
teeming with water vapor, the low temperature at Corpus Christi was
81 degrees. Despite the recent rash of high humidity, rain has been
sparse. Indeed, the .01 inches of rain that fell late Friday ended
a dry streak of 38 days. The last time it rained was April 27, when
a scant .02 inches were measured. Moreover, since March 17, only
.05 inches had fallen before Friday's sprinkle, marking the city's
second longest period with a total of .05 inches of rain or less. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
