<HEADLINE>
FOR LANCE ARMSTRONG, EVERY DAY IS A SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Pa.)  (bl) 
 By FRANK LITSKY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ There were times during that awful siege when
Lance Armstrong, whose self-confidence had always matched his
extraordinary cycling ability, was not sure he would live, let
alone race again. The testicular cancer he had ignored had spread
to his abdomen and brain, and doctors gave him at best a 50-50
chance to survive.
</P>
<P>
   After surgery in October 1996, extensive chemotherapy and 18
months away from competition, he has survived and is racing again.
But the ordeal has changed him.
</P>
<P>
   He is no longer the brash wunderkind who, at age 21, won the
world and U.S. professional road-racing championships and a stage
of the Tour de France. At 26, the brashness has diminished, partly
because of his health travails, partly because of natural maturity,
partly because of the added responsibilities of his recent
marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Partly, too, because he had seldom wondered about his future.
Now he wonders. To start with, he is unsure what will make his
comeback successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all relative,'' he said in an interview this week.
``How do you relate a success or failure? Do I get back to the
level I was at previously? No. That probably will never be. But I
survived a deadly illness when I should have died. That's success,
so it wouldn't be fair to call my return a failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's uncertain. It will be very tough and I'm just very
cautious. I want to be realistic. I don't want to raise my
expectations too high and be disappointed. It's better to be
conservative and shoot for minor objectives for now. It's really
like starting over.''
</P>
<P>
   The starting over began in March in the seven-day Paris-Nice
race in France. Halfway through the first day, he realized his mind
was not ready, so he quit the race and returned home to train more.
</P>
<P>
   Now he is back, stronger mentally and physically. He is the
leader of the U.S. Postal Service team, one of the favorites in
Sunday's $120,160 U.S. pro championship in Philadelphia. The
156-mile race, with 10 trips up the Manayunk Wall and its 17
percent grade, is built for the old Armstrong, but race fitness
comes through extensive racing, and he is not there yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started training again in February,'' he said, ``my
lack of fitness gnawed at me. It's in perspective now. It's not
going to come back overnight. I'm sure it will come back if I give
it enough time, but I don't know how much time is enough. It's
better to do a day at a time. I can see just riding out this year
and creating some base. The early indication is that it's not
impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong was fit enough to have raced Tuesday in Lancaster,
Pa.; Wednesday in Wilmington, Del., and Thursday in Trenton, N.J.
He finished second in Lancaster to Frankie Andreu, a longtime
teammate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lancaster wasn't a World Cup or anything,'' Armstrong said,
``but I hadn't done seven race days this year and most riders there
had done 30 or 40. But clearly I was in the race. If that is any
indication, I can come back.''
</P>
<P>
   That Lancaster performance impressed Andreu.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's doing good,'' Andreu said. ``He's a little more relaxed
than he used to be, but I don't know if he's enjoying it more.
Maybe he doesn't feel he's under as much pressure. Before, he felt
he had to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Gorski, the manager of the Postal Service team, said
Armstrong had made immense progress in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's doing great,'' Gorski said. ``I think he's adjusted. In
Paris-Nice, he learned he was not ready to compete at his old level
and may never be. I think he has accepted that. I think he's at
peace with himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he will be back to his old level, and I'm not
disappointed in that. What he's doing now is a huge accomplishment.
It would be unfair to him to expect more.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there are new interests. Last week, the Lance
Armstrong Foundation for cancer research, awareness and education
grossed almost half a million dollars in fund-raisers in Austin,
Texas, where Armstrong lives.
</P>
<P>
   Here, he visited with cancer patients at a children's hospital
Friday and took part in a cancer-facility fund-raiser Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I leave a hospital,'' he said, ``I feel so thankful that
I was once there and lived that life and have come out of it and am
hopefully cured. At the same time, it's always hard for me because
I relate. I don't think I'm that far from going back.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
