<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: MORE FROM THE BIG BLUFFER IN THE BRONX 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The voice is familiar. So is its blustery bluff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politics,'' the voice growled, ``has driven more teams from
New York City than any of us care to remember, most recently the
football Giants and Jets to New Jersey. I do not want to move the
Yankees from New York, but I must warn: he is bringing us
dangerously close.''
</P>
<P>
   The voice is that of George Steinbrenner and ``he'' is Peter
Vallone, the City Council speaker who has dared to disagree with
the Yankees' principal owner over New York's civic wisdom in the
much debated issue of building a new ball park for the Yankees on
Manhattan's West Side. To the principal owner, Vallone's
unpardonable sin was suggesting a referendum on whether city money
should be used to build new ball parks for both the Yankees and the
Mets.
</P>
<P>
   To that familiar voice, the City Council speaker, in defiance of
the principal owner's pal in a Yankee cap and Yankee jacket, Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani, dared to want to put to a taxpayers' vote whether
maybe as much as $600 million of taxpayers' money be gift-wrapped
for ball parks.
</P>
<P>
   At least the Mets' owners have indicated a willingness to
contribute a fair share toward the cost of a new stadium near Shea
Stadium. But as yet, the familiar voice of the Yankees' principal
owner has not been heard offering any whip-out to defray any cost.
</P>
<P>
   To listen to that familiar voice bark that the City Council
speaker is just trying to hype his gubernatorial campaign, you
would think the principal owner was referring to a Yankee manager,
a player, even a secretary. Somebody the principal owner could fire
at the drop of a pop fly.
</P>
<P>
   The principal owner should know that he can't fire the City
Council Speaker the way he fired Billy Martin and Yogi Berra and
Dick Howser and Buck Showalter. He can't let the City Council
speaker depart as a free agent, as Reggie Jackson did. He can't
trade the City Council speaker.
</P>
<P>
   The principal owner should also know that he can't buy the City
Council speaker, as he did Orlando (El Duque) Hernandez. And
everybody else should know that whenever the principal owner talks
about taking his team anywhere, he's bluffing.
</P>
<P>
   To hear him hint about moving the Yankees to New Jersey, you
would think there were a stadium in the Meadowlands already built,
or at least under construction. But there is not only no stadium in
New Jersey, there's also no proposal for a stadium, no plans, no
financing, no nothing.
</P>
<P>
   In growling at Vallone, the principal owner acknowledged that he
hasn't talked to Gov. Christie Whitman about the Yankees for
``about a year,'' but added, ``if it's impossible to stay in New
York, I will accept her invitation,'' presumably to transplant his
team to the Garden State.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman's invitation to what? To discuss if the Yankees will win
120 games this season? To her credit, Whitman has never sounded in
favor of spending state money to lure the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   The principal owner had his chance in 1987, but New Jersey
voters rejected a referendum on a $185 million bond issue to
finance a stadium in Lyndhurst near the Meadowlands Sports Complex
as soon as a major league club committed to locate there and use
the words ``New Jersey'' in its name.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder the principal owner doesn't want a New York
referendum. He knows that too many city taxpayers believe that
money would be better spent on schools, hospitals, housing,
transportation and real-world issues. He knows other cities have
rejected similar referendums.
</P>
<P>
   As for the principal owner's line that New York politics
prompted the Giants and Jets to move to New Jersey, it wasn't New
York politics. It was New Jersey politics, inspired by Sonny
Werblin's creation of the sports complex, that persuaded the Giants
and Jets to go there.
</P>
<P>
   As for the principal owner's line that New York politics
prompted the Dodgers to jump from Brooklyn to Los Angeles in 1957,
it wasn't New York politics. It was Los Angeles politics, in
gift-wrapping land for Dodger Stadium there, that made Walter
O'Malley an offer he couldn't refuse.
</P>
<P>
   During the last few years, the principal owner has promised
every so often to announce his plan beyond the expiration of the
Yankee Stadium lease in 2002, but he has yet to announce anything
specific. Now he complains that the issue has become ``too
emotional and too political.''
</P>
<P>
   But the principal owner hasn't announced a ball park plan
because there is no plan. There is no West Side stadium, there is
no New Jersey stadium. There is only Yankee Stadium in the Bronx,
where the Yankees belong and should stay.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever else the principal owner proclaims, he's bluffing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
