<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALVAGING HOLYFIELD FIGHT WILL BE COMPLICATED MATTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A day after his heavyweight championship fight was
canceled, Evander Holyfield was relaxing in Atlanta, watching his
children compete in a track meet. Meanwhile, his lawyer, Jim
Thomas, and officials at Showtime and New York's Madison Square
Garden were left sifting through the rubble of a postponed boxing
show that may or may not be salvageable.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield was supposed to fight Henry Akinwande, the World
Boxing Association's No. 1 contender, at Madison Square Garden on
Saturday night. But the show was postponed Friday by the New York
State Athletic Commission after it discovered that Akinwande was
infected with hepatitis B, a highly contagious virus that can cause
liver damage.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Munick, the Madison Square Garden vice president of
athletics, said the arena would maintain its control of the bout if
it comes off. But the Garden will have to find a spot on the
calendar for it. Everything hinges on how quickly Akinwande becomes
free of the hepatitis virus.
</P>
<P>
   Akinwande's manager, Jean Christophe Courreges, had Dr. Donald
Kaminsky, who is independent of the commission, administer another
blood test to Akinwande on Friday. Courreges expects to have those
results Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said he would await the results of that test before
trying to decide what Holyfield's next move would be.
</P>
<P>
   As Thomas sees it, Holyfield has three options that involve his
getting in his mandatory title defenses against Akinwande and
Vaughn Bean, the International Boxing Federation's No. 1 contender,
and fighting Lennox Lewis, who holds the World Boxing Council
championship.
</P>
<P>
   If Akinwande is available shortly, then Holyfield fights
Akinwande next month, meets Bean in September and possibly squeezes
in Lewis in December. The next scenario is to fight Bean, Lewis and
then Akinwande. The third situation would have Holyfield meet
Akinwande and then Lewis and fight Bean next year.
</P>
<P>
   One scenario that Thomas did not mention involves eliminating
Akinwande altogether. Thomas was asked whether Holyfield had
fulfilled his obligation to the WBA to meet its No. 1 contender by
being available and ready to fight, but then having the show
postponed or canceled because Akinwande was not fit to fight. ``I'm
still analyzing that,'' Thomas said. ``It's a very good question.
My immediate inclination is to say yes he has.''
</P>
<P>
   All of this is predicated on Holyfield's being able to get a
pay-per-view date on Showtime Event Television.
</P>
<P>
   Showtime executive producer Jay Larkin said Holyfield and
Akinwande may have already missed their pay-per-view window.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pay-per-view calendar is not very promising for the
immediate future,'' Larkin said. ``There are no available dates in
the next two weeks. Then you have the World Cup, and there are no
international dates during the World Cup. So, now you're looking at
the end of July or the beginning of August.''
</P>
<P>
   That cuts into Holyfield's timetable. He hasn't fought since
last Nov. 8 when he knocked out Michael Moorer in the fifth round
in Las Vegas. An August fight means that he will probably get into
the ring again in November or December. If the IBF holds him to
fighting Bean, then Holyfield can't possibly get around to meeting
Lewis this year.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis has a mandatory defense against Zejlko Mavrovic of Croatia
on Sept. 26, which means that he will not be available again until
at least the end of November or early December.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Lennox were available right now, we'd be in negotiations
this minute trying to get a fight with him and Holyfield,'' Larkin
said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
