<SLUG> BC-TEN-FRENCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SANCHEZ VICARIO TOPS SELES AT FRENCH OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By ROBIN FINN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Arantxa Sanchez Vicario had that old Spanish magic
working for her on a muggy afternoon at Roland Garros on Saturday
afternoon; Monica Seles didn't stand a chance.
</P>
<P>
   The persistent baseliner from Barcelona won her third French
Open championship, 7-6 (7-5), 0-6, 6-3, and put an end to Seles'
emotional run to the final in her first tournament since her father
and coach, Karolj, died last month.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez Vicario sounded almost apologetic for winning her first
Grand Slam title since the 1994 U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't express what I feel right now,'' Sanchez Vicario said
when receiving the trophy. ``It was a very difficult match, filled
with emotion.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spaniard then turned to Seles, with tears in her eyes, and
said, ``I'm so sorry I beat you. I don't think you are the one who
deserved to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Spanish champions at the French Open are old hat, the
arrival of 12th-seeded Carlos Moya and 14th-seeded Alex Corretja,
neither of whom are regular suspects in the Grand Slam winners
circle, in Sunday's finale is not the surprise it would be had it
happened anyplace else.
</P>
<P>
   Five of the eight Grand Slam titles won by Spanish men have come
at this site, and two of them, Manolo Santana and Sergi Bruguera,
have won the event twice.
</P>
<P>
   Spaniards are, after all, born and bred to survive red clay
ordeals like the seven-round obstacle course that must be
negotiated by the winners of this event: sprinters need not apply.
The French Open rewards those champions who can go the distance,
weather a hundred hundred-ball rallies, ignore the grit that cuts
into their skin and racquet strings, and never betray a hint of
boredom or fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   The last time two Spaniards met in the final was 1994, when
Sergi Bruguera made his a back-to-back championship run at Roland
Garros by picking up his second career slam title at the expense of
the dark horse in the mix, Alberto Berasetegui. Then as now,
Spain's Sanchez Vicario won the final on the women's side: Spain
enjoyed two champions in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   According to the 24-year-old Corretja, this weekend again
presents a no-lose scenario for Spain: ``I've been working my whole
life to find a place in the final of a Grand Slam, and I know I'm
going to play a friend, so I think we already won, both of us, and
that's the most important thing,'' said Corretja, who trains with
Moya and the rest of the so-called Spanish Armada in Barcelona and
has been making ice cream runs with Moya and the usual gang here in
Paris. ``No matter who the champion is, I think we already won the
tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the 21-year-old Moya, who took Boris Becker's advice
about cultivating his prowess on hardcourts and made a stunning run
to the 1996 Australian Open final, Corretja has never reached the
final round of this or any slam.
</P>
<P>
   Though Corretja and Moya have played each other just three
times, all of the confrontations happened, naturally, to be on clay
courts. All of them were decided, improbably, in straight sets, a
result that seems unlikely in this three-of-five-set format.
Corretja leads the rivalry 2-1, but Moya captured their most recent
meeting, 6-3, 6-2, at Monte Carlo.
</P>
<P>
   Moya said his experience at the Australian Open, where he was so
astonished at reaching the final that he virtually surrendered the
title to Pete Sampras before they'd even walked out on the court,
had changed his approach to this final. He's not an ingenue anymore
and, despite his fondness for his opponent, he's not going to be
satisfied with anything short of a Grand Slam championship on
Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe one time to play a Grand Slam final is a coincidence,
but I don't think two times is a coincidence,'' said Moya. ``I
think now is different because I'm not going to go to the court as
a loser as I did there in Australia. Here I want even more, and I'm
going to do my best to win the tournament. I don't want to lose in
a final again. I just want to be the winner.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-06-98 1535EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980606.0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-06 15:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7434 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALIF-CENSUS-ART-645&AMP;     06-06 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-CENSUS-ART-645&AMP;ADD-NYT) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW CENSUS METHOD GETS TEST RUN IN CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wis., S.C.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(lb) 
 By STEVEN A. HOLMES    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Cindy Jumper pulled her blue Toyota to the
curb in front of a gray frame house on a quiet street. She could
hardly contain her excitement. ``Great,'' she said out loud to
herself. ``The door's open.''
</P>
<P>
   A jumble of children's toys scattered about the front porch
indicated that someone did live here. The wide-open front door
indicated more: that this time, unlike the last time Ms. Jumper had
visited, the occupants were at home. A knock brought forth a
slender woman with short, dark hair, a small boy and a roly-poly
black-and-white puppy. The woman was soon seated in a wicker porch
chair, answering Ms. Jumper's questions on a census form.
</P>
<P>
   While Republicans and Democrats 3,000 miles away argue the
legality and the merits of the Census Bureau's plan to change the
way it will conduct the United States' head count in the year 2000,
the bureau is quietly _ and, it says, successfully _ testing that
new method in California's ethnically and economically diverse
capital city.
</P>
<P>
   Since the beginning of April, temporary Census Bureau employees
like Ms. Jumper have fanned out across Sacramento, interviewing
residents in households that did not return the forms mailed to
them in early March. But the number of households that will be
visited is different in Sacramento from that in any previous
census.
</P>
<P>
   This river city of about 374,000 is one of three sites where the
bureau is conducting its dress rehearsals for the next census.
Unlike the other two _ an Indian reservation near Menominee, Wis.,
and 14 counties in and around Columbia, S.C. _ it is being used for
a large-scale test of a method called statistical sampling, which
will be used to estimate the size and characteristics of its
population.
</P>
<P>
   Following the procedure that has been used in every census since
1970 and will be used again in 2000, the bureau mailed forms to
households in the Sacramento test asking them to provide
information on the age, sex, race, marital status and income of
every resident.
</P>
<P>
   But in previous years, census takers _ known at the bureau as
enumerators _ were sent, repeatedly if necessary, to each residence
that failed to mail back the form. In contrast, the enumerators in
the Sacramento test were sent only to a randomly selected sample of
households in each neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Census Bureau statisticians in Washington monitored the return
rate for the forms in each of the city's census tracts, and from
their findings determined how many households in each tract would
receive a visit from an enumerator.
</P>
<P>
   If half the houses sent back their forms, census takers would
have to get interviews from four out of every five of the remaining
households. If 70 percent responded, they would have to visit two
out of every three. From that sample, statisticians plan to
extrapolate the size and makeup of all the households that failed
to mail back their forms.
</P>
<P>
   The bureau hopes the new method will reduce the cost of
conducting the census and improve on the accuracy of the 1990
results. That year's head count, the bureau has admitted, missed
more than 10 million people, mainly blacks in the inner cities and
Hispanic residents in Texas, New Mexico and California. It also
double-counted another 6 million people, mainly college students
and affluent white owners of more than one home.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have attacked the bureau's plans, contending that
they violate instructions laid out in the Constitution on how the
census is to be conducted every 10 years. Since many of those who
were missed in 1990 tend to live in solidly Democratic districts,
Republican strategists privately fear _ and Democratic strategists
privately hope _ that a more accurate count would give the
Democrats an advantage when the data from the census is used to
draw boundaries for state legislatures and the House of
Representatives.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   With the political stakes so high, the Sacramento test is being
closely watched by the Clinton administration and House
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   As a test site, Sacramento mirrors the problems the Census
Bureau experienced in 1990. Officials estimate that at least 11,400
people were missed by the 1990 tally in Sacramento. And the
experiences of Ms. Jumper and other census takers illustrate how
difficult _ and expensive _ it is to get a complete count.
</P>
<P>
   On a gloriously sunny day, David Granados, 19, a census taker
who is also a student at a local community college, walked the
leafy streets of a working-class neighborhood near Sacramento High
School. Fewer than 44 percent of the households in that census
tract had returned their forms; he would have to get interviews
from four out of every five dwellings that had not responded.
</P>
<P>
   Granados was visiting many of the houses for the second or third
time. When he determined that no one was home, he left a notice
indicating that he had been there and listing a number where he
could be reached to set up an appointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just have to keep coming back five or six times and call
them six times,'' he said. ``If you don't get a response after six
times, then you have to use other means.''
</P>
<P>
   Those other means could include asking neighbors or the local
letter carrier. It could also mean finding the owner of the house
by looking through land records, and asking that person if he or
she knows anything about the people living there.
</P>
<P>
   It was this process, undertaken for every household that did not
mail back its form, that pushed up the costs of the 1990 census.
The process was also blamed for many of the mistakes, since the
longer it takes to gather information, the more time there is for
the data to become outdated and erroneous.
</P>
<P>
   There have been problems with the test here. Some Hispanic
enumerators have complained that they were assigned to non-Hispanic
areas, wasting their fluency in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   A special telephone number was set up so that people who speak
Chinese, Russian, Spanish, Vietnamese or Mien, a Laotian dialect,
could talk to someone and receive help in filling out their forms.
But the instructions telling callers which numbers to press were in
English.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like a lot of things that were done wrong in 1990
they're doing again,'' said May Lee, director of the Asian Resource
Center, who serves on a local advisory group recruited by the
Census Bureau. ``Did all the surveys and focus groups that were
done after 1990 go down a black hole?'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
