<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL NOTES: SOUTH CAROLINA, OKLAHOMA, FLORIDA, OHIO 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Likely Challenger Is Gaining on Hollings
</P>
<P>
   Final polls indicate that when South Carolinians vote Tuesday
for candidates to run in the fall contest for the U.S. Senate,
Democrats will renominate the incumbent, Ernest Hollings, and
Republicans will nominate Bob Inglis, the congressman from the 4th
District in the state's northeastern corner. But that is not the
news about this seat that is crucial to the control of the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The news is that over the past six months, according to the
polls, Inglis has closed to within five percentage points or so of
Hollings in theoretical fall matchups. More precisely, Inglis has
managed to cut Hollings' lead to five points or so _ from about 15
points in December _ at the very time when the senator has been
pouring more than $600,000 into re-election advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Being the incumbent, Hollings, a political moderate first
elected in 1966, is in a position to raise more money than a
challenger, and to spend even more on television, certainly more
than Inglis, who refuses to take political action committee money.
But can the congressman's momentum be slowed?
</P>
<P>
   Six years ago, Hollings narrowly avoided defeat, winning
re-election by 50 percent to 47 percent over his Republican
opponent, Thomas Hartnett. Since then, his ``negatives'' have risen
even more in the polls, as South Carolina has turned ever more
Republican and conservative, and his age _ now 76 _ has become a
bit of an issue.
</P>
<P>
   Inglis, 38, is a solid Republican conservative. In South
Carolina these days, as in much of the South, being a solid
Republican can be like money in the bank when it comes to
elections.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma Incumbent May Run Yet Again
</P>
<P>
   For 14 years between 1976 and 1990, Wes Watkins represented
Oklahoma's 3rd Congressional District, in the southeastern part of
the state, as a Democrat. Then he left Capitol Hill and his party,
ran two unsuccessful races for Governor as an independent, and
eventually settled into a business career.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, sensing that the Republican wave sweeping through
the South was also beginning to sweep through the 3rd Congressional
District, known as Little Dixie, he switched to the Republicans and
won back his old seat. He was preparing to seek re-election this
fall when a back ailment forced him to withdraw.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders in Washington despaired about finding another
candidate capable of holding the seat, given the nimble political
footwork Watkins demonstrated in 1996 in pulling both Republican
and Democratic votes. They tried mightily, but in vain, to talk him
out of stepping down.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic leaders sensed a good opportunity to recapture the
Third and whittle down the Republican majority on Capitol Hill. But
they, too, had doubts about recruiting a strong candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Given all that confusion, the race to replace Watkins has seemed
for weeks to be on hold and wide-open.
</P>
<P>
   Re-enter Watkins.
</P>
<P>
   A few days ago, he announced that he had undergone back surgery
and felt ``very good'' _ so good that he was reconsidering his
decision not to seek re-election.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm kind of reflecting,'' he said. ``I'm not being coy or
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking for a No. 2 For a Race in Florida
</P>
<P>
   Candidates for governor in Florida must name running mates well
in advance of the nominating primaries, a requirement designed to
give voters a better feel for each candidate's particular brand of
politics and decision-making.
</P>
<P>
   Just as in presidential elections, the candidates for lieutenant
governor chosen here tend to be those who can add the maximum
amount of ideological, ethnic, gender and geographical balance.
</P>
<P>
   This year's Florida primaries are set for Sept. 1. But the
deadline for picking running mates is mid-July and groups
representing conservatives, liberals, women, blacks and Hispanics
are intensely lobbying the likely Democratic nominee, Lt. Gov.
Buddy MacKay, and his likely Republican opponent, Jeb Bush, son of
former President George Bush and brother of Texas Gov. George W.
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The other day, 20 or so conservatives, including John Dowless,
the executive director of the Christian Coalition of Florida, a
major political force in the state, showed up on Bush's doorstep,
insisting that he pick an opponent of abortion. Such a choice would
stand Bush well with a great many party loyalists _ he says he
personally opposes abortion _ but might cost him the votes of
independents inclined to support him should he balance his ticket
with a proponent of abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``We encouraged him in no uncertain terms,'' Dowless said later,
the implication being that Bush, who leads MacKay in theoretical
pairings in the polls, should not take his political base for
granted.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, in an early decision on a running mate, Bush named
Secretary of State Sandra Mortham, only to have her withdraw when
questions were raised about how she handled her state job. He
promised the conservative activists who came to call that the
second time around he would look for ``the most qualified person.''
</P>
<P>
   MacKay, if anything, is feeling even more pressure about his
choice for No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Political professionals say he badly needs a running mate who
could add geographical and ethnic or racial diversity to the
ticket, ideally someone from heavily urban South Florida, where the
Democratic Party, through various political miscues, has lost some
of its standing with blacks and Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   But his overtures to several possible candidates reportedly have
been rejected on grounds that he is headed for defeat, no matter
whom he chooses.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Is Nominated For Box of Wheaties
</P>
<P>
   The way Ohio's congressional delegation sees it, Sen. John Glenn
possesses ``every attribute of a champion.'' That's the phrasing 17
members, Democrats and Republicans, used recently when they asked
General Mills to honor Glenn by featuring his square-jawed,
all-American visage on a box of Wheaties.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn, a Democrat and the first American to orbit Earth, is
retiring this year and has talked the National Aeronautics and
Space Administration into letting him suit up again, in October, at
the robust age of 77. This time he will fly aboard a shuttle
mission.
</P>
<P>
   General Mills has agreed to consider the request, saying there
is no question that the senator has shown the right stuff in a life
``filled with service, glory and heroism.'' But company officials
note that Wheaties boxes traditionally have featured only famous
athletes and, they add, such marketing history must be considered a
``strike'' against putting an astronaut and Senator, however
famous, on a box.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn says that considering his age _ he will carry out aging
experiments while in orbit _ perhaps his legislative colleagues
should have forwarded their request to Geritol.
</P>
<P>
   Political Calendar
</P>
<P>
   Besides South Carolina, Maine, Virginia and North Dakota will
also hold primaries on Tuesday. In Arkansas, Democrats will hold a
primary runoff to elect a Senate nominee. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
