<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYS-POL-CONVENTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORDERLY OR CHAOTIC, THE CONVENTIONS' TIME HAS PASSED 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the New York state Republican convention sailed toward
adjournment last week, the party's five candidates for office
gathered on stage, raising their arms in victory as red, white and
blue balloons tumbled from the ceiling and delegates swayed to
Bruce Springsteen's ``Born to Run.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the concluding hours of the Democratic convention
had offered the image of a Westchester County delegate in tears,
her loyalties torn among the Senate candidates fighting to get on
the primary ballot. It was a memorable image of a divided
convention that had turned over the selection of its candidates to
primary voters Sept. 15.
</P>
<P>
   For Republicans, the lesson in these contrasting images is that
the Democrats are hurtling toward damaging primaries and certain
defeat. ``They had 15 candidates going in and 14 coming out,'' Gov.
George Pataki said in an interview, offering a succinct and
dismissive commentary on the Democratic convention.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats' view is that the Republicans have fallen under
the sway of a small group of bosses. ``What we have here is a
tightly scripted media show with a predetermined outcome,'' said
state Democratic chairwoman Judith Hope.
</P>
<P>
   But both interpretations may have missed the real import of
these last two weeks. If anything, the back-to-back gatherings
served to illustrate just how irrelevant state political
conventions have become. These sessions have become rituals _
expensive, elaborate and legally required, to be sure, but
nonetheless pieces of political stagecraft that, in this age of
television and independently financed candidates, have less and
less to do with the campaigns ahead or what voters will do in the
fall.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans leaders asserted that their convention had achieved
its main purpose: choosing a slate of candidates, and shielding it
from the challenge of a primary. But the 406 Republican delegates
at the convention had little to do with that result.
</P>
<P>
   The unity of purpose was, rather, evidence of the dominance over
Republican politics wielded by Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, party chairman
William Powers and Pataki, the men who actually decided which
Republicans would run for office this year.
</P>
<P>
   And notwithstanding the satisfaction among Republicans judging
the Democratic convention, there was probably little the Democrats
could have done to avoid primary battles. There are too many
credible candidates with too much money and independent sources of
support running for the party's nomination for Senate, governor and
attorney general this year. The party, out of power, does not have
the kind of political authority needed to keep followers in line.
</P>
<P>
   And even if the Democrats did have the wherewithal to prevent
intramural battling for nominations, would it matter? Many
Republicans and Democrats assume that primaries are necessarily bad
for the party; Democrats in particular remember the damage the
party inflicted on itself with the primary that preceded D'Amato's
last victory.
</P>
<P>
   But there is ample evidence that a primary can sometimes be
helpful to a party out of power.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic have three unusually strong candidates for
Senate: Geraldine Ferraro, Mark Green and Charles Schumer. As a
result, there is almost certainly enough inherent interest and
drama in this race to assure the candidates attention that money
cannot buy. That is particularly valuable when many voters,
generally satisfied with the way things are going, have shown
little interest in politics, said Lee Miringoff, director of the
Institute for Public Opinion at Marist College in Poughkeepsie,
N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The experience of a primary _ the give-and-take with other
candidates and the media _ can help sharpen candidates' instincts,
force them to think through the nuances of their positions, and
develop responses to political attacks. Those are important skills
for whoever goes up against the politically resourceful D'Amato in
the brief general election campaign that will start on Sept. 16.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ferraro, Schumer and Green all assert they can avoid a
repeat of 1992, and will use the primary to attack D'Amato rather
than one another. D'Amato has told friends he does not believe they
will be able to do that; but if they can, the primary could
effectively set the table for the general election campaign against
D'Amato.
</P>
<P>
   None of which is to say the Republicans did not emerge with
significant advantages from their convention. Unlike Democrats, the
Republicans leaders will all be working for, contributing to and
voting for the same candidates. There is no strife in the party,
and there is general agreement on the message.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders, jubilant at their convention's result,
compared it to the smooth and flashy Democratic convention that
nominated Mario Cuomo for a fourth term in 1994. ``The people in
this room are happy to be at a convention that was settled before
they came,'' Joseph Mercurio, a Republican consultant, said on the
convention floor Friday. ``They didn't come here to fight over
scraps. They came to get their marching orders for the fall
campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   But there was a cost to that as well. There was a palpable sense
of energy in the hotel hallways and bars and on the floor of the
Democratic convention in Rye Brook. For Republicans gathered in
Manhattan, though, lethargy ruled the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to get some people in here,'' John O'Mara, a
longtime political adviser to Pataki and D'Amato, implored party
workers after surveying a convention hall filled with empty seats
just as the vote for D'Amato's renomination was about to begin. And
after the first day, in which party officials took note of row
after row of empty seats reserved for onlookers who never came, the
Republicans pulled a divider across the middle of the ballroom at
the Sheraton New York Hotel and Towers to make it seem less empty.
</P>
<P>
   In the long run, most politicians believe that the Republicans
are in a dominant position going into the fall election. But
ultimately, the explanation for that has little to do with what
happened in New York last week or in Rye Brook the week before.
</P>
<P>
   There is, in short, less and less reason to believe that there
is much of a connection between the flash of a convention in June
and the results of an election in November.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Cuomo. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
