<HEADER>
A7442 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PA-DEATHPENALTY-RACIS     06-06 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PA-DEATHPENALTY-RACISM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RACIAL DISPARITIES CITED IN DEATH-PENALTY CASES 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By FOX BUTTERFIELD    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new study on racial disparities in death-penalty cases has
found that black defendants in murder cases in Philadelphia are
nearly four times more likely than other defendants to be sentenced
to death, even when the circumstances of killings are the same.
</P>
<P>
   The study is the latest in a series of reports over the past
decade that have found racial disparities in death-penalty cases.
It was released in Washington as part of a report by the Death
Penalty Information Center, a research and advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   The center is lobbying Congress and the states to adopt laws to
allow prisoners on death row to challenge their death sentences on
the basis of racial disparities, just as people can now sue for
discrimination in housing and education.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, the Supreme Court ruled that defendants could not use
evidence of racial disparities in death sentences as evidence of
bias in their own cases, even though the court accepted as true a
study of Georgia death sentences showing that killers of whites
were far more likely to be sentenced to death than killers of
blacks.
</P>
<P>
   The findings reported on Thursday were immediately challenged as
statistically flawed and politically motivated by groups that favor
the death penalty. Diane Clements, director of Justice For All, a
victims' rights group in Houston, said that earlier work by the
main author of the Philadelphia study, David Baldus, a professor of
law at the University of Iowa, ``has been discredited by poor
methodology.''
</P>
<P>
   Baldus was in Sarajevo, Bosnia and Herzegovina, and could not be
reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The Philadelphia study was released in summary form in a report
titled, ``The Death Penalty in Black and White: Who Lives, Who
Dies, Who Decides.'' It will be published in full in the Cornell
Law Review this fall.
</P>
<P>
   The report, drawing on previous research in other states, also
found what it called a ``disturbing and consistent trend'' in
death-penalty states that makes defendants more likely to be
sentenced to death for murder if the victim is white.
</P>
<P>
   As researchers moved north to Pennsylvania from Southern states,
where executions are most common, they said they found little
disparity in death sentences based on the race of the victim, but a
large disparity in the race of the defendants, with blacks far more
likely to be charged.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, according to a study by Baldus that was the basis of
the 1987 Supreme Court case, defendants whose victims were white
faced odds of receiving a death sentence 4.3 times higher than
those whose victims were black, even when other circumstances of
the slayings were similar.
</P>
<P>
   Other studies have found that in Florida the odds of a death
sentence were 4.8 times higher when victims were white; in
Illinois, 4 times higher; in North Carolina, 4.4 times higher, and
in Mississippi, 5.5 times higher.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Dieter, the center's executive director, said the
disparities showed that ``white victims are considered more
valuable in the criminal justice system than black victims.''
</P>
<P>
   But he acknowledged in a telephone interview that if this racial
imbalance could be eliminated and the death penalty was invoked as
often for black victims, even more blacks might end up on death row
than at present. Most slayings occur within racial groups, with
whites killing mostly whites and blacks killing mostly blacks.
</P>
<P>
   In April, the report noted, Kentucky enacted the first state law
allowing defendants to challenge racial disparities, after an
investigation found that all of the inmates on the state's death
row were there for slaying whites and none for killing blacks. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-06-98 1600EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
