</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYC-BUDGET-320&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI PARRIES COUNCIL'S BUDGET PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A day after the City Council defied Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani by passing a budget without his consent, he struck back
Saturday, declaring that New York would collect less money next
year than the Council had assumed. The move escalated a game of
political brinkmanship, with higher property taxes as the stakes.
</P>
<P>
   In a curt letter to the Council, the mayor estimated that the
city's revenues would be $251 million less than he had projected in
April. The Republican mayor said that unless the
Democratic-dominated Council cuts the spending it had added to his
proposed budget, the Council will have to raise property-tax rates
to balance the books.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is a very good exercise for them in leadership,
or the possibility of leadership,'' Giuliani said at a news
conference Saturday. ``If you want to lower taxes, you have to
lower expenses.''
</P>
<P>
   Council members had expected the new figures. They said the
mayor was skillfully exploiting his power under the City Charter to
set revenue estimates. The property-tax rate is the only one the
City Council sets independently. The Council's staff estimates that
to cover the shortfall, the average homeowner's property tax would
increase $48.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor said in the letter that over the next five days he
planned to veto most of the items that would be needed to bring
spending into line with the new revenue estimates. ``With regard to
any remaining gap, I am hopeful that we can work together so that
it will not be necessary for you to raise the tax rates,'' he
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Council's additions to the mayor's proposed budget are
weekly recycling collections for areas of the city that now get
service every other week; a program to keep some elementary schools
open from 3 to 7 p.m.; and reduced tuition for City University of
New York students who graduate from high school with a B average
and maintain it in college.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Friday, the Council passed a $34 billion budget amid
self-congratulatory speeches and standing ovations. Speaker Peter
Vallone crowed that the Council was finally coming into its own as
an equal branch of government, and Councilman Herbert Berman, the
chairman of the Finance Committee, declared that the vote would be
``grist for some future master's thesis.'' The euphoria lasted less
than eight hours _ from 4:08 p.m., when the budget passed, to 11:51
p.m., when the mayor's office paged the Council Finance Director,
Thomas McMahon, to deliver the new revenue estimate.
</P>
<P>
   Vallone issued a statement Saturday calling the new figure
``fabricated'' and saying his staff would work through the weekend
to find an alternative to raising property-tax rates, which are to
be set Monday. ``It is incredible that the mayor would seek to
raise property taxes in the midst of the biggest budget surplus in
city history,'' he said. ``The City Council refused to raise
property taxes during the bad times. We're certainly not going to
allow a Giuliani tax hike now.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said he had settled on about three-quarters of his
vetoes, which he called ``a road map as to how to straighten their
budget out so that they don't have to raise property taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   The budget passed 43-7, with all the Republicans voting against
it and one Democrat not voting. So Michael Clendenin, a Council
spokesman, said the Council would easily override the mayor's
vetoes, which takes 34 votes. That foretells a long battle between
now and July 1, when the new fiscal year begins.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, the mayor accused the Council of ``illusory
calculations'' and of spending ``make-believe money.'' He indicated
he could adjust a few figures himself to restrain the Council from
imposing what he saw as an irresponsible budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to give them a revenue estimate,'' Giuliani said, ``and
obviously, that revenue estimate is going to be lower _ either
lower, considerably lower or substantially lower _ than it was
before, because the action that they've taken both in the budget,
which I've just outlined, and in future years does some damage to
the city this year, and significant and substantial damage in the
year 2000, 2001 and 2002.''
</P>
<P>
   Vallone responded by pointing to the city's financial vigor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard for me to believe that in the face of what everyone
acknowledges to be the largest surplus in memory,'' Vallone said,
``that he would just arbitrarily lower the revenues and thereby
increase the real-estate taxes. That would be a real unusual thing
for a Republican mayor to reject the largest tax cut in the history
of the city and, in the face of the largest surplus, to ask for a
larger real-estate tax. That, to me, are three non sequiturs in a
row.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor returned to City Hall at 8:30 Friday night to discuss
the new revenue estimate with his staff. Council staff members, who
gathered at a nearby bar, contended that the number was a political
creation and started a pool on the new estimate, with entries
ranging from $100 million to $1.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani maintained, however, that much of the adjustment was
made because of changes in state and federal policy that the
Council should have known about, and that some of the reduction
would be caused by decisions in the
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Gifford Miller, D-Manhattan, called the new number
``bogus'' and said the mayor was taking a different position from
most other budget analysts and credit-rating agencies. ``It's
ironic that the mayor, now that he doesn't have the same control
over the budget that he used to, would suddenly switch course and
claim the city is not in sound fiscal condition,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's budget director, Joseph Lhota, said he believed that
fiscal monitors would find the new estimates to be accurate and
necessary. ``The only thing we took out of the budget are state and
federal revenues that we're not going to receive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the budget dust-up as he left his news conference
Saturday, the mayor said with a laugh, ``I enjoy it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
