<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-JAZZ-MALONE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALONE'S EYES ARE ON GOAL, BUT BALL WON'T COOPERATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ Scottie Pippen whispered into his ear as he
stepped to the free-throw line for two crucial free throws in the
final seconds of Game 1. ``The Mailman doesn't deliver on
Sundays,'' Pippen coyly told Karl Malone.
</P>
<P>
   Malone smirked and shrugged his shoulders _ and promptly missed
both shots.
</P>
<P>
   The misfires last June not only helped the Chicago Bulls
eventually slink away with another title but also left Malone's
teammates pondering the delicate nerves of their 6-foot-9-inch,
260-pound power forward, a large man who had trouble completing the
smallest of tasks.
</P>
<P>
   With Game 3 of the National Basketball Association finals
looming at the United Center in Chicago on Sunday, Malone is
chucking up shots, most of which are careening off the back iron.
His bad aim is not just relegated to the weekends, either.
Wednesdays. Fridays. Whenever. Like perennial runners-up Charles
Barkley and Patrick Ewing before him, Malone is standing on the
perimeter and hoisting away the Jazz's best chance for a world
championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a problem with Karl shooting out there,'' Jazz
coach Jerry Sloan said after Utah lost its home-court edge Friday
night at the Delta Center. ``They're quick getting out of a double
team to cover other people on the perimeter, and that's why we've
always played that way with him.''
</P>
<P>
   But if Malone does not stop missing, the Bulls will soon be
celebrating. Beyond Michael Jordan's 37 points and Steve Kerr's
clutch rebound and assist with less than a minute remaining,
Chicago won Game 2, 93-88, partly because Malone could not find his
range.
</P>
<P>
   He missed 11-of-16 shots and attempted only four field goals in
the second half. His last basket came with 4 minutes 30 seconds
left in the second quarter, meaning the brawniest player on the
floor was a nonfactor the final 28 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Malone is 14-for-41 in the first two games of the series,
numbers that bear a disturbing resemblance to his production in
last year's NBA finals. He shot only 60 percent from the line for
the 1997 series, missing 23 out of 58 free throws. He averaged 23.8
points and 10.1 rebounds, but hit only 44 percent of his shots from
the field.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 6, with the Jazz's season on the brink, he scored 21
points but missed 8-of-15 free throws. The more his Hall of Fame
status blossoms over 13 seasons, the more his reputation as a
clutch player shrinks into oblivion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot of things that maybe I could have done or whatever,
but I didn't,'' Malone said after Game 2. ``And I take
responsibility for that, and you can't shy away from that. What we
try to do as a team is on my shoulders, and when I don't do it, you
have to face the firing squad.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone is good at shouldering the blame. He did it last June,
too, owning up to his own shortcomings with his team's season at
stake.
</P>
<P>
   ``All year, I make those shots and it just came at a kind of
time to not make them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the Jazz could dethrone the Bulls if he did not begin
to start making his shots, he added, ``No. Point blank, no. We will
not win this series if I don't play better. And that's just fact.
That's just the way it is. We have other guys that step up, but if
I don't play well _ if Karl Malone doesn't play well _ we don't win
this series.''
</P>
<P>
   He looks comfortable on the finals stage, even when his game is
suffering. Playing in a small market, his encounters with the
national media come but a few times a year. He loves to verbalize
his feelings whenever given the chance _ and his outspokenness has
often created rifts between players on his team and around the
league.
</P>
<P>
   Whether voicing concern about Magic Johnson playing with HIV _
before Johnson's original comeback in 1993 _ or taking teammate
Greg Ostertag to task for not hustling, Malone has spoken his mind.
</P>
<P>
   And now the finals provides the attention and forum _ his dream
come true _ an event with all the trimmings. His striking candor
and carefree attitude play well in a league suddenly short on
accessible superstars.
</P>
<P>
   Still, once he stepped onto the court, that pillar of strength
in the post has often been reduced to another big, strong player
with limited skill. With the world watching, he is wilting _ one
clanking miss at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Malone's teammates are at a loss for answers. They remember the
hulking presence who used his marksmanship and his muscle to carve
up the Los Angeles Lakers in the Western Conference finals two
weeks ago, not the frustrated spectator from the past five days.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Rodman's efforts to swat the ball away from Malone as he
received entry passes into the post helped throttle him offensively
in Game 2. But Malone was often standing by himself after screening
for John Stockton and waiting for the pass. He kept firing and
missing. He was not executing the Jazz's offensive staple; he was
running the pick-and-roll over.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll be fine, everyone struggles once in a while,'' Bryon
Russell said. ``We all have faith in him. We aren't going to stop
going to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Antoine Carr, ``We need to get him rolling, one way or the
other.''
</P>
<P>
   Leading up to Game 3, Malone has decided to ask for his space.
``I just want to get away from basketball,'' he said. ``I guarantee
whoever is at my house right now won't mention basketball. And I
doubt if there will be anyone around the house when I walk in.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, as the owner of a Harley-Davidson motorcycle and a
natural-rain compact disk, Malone was possibly thinking about a
mountainous retreat before the team left for Chicago on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere far, far away from Michael Jordan and his team would
be a start, a peaceful and serene place, where the Mailman can
regain his confidence and prepare to finally deliver on a Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to play well, but in times like this it's really only
one person that can correct it _ and that's me,'' he said.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
