<SLUG> BC-HKN-COLUMN-STANLEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOCKEY COLUMN: MURPHY CREATES HIS OWN LUCK 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ About a year ago, Larry Murphy seemed near the end of
a long and semi-distinguished career. After modest success in Los
Angeles, Washington and Minnesota in the 1980s and two Stanley Cup
rings with Pittsburgh in the early 1990s, the veteran defenseman
was toiling for the Toronto Maple Leafs, a team hardly in danger of
qualifying for the post-season playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Even the polite fans of Maple Leaf Gardens were booing and
heckling Murphy. It was as if someone had passed a law that said
whatever could go wrong would go wrong. But then everything started
to go right for Larry Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   His luck changed on March 18, 1997, right after St. Patrick's
Day, when Toronto sent him to Detroit for future considerations.
Murphy soon helped the Red Wings to their first Stanley Cup
championship since 1955.
</P>
<P>
   This season, which included his 37th birthday, Murphy was the
only player on the Detroit roster to play all 82 games of the
regular schedule. He also has appeared in all 18 playoff games. The
most important was Friday night in Joe Louis Arena, Game 6 of the
Western Conference finals against Dallas. In it, Murphy played 29
minutes 21 seconds, more than any skater on either team. Among
other chores, he scored the winning goal and set up the other one
to lead the Wings to a 2-0 victory over the Stars and a 4-2 triumph
in the series. Detroit next faces the Capitals in the championship
round beginning on Tuesday night at Joe Louis Arena.
</P>
<P>
   On a multidimensional roster that is deep in most hockey
necessities, Murphy is a critical component: the savvy veteran rear
guard whose poise and opportunism are most evident at the most
important times. One of those moments came in the first period,
when Murphy jumped off the bench during a penalty kill to turn a
one-on-one break into a two-on-one. Murphy and Bob Rouse, another
veteran defenseman, had read the play perfectly. Rouse ``hustled''
to the bench, Murphy said, so that Murphy could come on quickly
``with a little jump.'' It was a slick, shrewd move that proved
pivotal.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was so upsetting was that everybody was on the other side
of the ice,'' Murphy said of the Stars. ``I was the only guy on
this side of the rink.'' So he took Darren McCarty's pass and beat
goalie Ed Belfour with a backhanded shot.
</P>
<P>
   In the locker room afterward, Murphy's face looked exhausted
beneath the perspiration, the scratches and the little red welts.
He said his team felt a combination of ``jubilation and relief''
about not having to go back to Dallas for Game 7 on Sunday. The
Stars, big and rugged, had the best regular-season record. They
played at least as well as Detroit in this series. The Wings never
got ``on track,'' Murphy said, until the final game. ``The rest of
it was just a scramble,'' Murphy said. ``These games are tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Compared to last year, he said, this season's playoffs have been
``a grind.'' On most teams, Murphy would be the grand old man of
the defense. On this team, the honor goes to Slava Fetisov, who
turned 40 at the start of the tournament. His face now a mask of
scars and bruises, Fetisov has a style that involves more hitting
than Murphy's. Like many Wings defensemen, Fetisov must compensate
for the loss of Vladimir Konstantinov, the heavy checker whose
career ended last spring when he suffered brain damage in a
limousine crash a week after the cup was clinched.
</P>
<P>
   On the forward lines, the collision work is handled by Martin
Lapointe, Darren McCarty, Kirk Maltby and Kris Draper. Lapointe,
playing with great snarl, just finished the best two weeks of his
career. He has picked up for Brendan Shanahan, a veteran power
forward who used to combine scoring and rough stuff
</P>
<P>
   At center, Steve Yzerman and Igor Larionov can still skate and
pass well. But neither whips the puck past goalies the way he did
in his youth. For that, the Wings rely on Slava Kozlov and Sergei
Fedorov.
</P>
<P>
   By scoring his first goal of the series Friday, Fedorov
increased his post-season total to 9, most in the league. Clobbered
and knocked dizzy early in the game by Richard Matvichuk, Fedorov
came back with impressive vigor both attacking and defending. Late
in the game, he bowled over Derian Hatcher, the biggest and meanest
man on a big, mean team. It was one of a hundred such moments in a
most definitive game played by a gritty group of smart, tough, old
pros who are trying to be the first team to repeat as champions
since Murphy and the Penguins of 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``They paid a very heavy price to win,'' Dallas coach Ken
Hitchcock said of the Wings. ``They responded as champions do.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
