<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUBIOUS CLAIMS OF ENVIRONMENTAL DANGER ARE THE REAL THREAT TO
HUMANITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1997 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: In case you missed it, asbestos apparently doesn't pose
nearly the lung cancer risk U.S. regulators claimed more than a
decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   A report published in last month's New England Journal of
Medicine by three Canadian scientists says the Environmental
Protection Agency model ``overestimated the risk of
asbestos-induced lung cancer by at least a factor of 10.'' The
claim is based on extensive research done in a Quebec area having
one of the world's heaviest concentrations of asbestos mines and
mills.
</P>
<P>
   Some scientists have been quick to dispute the Canadians'
conclusions, but a synopsis of the findings seems to reflect sound
science. They did their research among women living in
asbestos-laden air during the 1940s and '50s before modern
pollution-control equipment was available. Even though the
community's exposure levels were five times higher than the maximum
limit for asbestos workers today, the women proved no more likely
to develop lung cancer than women in relatively asbestos-free areas
of the province.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody, it should be noted, disputed the danger from exposure to
massive asbestos ingestions of the sort shipbuilders encountered a
half-century or more ago. What critics of the early asbestos
regulation warned against was the sort of overreaction regulators
seem incapable of resisting.
</P>
<P>
   The warnings went unheeded and billions of dollars have since
been spent on required asbestos removals. Not only were these
efforts often economically wasteful, but the very act of removing
asbestos may have posed greater dangers than leaving it alone.
Nevertheless, there was a lot of money to be made from the scare,
and financial incentives soon overwhelmed calls for common sense.
</P>
<P>
   This has been par for the course when it comes to real and
imagined environmental dangers in America. Has there been any
environmental scare that proved valid?
</P>
<P>
   The list of threats that have been either entirely discredited
or shown to be much less dangerous than claimed seems to grow with
each passing year: Acid rain, cyclamates, pesticides, global
warming, ozone depletion, second-hand tobacco smoke.
</P>
<P>
   The environmental movement and its government and media allies
have always made a number of dubious assumptions as they've pressed
their crusade. One is that most human beings need to be protected
from themselves by those who are smarter and more environmentally
responsible. This assumption is buttressed by the belief that
humans are like hot-house flowers lacking the wherewithal to
survive the everpresent toxins that are part and parcel of normal
life on the planet Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever government has gotten involved, another assumption is
that economics and environmental concerns bear no relationship.
Once a problem is created, identified and adequately publicized,
the regulatory response is that money should be no object when it
comes to eliminating the perceived threat. If the taxpayer can't be
forced to pay the freight, government imposes the financial
responsibility on the private sector, and cost-benefit
considerations are out of the question.
</P>
<P>
   The economist-journalist Warren Brookes warned in a cautionary
essay in the early 1990s that while wanting to save the Earth was a
worthy goal, it should be an informed undertaking. The problem with
the movement is that it has always reacted to dubious claims first
and informed itself later, if at all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-06-98 1712EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980606.0138 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-06 17:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7476 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEANIE-BABIES-KAN &LR;      06-06 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEANIE-BABIES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESSES EXPLOIT BEANIE BABY BALLYHOO TO REAP BONANZAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER MANN  
 c. 1997 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Businesses and ball clubs facing lagging
sales are turning to the latest marketing medicine: a shot of
Beanie Babies.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald's is selling more food than ever by stuffing a Teenie
Beanie Baby in the bag along with those burgers and fries.
</P>
<P>
   Since the fast-food chain started giving away a reported 250
million Teenie Beanie Babies on May 22, cars have clogged its
restaurants' drive-through lanes, and customers have crowded
counters, many hoping to build sets of the 12 tiny stuffed animals.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald's isn't alone in mining the Beanie Baby mania, a fad
that doesn't seem to be flagging.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City Royals recently gave away 13,000 Roary Beanie
Babies at its game against the Oakland A's, boosting attendance by
83 percent over its previous Sunday afternoon outing, May 10.
</P>
<P>
   Other ball clubs, including the Detroit Tigers and the New York
Yankees, have experienced similar results riding the Beanie Baby
wave, although in some instances the ``fans'' didn't stick around
for the game.
</P>
<P>
   Most Beanie Baby collectors are behaving like civilized people,
but others have resorted to guerrilla tactics to hunt and capture
as many Beanies and Teenies as possible.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald's had a similar giveaway last year, and 100 million
Beanie Babies were scooped up. This time McDonald's set clear
ground rules for customers, including one that they could purchase
the toys only every two hours.
</P>
<P>
   But recently a crowd at a McDonald's in Overland Park, Kan.,
decided they were on a mission.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Dixon, an employee of a Godfather's Pizza next to the
McDonald's, described what he saw May 23, the day after McDonald's
started its latest Teenie Beanie Baby giveaway:
</P>
<P>
   ``Our parking lot started filing up with cars, and so was
McDonald's and the gas station across the street. It was just crazy
amounts of people. People were coming in here to use the bathroom
to change their clothes and then changing cars in our parking lot
so employees wouldn't recognize them. It really started getting
crazy. There were minivans and Blazers full of people. Our manager
asked them to leave, so they just started changing clothes in the
parking lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, Dixon said, the police were called to monitor the
situation and eventually direct traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were obviously breaking the rules. These were
normal-looking people, but it was like they had some master plan to
get their hands on those Beanie Babies,'' Dixon said. ``But why? I
don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Psychologist Robert Schachter of New York said he didn't think
Beanie Babies themselves generated mass insanity, but added:
``That's not usual behavior under any circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Even some die-hard collectors don't know why they're maniacally
driven to collect the critters.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Austin American-Statesman, a woman in that
Texas city dissected a Wrinkles the Dog to determine whether some
chemical inside was compelling her to add to her 500-plus Beanie
Baby collection.
</P>
<P>
   Schachter said it was really Ty Inc., the marketer of Beanie
Babies, that had induced the craze by randomly yanking certain
models off the market without warning.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately prices for the ``retired'' Beanie Babies, most of
which are made in China, go crazy on the secondary market. Even
rumors of such actions cause prices to spike.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of Web sites on the Internet are devoted to Beanie
Babies, and many include price lists. At a recent Beanie Baby show
in California, a woman displayed an ``Employee Bear'' she'd just
bought for $4,600.
</P>
<P>
   A chat room at one of the Web sites contained a discussion of
the McDonald's Teenie Beanie Baby promotion. One woman described
how she'd bought some Happy Meals to get the toys and then offered
the food to a homeless woman, who said, ``Ugh, not another Happy
Meal.'' She then directed the benevolent collector to others
willing to take the meals.
</P>
<P>
   One local woman, who asked that her name not be used, admitted
having thousands of Beanie Babies. She has four full sets of every
Beanie Baby issued and extras.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want my friends to know how addicted I am to Beanie
Babies now,'' she said. ``It's starting to get embarrassing.''
</P>
<P>
   But she perked up when asked why she collected Beanie Babies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I'm collecting one set each for my three children and then
one for me for my retirement!''
</P>
<P>
   Psychotherapist Susan Maxwell of Los Angeles said she understood
why children loved and collected Beanie Babies but was less clear
why adults were caught up in the craze.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think the artificial scarcity'' creates a more frenetic
atmosphere ``because they feel like they're missing out on
something,'' Maxwell said. ``Some people think by collecting
something desirable, it will bring something mystical, magical to
their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Although some view the whole collecting mania as crazy, others
say it has positive aspects.
</P>
<P>
   Another local collector, who also asked that her name not be
used, said collecting and talking about Beanie Babies was something
her whole family got involved in. She said she wanted to remain
anonymous not because she was ashamed but because she didn't want
to be lumped with ``crazies.''
</P>
<P>
   One of her sons, age 10, is attracted to all the Beanie Baby
dogs and is serious about his collection. The other, age 7, likes
the quirkier ones and enjoys playing with them.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night at a local McDonald's, Trisha Brown won the
12-critter Teenie Beanie Baby set being distributed in a special
drawing. She gave the set to her niece, Lexie.
</P>
<P>
   Lexie's mother, Theresa Storrer, said the whole family was into
collecting Beanie Babies. Together, they have about 200.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not long ago we thought the market was about to go flat, but
after seeing what's happened with McDonald's and its giveaway, I
don't know,'' Storrer said. ``It looks like this thing could go on
for a long, long time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
