A7477 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOMBING-SENTENCES-KAN     06-06 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOMBING-SENTENCES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS A CHAPTER IN THE OKLAHOMA CITY BOMBING ENDS, AMERICA REMAINS
CHANGED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 1997 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Two Americans, former soldiers at that, now stand
convicted of plotting a crime that toppled a federal building,
killed and injured hundreds of their countrymen and made a nation
feel less secure.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Terry Nichols was sentenced to a lifetime behind
bars for his role in the 1995 Oklahoma City bombing, which killed
168 persons and injured more than 500. Timothy McVeigh waits on
death row.
</P>
<P>
   Three years of investigations and trials bring this federal case
to a close, but can this country ever be the same?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a time when America lost its sense of security,'' said
Martin Cash, a Department of Veterans Affairs employee who lost an
eye in the blast.
</P>
<P>
   Even the simple act of parking near federal buildings and some
county courthouses has changed: Parking frequently is prohibited
because a car or a truck could hide a bomb.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a vulnerable people,'' Larry Mackey, lead prosecutor in
the Nichols trial, said after the sentencing. ``We have learned
that from this case in a way I hope we'll never see again.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that vulnerability doesn't change who we are. It reminds
us of our responsibility to each other. When there is crime, we all
have to step forward as a nation and individually.''
</P>
<P>
   If the country feels more vulnerable because of the bombing, it
should also feel more resilient, Judge Richard Matsch said Thursday
before sentencing Nichols. Nichols was found guilty of conspiracy
and involuntary manslaughter. A year earlier, a jury found McVeigh
guilty of murder and conspiracy and sentenced him to death.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only inference that can be drawn from all this evidence
was that there was an intention here to change the course of
government, change the policies of government through fear and
intimidation,'' Matsch said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you know, it didn't work out that way. Quite the
contrary.''
</P>
<P>
   Matsch said he was impressed that federal workers showed up at
temporary headquarters the day after the bombing to keep the
government in business.
</P>
<P>
   ``What occurred to me was that a community became even more
united and, I think, perhaps the country as well,'' Matsch said.
</P>
<P>
   In Oklahoma City, the destroyed federal building is being
replaced by three buildings, none over three stories tall, said
Paul Heath, a psychologist who leads a group for bombing survivors.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people who are somewhat frightened by being in
government buildings, but by far the majority of people believe
that their government is capable of protecting them and carrying on
business,'' Heath said.
</P>
<P>
   Heath said the end of the McVeigh and Nichols trials should
hasten the healing process for Oklahomans, who were affected more
than most Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``This certainly will go a long, long way,'' Heath said,
describing the trials as a painful distraction. ``The trial was
necessary for me, but I really wanted it to be over.''
</P>
<P>
   Rudy Guzman, whose brother Randy Guzman, a Marine captain, was
killed in the blast, attended most of the Nichols and McVeigh
trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to move on,'' Guzman said Thursday. ``I'm closing
this chapter and going back home to California. Randy is never
going to come back, but I'm satisfied (Nichols) is actually going
to pay the price now.''
</P>
<P>
   Marsha Kight, whose 23-year-old daughter died in the bombing,
said the Nichols sentencing did not ease her pain but had increased
her empathy for people who lose a friend or relative to crime.
</P>
<P>
   The sentence ``brings a lot of emotion, but it sure won't bring
closure,'' Kight said. ``I will continue to fight for (crime
victims) as I did for my daughter. It's too important. I can't turn
my back.''
</P>
<P>
   People like Kight may have to bear yet another bombing trial,
this time in Oklahoma state court.
</P>
<P>
   A state grand jury has heard from more than 100 witnesses in an
investigation that could lead to indictments of Nichols and McVeigh
on state murder charges. Both could face the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   They can be tried again, because the federal charges dealt with
the deaths of eight federal agents. The state charges would be for
the deaths of the 160 other victims.
</P>
<P>
   The grand jury inquiry also has tried to identify any others who
assisted McVeigh and Nichols, such as the suspect known only as
John Doe No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   The federal cases will give state prosecutors an advantage over
the defense, said Scott Robinson, a Denver trial lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know who all the witnesses are and how they'll do, and
the defense loses the element of surprise,'' Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahomans have a right to seek justice, Mackey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I'm delighted that the people of Oklahoma City
have convened a grand jury, that they are going through that
evidence with great diligence,'' Mackey said.
</P>
<P>
   There also is the possibility of more federal proceedings.
Nichols and McVeigh are requesting new trials.
</P>
<P>
   The wait for justice in the McVeigh and Nichols cases has been
long, Mackey acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message here is `Trust your American judicial system,' &UR; ''
Mackey said. ``Be patient; it takes time. Give the system time, and
that system will prevail.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
