<HEADER>
A7478 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VACCINATIONS-ABORTION     06-06 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VACCINATIONS-ABORTION-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABORTION ISSUE CAUSES SOME TO RESIST VACCINATIONS FOR THEIR
CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALAN BAVLEY  
 c. 1997 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOB NOSTER, Mo. _ Todd Parish didn't mind when his 1-year-old
son, Timothy, was vaccinated against chickenpox two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   But that was before the Air Force sergeant at Whiteman Air Force
Base learned that cells derived from aborted fetuses were used to
make the vaccine. And that similar cells were used to make the
hepatitis A and rubella shots Parish got several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Parish, who describes himself as a conservative Christian and a
staunch opponent of abortion, was appalled.
</P>
<P>
   Now he is battling the military over whether soldiers should be
informed about how vaccines are made and be allowed to reject them
on moral grounds.
</P>
<P>
   He is also refusing to let his 6-year-old daughter, Ashley, get
a chickenpox shot, even though it is required of children attending
military-run elementary schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not know when I was injected what I was getting,'' said
Parish, 27. ``That tramples on my moral convictions. Unknowingly, I
became involved in something I find immoral and hideous.''
</P>
<P>
   The armed forces require their personnel to be vaccinated for a
variety of diseases.
</P>
<P>
   And when vaccinations are deemed necessary, no exceptions are
made for soldiers with moral qualms, said Department of Defense
spokesman Jim Turner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's for the safety of the group,'' Turner said. ``He (a
soldier) has to be reliable. Maybe somebody could die because he's
not doing his job.''
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Department does allow vaccination exemptions for
children on religious grounds. And Parish plans to exercise that
option.
</P>
<P>
   He and his family were to leave his base near Knob Noster on
June 7 for Ramstein Air Base in Germany. The only school there is
operated by the Defense Department. Parish and his wife, Kara, 25,
said they would rather teach Ashley at home than let her be
vaccinated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not so crazy about that,'' Parish said. ``But if I have
to, I will.''
</P>
<P>
   Parish has filed a grievance with the Air Force about the way
vaccinations are handled. His case has been referred to the
Department of Defense inspector general's office, which would not
comment on it.
</P>
<P>
   Parish won't be fighting the military alone. His case has gained
the support of the Rutherford Institute, the legal defense
organization that handled Paula Jones' unsuccessful sexual
harassment lawsuit against President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like this one a lot,'' said Ron Rissler, the institute's
legal coordinator. ``This deals with his religious beliefs,
parental rights. And we're disturbed about the use of fetal tissue.
That's a violation of the sanctity of human life.''
</P>
<P>
   Cell lines derived from fetal tissue provide a medium for
growing viruses used in vaccines. They long have been used in
medical research.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers and manufacturers prefer fetal cells because they
can go through many more divisions than mature cells. That means
fetal cell lines do not have to be replaced very often and can be
used over time to produce uniform batches of vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   The cells used to make Varivax, the chickenpox vaccine, came
from tissue taken from two fetuses from therapeutic abortions
performed in the mid-1960s in Sweden and Great Britain. The cells
are many, many generations removed from those of the fetuses
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Parish said he is not opposed to vaccines in general. He gets a
flu shot every year.
</P>
<P>
   He isn't opposed to the use of human tissue in medicine, as long
as the donor of that tissue is able to consent. Parish has signed
up to be an organ donor.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I still think the use of fetal tissue for my gain
shouldn't happen,'' he said. ``By accepting this vaccine, we're
encouraging the development of more fetal tissue products. We're
helping people profit from the death of two fetuses.''
</P>
<P>
   Parish's moral concerns are very real ones, said M.C. Sullivan,
a bioethicist with the Midwest Bioethics Center in Kansas City, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly some people will say: `Don't waste this valuable
(fetal tissue) resource. Let's find some good in this.' But are we
meant to be seen as potential human salvage yards?'' she asked.
``He raises very serious issues.''
</P>
<P>
   The use of fetal cells has become a subterranean issue among
some anti-abortion groups, erupting occasionally on the Internet or
taking hold in church groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's part of the overall concern we in the pro-life community
have about the rights of the unborn,'' said Douglas Peterson of the
group Stop Fetal Tissue Research, based in McHenry, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Kara Parish brought the fetal tissue-vaccine connection to her
husband's attention after she learned about it at a women's Bible
study group.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Merck &AMP; Co. Inc., the manufacturer of Varivax,
said the connection between the vaccine and any tissue taken from
aborted fetuses is tenuous at best.
</P>
<P>
   ``Merck does not see this as fetal tissue per se,'' said Donna
Cary. ``Someone took a small sample of cells and put them on a
petri dish 30 years ago. It was a little scraping.''
</P>
<P>
   The chickenpox vaccine was developed using virus taken from a
3-year-old Japanese boy in the early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   A Japanese researcher weakened the virus by growing it in both
human fetal cells and animal cells. From this virus strain, Merck
produced its vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   The vaccine must be grown in fetal cells because that was the
primary medium used to develop and test it, Cary said.
Manufacturing it with animal cells could make the vaccine less safe
or effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``These types of cell lines are used in so much research, if
they were banned it would pretty much shut down medical advances,''
Cary said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
