<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 OF JETS' QUARTERBACKS ARE JUST LEARNING, FOR NOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ Neither Neil O'Donnell nor Glenn Foley was
around this week for the Jets' rookie camp. Instead, the team was
directed by Ray Lucas, the Rutgers product, and Chuck Clements, the
quarterback out of East Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Like O'Donnell and Foley, neither of them knows what's going to
happen this season. But Lucas and Clements have a lower profile.
They hang out together, scratch their heads during meetings and
avoid controversy.
</P>
<P>
   The rookie camp was Lucas' first foray on the field after an
off-season of intensive meetings and drills.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets are attempting to make a professional quarterback out
of him. Thus, coach Bill Parcells patted him on the back after he
drilled a completion into the hands of a wide receiver.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder the quarterback coach, Dan Henning, used the word
``amazing'' after another Lucas completion.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets have a starting quarterback. But no one knows who he is
_ the up-and-coming but injury-plagued Foley, or the experienced
O'Donnell, whose refusal to take a pay cut has left his status
unclear.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets also have another quarterback in camp _ Scott Frost,
who directed the nation's top-rated offense while leading Nebraska
to a share of the national title. Frost is trying to make the team
as a safety.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas is no rookie. He is going into his third season after an
outstanding career at Rutgers. But after starring as a demon
special-teamer on the Jets last year as well as a third-down option
specialist, he wants to throw the ball. So far in his pro career,
he has thrown five passes.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas is still trying to master the system, though, and
acknowledges that in meetings with O'Donnell, Foley and Clements,
he often wonders what Henning is talking about.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I think I'm in another world,'' Lucas said. ``They
ask me, `Do you understand?' and I say, `No, but when I go
downstairs to the locker room I'll ask someone and find out.'''
</P>
<P>
   Henning, who tutored Joe Namath and Richard Todd more than two
decades ago on the Jets, changed Lucas' mechanics in the
off-season. He told him to take shorter strides and to make
decisions more quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't know how this whole thing will be played out,''
Lucas said, ``but I'm still hoping Coach Parcells will use me on
third down.''
</P>
<P>
   He also wants to remain on special teams, even though he has put
on 15 pounds to be able to take a quarterback's pounding and has
switched uniform numbers, from 18 to 6.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas did not throw a National Football League pass until the
Jets' regular-season finale at Detroit. He he came in for O'Donnell
against the Lions and connected on a third-and-1 play.
</P>
<P>
   He helped lead the Jets to a field goal, then came in later with
the Jets leading by 10-6, brought them to the goal line, but threw
an interception. The Jets went on to lose in a game that cost them
a playoff appearance.
</P>
<P>
   The first time Lucas met Henning, they discussed that
interception.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have to think about it,'' Henning told him, ``don't do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucas understands that when the veterans are back for the start
of summer camp, his time will be limited. If both Foley and
O'Donnell are there, then there will be a quarterback shootout, and
that means precious few snaps for the No. 3 man.
</P>
<P>
   Or precious few snaps for Clements, for that matter. Clements,
who was a rookie with the Jets last season, tossed more than 50
touchdowns in his last two seasons at Huntsville High in Texas,
where his father coached him. He was also a big star at the
University of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   But his NFL experience consists of five plays in last season's
opening rout of Seattle. Clements handed off three times and knelt
down twice. ``To this point in my life, it's still the greatest
thrill of my career,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Two young quarterbacks. One remembering the first game of the
season, another trying to forget the last. Neither knows when he
will throw his next pass.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
