<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-BELMONT-JERKENS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JERKENS AND SON BECOME NEIGHBORS AND RIVALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
(lb) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ Fathers and sons have appeared across the racing
stage over the years with mixed results and relationships.
</P>
<P>
   B.A. and Jimmy Jones won the Kentucky Derby eight times for
Calumet Farm, and swept the Triple Crown twice. Max and Buddy
Hirsch were a team until Buddy left for Chicago with a short string
of horses and this advice from his father: ``If you run out of
money, sell one of the horses.'' And trainer Syl Veitch was the
father of John Veitch, the trainer of Alydar, who ran second to
Affirmed in all three races in the Triple Crown, 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Now the 130th Belmont Stakes has produced Allen Jerkens and his
son Jimmy, once bonded in the family racing stable, now neighbors
in adjoining barns at Belmont Park and, for the first time, rivals
in the Belmont Stakes. Allen, 69, the master of the upset in racing
lore, is the trainer of Limit Out, and Jimmy, one of his four
children, trim and serious at 39, is the trainer of Thomas Jo.
</P>
<P>
   The family's racing interests have been housed in Barn 30
(father) and Barn 31 (son), although Jimmy keeps six of his horses
in Allen's barn across the driveway and is just as familiar there
now as he was during the 20 years he served as an assistant to his
famous father. He considered the age-old question of the father who
casts a long shadow.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew that Dad had the reputation of a giant-killer in
racing,'' Jimmy said. ``But the fact that he was our father was
enough. That already made him the greatest, not his reputation in
racing.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen Jerkens, a man of few words, was the youngest trainer ever
elected to the Hall of Fame in 1975 when he was 45. He has now been
a horse trainer for 48 years, he has won 3,200 races, including 200
stakes, and four times he was the leading trainer in New York. He
trained such stars as Beau Purple, Devil His Due, Missy's Mirage
and the great filly Sky Beauty.
</P>
<P>
   But his legend grew with each upset he scored over some of the
giants of racing.
</P>
<P>
   In 1962, Beau Purple outran Carry Back in the Suburban Handicap,
the year after Carry Back won the Kentucky Derby and Preakness. In
1967, his Handsome Boy upset Buckpasser in the Brooklyn Handicap.
In 1973, reaching a peak of unlikely success, his colt Onion outran
the mighty Secretariat in the Whitney at Saratoga when Secretariat
was the 1-10 favorite. A month later or so later, Jerkens did it
again: His horse Prove Out rallied to defeat Secretariat by four
and a half lengths.
</P>
<P>
   He also saddled horses who outran Forego, Riva Ridge and Cicada
and three times outran Kelso.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's probably overdone,'' Jerkens said. ``It doesn't
really matter, but it gets a little annoying.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen Jerkens was born in Islip and remembers how the family got
involved in horses.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father was in the riding-stable business,'' he said. ``He
also liked to patch up broken-down racehorses, and have someone
bring them back for racing for him. I wanted to be a jockey at
first, but realized I was too large for that. So, I became a
steeplechase rider for a short time when I was 17. And I took out
my trainer's license in 1950, and here we are.''
</P>
<P>
   He is regarded not only as a giant-killer in racing circles but
also as a strong, silent type who usually goes straight from
paddock to railing to watch his horses run. He avoids sitting with
the horse's owner, preferring to endure his race-time agony in
private, win or lose.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Jerkens, who went out on his own as a trainer last fall,
has not lost any of his fealty to his father. They talk about
horses and races, just as they always did, but they also keep a
discreet distance when running their horses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ran against each other twice before the Belmont,'' Jimmy
said. ``Allen won both races. I ran second once and out of the
money the other time.''
</P>
<P>
   He smiled, and said with the resigned but proud air of the son
of a celebrated father, ``But he had the favorites both times.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
