<P>
   (NYT7) PESHAWAR, Pakistan -- June 6, 1998 -- PAKISTAN-GUNTRADE,
6-6 -- Gun dealers in Peshawar show their wares. Peshawar has long
been a place where gunsmiths have passed along the skills to make
exact duplicates of firearms. In bazaars and along roads leading
north toward the Hindu Kush mountains and the foothills of the
Himalayas, hundreds of shops offer a dazzling array of firearms.
Many of the weapons sold here find their way into neighboring
Afghanistan, where war has been raging almost continually for more
than two decades and seems unlikely to end soon. (New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- June 6, 1998 -- NY-ROCKEFELLER-CENTER, 6-6 --
Tourists taking in the sights at Rockefeller Center. Bringing
tourists to the heart of Rockefeller Center, by way of redesign, is
part of its new owners' plan for speeding the area's recovery and
turning it into a year-round attraction for shoppers and a
destination for restaurant- and entertainment-seekers. Critics
contend that the ``new face'' for the center will not only
transform its retail stores, but also its landmark architecture.
(Nancy Siesel/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. -- June 6, 1998 --
MEDALOFHONOR-REUNION, 6-6 -- Col. George Day, left, and Vice Adm.
James Stockdale, both Medal of Honor recipients, attending a
convention of the Congressional Medal of Honor Society. Stockdale,
was captured during the Vietnam War and inflicted a near-fatal
wound on himself rather than disclose critical information to his
captors. For most, the Medal of Honor, the nation's highest
military award for bravery, has bound together men who were once
strangers. (Dith Pran/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) LYNBROOK, N.Y. -- June 6, 1998 -- FAMILIES-MEDICALCARE-3,
6-6 -- Katie Cunningham, 9, healthy and active after an intestinal
transplant, still requires a catheter in her bladder three times a
day. Over the years, Katie's mother, Regina Cunningham, 41, has not
only wrestled with tubes in her daughter's chest and with pumps for
food or antibiotics, she has also learned to spot infection before
doctors do. Ms. Cunningham feels that she has received inadequate
training, and is exhausted from her ``medical duties.'' ``It's very
stressful,'' she says ``You ask yourself: Am I doing the right
thing? After all, I'm not an expert.'' (Edward Keating/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- June 6, 1998 -- FAMILIES-MEDICALCARE-2, 6-6
-- Jack Kaufman, 70, at home with his wife Phyllis, has a feeding
tube implanted in his stomach, after suffering a stroke. Dealing
with the machine has been overwhelming for Mrs. Kaufman. ``In my
time, I've never learned anything about computers. And all these
buttons! I'm scared of it,'' she says. Still, because of the
advantages patients have at home -- familiar surroundings and away
from the risk of infection in hospitals -- many cases of caregiving
prove more joyous than painful, even if families are providing care
in a way that would have been unheard-of only a few years ago.
(Edward Keating/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) HICKSVILLE, N.Y. -- June 6, 1998 --
FAMILIES-MEDICALCARE-1, 6-6 -- Two-year-old Jimmy Knight, at home
in Hicksville, N.Y., has a condition that requires a tracheotomy
tube to suction out mucus from his lungs. Like millions of families
across the United States, the Knights find themselves in the midst
of what many experts say is a fundamental shift in health care:
Families are performing an unprecedented amount of technical
medical care in their homes, much of which would once have been
provided by doctors or nurses alone. (Edward Keating/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) SACRAMENTO, Calif. -- June 6, 1998 -- CALIF-CENSUS, 6-6
-- David Granados, a census taker, also known at the Census Bureau
as an enumerator, in Sacramento, goes door to door with forms. The
Census Bureau is testing a new method called statistical sampling,
for gathering data as part of its dress rehearsal for the next
nationwide head count in the year 2000. Republican strategists
privately fear -- and Democratic strategists privately hope -- that
a more accurate count would give the Democrats an advantage when
the data from the census is used to draw boundaries for state
legislatures and the House of Representatives. (Peter DaSilva/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
