<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-06 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7485 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-PIAZZA-NYT &LR;      06-06 0405
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PIAZZA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALENTINE SEETHES AS PIAZZA MUST SIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Mike Piazza spoke too optimistically about possibly
pinch-hitting Saturday. His swollen left hand prevented him from
even swinging a bat, while Mets manager Bobby Valentine spoke
rather angrily about Boston's Pedro Martinez for injuring Piazza
with an inside fastball on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza, who wore a gauze wrap around his hand, tossed a ball
Saturday and insisted that the swelling had diminished and that he
simply wanted to take the day off to be safe. But the catcher's
prognosis did not stop Valentine from wondering aloud if Martinez's
2-2 pitch with first base open in the first inning had a purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't like it,'' Valentine said. ``Whatever it was, I
didn't like it because of the way the pitch wound up. He's not
playing today.''
</P>
<P>
   When Valentine was asked if he did not like it simply because
Piazza was injured or because he thought Martinez intended to drill
Piazza, the manager said: ``I don't like it for all of the above
reasons. There's nothing about the situation I like. He has pretty
good control most of the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, who is notorious for buzzing hitters with inside
pitches, said, ``The ball just ran up and in on me.'' Boston
catcher Jim Leyritz added that Martinez ``absolutely was not
throwing at Piazza,'' and that he threw a tailing fastball inside
because Piazza had looked so bad on a previous high-and-tight
pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a whiner, I'm not a complainer,'' said Piazza, who
intimated strongly on Friday that Martinez had aimed at him. ``It's
part of the game. Unfortunately, it happens. Fortunately, it's not
broken and that's it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Valentine was still seething, enough to vehemently disagree
when a reporter repeated Martinez's assertion that Piazza was
diving into the pitch and enough to gloat about the Mets' 9-2
victory, which included four homers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four home runs is a pretty good way of answering that
nonsense,'' Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza planned to continue receiving ice treatment on his hand
Saturday and before Sunday night's game against the Red Sox, but it
seemed improbable that he would play before Monday against Tampa
Bay at Shea Stadium, if then.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little tender,'' Piazza said. ``When you get in a game,
adrenaline starts to flow. I'll take an extra day to make sure.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-06-98 1736EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
