<HEADER>
A7487 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-NYT &LR;      06-06 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASKETBALL NOTEBOOK 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ In an effort to head off a potential boycott of
the world championships in Athens this summer, USA Basketball has
sent letters to team members threatening legal action if the
players fail to honor their signed contracts with the organization,
according to two agents representing players on the team.
</P>
<P>
   The move comes after commissioner David Stern of the National
Basketball Association questioned the patriotism of players who
might bow to pressure from the National Basketball Players
Association to not play in the games, which run from July 29
through Aug. 9.
</P>
<P>
   The union president, Patrick Ewing, has quietly been encouraging
members of the team, including Knicks teammate Allan Houston, to
not represent the NBA until the league's labor problems are solved.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan chimed in with his support last Thursday, stating
that the player boycott would serve as a counter to a potential
lockout by the owners on July 1 _ the day after the current
collective bargaining agreement between both sides expires.
</P>
<P>
   Whether USA Basketball will file separate suits charging breach
of contract against the players is unclear. But the action is the
latest indication that players and owners have a long summer ahead,
and that a lockout is almost certain.
</P>
<P>
   The key issue is the owner's request for a hard salary cap, a
proposal that would ultimately put a ceiling on how much a team can
pay its players in a given season.
</P>
<P>
   L.A. Confidential
</P>
<P>
   The league's best running soap opera is still ``As the Bulls
Turn.'' But the Los Angeles Lakers are beginning to make a ratings
push.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry West, whose front-office wizardry has been responsible for
the franchise's success over the last two decades, is still miffed
at owner Jerry Buss' failure to reward his loyalty and commitment
with dollars. The two are expected to meet Monday to discuss West's
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no health issues involved _ it's basically about
money owed to Jerry,'' a Lakers team official said.
</P>
<P>
   West was promised a bonus of several million dollars by Buss
after signing Shaquille O'Neal in 1996. Rather than pay West a lump
sum, the Lakers owner has doled out the money over time. West, the
team official said, feels it is a matter of principle that he be
paid the balance in full before he can decide to stay in his job.
</P>
<P>
   West has also requested a long-term annuity after he retires and
was said to be upset about the owner pulling the plug on a
potential deal for Mitch Richmond at the beginning of the current
season. The Lakers were prepared to send Eddie Jones to Sacramento,
but reneged at the last minute because Buss was apparently worried
about compensating Richmond after his current deal expires.
</P>
<P>
   Also at issue in Monday's meeting is whether Del Harris will
indeed return as the team's coach. Another team official termed
Harris' chances at ``50-50'' after the Lakers were swept by Utah in
the Western Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   With O'Neal able to exercise an out clause in his contract and
Kobe Bryant's current deal eligible for an extension, there is
plenty of uncertainty in the air. In fact, there is but one
clear-cut plan for the Lakers at the moment: trading the
disenchanted point guard Nick Van Exel.
</P>
<P>
   No. 1? Probably Bibby
</P>
<P>
   Some teams are worried about his size and others are worried
about his durability. Still, Mike Bibby is beginning to emerge as
the player the Los Angeles Clippers will take with the No. 1 pick
in the draft on June 24 in Vancouver, B.C.
</P>
<P>
   The unpolished, 6-foot-2-inch, 180-pound Arizona point guard
will most likely go ahead of Michael Olowokandi, the 7-foot,
265-pound project from the University of the Pacific; Kansas
forward Paul Pierce, and North Carolina's Antawn Jamison.
</P>
<P>
   Vancouver, meanwhile, is flirting with trading its No. 2 pick
and has even had discussions with Toronto, an Eastern Conference
team official said. But the Grizzlies are leery. Even though they
play in different conferences, their Canadian rivalry would make
the move akin to the Knicks and Heat swapping players.
</P>
<P>
   How weak is this year's crop of talent? Denver Nuggets general
manager Dan Issel recently brought Olowokandi in for a workout.
Without any players around to gauge his talent, Issel suited up and
played defense against the nation's premier big man.
</P>
<P>
   He blocked Olowokandi's first two shots.
</P>
<P>
   The Wizards Get Blunt
</P>
<P>
   Give Wes Unseld credit. Unlike many of his spin-doctor
colleagues, he is honest.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Wizards general manager recently sent a letter to
season ticket-holders, informing them that last season's dismal
performance would not be tolerated again.
</P>
<P>
   He expressed his dismay about the team's off-court problems and
said any future incidents would be punished by ``the most extreme
measures possible'' under the league's collective bargaining
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The Wizards, one of the league's most talent-laden teams,
narrowly missed the playoffs last season. They were not only
hamstrung by on-court problems, but also were undermined by mayhem
off the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to clean up our approach,'' coach Bernie Bickerstaff
told The Washington Post. ``We've got to clean up our loyalty to
the fans, the organization and the game.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
