<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-FRENCH-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SELES WINS OPPONENT'S SYMPATHY, NOT THE TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Monica Seles, who somehow willed her way into the French
Open final a few short weeks after losing her father to cancer, had
sympathy and tragedy on her side of the net. If anyone deserved a
happy ending to two draining weeks on this soggy red clay, it was
Seles.
</P>
<P>
   A three-time champion here, she made an inspired bid for a 10th
career Grand Slam singles crown at the very event that launched her
back in 1990. When she won then, she was a giggling 16-year-old
juggernaut who seemed not to have a care in the world beyond
drilling tennis balls at and past her every foe.
</P>
<P>
   But because the adversary across the net Saturday was the
two-time champion Arantxa Sanchez Vicario, the same indefatigable
Spaniard whom Seles defeated here in the 1991 finale and thrashed
again in the 1993 U.S. Open, Seles failed to gain the full measure
of spiritual and emotional redemption she sought.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez Vicario _ who hadn't won a Grand Slam title in four
years and had her own redemptive issues roiling in the back of her
mind as she headed into this poignant finale _ refused to
relinquish her personal designs on the 1998 French Open
championship in order to spare Seles further heartache. Instead,
Sanchez Vicario carried off a masterly 7-6 (7-5), 0-6, 6-2 victory
first and apologized for it later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so sorry that I beat you,'' Sanchez Vicario told Seles,
and the rain-splattered crowd, as she gave her acceptance speech.
``I have a lot of respect for you and what you did here to get to
the final,'' said Sanchez Vicario, who complimented Seles for
showing such ``professionality'' so soon after the death of her
father, Karolj.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez Vicario also declared that regardless of the invasion of
women's tennis by the parcel of teen-agers, the French Open
campaigns of Seles and herself stood as living proof that ``we have
a long way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Seles, she added, ``She also is a great champion, and I think
this is better for women's tennis, because it shows we're still in
there.'
</P>
<P>
   What the 26-year-old Sanchez Vicario did Saturday was play a
vintage brand of tennis. She scurried and scampered and, in her own
special way, went for the jugular just as she had when she won her
first Grand Slam title here in 1989 at 17. She did so again at
Roland Garros in 1994, when she regained her form and ended a
five-year Grand Slam drought.
</P>
<P>
   She chugged to and fro on the red grit like a little locomotive
content to take the most indirect of routes to her destination. She
sent defensive topspin lobs into the gloomy sky like clay pigeons
at a skeet shoot, then patiently waited for her impatient opponent
to try to shoot them down.
</P>
<P>
   Exhausted but successful after the 51-minute first set was
decided with a tie breaker, Sanchez Vicario bided her time in the
second, let Seles expend ample energy in the act of leveling the
contest, then cleverly revved up into full retrieval-and-rebuttal
mode when the match was on the line in the final set.
</P>
<P>
   In all, Seles made 48 unforced errors and made Sanchez Vicario
pay for just five of the 14 break opportunities she allowed. ``I
made so many errors against Arantxa that you just can't make,''
Seles said, ``and she played really well whenever she was down,
just hit some great shots, and when I was up, I did just the
opposite.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``In the first set, I ran out of gas there, and Arantxa is such
a great player, she just ran down everything,'' said Seles, who
undermined herself by choosing all the wrong shots as she served
for the opening set at 5-4.
</P>
<P>
   Seles chastised herself for stubbornly attempting ``stupid drop
shots'' with the humidity-laden balls. Then, by slamming an
elementary overhead into the net at 30-30, she took herself to
break point instead of set point. Although Sanchez Vicario failed
to convert that one, a couple of forehand errors from Seles set up
and then converted the Spaniard's second break point for her.
</P>
<P>
   In the tie breaker, a cascade of puffballs from Sanchez Vicario
goaded Seles into swinging backhand volley errors on the fourth and
fifth points, giving the Spaniard a 4-1 lead. Though Seles crept
back to knot the tie breaker, 5-5, a netted forehand return
followed by another netted forehand after a lengthy rally at set
point gave the set to Sanchez Vicario.
</P>
<P>
   Not much more than a bystander in the middle set, Sanchez
Vicario resurfaced with a vengeance, and a plan, in the third.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew in my mind that the third set was going to be a
different story,'' she said. ``It was important to start really
well, concentrate a little more, play a little more deep, stay into
the match and be able to be ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the key, to start a little better in the third set,
to hang in there,'' said Sanchez Vicario, who has built an entire
career doing precisely that.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of crumbling when she faced two break points in the
first game, the Spaniard staved them off and broke Seles for a 2-0
lead that she improved to 3-0 by saving another break point in the
third game. Down 15-40 in the fifth game, Sanchez Vicario again
bounced back, a recovery that demoralized Seles.
</P>
<P>
   In deep trouble at 2-5, Seles didn't save herself: More
defensive lobbing from Sanchez Vicario produced another netted
overhead, a mistake that was followed at break and match point by
yet another swinging backhand volley that missed its mark.
</P>
<P>
   Though it takes more than a tennis match to make Seles cry these
days, she made it clear she wasn't delighted about working her way
into the final round only to lose there. ``I'm happy that I got
this far and everything, but every time I lose, I'm disappointed,''
she said. ``In the finals or in the first round, it's equally hard
to take.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez Vicario was not unmindful of the fact that the
sympathies of the crowd were clearly in Seles' corner. ``It's
happened to me here before,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But if anyone deserved a sympathy vote, it was Seles. She had
lost her chance to win a fourth consecutive French Open title in
1993 because she was stabbed in Germany three weeks before the
Paris tournament began, played last year's Open with one eye on the
ball and the other on her terminally ill father, and competed this
year despite losing her parent and coach to cancer on May 14.
</P>
<P>
   Seles just didn't receive Sanchez Vicario's sympathy vote, at
least not for the duration of the 1-hour-53-minute match. ``But if
I lose, I lose with somebody who deserves to win,'' the Spaniard
said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, her victory guaranteed Spain a repeat of the triumph it
enjoyed here in 1994, a sweep of the singles titles. With Carlos
Moya and Alex Corretja squaring off in the men's final on Sunday, a
Spanish champion is assured. ``Obviously I would like them both to
win,'' said Sanchez Vicario, gracious to the end.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
