<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FOSTER-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYIS: GIULIANI'S FOSTER CARE PLAN FACES POLITICAL MINEFIELD 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By NINA BERNSTEIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New York City treats its foster care system like a
slot machine, a child welfare commissioner complained in the
mid-1970s: it pours in money and hopes for the best.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, would-be reformers inside and outside city
government have tried to turn the hundreds of millions of dollars
the city spends yearly on foster care contracts into a force for
controlled improvement, rather than a gamble with the lives of
abused and neglected children.
</P>
<P>
   A plan to refocus the system along community district lines and
put the pieces up for bid, announced by Mayor Rudolph Giuliani last
week, is the most sweeping effort in almost 20 years to change the
way the city does business with the private, nonprofit agencies
that care for most children in foster care.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, the plan seems to concern uncomplicated shifts
in social work philosophy _ delivering services to children in
their neighborhoods rather than dispersing them throughout the
region. But underneath, it presents a minefield of power politics
and patronage in a city where racial, religious and ethnic
interests have historically clashed over children as they battled
for a bigger share of public money and social clout.
</P>
<P>
   Foster care has long been a key source of both. Last year 23 of
the 50 biggest city contractors were foster care agencies, and 10
of them alone handled about half the city's $614 million foster
care budget, according to an analysis by Child Welfare Watch, an
independent publication. Most of the 10 are at least 100 years old
and have well-established influence at City Hall through their ties
to the city's major religious leadership and through trustees and
boards drawn from the city's business establishment. Newer,
smaller, agencies include minority-run programs started through
state grants in the 1980s and nurtured under the Dinkins
administration.
</P>
<P>
   The last overhaul comparable to the one detailed Wednesday by
Nicholas Scoppetta, commissioner of the Administration for
Children's Services, was acclaimed in 1979 as a revolution. But
after a promising start, it was derailed by the pressures of city
politics, economic downturns and roller-coaster shifts in the
city's foster care population. Regardless of the value of
neighborhood-based services, how much difference the new plan makes
will ultimately depend on whether Scoppetta can safely steer it
through such pitfalls.
</P>
<P>
   Politics will inevitably be part of the scramble for the $614
million pot the plan opens to redivision. The change presents the
possibility of new jobs and public money in neighborhoods riven by
ethnic rivalries, and the expansion or contraction of institutions
with major campaign contributors on their boards.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's unveiling of a system redesign came six weeks before
the scheduled start of trial in Marisol vs. Giuliani, a
class-action lawsuit brought late in 1995 by Children's Rights
Inc., a national nonprofit children's advocacy organization.
</P>
<P>
   The federal lawsuit aims at all aspects of the city child
welfare system, from child-abuse investigations through foster
care, and asks that a receiver be given full authority to
restructure the city's Administration for Children's Services on
behalf of more than 100,000 children. The city's position has been
that Scoppetta's changes make this lawsuit and other pending
litigation against the agency a dead letter if not a hindrance.
</P>
<P>
   Scoppetta's plan envisions a neighborhood-based child welfare
system reminiscent of the old settlement house model. It is based
on a longstanding social work consensus, honored far more in the
breach than the observance, that children should be placed close to
home. Under the plan, contractors are to be held responsible for
serving children and families in one community, supporting them
with a range of linked services, including health care, counseling
and drug treatment as well as foster care. Agencies that fail to
improve outcomes for children would risk losing their city
contracts.
</P>
<P>
   But veterans of the city's foster care wars, while admiring the
ambition of Scoppetta's effort, have not forgotten lessons from the
past.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, the Board of Estimate, then the powerful budgetary arm
of New York City government, outlawed the automatic contract
renewals and rate increases that had become common for foster care
agencies and adopted measurable performance standards. One of the
standards detailed in the resulting program assessment system was
children's placement in their home borough. That was a less
ambitious geographical requirement than the one in Scoppetta's
plan, yet the city abandoned it in 1985 as soon as foster beds fell
short of need. Today only 6 percent of the 42,000 children in
foster care reside in their own community district, though nearly
every district has enough foster families to accommodate the foster
children it originates.
</P>
<P>
   Many other requirements detailed in contracts fell by the
wayside in the late 1980s as the balance of power between the
agencies and the city shifted with the rising number of children
pouring into care. Fueled by deepening poverty, homelessness, AIDS
and crack, the foster care population rose from a low of 17,000 in
1985 to almost 50,000 in 1991. That year, the assessment system was
eliminated in budget cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The moment the numbers exploded, the message to the city was,
you can be assessing people until you're blue in the face _ who
cares when you're using every bed they have?'' Steven Cohen, who
oversaw the city's contract relations with the agencies until 1985,
once explained. ``You can't regulate anything when the suppliers
control the market.''
</P>
<P>
   The most dramatic show of contractor clout came over church
precepts. When Cardinal John O'Connor publicly threatened to end
his archdiocese's role in the foster care system, the city chose
not to enforce a contract requirement that teen-agers have access
to family planning.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor then, Ed Koch, quickly repudiated the court-ordered
consent decree that mandated such services, though it had been
negotiated by his own corporation counsel. Potentially at stake
were not only a quarter of the city's foster care beds, but Roman
Catholic votes in a difficult election year.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last week, Scoppetta was impatient with
references to past failures. ``I don't know that there's ever been
a concerted effort to do it the way we're doing it,'' he said.
``Agencies were not really held accountable. Isn't it time to
change that?''
</P>
<P>
   But children's advocates are concerned about the city's own
accountability. For more than a decade the city has been under
judicial order to promptly evaluate children who come into city
custody and to place them in the best program available for their
needs. Last year no more than 6 percent of children placed had
timely initial evaluations, according to city data. Hit-or-miss
telephone brokerage has remained the city's dominant method of
placing children, in part because it still lacks the computer
capacity to find vacancies accurately.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as 1996, for example, Spanish-speaking children from
Sunset Park in Brooklyn were assigned by the city to foster
families in Harlem who spoke no Spanish, despite vacancies in their
own neighborhood linked to the Center for Family Life, a national
model of the kind of community services network that Scoppetta is
trying to create citywide.
</P>
<P>
   ``I credit them for their aspirations,'' said Marcia Robinson
Lowry, director of Children's Rights Inc. ``What is dangerous here
is if they want to declare victory and go home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
