<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-HERON-STATUE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: A MONUMENT TO THE BAY ROILS WATERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By EVELYN NIEVES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTHOLD, N.Y. _ No one has claimed the heron isn't big. Why,
big is too small a word for it. The heron is breathtakingly
colossal: 40 feet tall, two tons of twisted steel, with a beak that
seems to reach the sky. Standing on a groin extending from Jim and
Barbara Miller's waterfront back yard, it can be seen from Cedar
Beach, about a half-mile away, and, as the neighbors tell it, from
just about everywhere else, clear across Shelter Island Sound.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, a former commercial fisherman who runs a company that
cleans up oil spills and other sea calamities, calls the heron a
monument to Peconic Bay, whose waters have allowed him to ply a
decent trade, raise six children and buy a big, lovely house on
three acres.
</P>
<P>
   But neighbors say the bird is an eyesore.
</P>
<P>
   They want it gone. They've written to the Army Corps of
Engineers, the state Department of Environmental Conservation and
the town. ``I must now worry about the increased boat traffic that
will be attracted to view such a large object,'' complained Ann
Smith.
</P>
<P>
   And Robert Scott worried about what could come next. ``Art and
its appreciation is personal in nature,'' he said. ``Where would
such a precedent lead us?'' Others on this remote edge of Long
Island's North Fork fretted that the bird might blow away in a
storm, wrecking their houses and endangering life and limb.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nonsense!'' said Miller, as he showed off the heron on his
shell-strewn, pebbly beach the other day. ``This bird hasn't
attracted hordes of boats. It's not the only large piece of art in
town and it's bolted to withstand hundred-mile-an-hour winds.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. But the town building inspector has jumped into the fray.
And now the Great Heron is the subject of a great debate: When is a
sculpture ``a structure''?
</P>
<P>
   The Millers, who were slapped with a summons for a building-code
violation, say never. At least not in this case. ``We got the
necessary approvals from the town trustees and the DEC,'' Miller
said. ``People wrote letters, so the town said we got to do
something. So they did something.''
</P>
<P>
   This has made arts organizations, like the National Campaign for
Freedom of Expression in Washington and the East End Arts Council
here, pretty edgy. Their concern is that if the Millers have to
remove the heron, it would set a national precedent. Any group of
people who didn't like a public display of art could try to have it
removed, starting an onerous fight for its owner.
</P>
<P>
   But Miller takes the issue in stride. ``I'm a pretty positive
kind of a guy,'' he said, ``so I don't think of things like
defeat.''
</P>
<P>
   The Millers are due in court later this month. But their lawyer,
Harvey Arnoff, said he was considering an application to stay the
enforcement of the zoning code. ``The town has no code for art,''
he said. ``And if they want to apply the strict definition of the
building code to this, then the statues in front of the various
churches are illegal, as are birdbaths.''
</P>
<P>
   Funny thing is, the heron has attracted a lot more attention
than it would have if no one had complained. The Millers'
neighborhood is very private. Houses are announced with great stone
pillars and long, shaded driveways. Shrubs are meticulously coifed,
but the houses always look as if no one is home.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its size, the heron is too far from the beaten track,
from the trendy Hamptons _ on a beach where only the people who
live here play _ to have garnered much notice if people from far
and wide hadn't heard about it.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, some people actually like the bird. Last weekend,
dozens were among the 80 who joined the Millers and the heron's
creator, Roberto Julio Bessin of Centerport, at a ceremony
dedicating it to Peconic Bay. (Bessin made it in 1988 and displayed
it in his yard for three years without a snag.)
</P>
<P>
   Just as the ceremony was starting, thunder and lightning cracked
the sky, which everyone thought was quite appropriate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
