<SLUG> BC-NY-HOMELESS-549&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETARDED ADULTS LIVING IN HOMELESS SHELTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOSEPH BERGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARRISON, N.Y. _ The homeless shelter at the Westchester County
Airport here is tidier than many of its New York City cousins, but
experts still would not consider it the most congenial place for a
mentally retarded person to live.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, 26 mentally retarded adults are living in this and other
county shelters because of a statewide shortage of beds in group
homes or in supervised apartments, county officials disclosed last
week.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the retarded adults, officials said, wound up in the
county's shelters after living with aged or frail parents who could
no longer care for them. Others were unhappy with their group homes
and wandered off; still others wore out their welcome with
relatives.
</P>
<P>
   The disclosure that retarded adults are living among a homeless
population that includes drug and alcohol addicts and ex-convicts
embarrassed county officials and local state legislators and caused
some to wonder whether the situation in Westchester suggested a
statewide problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there are 25 here, then there are 250 in New York City,''
said Assemblyman Richard Brodsky, D-Greenburgh. ``What sort of
society takes mentally retarded people and forces them in homeless
shelters?''
</P>
<P>
   But Deborah Sturm Rausch, a spokeswoman for the state Office of
Mental Retardation and Developmental Disabilities, said state
officials had surveyed other counties and concluded that the
situation in Westchester was an isolated one.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Wiviott, a spokeswoman for the New York City Department of
Homeless Services, said she was sure there were some mentally
retarded people whose condition had been misdiagnosed and as a
result were placed in a shelter system that cares for 7,000 single
adults a night. But department workers, she said, did not encounter
enough such cases to consider the homeless retarded a major
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Brodsky and some county officials attributed the shortage of
beds to Gov. George Pataki's decision to halt spending for new
group homes for several years, ending last year. Roughly 6,500
people in the state, including 100 in Westchester, are on waiting
lists seeking placement. Although the governor has authorized some
1,500 new slots, such homes often face stiff neighborhood
resistance.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of mentally retarded people in shelters came to light
on Tuesday night at the annual dinner of the Westchester
Association for Retarded Citizens. Morton Steinberg, a founder of
GROW, an advocacy group for the retarded, said he learned in
February that a handful of retarded people were homeless, but in
discussions before and during the dinner it emerged that the actual
number was 26.
</P>
<P>
   The large number of homeless retarded crystallized a problem
that distresses many elderly parents of the retarded. These parents
are desperate to place their retarded children in community
residences, fearing that the children will otherwise end up
homeless when the parents die.
</P>
<P>
   Mildred Rigano of New Rochelle is 78 and her husband, Philip, is
80. Their son, Robert, is mildly retarded _ he can sign his name
but cannot read very much _ and has been living with them all his
life. For 12 years they have been unable to find a slot for him in
a community residence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're concerned if something happens to us, what will happen
to him,'' she said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Steven Friedman, the county's community mental health
commissioner, said that retarded people, especially the high
functioning ones that have ended up in the homeless shelters,
needed work experiences and literacy programs and that it was
difficult to provide such rehabilitation in shelters.
</P>
<P>
   He said that in 1995 the county was able to place 80 to 100
people a year in group residences; but given the state shortage of
beds since then, it had been able to place only 30 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Brodsky announced Friday that he was asking for $275,000 to
provide rent subsidies and counseling for the 26 adults in the
shelters. He called the emergence of homeless retarded ``a
breakdown in the bureaucracy'' and a lapse of ``a moral compass.''
</P>
<P>
   There was bipartisan dismay over the problem, with both
Democrats and Republicans accepting responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sad commentary that people with disabilities are being
dumped in homeless shelters,'' said State Sen. Nicholas Spano,
R-Yonkers, who for many years led the Senate committee on mental
health. ``Everybody should recognize that we are all to blame.''
</P>
<P>
   He, too, announced legislation that would give state officials
no more than 30 days to place a retarded person without a home in a
community residence.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's office did not return phone calls seeking a
response. But Spano said that Pataki last year provided for the
creation of 600 new residential slots and that the state
Legislature added another 57. In this fiscal year, Pataki has
included money for 867 new slots.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Office of Mental Retardation and Developmental
Disabilities sent a team to Westchester on Thursday to assess the
26 retarded people in shelters and recommend placements for them.
</P>
<P>
   At the homeless shelter here, set among hangars, airport runways
and fuel trucks, some of the regular residents did not think it was
the best place for retarded adults. ``It's more like a jail setting
here,'' said Abdullah Abraham, who has lived at the shelter for a
year. ``Mentally retarded people have more needs than homeless.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
