<SLUG> BC-NY-FIREFIGHTER-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIREFIGHTER WHO LOST HIS LIFE PUT SAFETY FIRST 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MIRTA OJITO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ His profile fits that of most other good guys who die
heroically, on the job, saving other people's lives. Fire Lt. James
Blackmore, 48, was a quiet, unassuming man who spent a lot of time
with his family and liked to golf.
</P>
<P>
   He had a wife, four children, a house and, years ago, a boat. He
lived a good, simple life and had a job he loved. He was a Vietnam
veteran who never talked about his combat experiences, a careful
man who spent many hours reading safety manuals and was precise in
conducting fire drills.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were no short cuts with him,'' said Lt. Kevin McGoldric
of Engine Co. 332 in Brooklyn, where Blackmore was assigned.
``Safety, above all, was his primary consideration.''
</P>
<P>
   Blackmore died Friday night battling a five-alarm fire that
consumed a city-owned three-story apartment building in Brooklyn.
He and five other firefighters fell through the second floor, which
snapped after it was weakened by flames.
</P>
<P>
   As his fellow firefighters at Engine Co. 332 and Ladder Co. 175
awaited a delivery of the black bunting that would drape the
Brooklyn fire house where he was assigned, they remembered
Blackmore as a man who was too young and too good to die.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone loved him,'' said Capt. Gerard Donbrowsky, commander
of Ladder Co. 175. ``He was an all-around great guy. We are all in
mourning.''
</P>
<P>
   Blackmore's wife, Susan, said from their home in Farmingdale,
N.Y., that he was born in Ozone Park, Queens, the son of Elizabeth
and Robert Blackmore, who now live in Florida. He was the second
born of seven brothers and sisters and the only career firefighter
in the family, although his father was once a volunteer
firefighter. He went to several colleges but never finished his
degree in education, and he served in Vietnam from 1967 to 1971,
Mrs. Blackmore said. He became a firefighter 21 years ago and had
been cited for bravery five times, his fellow firefighters said.
</P>
<P>
   When he was not battling fires, Blackmore was playing with his
children in his back yard, his family and neighbors said. He had
three girls _ Sara, 13, Jackie, 11, and Claire, 9 _ and a boy,
Brian, 7. Because he had a firefighter's schedule, he was home
three days a week and had plenty of time to work around the house
and chat with neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always outside, taking care of the house or playing
ball with the children or, in the winter, fooling around in the
snow,'' said Michael Neglia, a neighbor who lives across the
street. ``He was a good, friendly guy. You couldn't say anything
bad about him.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before he died, Blackmore had been talking to other
firefighters about the computer he had just bought for his
children. Mrs. Blackmore, a nurse, said he had also been talking
about returning to school to finish his degree.
</P>
<P>
   ``He loved everything, and I loved him very much,'' Mrs.
Blackmore, 41, said. ``But there was nothing he liked more than
going to a fire.''
</P>
<P>
   McGoldric said he would always remember Blackmore as he last saw
him: sitting on a white plastic chair, smiling and surrounded by
firefighters who were posing for the annual picture of the ladder
company. That was Wednesday, two days before Blackmore battled his
last fire.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
