<HEADLINE>
TV SPORTS: DISNEY COMMITTING TO COMPLETE SOCCER COVERAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Program times are for New York area.)  
(lb) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This World Cup thing matters at Walt Disney's ABC, ESPN and
ESPN2.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the biggest deal on earth,'' said Bob Ley, the event's
lead play-by-play announcer, soccer dad and rabid fan since the
1970s. ``We all remember how we felt as Americans in 1980 when the
U.S. hockey team defeated the Soviet Union. Every nation can
attempt to feel that way during the World Cup. Translate it in
those terms _ love of country and love for a beautiful game.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only will each of the 64 games be carried live from France.
</P>
<P>
   Not only will each game be preceded by a half hour pregame show.
</P>
<P>
   Not only will ESPN2 carry a nightly recap show at 7:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   And not only will ESPN2 replay the day's top match most nights
at 8.
</P>
<P>
   But also, ABC will pre-empt ``General Hospital'' on June 15 for
the U.S.-Germany game and on June 25 for the U.S.-Yugoslavia
contest. (``GH'' fans will be able to see their soap in prime time
on those nights.) In New York, Channel 7 will pre-empt ``Oprah''
and the early news for the 2:30-6 p.m. broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   Now that's a Disney-wide commitment.
</P>
<P>
   For the $22 million being paid for the World Cup rights, ABC
will televise 14 matches, ESPN 27 and ESPN2 23. All three of the
U.S. team's first-round games will receive maximum exposure on ABC.
In 1994, the three American games averaged a 7.0 Nielsen rating,
above ABC's overall 5.3 average.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American games are important,'' said Ley, who became a
soccer enthusiast when he attended Bloomfield High School in New
Jersey during the North American Soccer League's heyday. ``Even in
the rosiest scenario _ the U.S. gets to the third round _ there are
still 59 games without the Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   As for whether Americans will be interested in games that don't
involve the U.S. team, Ley said: ``We have great stories to tell.
We'll reel people in with them. These players aren't going to be 11
shirts, but good guys and bad guys. I'd like to think Americans can
think outside their borders.''
</P>
<P>
   He fondly recalled the biggest surprise of the 1994 World Cup.
``Who would have thought we'd fall in love with a bunch of swarthy
Bulgarians?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, I'd forgotten that.
</P>
<P>
   The ABC-ESPN-ESPN2 format improves upon the 1994 setup, when the
event was played in the United States. Back then, there were more
than a dozen tape-delayed games. Also, there were no pregame shows,
just five minute lead-ins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our biggest failure was to cover as many matches as possible
in two hours with only five minutes before each game, and no other
ancillary programs,'' said David Downs, the senior vice president
of ABC for network operations.
</P>
<P>
   As in 1994, all commercials will be crammed into pregame and
halftime, allowing each 45-minute half to be shown uninterrupted.
</P>
<P>
   The production comes mainly from French cameras and tape
machines, and the Disney networks will augment some matches with
equipment of their own. But Geoff Mason, the executive producer for
ABC and ESPN, cautioned that the coverage will be respectful, not
revolutionary.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, no glowing ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing we can do is allow the flow of play to dictate
what our coverage style is,'' Mason said. ``If we are disciplined
enough to stay out of the way of this event, it'll work. We won't
be boring. Football is about pace and flow. The coverage the French
have put together, and our announcers, will allow us to reflect
that flow and pace. That's the best approach we can take.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Mason said the telecasts' main innovation will be used during
the pregame and halftime shows: a computer-generated ``virtual
replay'' system that uses video from stadium cameras to show
various plays from numerous angles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Otherwise, no exploding graphics, no bells and whistles,'' he
said. ``I know it's not politically correct to say that, but this
game is damned interesting. We want to show it in the most
interesting way.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the productions are too laid back, ABC, ESPN and ESPN2
risk boring casual and new viewers of soccer. There should be some
daring _ not enough so that cutting to close-ups means missing
action that is better viewed from a standard high angle, but enough
to excite rookie and veteran fans.
</P>
<P>
   The announcers _ in addition to the Ley-Seamus Malin team, the
voices include J.P. Dellacamera and Bill McErmott, and Roger
Twibell and Mike Hill _ need to bring enthusiasm. It need not be as
over the top as Univision's Andres Cantor, but they should realize
that Cantor's style is so seductive that he is worth listening to
even if you don't know Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, they must resist using too much inside soccer talk while
explaining simply the rules, plays, offenses and defenses. The
model, as usual, for deftly explaining a fast-moving sport amid
heavy action is hockey's Mike Emrick.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key to getting people to understand the game is not to
force principles on them, but to allow the flow of play to dictate
the points that will help educate,'' Malin said. ``I don't think
you can inject artificially facts or opinions or explanations where
the game isn't throwing them open for discussion. If you do that
and you have 64 telecasts, you can cover the basics of the game
without being a boring drill instructor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
