<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-MARLINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONE HEARS BARKING, BUT IT'S ONLY A JOKE
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The instant David Cone was bitten on the right index finger last
week by Veronica, his mother's Jack Russell terrier puppy, Cone
knew he would be the object of jokes from teammates. David Wells,
one of Cone's fellow starting pitchers, barks and growls and howls
every time reporters gather to ask Cone about his finger.
</P>
<P>
   The teasing is coming from all over now, however. On Friday,
Cone went to speak at a school in Harlem, P.S. 117.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had 9-year-olds asking me about dog bites,'' Cone said with
a chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   Cone says the cut is drying up, and he will most likely start
Sunday's game against Florida, two days earlier than expected.
Because David Wells is bothered by a sore shoulder, Cone will take
his place, and then Orlando Hernandez will probably start on
Tuesday in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   For the time being, Ramiro Mendoza will remain in the rotation.
Mendoza has pitched well over all, but his outings in the next few
weeks may be extremely important to his future in the rotation. If
he pitches poorly, he will provide the avenue for change.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Irabu Welcomes Nomo
</P>
<P>
   In the years they both pitched to Japan, Hideki Irabu never
developed a close friendship with Hideo Nomo, who was acquired by
the Mets in a trade Thursday night. But because Nomo was the first
Japanese-born pitcher to make an impact in the major leagues,
paving the way for Irabu and others to come here, the Yankees'
pitcher refers to Nomo, in his native language, as ``senpai'' _ an
elder.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu said Friday that he is pleased Nomo has joined the Mets
and Masato Yoshii, with whom Nomo is close friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy the trade worked out the way it did,'' Irabu
said through his interpreter, George Rose. ``Mutually, we're all
going to go out and do our best. It's nice to have guys like that
nearby.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Yankees' rotation remains in place, Irabu will not pitch
in any of the three interleague games against the Mets at the end
of this month. Joe Torre, the Yankees' manager, is not inclined to
set up any kind of a matchup between Irabu and Nomo, or Irabu and
Yoshii.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're interested in playing baseball,'' Torre said, adding
that while marketing people would want that duel, he's worried
about winning games.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu, too, said he doesn't really care about pitching against
either of his countrymen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just looking forward to talking to them at the ball park
when we play the Mets,'' Irabu said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Sympathy for Leyland
</P>
<P>
   Joe Torre visited briefly with Jim Leyland, the manager of the
Florida Marlins, a team that has the worst record in the big
leagues after winning the World Series last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Marlins have stripped their payroll and traded away
virtually all of their star players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel bad for Jim,'' Torre said. ``The thing about being the
world champion is that you win the last game, and then you go home.
When you really enjoy it is when you walk out on the field the next
year. I sensed he couldn't wear the crown like he wanted to.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Planning for Interleague Play
</P>
<P>
   When the Yankees play the three-game series in Montreal next
week, they will be without the designated hitter for the first time
this year and may have need for pinch-hitters.
</P>
<P>
   In preparation for that, the Yankees intend to call up a
right-handed-hitting position player from Class AAA _ probably
outfielder Shane Spencer, possibly Mike Lowell _ to give them 14
position players.
</P>
<P>
   If Ramiro Mendoza stays in the rotation, Orlando Hernandez will
go back to the minors.
</P>
<P>
   But if Hernandez stays, then newly acquired Scott Brow will be
headed to Class AAA Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   Close to Perfection
</P>
<P>
   Graeme Lloyd, the Yankees' left-hander, completed a strange feat
Thursday night, in pitching 1 1/3 innings of relief. Of the last 29
batters he's faced, Lloyd has retired 27, allowed one hit and one
walk. In a sense, he pitched a one-hitter over his last 12
appearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to be perfect in my own way,'' Lloyd said, with a
laugh. ``I'm hitting my spots. I haven't been worried about the
hitters at all. It's par for this team _ you want to do well, so
you're not left behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Other numbers, some bizarre, some incredible:
</P>
<P>
   _ In his first 82 2/3 innings, David Wells has allowed 17 home
runs and 17 walks.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bernie Williams, the Yankees center fielder, has 10 hits in
his last 15 at-bats with runners in scoring position, since May 23.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Yankees' bullpen has not allowed an unearned run since
April 30. That encompasses a span of 32 games. The entire Yankees
staff has allowed a total of three unearned runs in the last 32
games.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
