<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: DESORMEAUX HOPS ABOARD DESTINY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   By race time late Saturday afternoon, Kent Desormeaux had long
since come to believe that fate surely meant for him to be in post
position No. 8, aboard a sliver of a horse named Real Quiet,
shooting for the first Triple Crown in 20 years in the Belmont
Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   Why would he not believe this after what he had been through,
where he had come from to be there?
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a devout Catholic boy from Louisiana, I'd have to say
this is all God's will,'' he said. ``Absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   Athletes who expect us to believe they were chosen to win at the
expense of others are one thing. Desormeaux wasn't referring to any
divine race fixers.
</P>
<P>
   He was saying that in his mind, his heart, he was only destined
to find the trainer, Bob Baffert, who was supposed to help him
revive a comatose career, just as he was meant to nearly come back
from the dead six years ago after a horrific fall at Hollywood
Park.
</P>
<P>
   This was before he would come down with what was diagnosed
industrywide as a lousy attitude, and suffer the symptoms of being
virtually out of work.
</P>
<P>
   This was six years ago, three years after Desormeaux, at 19, set
a single-year record with 598 victories, working the prestigious
Southern California triangle of Santa Anita, Del Mar and Hollywood
Park.
</P>
<P>
   Three years before he would become the youngest jockey ever to
record his 3,000th victory.
</P>
<P>
   This was smack dab in the middle of what he previously thought
was the height of his prosperity, when his mount rebelled like a
defiant teen-ager and Desormeaux took the most painful fall from
grace, and the world went dark at the very time his wife needed him
to be her shining light.
</P>
<P>
   Sonia Desormeaux, not yet eight months pregnant, was bedridden,
hospitalized, on that day in December, 1992, when her husband was
riding a horse named Judge Hammer at Hollywood Park. He had just
taken the lead, but the horse wanted to veer left and Desormeaux
administered a couple of quick spanks to the left side. The horse
veered right. Desormeaux did not go with him. Every horse but the
last one passed him by.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trailing horse got me,'' he said. ``Kicked me in the
head.'' He rubbed his temple, as if to pinpoint the spot and said,
``Judge Hammer got me hammered.''
</P>
<P>
   He could afford to joke about it now, but the ambulance driver
who rushed Desormeaux to Centinella Hospital would say that on his
previous trip, he had picked up a man who had also taken a severe
blow to the head, and had a similar lifeless look, the same black
eyes, as him. The internal bleeding inside the skull. Blood oozing
from his ears. The first guy didn't make it.
</P>
<P>
   When the doctors looked at Desormeaux, they weren't placing bets
at the window that he would either.
</P>
<P>
   About 30 hours later, he awakened and asked for his wife. It
wasn't much later that she went into labor and began screaming for
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I begged and pleaded the doctors to let me go watch the birth
of my child,'' he said. ``They strapped me flat and wheeled me back
into the ambulance, over to Methodist Hospital, near Santa Anita.
I'm laying watching it, and every time she would have a
contraction, they would lose my son's heartbeat.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, they rushed Sonia Desormeaux off for an emergency
C-section. Desormeaux, heavily sedated, passed out. When he awoke
this time, he was told he had a son.
</P>
<P>
   The family Desormeaux was still a long way from leaving the
hospital, or the proverbial woods. Sonia Desormeaux developed
toxemia during the delivery.
</P>
<P>
   Baby Joshua weighed barely 4 pounds and was under 24-hour
emergency care. Desormeaux remained confined to his bed.
</P>
<P>
   So there they were, on Dec. 16, medicated under one hospital
roof and clinging to the hope that they would somehow survive this
together.
</P>
<P>
   Nine days later, Christmas Day, Kent and Sonia Desormeaux
dressed their son and took him home.
</P>
<P>
   So it is more than understandable that Desormeaux believes he
was guided along the road to Churchill Downs and Pimlico last
month, if not to the actual winner's circles. It is believable.
``When it is your turn, it is your turn,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   By the early spring of last year, it was his turn to go helmet
in hand to Santa Anita and ask Baffert for mounts. He started
slowly, working out horses. Another rider got hurt. Desormeaux
wound up aboard Real Quiet, Baffert's No. 2 Derby entry. In the
stretch at Churchill Downs, Real Quiet blew by Baffert's No. 1,
Indian Charlie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go get 'em, Meaux money,'' Gary Stevens shouted.
</P>
<P>
   Is this fate? Baffert, with a Triple Crown at stake, was not
about to run Indian Charlie in the Belmont Stakes. Stevens, one of
the world's leading jockeys, switched stables to Prestonwood Farm's
Victory Gallop, second to Real Quiet in the Derby and the
Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   When he envisioned how the Belmont would be run in the countdown
to the race, Desormeaux would see his horse pulling away from
Victory Gallop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll have run the race 150 million times in my head before it
goes off, putting myself in situations that will arise in the
race,'' he said. ``They'll all be in my dream, and all the dreams
end up with me in front.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that is his dream, his plan. He was willing to admit
there could be another.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
