<HEADLINE>
CARDIAC SURGEON WINS AVON MINI MARATHON 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RON DICKER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The absence of world-class runners left more glory
for others to bask in Saturday at the Avon Mini Marathon in Central
Park.
</P>
<P>
   For the winner, Kim Griffin, it was a day to confirm that a
nagging Achilles' injury had finally healed. Griffin, a cardiac
surgeon from Manhattan, seized the lead in the shadow of her
employer, Mount Sinai Hospital, at the 7-kilometer mark and
captured the 10-kilometer race in 35 minutes 26 seconds. Jennifer
Latham of Croton-on-Hudson, N.Y., finished second in 35:33, and Sue
Kelly of Atlanta was third in 36:06.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't thinking I had a chance to win,'' Griffin said. ``I'm
a little bit out of shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffin, who is 36, was the NCAA 10,000-meter champion in 1982,
but she would have been just another club runner in Saturday's race
had elite competitors been invited. Avon recently took over
sponsorship of the annual race from Advil, and organizers geared
this year's event toward encouraging local talent, said Kathrine
Switzer, Avon's program director. Next year, the likes of Kenya's
Tegla Laroupe will return when the race becomes a world
championship for the Avon road-racing circuit.
</P>
<P>
   For Johanna Rhyins, a 12-year-old from Manhattan, Saturday was
another chance to astound her doctors. She was born with a hole in
her heart and had open-heart surgery at age 6. She began running
competitively at 7 and is now a very good age-class runner.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fifth mile I had trouble,'' said Rhyins, who was timed in
43:28. ``My legs tightened up.''
</P>
<P>
   All of the 6,000 competitors benefited from ideal race
conditions: morning temperatures in the low 60s with low humidity.
</P>
<P>
   Karin Stenstrom and three friends, all visiting from Sweden,
chatted about the race afterward on the lawn by Tavern on the
Green, glancing up at the breeze-swept sky as if it were a mirage.
</P>
<P>
   Stenstrom celebrated her sub-1-hour time with an iced tea and a
cigarette. ``I'm the bad one,'' she said sheepishly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
