<SLUG> BC-OBIT-KRAUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANNE KRAUS, 73, ADMINISTRATOR OF HOMES FOR MENTALLY RETARDED
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Anne Kraus, who was inspired by the plight of her
firstborn to devote herself to those with mental retardation and
other developmental disabilities, died on Monday at Long Island
Jewish Medical Center, in Queens County. She was 73 and lived in
Rego Park, Queens.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was leukemia, her family said.
</P>
<P>
   At her death, Mrs. Kraus was the director of general services at
the New York City Association for the Help of Retarded Children.
She had served on the board of directors for a number of years and
as association president from 1967 to 1970.
</P>
<P>
   The association operates about 100 group homes in New York City.
Mrs. Kraus was instrumental in the creation of one of those group
homes, the Melvin M. Kraus Residence in Manhattan, named after her
stricken son. Melvin was born in 1949 and died in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   As director of general services, Mrs. Kraus was involved in
keeping the homes comfortable and attractive. She organized trips
to the agency's summer camps in the Catskills and ran a car pool
that took residents and nurses to doctors' offices.
</P>
<P>
   She looked after the needs of board members and organized annual
dinners and meetings for them and family members, as well as
special parties for donor groups.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Kraus was born Hanneliese Bender in Frankfurt, Germany, and
reached England in the late 1930s on a Kindertransport. While in
England she trained at the Sheffield School of Nursing.
</P>
<P>
   Reaching New York in 1946, she worked as an operating-room nurse
in a Manhattan hospital until her marriage to Walter Kraus in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband died just over a year ago. Mrs. Kraus is survived by
their other son, Lawrence, of Poughkeepsie, N.Y., and two
grandsons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
