</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: GRIEVING SELES FOUND SERENITY ON THE COURT
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ She uses the word ``weird'' to describe her state of
mind, the heightened consciousness, the serenity.
</P>
<P>
   The Magyar Valley Girl is long gone, the giggle long lost or
suppressed. She is now a woman, a woman in mourning, a
European-American woman in black, putting her grief into her
backhand.
</P>
<P>
   Her purposefulness, the last gift from her father, helped Monica
Seles reach the final of the French Open. The crowd knew the
particulars, which meant that Arantxa Sanchez Vicario had to hear
chants of ``Moh-Nee-Kah! Moh-Nee-Kah!'' in steamy Roland Garros
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Even Sanchez Vicario was sympathetic, ``but this is a game,'' as
she graciously informed the crowd later, and Sanchez Vicario had
more legs and mind and strokes on this afternoon, winning by 7-6
(7-5), 0-6, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   There is a song by the vastly underdiscovered American
folk-country singer, Iris Dement, about how she had to go back on
the road after the death of her father because she had a series of
concerts. The song is called, ``No Time to Cry.'' This is where
Monica Seles is now. Her tennis got her through these weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Many athletes who lose a parent will openly dedicate their next
season, their next game, to the absent parent, but Seles declined
to make the French Open a memorial to her father, who died on May
13.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Seles said the other day after demolishing Martina
Hingis in the semifinals. ``I mean, my dad just really wanted me to
do what I wanted to do. Tennis is one of the things that I love to
do. He was the one who started me with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I miss him tremendously, but win or lose, it doesn't make a
difference in my thinking about my dad, or not thinking about
him.''
</P>
<P>
   She wore black on the court Saturday, with a touch of yellow at
the throat, but she insists that was merely what her sporting-goods
sponsor happened to put in her kit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really glad it's not a bright color, because it just feels
more appropriate,'' she said the other day. ``I try to give respect
to Dad. Sometimes I've been wearing black, I know the past two
weeks, but I really don't think consciously _ maybe a little bit
subconsciously, but not fully consciously.''
</P>
<P>
   Seles acted and played like a grown-up in this tournament, a
mature woman in black, leaning into her strokes, distracted by
nothing, until Saturday, when she tried far too many drop shots
against a familiar opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should have noticed that a lot sooner and stopped doing
those plays, because they were free points to Arantxa,'' Seles said
later.
</P>
<P>
   Her focus came from her father, Karolj, who had postponed the
next stage in his life to counsel her after the ghastly stabbing on
court in Germany. When he fell ill, she staggered through her
tournaments, she and her mother calling at odd hours from European
locker rooms or courtside mobile phones, back to Florida, just to
check up on him.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, when he knew his illness was terminal, Karolj Seles
put his life in order. He made a return trip to Europe, to his
familial and professional bases, where long before he had a
daughter with a two-handed killer stroke he had been a notable
artist and cartoonist.
</P>
<P>
   He made a pilgrimage to Italy, to Bordighera, for the annual
reunion of cartoonists, political humorists, the people of thought
and ideology who had been his life. He and his wife went back to
their old apartment in Novi Sad, in what is left of Yugoslavia,
where the Hungarian-speaking Seles family had lived along with
thousands of others of Hungarian ancestry. They went to Kanjizza,
in the north, where Monica's Serbian maternal grandmother still
lives. Karolji had always claimed that when Monica was settled in
tennis, he would retire to this northern post of Serbia, not far
from the Hungarian border, where he would help his in-laws distill
the fiery plum brandy, Slivovice.
</P>
<P>
   He died in Florida just before the clay-court tournament here,
where she had won her first Grand Slam championship in 1990. She
had the freedom to throw herself back into her work, and she
produced glorious throwback victories over Jana Novotna and Martina
Hingis.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, she was asked if she had felt comfortable, back in
her old routine, but she said: ``I really don't know because I
don't remember how I used to feel. So I'm just in the present, what
it is right now.''
</P>
<P>
   All she knew was that life had conspired to give her a Grand
Slam tournament at a time when she needed to work. As the
songwriter put it, she had no time to cry. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-06-98 1746EDT &QL; 
