</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAIL-MAXIYACHTS-645&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST ANOTHER DAY ON DECK FOR TITANS OF INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By BARBARA LLOYD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It happens all the time on big sailboats. A crew member jams a
finger in some piece of deck hardware. It's off to the hospital for
stitches, then back on board for the next race. But this time it
was Rupert Murdoch, and no one assumed anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rupe, Rupe, Rupe,'' the boat crew chanted that night as the
Australian magnate of the news media walked into the team dinner in
Sydney. A local hospital had repaired the sliced index finger, and
Murdoch was back. ``Are you going to go?'' the chorus chimed. ``Are
you going to go?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' Murdoch said, he was. And so for the next three days,
he resumed his crew position on board Sayonara, the 80-foot
maxiyacht owned by his friend Larry Ellison. It was the 1995
Sydney-Hobart Race, a 635-mile Australian competition that Sayonara
ultimately won.
</P>
<P>
   On board for nearly three days of offshore competition were the
two titans of global technology: Murdoch, chairman of News Corp., a
worldwide communications firm; and Ellison, a software giant from
San Francisco who is chief executive officer of Oracle Corp.
Compared with their daily dealings ashore, life at sea offered a
relatively tranquil hiatus.
</P>
<P>
   That was three years ago. But fleet gatherings are an ongoing
affair each year for such owners and friends. On Saturday, a small
but powerful fleet of maxiyachts is expected to gather in Newport,
R.I., for the start of the annual maxi world championship. At least
four of the big $2.5 million yachts will compete in a series of day
races and one short offshore race, culminating the following Friday
in the Newport-Bermuda Race.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are in this for the maintenance of a Corinthian spirit in
yachting,'' Bob Hale, navigator for the yacht Boomerang, said
recently. ``Owners continue to sail their own boats. And although
anyone with a maxi is in a financial position to hire a crew, the
idea is to have the owner steer his own boat in races with
friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the big maxiyachts of the world rope in titans of
industry with their seductive style: fast, expensive boats that
offer leisure time with just enough competitive spirit to keep
corporate moguls in personal overdrive. It's not surprising that
when they meet now and then in a corporate boardroom, the talk
swings first to a savored victory on the water.
</P>
<P>
   George Coumantaros of New York, the owner of Boomerang, is the
epitome of the amateur owner who steers his own boat rather than
hiring a professional racer. Coumantaros, who owns Southern Star
Shipping in New York, would like others who join his elite pastime
to play willingly by the same rules. But the rules have been by
necessity spelled out: An owner must steer his own boat at the
start, and up the first leg of each race, as well as one-third of
the race from then on.
</P>
<P>
   Given who the owners are, it's not hard to fathom how deep their
will to win is. Ellison, who is relatively new to sailing, has
hired Chris Dickson of New Zealand, one of the best yacht racers in
the world, as an alternate helmsman.
</P>
<P>
   Murdoch is a lifelong sailor who competed in his first
Sydney-Hobart race 34 years ago. But he has not yet joined in the
maxi race circuit; he owns a 140-foot cruising sailboat. Murdoch is
not expected to sail with the Ellison team in Newport.
</P>
<P>
   Russell Coutts, another New Zealand sailor with top professional
credentials, often sails as alternate helmsman on Morning Glory, a
maxiyacht owned by Hasso Plattner, a German software entrepreneur.
Another prominent player in the maxi fleet is Alberto Roemmers, a
wealthy Argentinian who owns the maxi Alexia.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Dolan, the chief executive officer of Cablevision Systems
Corp., a New York firm that also owns Madison Square Garden, has
campaigned the maxiyacht Sagamore over the last three years. He
recently donated the maxi to a nonprofit group while awaiting the
completion next year of a new maxiyacht.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The mix of owners and high-profile crew has caused problems in
the past.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, when he started campaigning Sayonara, Ellison caused a
stir at the Kenwood Cup in Hawaii by turning the helm over to
Dickson during a particularly dicey start. The International Class
A Yacht Association of maxi owners refused to acknowledge
Sayonara's standing in that race. And unless Ellison agreed to
change his ways, the group was ready to totally ignore him.
</P>
<P>
   Ellison agreed to change his ways in the next regatta, the Big
Boat Series that autumn in San Francisco. ``Larry drove the whole
time,'' said Bill Erkelens, Sayonara's boat captain. ``He could
have gotten intimidated by being at the starting line in 25 knots
of wind and fairly new to this particular boat, but instead he
agreed to play by the rules.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
