<SLUG> BC-RAC-BELMONT-EXTRA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELMONT FIELD REDUCED TO 11 BY 2 LATE SCRATCHES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO and JAY PRIVMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two horses, Hanuman Highway and Hot Wells, both long shots, were
scratched from the Belmont Stakes for widely differing reasons
Saturday, reducing the field to 11 in the hours before the race.
</P>
<P>
   Hanuman Highway, who drew the No. 1 post position on the rail
and was 30-1 in the early track line, ran second in the Arkansas
Derby and seventh in the Kentucky Derby. He was forced to withdraw
after he came down with a case of colic during the night. His
trainer, Kathy Walsh, said the colt was being treated at Belmont
Park and she hoped it would prove to be only a temporary setback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a call about 3:30 this morning,'' she reported, ``and I
came right down here. Everyone's upset, but it seems like he'll be
all right. He tends to get keyed up, that's probably how he got
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Walsh said that some symptoms appeared two days earlier, but
they disappeared. However, during Friday night, the colt got sick
again, apparently with colic, which involves a blockage of the
intestines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to walk him as long as we could this morning,'' Walsh
said. ``Sometimes they can walk this off. But it just didn't get
better. He is resting comfortably in his stall, and we'll keep a
close eye on him. Colic can be very temporary, or it can be very
serious.''
</P>
<P>
   The other horse, Hot Wells, was scratched because his owner was
not licensed in New York state. The owner, Michael Lasky, was
turned down for an owner's license in 1982 when the state Racing
and Wagering Board ruled that he was the publisher of tip sheets.
Lasky now is the founder and operator of the Psychic Friends
Network.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although Lasky's activities have apparently not been judged to
be illegal,'' the board ruled at the time, ``such activities foster
and present to the public a view of racing that is contrary to its
best interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Hot Wells, winner of the Southwest Stakes, ran fourth in the
Preakness and was quoted as 30-1 in the Belmont. He is trained by
Tom Amoss and drew the No. 9 post position in the starting gate.
</P>
<P>
   Memories of Affirmed
</P>
<P>
   The Triple Crown quest of Real Quiet brought back sweet memories
for Louis and Patrice Wolfson, who owned Affirmed, the winner of
the 1978 Triple Crown and the last of the 11 3-year-olds who have
captured the Kentucky Derby, Preakness Stakes and Belmont Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   The Wolfsons spent much of the week participating in anniversary
celebrations at Belmont Park that honored Triple Crown winners
Affirmed, Secretariat (1973) and Citation (1948). They maintain a
home in Old Westbury, N.Y., and visited several of their current
runners who are based at Belmont Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's been so wonderful about this anniversary has been going
down to the basement and bringing up the old pictures,'' said
Patrice Wolfson. She was walking around the stables with an
oversized bag that had pictures and news clippings from Affirmed's
racing days. ``Affirmed looked so young then. As a 4-year-old,
that's when he got big.''
</P>
<P>
   Affirmed went through a celebrated series of races with
arch-rival Alydar, who is the only horse to have finished second in
all three Triple Crown races. In the Belmont Stakes, Affirmed won
by a head after a prolonged stretch drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a series you can't duplicate,'' Wolfson said. ``Alydar
was probably the most brilliant horse who never was a champion.''
</P>
<P>
   The week of the 1978 Belmont, Wolfson said she and her husband
came to the barn every morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were nervous. That was the one time he had to win.
Everything was on the line,'' she said. ``And we were never
overconfident running against Alydar.''
</P>
<P>
   In the stretch, Alydar briefly put his head in front, ``but I
knew Affirmed would fight back,'' Louis Wolfson said.
</P>
<P>
   Affirmed was bred, raised and raced by the Wolfsons. He was like
a pet to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would nuzzle his head in my arms,'' Patrice Wolfson said.
</P>
<P>
   Added Louis Wolfson: ``You could go in his stall and hug him.''
</P>
<P>
   Affirmed is now 23 and is a stallion at Jonabell Farm near
Lexington, Ky. The Wolfsons can hardly believe 20 years have
elapsed since the Triple Crown, but they are reminded of it when
they visit the stables at Belmont Park. They have a 2-year-old
daughter of Affirmed with the trainer Mark Hennig. And Affirmed's
best runner, the mare Flawlessly, has her first foal, a 2-year-old
filly, in the barn of the trainer Allen Jerkens.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's so wonderful about this business is that you think of
20 years ago, and then you look at this,'' Patrice Wolfson said,
pointing at Flawlessly's daughter _ Affirmed's granddaughter _
``and it's all connected.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Large Belmont Crowd
</P>
<P>
   Spectacular weather and the chance for a Triple Crown sweep
brought a large crowd to Belmont Park Saturday. The fans arrived
early with beach chairs and blankets and enveloped the grandstand
apron from the finish line to the top of the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd was expected to rival the 70,682 who came last year to
see Silver Charm attempt to capture the Triple Crown, but fall
short of the record Belmont crowd of 82,694, set in 1971 when
Canonero II was shooting for the Triple Crown. Both Silver Charm
and Canonero II lost.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
