<SLUG> BC-COMMERCIAL-REAL-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: TECHNOLOGY'S EFFECTS ON DESIGN AND MARKETING  
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOHN HOLUSHA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   At both the glitzy marketing end of the real estate business and
the utterly practical working level, new technology is changing the
way office buildings are designed and the way they are offered to
customers.
</P>
<P>
   The new technology is obvious in an interactive CD-ROM that
markets retail space and signs at 4 Times Square, the new building
under construction by the Durst Organization at 42nd Street and
Broadway. Slip the CD-ROM into a computer and the presentation
opens with a pictorial history of the last 100 years of Times
Square, complete with background music from each era. On another,
promoting 2 Broadway, viewers can move the mouse pointer to a
floor, click, and see what the views out the windows of that floor
will be.
</P>
<P>
   New technology is less obvious, but no less present, in the work
of the people who design the systems that make buildings work _ the
lighting, air-conditioning, elevators and so forth. One way they
are trying to avoid ``sick building syndrome'' is by supplying more
air to the places people work, without consuming more energy.
</P>
<P>
   It was appropriate that the Durst building should go the
high-tech marketing route, since it will be something of a
technological marvel when the first retail tenants start moving in
late this year. Because almost all the office space was leased by
the Conde Nast publishing company and the Skadden, Arps, Slate,
Meagher &AMP; Flom law firm before a spade was put into the ground,
marketing efforts have focused on the multistory retail space at
the base of the building and on the large, illuminated signs that
will sit above the stores as well as at the very top of the
48-story structure.
</P>
<P>
   The Dursts have presented 4 Times Square as a green building,
one that will both conserve energy and improve the environment of
the 8,000 people who are expected to work there. Special glass in
the building's skin admits light but keeps out the heat that can
overtax the cooling system. And the panels between the windows are
photovoltaic cells, which convert sunlight to electricity to meet a
small part of the building's power demand.
</P>
<P>
   After the opening sequence on the CD-ROM marketing the building,
the viewer is presented with a series of screens with buttons on
them. When the computer mouse is used to click on the buttons, the
locations of planned new hotels and retail stores are displayed on
maps that show their relation to 4 Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   Although the building is not yet finished, the use of animation
shows how it will be seen in relation to its neighbors and displays
the sightlines for the signs. The 60- by 60-foot sign that is to
face west on the roof will be easily visible in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The mouse can also be used to travel around the neighborhood at
street level, zooming in and out.
</P>
<P>
   On another CD-ROM, prospective tenants at 2 Broadway, which is
undergoing a major renovation, can check out the views from the
various floors, including those overlooking New York Harbor and the
Statue of Liberty.
</P>
<P>
   The CD-ROMs were created for Williams Real Estate Co., which was
a consultant to the Dursts, as a means of helping to distinguish it
from the brokerage pack, said Michael Cohen, director of brokerage
services for Williams. (He is not to be confused with Michael
Cohen, president of the company.)
</P>
<P>
   ``There is only so much that you can put on paper, and every
broker in this city is inundated with paper,'' he said. ``Mostly
they look at it briefly and then throw it out or pass it on to the
research department.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, most people are conditioned to regard CDs as
valuable items, with the music versions costing $15 or more,
although the actual cost of making copies is modest once the
presentation has been completed, just as it is with printed
material. As a result recipients are more likely to save the
presentation than if it had arrived in printed form, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he sends CD-ROMs to prospective tenants and brokers and
follows up with visits to demonstrate what is on the disk, for
those not computer-literate enough to load and run it on their own.
``It's a way of distinguishing ourselves,'' he said. ``The `wow'
effect gets people's attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said he developed the CD-ROMs with a partner, David
Williams, an architect and animator. The CD-ROMs, he said, are
produced like an advertisement, with video, photography, audio and
animation combined to follow a story board prepared in advance to
guide the production.
</P>
<P>
   He said the disks had practical value, in addition to the
``wow'' effect, particularly in dealing with clients in other
cities. Showing them the outdoor views from the different floors at
2 Broadway, or the placement of the signs on 4 Times Square, gives
decision-makers something to consider before actually visiting a
property. ``They will still visit,'' he said, ``but maybe it's just
one trip rather than multiple trips.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other end of the technology spectrum, engineers are
trying a new approach to keep office workers comfortable while
saving energy. Since many offices have raised floors to accommodate
the wiring for personal computers, copiers and fax machines, the
idea is to use the space for ventilation as well.
</P>
<P>
   In a review of developments at 4 Times Square, Bruce Fowle, a
principal at Fox &AMP; Fowle Architects, which designed the building,
wrote that under-floor air distribution was an innovation his firm
would consider for its next project. The firm is also designing the
Reuters Building at 42nd Street and Seventh Avenue, which has been
designated 3 Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is, without question, the way of the future,'' he
wrote. ``Under-floor air allows you to eliminate duct work, give
individualized air supply, reduce floor-to-floor heights and
increase layout flexibility, thereby reducing energy, material and
waste.''
</P>
<P>
   Most modern buildings have a system of overhead ducts to deliver
cooling air. But because most people work sitting down the air has
to be blown down toward the floor, competing with the heat rising
from computers, desk lamps, copiers and other office machines.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   With an under-floor system, the air is blown through an
adjustable grille in the floor near where people sit. The idea is
to cool people, rather than the entire interior volume of a
building.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you supply air overhead, you have to cool it to 55 to 60
degrees to maintain 72 degrees at a workstation,'' said Marvin
Mass, a partner in the Cosentini Associates engineering consulting
firm. He said that an under-floor system could use air as warm as
65 degrees to maintain 72 degrees at the critical breathing level.
</P>
<P>
   Being able to use warmer air means that less energy needs to be
used to run air-conditioning equipment, and less energy means lower
costs. It also means fresher air. In warm months building operators
tend to recirculate interior air to hold down the cost of cooling
the cleaner _ but warmer _ outside air.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Mass blames 1970's federal energy-conservation
regulations for what has become known as ``sick building
syndrome.'' To hold down energy usage, more modern buildings use
less fresh air than those built earlier. As a result, gases emitted
by carpeting, paint and machines tended to recirculate rather then
be eliminated and replaced by fresh air.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buildings put up in the '50s, '60s and early '70s have plenty
of fresh air,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mass said that air-conditioning and other interior systems were
considered standard for many years, but that lately new approaches
were being considered.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a time of change, and that is a good thing,'' said Alan
Traugott, a principal of Flack &AMP; Kurtz, an engineering company.
``It means we are getting away from catalog engineering,'' he said,
referring to the practice of designing systems using standard
references rather than a creative approach.
</P>
<P>
   Because they work best in an open layout, rather than in a space
with many closed offices, under-floor systems are more suitable for
corporate headquarters than for multitenant projects, said Douglas
Mass, Marvin Mass' son, who is also a partner at Cosentini.
</P>
<P>
   Because they are relatively new in this country, under-floor air
systems can cost slightly more than standard overhead
air-conditioning, Douglas Mass said. But because new ducts do not
need to be designed and fabricated every time offices are moved,
operating costs are typically lower.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Owens-Corning headquarters in Toledo, Ohio, had been
built with an under-floor air system. ``The facilities manager told
me he saved $500,000 in a year on his budget for moving people,''
the younger Mass said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
