<SLUG> BC-GAY-BISHOP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWARK DIOCESE DOES NOT CHOOSE GAY CLERIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TATIANA WITH RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Episcopal Diocese of Newark could have made the
Reverend Canon Gene Robinson of New Hampshire the country's first
openly gay bishop on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But it didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, 50, canon to the bishop of New Hampshire and executive
secretary of the Province of New England, was bypassed by the
almost 500 diocese members who cast their ballots at St. Peter's
Church in Morristown, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   They selected the Rev. John P. Croneberger, 59, rector of the
Church of the Atonement in nearby Tenafly, N.J., to lead the
diocese of 43,000 communicants and 123 churches. Croneberger, one
of six candidates who had vied for the post, will succeed the Right
Reverend John S. Spong, who has announced he will retire on Jan.
31, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson's candidacy had caused an uproar in the Episcopal
Church in America, which has been divided over the issue of
homosexuality. Many conservatives in the 2.5 million-member
denomination, who believe the Scriptures condemn homosexuality,
were watching the vote carefully.
</P>
<P>
   But Dale Gruner, spokeswoman for the Diocese of Newark, said she
believedRobinson's sexual orientation made no difference Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not believe that weighed into the vote in any significant
manner,'' Gruner said. ``He ran third throughout, and the mood of
the diocese was that they wanted someone they knew well, which is
why Croneberger and McKelvey ran as the leaders in this all day.''
</P>
<P>
   The Right Reverend Jack M. McKelvey, Bishop Suffragan of the
Diocese of Newark, was neck-and-neck with Croneberger until the
third ballot, after which he withdrew.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking from his home in Weare, N.H., Saturday afternoon,
Robinson said he was disappointed he was not elected, but said he
was thankful and honored to have been in the running.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was treated with respect and hospitality and warmth
throughout the process. ... There was no unpleasantness, no
prejudice and only courteous and warm behavior,'' said Robinson,
who was married with two daughters before he acknowledged his
homosexuality. ``My sexual orientation played a small and
appropriate role in all of our discussions. They were far more
interested in knowing who might best lead them into the next
century than my orientation.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the fifth time in the past few years that Robinson was
considered for a bishop's post, he said. In the four other cases,
the dioceses stopped short of nominating him for fear of the
controversy it would generate, Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Newark, perhaps because it is no stranger to controversy, was
bold and courageous enough to make the nomination,'' said Robinson.
``Now that they have paved the way, maybe it will not seem like
such an intimidating prospect to other dioceses _ at least, that is
my hope. I hope that my participating in this way made that small
contribution.''
</P>
<P>
   Newark's bishop, Spong, who has served that diocese since 1976
and is the most senior prelate in the Episcopal Church, has
long-supported the ordination of openly gay clergy and the blessing
of same-sex unions.
</P>
<P>
   Reverend Edward Rodman, canon to the bishop of Massachusetts,
said he was disappointed that Robinson was not elected, but he
thought the vote showed that ``there are fair-minded people in this
world'' and that ``an openly gay priest is a viable candidate.'' He
said it is just a matter of time until someone who is openly gay
gets elected as bishop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope it is not as long as it was to get a woman,''
Rodman quipped.
</P>
<P>
   The first woman bishop, Right Reverend Barbara C. Harris of the
Diocese of Massachusetts, was consecrated only nine years ago.
There are currently eight women among the church's 200 bishops.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the people in Newark judged me on my merits,'' said
Robinson. ``I felt honored all the way through that process and I
just feel deep gratitude for the opportunity to talk to people
about my life and my ministry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think any time you can tell the truth about yourself and
sing the Lord's song at the same time, it is a great moment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
