<SLUG> BC-RAC-BELMONT-BAFFERT-587&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAFFERT WAS WEARY AS THE MARATHON CAME TO AN END 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also RAC-BELMONT) 
(mk) 
 By JAY PRIVMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ Bob Baffert hid behind his dark sunglasses. He
tried to rally one more time for a morning of jokes, but his body
language betrayed his emotions.
</P>
<P>
   It was nearly 11 hours before Saturday's Belmont Stakes, in
which Real Quiet, whom Baffert trains, would attempt to become the
12th Triple Crown winner, only to lose by a nose. Baffert had no
real way of knowing the frustration that lay ahead, but as he
leaned against a wall near Barn 9 at Belmont Park, it looked as if
the rigors of the Triple Crown had already taken a bigger toll on
the trainer than the horse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've hit the wall; I'm exhausted,'' Baffert finally admitted.
``I just want to get the saddle on him, get him around the track
and get out of here.''
</P>
<P>
   For nearly two months, Baffert and those closest to Real Quiet _
the owner Mike Pegram, the exercise rider Larry Damore, the groom
Jose Saul Mancilla and Baffert's top assistant trainer, Eoin Harty
_ had been on a whirlwind tour. Real Quiet left his base in
Southern California in mid-April for the Kentucky Derby, which he
captured as an 8-1 long shot. Then it was on to Maryland for the
Preakness Stakes, where Real Quiet crushed his rivals by 2 1/4
lengths. And now they were just hours away from the 130th Belmont
Stakes, trying to put the bear hug on a prize that had eluded
Baffert one year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Baffert's Silver Charm won both the Derby and
Preakness, then finished second in the Belmont. Now, for the first
time, a trainer was back in consecutive years attempting a Triple
Crown sweep.
</P>
<P>
   ``We joked about it last year,'' said Damore, who is the
exercise rider for Real Quiet and Silver Charm. ``When we lost the
1996 Derby by a nose with Cavonnier, we talked about coming back
the next year and winning it. Then we won with Silver Charm. And
then when Silver Charm got beat going for the Triple Crown, we
joked about coming back the next year and winning the Triple Crown.
It's weird that it could happen now.''
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet's date with destiny began early Saturday morning. He
was out of his stall and on the track by 6:30 for a light jog. He
came back to the barn, was bathed by Damore and Mancilla, then was
walked by Mancilla around the barn's shed row. Then Real Quiet was
put back in his stall to await the Belmont Stakes, whose post time
was 5:27 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave him a little bit of grain, just a light breakfast,''
Baffert said.
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet had half a bucket of water to quench his thirst. He
also was allowed to nibble on his hay rack until 10 a.m., when that
was removed. ``He'll know something's up then,'' Baffert said. ``We
just want to keep him relaxed until the race.''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert was trying to remain calm, too, and said he would take
cues from watching George Steinbrenner at Friday night's Yankee
game. While a guest with his family in Steinbrenner's suite,
Baffert noticed that the Boss ``was focused.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was talking and entertaining us,'' Baffert said, ``but he
was watching every move of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert had a similar task, trying to prepare for the race while
marshaling his troops. He left the barn around 10 a.m. and headed
back to his Garden City hotel, where he would meet his wife and
their four children. Baffert also had various family members _
parents, brothers, sisters and in-laws _ to accommodate. He and
Pegram spent part of the morning figuring out where all their
friends and family would sit, and how many passes they would need
to get their entourage into the paddock before the Belmont Stakes.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Baffert planned to return to the track around 1 p.m. and remain
at the barn until Real Quiet was led to the paddock, about 45
minutes before post time. He had dozens of buttons that read ``Keep
It Real Quiet'' that he planned to toss to fans in the paddock and
grandstand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not nervous, but I'm thinking about the race; I've got my
game face on,'' Baffert said.
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``My main concern is being able to leave New York one
for eight.''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert, who is based in Southern California, was without
victory in seven previous starts in New York races.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert has relied on a trusted team throughout the Triple
Crown, particularly Damore and Mancilla, who have been with Real
Quiet every day since he left Southern California. The trip had
been rewarding, but difficult, Damore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been home for nearly two months, and I'll still be
on the road another week,'' Damore said.
</P>
<P>
   He and Baffert are returning to Churchill Downs to prepare
Silver Charm for a race there next weekend. ``I just bought a new
house back home, and I haven't seen my wife, Michelle,'' he said.
``She's a wonderful person to put up with my stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Damore, 39, gets on Real Quiet every morning. He is a former
jockey who retired after a nondescript career in which he won only
70 races while riding from 1978 to 1985. He has worked for Baffert
for nearly eight years, and gallops the trainer's best runners.
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet has ``a beautiful stride,'' Damore said. ``And the
faster he goes, the nicer and smoother he is. It's been fun
watching him develop. I get to work with him every single day. It's
like raising a little kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Damore said Real Quiet has a different personality than Silver
Charm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Silver Charm couldn't care less about anything,'' Damore said.
``Real Quiet looks around a lot. And he can be tough to gallop. A
few days before the Derby, he was pulling so hard he pulled some
muscles in my arm.''
</P>
<P>
   Mancilla also has battle wounds from Real Quiet. The colt has
bitten Mancilla on his right arm, and on his torso, just above his
right kidney.
</P>
<P>
   ``He kicks and bites,'' Mancilla said. ``I watch him more now.
Now, when I scold him, he doesn't play as hard. We're buddies.''
</P>
<P>
   Mancilla, 38, a native of Guatemala, has been in this country
since 1983 and has worked with horses since 1984. He has worked for
Baffert for five of the last six years; he took a year off to
return to Guatemala when his father, a cattle rancher, died four
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Mancilla has dark, curly hair that is hidden under a San
Francisco Giants baseball cap. He speaks little English, and though
he relied on Damore to interpret, Mancilla needed no translation
when playfully poking fun at Baffert.
</P>
<P>
   ``He give me the cheap horses,'' Mancilla said. Real Quiet was
purchased as a yearling for $17,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``He no like this horse.''
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet lost his first six races. After his fifth loss, Real
Quiet's groom at the time asked for another horse, so Baffert
turned Real Quiet over to Mancilla. Since then, Real Quiet has won
four of nine starts. His last two victories, though, put Real Quiet
and his corner men on the threshold of greatness. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-06-98 1857EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
