<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-06 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7531 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GINGRICH-COX     06-06 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GINGRICH-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Gingrich not following own advice, some say
</P>
<P>
   By Mark Sherman
</P>
<P>
   C. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Speaker Newt Gingrich's public appearance last week
with President Clinton could have come straight from Gingrich's new
book, ``Lessons Learned the Hard Way.''
</P>
<P>
   In his ``personal report'' about mistakes he had made in his
first three years as speaker, Gingrich acknowledged he sometimes
underestimated Clinton's ability to bounce back from trouble. He
titled the chapter, ``Pick Your Fights Wisely.''
</P>
<P>
   So rather than pick a public fight on Social Security, in which
Democrats traditionally have had the upper hand, speaker and
president shared a stage to proclaim jointly their desire to make
the retirement system financially strong for the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   But this example of Gingrich taking a chapter from his own book
is unusual and sharply contrasts with much of his behavior since
``Lessons Learned the Hard Way'' was published.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich lately has been much more confrontational than the
smiling, warmer and fuzzier speaker who graced the cover of his
book in jeans and leather jacket. In the space of two months,
Gingrich has attacked Clinton over allegations of illegal foreign
money in Democratic campaigns, slapped ``liberal'' and ``big
government'' tags on a tobacco bill that U.S. tobacco companies
hate, criticized Clinton administration foreign policy while in the
Middle East, initiated discussions about raising the pay of members
of Congress and backed off his support for a farm bill to provide
crop insurance to farmers because it also restored nutrition
benefits to legal immigrants who lost them in the 1996 welfare
reform legislation. The bill eventually passed after complaints
from farm state Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Dallek, a historian who has written a review of the book,
said the speaker appears to have abandoned ``a posture of
moderation'' that included learning the value of ``no comment'' and
counseling compromise instead of confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   In part, Dallek said, the onset of the 1998 campaign season
demands a more partisan and aggressive approach, particularly the
criticism of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like a yachtsman, he'll tack in one direction and then
another,'' said Dallek, who recently completed work on ``Flawed
Giant,'' his second book on President Johnson. ``He may have
written the book, but he needs to reclaim his hard edge and the
conservative ground.''
</P>
<P>
   A Republican critic, Arianna Huffington, was more pointed,
saying that Gingrich sharpened his tone in response to polls that
showed a depressed Republican base. ``There's a lack of
credibility,'' Huffington said. ``The book was one kind of attempt
to change his image and the change in tone was another kind of
attempt.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Ruskin, director of the watchdog group Congressional
Accountability Project, said Gingrich's closed-door discussion with
House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt about a congressional pay raise
feeds Americans' cynicism about politics. Gingrich aides stress no
decision has been made to increase members' pay, now $136,700 a
year.
</P>
<P>
   In a chapter titled ``Know the Difference Between Right and
Wrong,'' Gingrich wrote, ``The trustworthiness of our political
leaders goes through the heart of our political culture to the very
question of how much allegiance to their country can be demanded of
ordinary citizens. Cynicism is corrosive of everything that
Congress was meant to stand for and hence of our very democratic
system.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich's supporters dismiss the criticism as misplaced.
Christina Martin, the speaker's press secretary, said Gingrich
refrained from personal attacks on Clinton, even though he likened
the administration to ``The Jerry Springer Show.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He did not get involved in innuendo,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   In Israel, the speaker simply restated U.S. law that the capital
of the country is Jerusalem and that the U.S. embassy should be
there.
</P>
<P>
   Editorials that suggested Gingrich follow his own advice,
contained in the chapter ``Learn to Keep You-- Mouth Shut,'' were
off the mark, Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The speaker is on his game, in charge and winning,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Blankley, Martin's predecessor and a contributor to George
magazine, said Gingrich's desire to curb his rhetorical excesses
does not mean he plans to remain silent on policy issues. His
maturation as speaker should not suggest he will cave in at every
turn, Blankley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an easy contrast here, with the cover jacket, but it
misreads both the book and Newt's political needs,'' Blankley said.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of last year's reprimand by the House for violating
ethics rules and a failed effort to depose him as speaker, Gingrich
purposely lowered his profile and sought about rehabilitating his
image, Blankley said.
</P>
<P>
   The effort largely worked and culminated in the book tour, if
his revived poll numbers mean anything. At the same time, ``Newt
saw what was needed, and he did it,'' Blankley said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
