<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-06 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7532 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EVANDER-MAIN07-COX     06-06 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVANDER-MAIN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia Dome may be next site for fight
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After one of the world's most famous arenas was
forced to fold a boxing card because two boxers tested positive for
hepatitis B, one was pregnant, one had a broken hand and one was
being served court papers, Evander Holyfield's camp was looking to
stage a fight in more tranquil and, hopefully, sterile
surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Thomas, Holyfield's attorney, huddled with promoter Don King
and Showtime executive Jay Larkin for nearly three hours Friday to
try to clean up the mess after the cancellation of Holyfield's WBA
and IBF heavyweight title defense against Henry Akinwande at
Madison Square Garden. Akinwande tested positive for hepatitis B
and, though the results of a retest won't be learned until Monday,
Larkin said, ``it's 99.9 percent likely to come back dirty.''
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to project the incubation period for hepatitis
B, and Holyfield, who hasn't fought since beating Michael Moorer in
November, doesn't want to wait long for another bout. All parties
would prefer a unification bout against WBC champion Lennox Lewis.
But Lewis is likely to fight in September against Zeljko Mavrovic,
meaning Holyfield-Lewis could not take place before December and,
more likely, the spring.
</P>
<P>
   With Holyfield in need of an interim fight, and Akinwande's
status unknown, the current most probable scenario has the Atlanta
champion fighting in his hometown against IBF No. 1 contender
Vaughn Bean in August at the Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield desires to fight one last time in Atlanta before
retirement, have affordable tickets and possibly give some away to
youth groups. Thomas will open discussions soon with city and
sports officials and said the amount of financial support the fight
receives from businesses _ ticket guarantees, sponsorships, hotel
rooms, etc. _ will determine whether it comes off.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield, who was to earn $10 million for the Akinwande fight
and has made $62 million in his past three bouts, likely would have
to lower his financial demands in Atlanta, where the site fee would
not be as big as a casino town.
</P>
<P>
   But Thomas said, ``I don't sense he would (accept a reduced
purse) in Las Vegas or Atlantic City or here (New York) but I sense
he would be willing to do it to support his community, if the
people want it. If the people don't want it, why do it?''
</P>
<P>
   Other than fighting the IBF mandatory against Bean, these are
Holyfield's options, assuming Akinwande's second test comes back
positive:
</P>
<P>
   _ Attempt to revive talks for a fall Lewis fight with cable
operators. But Lewis is under contract with HBO for one more bout
and therefore has exclusive rights to it. HBO, not enthused about
the Mavrovic bout, may raise its purse offers to Holyfield and
Lewis. But it's more likely Holyfield and Lewis will wait until the
HBO deal expires to set up a bidding war with Showtime. Holyfield
wants $20 million, Lewis $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   _ The WBA could try to force a mandatory against its highest
ranked available contender, unknown fourth-ranked Jade Scott.
(Akinwande is No. 1; Ray Mercer, who also tested positive for
hepatitis B, is No. 2; Mavrovic is No. 3.). But Thomas said, ``If
Akinwande can't fight, our position is we made every effort to
satisfy our obligations to the WBA. We're moving on.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Holyfield could ignore mandates by the WBA and IBF at the risk
of being stripped to fight Lewis. But he has never ducked a
mandatory and wants to retire with all three belts.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of a Bean fight at the Georgia Dome has the support of
King and Larkin, whose Garden card was being lampooned for weeks.
Officials claim 8,000 tickets were distributed. But it was learned
only 4,000 actually were sold for a total gate of $500,000, as of
early Friday _ well short of the $3 million MSG guaranteed to King.
</P>
<P>
   By cancelling the card, the Garden lost only $100,000. But King
had spent about $2 million in promotional costs and wasn't insured.
All parties vehemently deny suspicions that Akinwande's blood test
was doctored because of the sluggish sales.
</P>
<P>
   But this card seemed doomed. Not only did Mercer test positive,
his scheduled opponent, Atlanta's Marcellus Brown, suffered a
broken hand and was scratched. Maria Nieves-Garcia, the scheduled
opponent for Christy Martin, tested as being 21 weeks pregnant,
much to her amazement. Roberto Duran, also on the card, was sued
during the week for child support but planned to fight despite
possibly having his purse garnished by a Florida court. Holyfield,
who last fought in Atlanta in 1991 against Bert Cooper at the Omni,
hopes there is support for a fight. As he recently said, ``You may
not get to see the last fight in my career. But you'd be able to
see this fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
