A7534 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAMSEY-COX     06-06 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAMSEY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ramsey case nears critical juncture
 &HT;    By Craig Schneider
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ While Colorado police are eager to have a grand jury
address the JonBenet Ramsey case, hoping it will force testimony
from those resistant to talk, at least one legal expert believes
the move probably will solve nothing and could end the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see (a grand jury) getting much from any suspect,''
said William Pizzi, a former federal prosecutor and a criminal law
professor at the University of Colorado Law School.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, should the process add nothing to the case, Pizzi
believes the grand jury may decide no charges are warranted. ``This
may be the last chapter,'' Pizzi said.
</P>
<P>
   Pizzi acknowledged that a grand jury proceeding can intensify
the probe. ``People have to testify under oath. It locks people
into their original stories,'' he said. ``There's a little more
pressure, a little more formality.''
</P>
<P>
   But just as people can refuse to talk to police, they can
decline to answer a prosecutor's questions before a grand jury if
they would be incriminating themselves, he said.
</P>
<P>
   As police and prosecutors huddled last week to discuss a
possible grand jury action, Boulder, Colo., Detective Division
Comdr. Mark Beckner said he has ``an idea'' who killed the girl but
lacked the evidence to charge someone.
</P>
<P>
   Boulder District Attorney Alex Hunter said he's leaning toward a
grand jury but may take a month to make up his mind.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Ramsey family _ John and Patsy and son Burke, who
have settled down in Vinings, northwest of Atlanta _ must adjust to
life once again in the limelight.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're coping as best they can,'' said Peggy Ramsey, John
Ramsey's sister-in-law, who lives in metro Atlanta. ``For them it
has been a compounded tragedy. They've lost their daughter, but
they've also had to deal with all this garbage in the media.''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``What's on their mind is that whoever did this is
still out there walking the streets _ and it was no one in this
family.''
</P>
<P>
   Diane Barnett Lough, who grew up with Patsy Ramsey in
Parkersburg, W.Va., said ``Life had been getting more normal for
them. They really wanted things to die down.''
</P>
<P>
   Lough, like Patsy Ramsey, a former Miss West Virginia, said
Patsy has been a stay-at-home mom pursuing the same kinds of
charities and volunteer work that engaged her before JonBenet's
death. She has also been spending much time with her son Burke,
volunteering at his school, the Lovett School in Atlanta. Lough
expects the heightened public interest in the case will upset the
family, though, ``They're pretty realistic. I don't think it's a
big surprise to them.'' JonBenet, 6, was found strangled and beaten
in her Boulder home, hours after her mother found a ransom note the
day after Christmas 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities say they'd like to question, among others,
JonBenet's parents, who stopped talking to police 13 months ago, as
well as her 11-year-old brother, Burke, whose lawyer cut ties with
police in February. As the number of suspects has narrowed, the
Ramsey parents remain under an ``umbrella of suspicion,'' police
said. But the parents insist they are innocent.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
