<HEADER>
A7542 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-     06-06 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROSEY REMEMBERS RFK'S FINAL DAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Rosey Grier heard gun shots ring out and horrified shrieks,
and he knew instinctively that the joyful evening had turned tragic
and that someone had shot Sen. Robert Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   He had been in another part of the Ambassador Hotel, but he
immediately charged through the milling crowd toward the kitchen
where he saw Kennedy lying in pool of blood on the floor and saw an
enraged mob angrily attacking the assassin.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were trying to kill him,'' says Grier, recalling the
reaction several spectators had in the immediate aftermath of the
eight shots that came out of a .22 caliber pistol held by a
24-year-old Jordanian immigrant named Sirhan Bishara Sirhan that
would take the life of Kennedy and would wound four bystanders.
``All I remember thinking was, `I've got to save this man. If I
allow him to die, then we're no better than he is.'''
</P>
<P>
   Rosey Grier still was a professional football player at the
time, a 6-foot-5, 300-pound defensive tackle for the Los Angeles
Rams.
</P>
<P>
   But he says he never faced greater resistance in his 14 seasons
on the gridiron than he did the next few tense minutes on that
early June 6, 1968, morning in Los Angeles when he and Rafer
Johnson and a couple of Kennedy aides fought to keep Sirhan from
being fatally mauled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just an unbelievable scene,'' says Grier. ``People were
grappling with Sirhan, and just pounding him. I grabbed him by his
legs with one arm, and threw punches at people to keep them away
with the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got really ugly. People kept shouting, `Let's kill him!
Let's kill him!' I finally was able to wrap my arms around Sirhan
himself, and then just kept fighting people off until the police
came.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember losing my voice that night because I kept screaming
for help. I also remember crying a lot that night. The crying still
hasn't stopped in me.''
</P>
<P>
   It was 30 years ago that the lives of Rosey Grier and Robert
Kennedy would intersect at such a tragically historic juncture.
</P>
<P>
   Grier had no idea when he agreed to give his support to Kennedy
for the Democratic presidential nomination that it would result in
his being present at one of this country's most notorious political
assassinations.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the final things Bobby Kennedy ever said was, `Rosey
Grier said he'd take care of anybody who didn't vote for me,'''
says Grier, referring to the speech Kennedy gave to campaign
workers at the Embassy Room in the Ambassador after scoring a
stirring California primary victory over Sen. Eugene McCarthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then a few minutes later he would be gone. That was a
horrible night for all of America and for the world. What we lost
that night was an idea. What we lost was a man who could have taken
us all to another level. What we lost was a man who could have been
a unifying symbol at a time when our nation was being torn apart by
the Vietnam War and racial tension. It was a huge loss for our
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosey Grier would go on after his NFL career had ended to do his
TV variety shows and acting and needle-pointing and singing and
preaching, but it would be a long time before he was over the deep
sorrow he felt about the death of Robert Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me about 12 years to work through it,'' says Grier.
``I felt for a long time that I had let the Kennedy family down,
that I had been there to protect Bobby Kennedy and simply hadn't
done so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, it was my job that night to watch out for Bobby,
along with his personal security guard, Bill Barry. The original
plan for Bobby that night was to go out the front way, and we all
were going to go to a nightclub in Beverly Hills called The Factory
to celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was standing off to the side when they rushed Bobby off the
stage, and into the kitchen. I heard later a maitre'd had
recommended they exit that way because it was faster. Before I knew
what happened, I heard the gun shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosey Grier had met Robert Kennedy a year earlier when he had
been invited to a Washington D.C. fund-raiser by Ethel Kennedy, the
senator's wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that Bobby Kennedy had stood up for Martin Luther King
when it wasn't popular to do so and I knew the Kennedys had done a
lot to help in the inner cities,'' says Grier. ``I hated flying,
but I flew back to D.C. and hit it off with Bobby immediately. We'd
laugh together and he was always punching me in a lighthearted
manner. We just connected immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   Grier has remained close to the Kennedy family over the years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime they've wanted anything, I'm there for them,'' he
says. ``I'll always make myself available to them. I always think
how things could have been so different in this country had Bobby
Kennedy lived. I think he would have been successful in leading us
through the change we desperately needed at the time, change we
still need. We all have to get together to make positive changes in
this country. This is no time to sit on the sidelines.''
</P>
<P>
   Grier, 65, these days works for Michael Milken's prostate
foundation when he isn't performing his non-denominational
ministerial duties at weddings, funerals and other occasions.
</P>
<P>
   His last public exposure came during O.J. Simpson's murder trial
when he was seen visiting Simpson at the L.A. County Jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just basically wanted to help O.J. find an answer to his
life,'' says Grier, who saw Simpson throughout his one-year
incarceration. ``Robert Shapiro kept reminding me, `Remember why
you came, Rosie.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt O.J.'s life was on the line, and he needed help. He was
dealing with a problem he couldn't solve, but I felt maybe God
could solve it for him. I read him passages from the Bible, and
shared with him the thoughts I had. We never talked about what
happened to his wife or to the other person he was accused of
murdering.''
</P>
<P>
   Still an imposing 300 pounds, Rosey Grier and his wife, Margie,
reside in Brentwood. They have two children, Rosey Jr., 26, and
Sheryl, 43.
</P>
<P>
   Rosey Grier is such a God-fearing man that he doesn't even seem
to hold any bitter feelings toward Sirhan, who has been attempting
to get out of prison in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you think Sirhan should be paroled?'' Grier is asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Sirhan should be treated like any other person in the
prison system,'' he says. ``I don't think his rights should be
politicized. It's up to the court system to decide what happens to
Sirhan. It's up to them to deal with those kinds of things. That's
why we have a court system.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Rosey Grier hasn't forgotten the man he revered who was
killed by Sirhan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seldom a day passes without me thinking of Bobby Kennedy,''
says Grier. ``I'm convinced a lot of things in this country would
be different today had he lived. Things would have been better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
