<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUP-ADVANCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Defending champion and star Ronaldo land in France with high
hopes
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The biggest World Cup of all starts Wednesday. Expanded to 32
teams, the 1998 Cup in France will be cashing in on nearly $500
million in rights fees and watched by more than a billion people
worldwide through the July 12 final.
</P>
<P>
   But biggest might not necessarily mean best.
</P>
<P>
   Since Air France pilots went on strike this week, teams, fans
and journalists descending on France have been greeted by a
logistics disaster. Threatened strikes by other transportation
workers loom, as the planet's largest sporting event returns to
France for the first time in 60 years.
</P>
<P>
   A severe ticket crunch has simmered for months in Europe, where
the French organizing committee's policy of earmarking 65 percent
of tickets for its own citizens has been criticized. In its first
major World Cup plunge, Nike will plaster its swoosh on the jerseys
of Brazil, Nigeria, Italy, the Netherlands and the United States.
And Disney's trio of ABC, ESPN and ESPN2 will devote 230 hours of
television coverage _ more than double the output four years ago _
to a nation supposedly uninterested in soccer.
</P>
<P>
   Feeling the heaviest burden are the players and coaches of the
32 teams, eight more than in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Soccer-obsessed Brazil, is rightly worried about a rash of bad
outings, including an unforgiveable loss to the U.S. in February.
</P>
<P>
   The four-time champions are favorites to repeat for the first
time since Pele made his mark for Brazil in 1958 and 1962. But head
coach Mario Zagallo acknowledged that his team has been playing
defensively as a result of extremely high expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would rather win playing ugly soccer than lose playing
attractive soccer,'' said Zagallo, a party to all four previous
crowns, as a player and coach. ``Everyone wants to win and I'm no
different.''
</P>
<P>
   Brazil has the man tapped to be the game's next great star.
Ronaldo, a 21-year-old striker who rode the bench in 1994, has
scored more than 60 goals in the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria features a number of stars from its 1996 Olympic
gold-medal squad, but the ``Super Eagles'' must survive a rugged
Group D with Spain, Paraguay and Bulgaria. For the first time in 20
years, Argentina will not have Diego Maradona, whose last World Cup
moment was leaving Dallas in 1994 after failing a drug test. Europe
offers the usual suspects _ Germany, England, Italy, France, Spain
and the Netherlands _ among the favorites. The U.S. has improved
since 1994 but might not get out of group play, now that advancing
teams must finish first or second. The Americans kick off with
formidable Germany on June 15 and later play powerful Yugoslavia
and unheralded, but extremely motivated Iran.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. has gone scoreless in two of its last four friendlies
and has been battling injuries to key players. ``In 1994, we played
not to lose. Now, we intend to win,'' U.S. coach Steve Sampson
said. ``Our goal is to get to the second round.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
