<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-06 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7550 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CUP-BRADLEY-COX     06-06 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUP-BRADLEY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Like clockwork, time has come for Dutchmen
 &HT;    By Mark Bradley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Brazil has the best players. Germany is the most disciplined. No
team will play harder than England. Italy is a nice blend of
seasoning and skill.
</P>
<P>
   As host nation, France has a disproportionate edge. Argentina
seems positioned to slipstream behind the big Brazilian hype. The
time may be right for an African team to win, and Nigeria is the
class of the continent. A slew of insiders are on record as liking
Yugoslavia's chances.
</P>
<P>
   There are reasons why any of the above could win the World Cup.
Here are reasons they won't:
</P>
<P>
   Brazil will be missing Romario, who was cut from the '98 team
because of a calf injury and whose absence will leave the great
Ronaldo alone up front. Germany is so strapped for a sweeper, the
key defender in its precise system, that it has pressed the
37-year-old Lothar Matthaeus into service. England goes to France
with two off-form strikers and could be consumed by the furor over
Paul Gascoigne's omission from the squad. Italy goes without Angelo
Peruzzi, its first-choice goalkeeper.
</P>
<P>
   France is sublime in midfield but lacks a target man. Argentina
will chafe under the handling of Daniel Passarella, its rigid
coach. Nigeria seems a better bet to lose in the semis than to take
the FIFA Trophy. Yugoslavia will go only as far as striker Predrag
Mijatovic can carry it.
</P>
<P>
   So who's that leave?
</P>
<P>
   Holland.
</P>
<P>
   The Netherlands once seemed the next dominant footballing
country. Dubbed The Clockwork Orange, the Dutch had splendid
players and a progressive system. They were unlucky to lose the
World Cup finals to host nations in both 1974 and '78. But after
that, nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Holland's team came to mirror its free-thinking society. The
famed Ruud Gullit grew so weary with the internal bickering that he
finally refused to play for his country. Edgar Davids, a combative
midfielder, was sent home from the '96 European championships after
a disgreement with the coach. Dutchmen would play vital roles on
the best club teams _ Amsterdam's Ajax, Italy's AC Milan, England's
Arsenal _ but somehow the national side became much less than the
sum of its high-priced parts.
</P>
<P>
   This is the summer Holland puts things right. The Dutch are made
up of accomplished footballers in the full flower of their career.
Striker Dennis Bergkamp and winger Marc Overmars led Arsenal to a
rousing English double _ the Premier League title and the FA Cup.
Clarence Seedorf was the midfield engine in Real Madrid's upset of
Juventus in the Champions League final.
</P>
<P>
   Davids, back in the Dutch fold, has been terrific for Juventus.
Manchester United just paid $17 million to buy Jaap Stam, a
world-record fee for a defender, from PSV Eindhoven. Edwin Van der
Sar is ready to claim the mantle of world's best keeper from
Denmark's Peter Schmeichel.
</P>
<P>
   There's a chance Bergkamp will miss the opener against Belgium
with a nagging hamstring pull, but that shouldn't derail the Dutch.
They're in the softest of the eight groups and could advance to
Round 2 working at half-capacity. By then, Bergkamp should be fine.
As Mexico '86 was Maradona's World Cup and USA '94 was Romario's,
France '98 will belong to Bergkamp.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
