<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-06 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7551 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CUP-CAPSULES-COX     06-06 1284
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUP-CAPSULES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WORLD CUP CAPSULES
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GROUP A:
</P>
<P>
   Brazil
</P>
<P>
   Morocco
</P>
<P>
   Norway
</P>
<P>
   Scotland
</P>
<P>
   _ Top players: Ronaldo, Rivaldo and Roberto Carlos of Brazil;
Noureddine Naybet of Morocco; Tore Andre Flo and Ole Gunnar
Solskjaer of Norway; Kevin Gallacher and Colin Hendry of Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   _ Outlook: Despite losing Romario to injury, defending champion
Brazil has more than enough talent to dominate this group. Ronaldo,
21, the world player of the year the last two years, will make his
World Cup debut. Carlos is a free-kick expert with his left foot,
but Brazil has holes in its midfield and defense. Scotland promises
a tough battle in the opener, but only Gallacher is a proven
scorer. The Scots have a chance to get out of group play, something
they've never done. Norway isn't fancy but beat Brazil last year
and has been making strides with players based in England. Morocco
is a nonfactor.
</P>
<P>
   _ Prediction: Brazil and Norway to advance.
</P>
<P>
   GROUP B
</P>
<P>
   Austria
</P>
<P>
   Cameroon
</P>
<P>
   Chile
</P>
<P>
   Italy
</P>
<P>
   _ Top players: Alessandro Del Piero, Demetrio Albertini and
Paolo Maldini of Italy; Marcelo Salas of Chile; Anton Polster of
Austria; Ribobert Song of Cameroon.
</P>
<P>
   _ Outlook: The Italians stumbled through qualifying and lost to
Sweden last week. Del Piero, a dazzling scorer for Juventus, has
been nursing a sore hamstring but is expected back, along with 1994
star Roberto Baggio, whose missed penalty kick in the Rose Bowl
helped cost Italy the title. Veteran keeper Gianluca Pagliuca is
back in the nets with an injury to Angelo Peruzzi. Chile could
challenge if strikers Salas and Ivan Zamorano get hot. Austria is
aging and injured but won't be easy. For Cameroon, forward
Marc-Vivien Foe is injured, and a coaching change has rattled
preparations.
</P>
<P>
   _ Prediction: Italy and Chile to advance.
</P>
<P>
   GROUP C
</P>
<P>
   Denmark
</P>
<P>
   France
</P>
<P>
   Saudi Arabia
</P>
<P>
   South Africa
</P>
<P>
   _ Top players: Zinedine Zidane, Didier Deschamps and Youri
Djorkaeff of France; Peter Schmeichel and Michael and Brian Laudrup
of Denmark; Saeed al-Owairan of Saudi Arabia; Benni McCarthy of
South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   _ Outlook: The hosts have never won the World Cup and have never
had a better chance. Zidane and Djorkaeff are perhaps the most
talented pair of creators in the tournament, but they're working
with untested forwards. Denmark has a veteran roster. Shmeichel,
36, is still going strong with England's Manchester United. Saudi
Arabia can score and is coached by Carlos Alberto Parreira, who led
Brazil to the top in 1994. South Africa's first World Cup probably
will be short-lived, although McCarthy is exciting.
</P>
<P>
   _ Prediction: France and Denmark to advance.
</P>
<P>
   GROUP D
</P>
<P>
   Bulgaria
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria
</P>
<P>
   Paraguay
</P>
<P>
   Spain
</P>
<P>
   _ Top players: Raul, Fernando Hierro and Luis Enrique of Spain;
Hristo Stoichkov and Emil Kostadinov of Bulgaria; Jose Luis
Chilavert of Paraguay; Victor Ikpeba, Sunday Oliseh and Nwankwo
Kanu of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   _ Outlook: D is for death, as in Group of Death. This draw will
be brutal. Spain's enormous talent has never materialized at the
World Cup, but hard-driving coach Javier Clemente can change that.
Raul is just 20 but already a star for European champ Real Madrid,
as is defender Hierro. Nigeria may have the most talent of anyone
except Brazil, but harnessing it has been a chore. Former U.S.
coach Bora Milutinovic has been on board since February with no
noticeable improvement. Bulgaria was a surprise semifinalist in
1994 and could be tough, but its core players are well into their
30s and don't have much speed. Keeper Chilavert is a dynamic
presence, but Paraguay might not be able to bridge the talent gap
in this group.
</P>
<P>
   _ Prediction: Spain and Nigeria to advance.
</P>
<P>
   GROUP E
</P>
<P>
   Belgium
</P>
<P>
   Mexico
</P>
<P>
   Netherlands
</P>
<P>
   South Korea
</P>
<P>
   _ Top players: Dennis Bergkamp, Clarence Seedorf and Edwin van
der Sar of The Netherlands; Marc Wilmots and Luc Nilis of Belgium;
Luis Hernandez and Claudio Suarez of Mexico; Choi Yong-soo of South
Korea.
</P>
<P>
   _ Outlook: Mexico has fallen dangerously in the last year and
might not survive the round robin. Coach Manuel Lapuente, who came
on after qualifying, mysteriously dropped prolific scorer Carlos
Hermosillo.suffered some disastrous results. The Dutch may have
their best outfit since Johan Cruyff led them to the finals in 1974
and 1978, but infighting has been legion ever since. Bergkamp is
coming off a terrific season for English double champions Arsenal.
Belgium is respectable, and given Mexico's present state, may edge
through. South Korea has been the best Asian team for several years
but never has advanced.
</P>
<P>
   _ Prediction: The Netherlands and Belgium to advance.
</P>
<P>
   GROUP F
</P>
<P>
   Germany
</P>
<P>
   Iran
</P>
<P>
   United States
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia
</P>
<P>
   _ Top players: Oliver Bierhoff and Andreas Moller of Germany;
Predrag Mijatovic and Dejan Savicevic of Yugoslavia; Kasey Keller
and Claudio Reyna of the U.S.; Khodadad Azizi of Iran.
</P>
<P>
   _ Outlook: The Germans are aging, injured and usually start
slowly. But they come up big in the World Cup and will be seeking
redemption for a disappointing quarterfinal finish in 1994.
Bierhoff had a superb season in Italy and Moller is a crafty
playmaker. The U.S. is sending its best team ever, but a lack of
goals is a concern. Striker Eric Wynalda's recovery from a knee
injury is slowly progressing. The U.S. has an outside chance to
advance but must get points in all three matches. Yugoslavia
returns following UN sanctions in 1994 with Mijatovic, who scored
the winning goal for Real Madrid in the European Cup final. Iran
has three veterans of the German leagues.
</P>
<P>
   _ Prediction: Germany and Yugoslavia to advance.
</P>
<P>
   GROUP G
</P>
<P>
   Colombia
</P>
<P>
   England
</P>
<P>
   Romania
</P>
<P>
   Tunisia
</P>
<P>
   _ Top players: Carlos Valderrama and Faustino Asprilla of
Colombia; Alan Shearer, Paul Ince and David Seaman of England;
Gheorge Hagi and Gheorge Popescu of Romania; Adel Sellimi of
Tunisia.
</P>
<P>
   _ Outlook: England's confident stride after qualifying has
turned into full-fledged anxiety, especially with the dismissal of
1990 veteran Paul Gascoigne. Shearer has been injured most of the
year, and it could fall upon 18-year-old Michael Owen to give him a
boost up front. Colombia has changed little from the disastrous
1994 squad that suffered a first-round exit and the tragic murder
of defender Andres Escobar, who scored an own goal in a loss to the
U.S. Carlos Valderrama is still dangerous as a creator. Romania
lacks speed, stamina and consistency. Tunisia will be fortunate to
get even a tie.
</P>
<P>
   _ Prediction: England and Romania to advance.
</P>
<P>
   GROUP H
</P>
<P>
   Argentina
</P>
<P>
   Croatia
</P>
<P>
   Jamaica
</P>
<P>
   Japan
</P>
<P>
   _ Top players: Gabriel Batistuta, Ariel Ortega and Hernan Crespo
of Argentina; Davor Suker and Robert Prosinecki of Croatia; Deon
Burton and Frank Sinclair of Jamaica; Hidetoshi Nakata of Japan.
</P>
<P>
   _ Outlook: Argentina's first World Cup appearance in 20 years
without Diego Maradona may be a golden one. Despite the despotic
tactics of coach Daniel Passarella, Argentina is coming on strong
and recently beat Brazil in Rio. Leading goal-scorer Batistuta has
taken a back seat to the tandem of Crespo and Claudio Lopez.
Croatia's first World Cup also could be special, especially if
Suker is productive. A knee injury to Alen Boksic, his partner at
forward, is a major loss. Jamaica and Japan will soak up the flavor
of the World Cup for the first time but aren't expected to
accomplish much.
</P>
<P>
   _ Prediction: Argentina and Croatia to advance.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
