<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-06 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7553 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CUP-REGIS-COX     06-06 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUP-REGIS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A new world for citizen Regis
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ David Regis describes the accelerated process to
become an American citizen as something ``that fell out of the
sky.'' His in-laws, Johnny and Danetta Fogle of Decatur, Ga.,
regard it as a godsend.
</P>
<P>
   Especially when it means being able to see more of their
precious granddaughter, Ella Camille, born 15 months ago to David
and his wife, Nikki.
</P>
<P>
   And for the United States World Cup team, Regis already has
proved to be well worth the painstaking effort to put him in the
red, white and blue uniform of Uncle Sam _ and Nike. The native of
Martinique, who moved to France at age 12, has played every minute
of the last two
</P>
<P>
   warmup matches for the Americans, who open against Germany next
Monday in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Regis (pronounced ray-jee), sworn in as a citizen on May 20, is
certain to start as a defender, using his deft left foot, solid
marking skills and strong ability to head balls on set pieces. That
he will be playing in, but not for, the country he once called home
is why his six-month odyssey began in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   And why the Fogles will watch the World Cup for the first time
in their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know the first thing about soccer until David came
along,'' said Danetta Fogle, proudly holding the official game ball
given to Regis and signed by his teammates after he made his U.S.
national team debut on May 24. ``Once he explained the rules to me,
it's been so much easier to understand.''
</P>
<P>
   David and Nikki Regis were neighbors who met over a baguette and
coffee in 1994 in Strasbourg, France, where she had chosen to study
abroad to complete requirements for a degree in French. He was
playing for Racing Club de Strasbourg, trying to make it up the
French first-division ladder and hoping to get noticed by the
national team coaching hierarchy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a dream to be able to play for your country, but
that never happened with France,'' said Regis, who speaks only a
few words of English while Nikki translates for him. ``Unless you
play for a big team, it's hard to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, he had options, thanks to his marriage to Nikki in 1995
in Atlanta, where Danetta Fogle is the director of Christian
education.
</P>
<P>
   Getting Regis through the maze of immigration bureaucracy is old
hat for the U.S. Soccer Federation. Despite a newly launched
program to develop more elite-level, native-born players, American
soccer authorities also want to maintain respectability gained from
a second-round finish in the 1994 World Cup. Seven players on the
current 22-man roster were brought up in another country, including
forwards Roy Wegerle and Preki Radosalvjevic, both of whom received
hastened citizenship because of their marriages to American women.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney for another partial American, David Wagner, whose
father is a U.S. military officer in Germany, heard of Regis'
potential eligiblity and promptly notified U.S. head coach Steve
Sampson.
</P>
<P>
   Worried about a defense that showed major cracks during World
Cup qualifying, Sampson flew over in December and saw Regis play
for the first time for his current club team in Karlsruhe, Germany,
across the Rhine River from Strasbourg. When Sampson told Regis in
April that he wanted to bring him on board, David and Nikki began
their whirlwind experience, which often became a maddening one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad it's over,'' Nikki said with a sigh and a smile. ``It
was a very tedious process. It's not as simple as snapping your
fingers.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. certainly isn't alone in looking for loopholes. Seven
of Jamaica's ``Reggae Boyz'' have spent most or all of their lives
in England. Tunisia and Japan each will be starting players born
and raised in Brazil. FIFA, the international soccer governing
body, simply abides by the respective immigration laws of its
member nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``An American is an American is an American,'' Sampson said in
regard to Regis, who was invited to training camp last month before
it was certain he would be able to play. ``This is a country of
immigrants, and David is doing nothing different than other
newcomers have done for years.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not, but his case was on a faster track than most. U.S.
immigration law allows the foreign spouses of Americans to become
citizens if they have been married for three years, or if their
husband or wife works abroad. Nikki hadn't been working since
becoming a mother. Their third anniversary, coincidentally enough,
falls on Wednesday, the opening day of the World Cup. The
federation lined up a job for her with its travel agency with the
intention of her being a France-based employee beyond this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We applied like everybody else to get a green card for
David,'' she said. ``The federation simply helped us through the
process.''
</P>
<P>
   There were some close calls. The Federal Bureau of Investigation
lost Regis' fingerprints, and he had to interrupt training in San
Diego to have another set made in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Studying for the citizenship exam wasn't easy, given the
language barrier. His teammates studied with him, although none
speaks French fluently. But when Regis had to write a sentence in
English _ ``Today is a nice day'' _ he aced it, and answered all 10
questions correctly. ``I think I know more U.S. history than a lot
of Americans,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His teammates welcomed him with open arms, singing ``The
Star-Spangled Banner'' to him before he dressed out for his first
game against Kuwait. The song brought a tear to his eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really surprised that the players were so open to me,''
Regis said. ``In Europe, every man is out for himself, it's more
dog-eat-dog. It was a new experience for me.''
</P>
<P>
   So will the larger task of becoming an American in the cultural
sense. That may be complicated because he is looking for a new pro
team in Europe, where he intends to complete his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``The responsibility for all of that lies with me, and I want to
do that very much,'' Regis said. ``It will take time, but once I
Iearn more about the language and spend as much time over here as I
can, the easier it will become.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
