</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSIDE-BASEBALL07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Johnson still Seattle's as trade waxes, wanes
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ First, the Seattle Mariners say they're going to trade
Randy Johnson. Then they're not. Then they are again. And then
they're not. The latest comes from team president Chuck Armstrong,
who issued a statement saying that Johnson will remain with the
club for the rest of the season. Armstrong added, ``We have no
plans to trade Randy Johnson.''
</P>
<P>
   But the real reason that Johnson hasn't been traded is because
other clubs haven't offered enough. It was reported last week that
the Dodgers offered right-handed pitcher Ismael Valdes and
infielder Wilton Guerrero. But when the smoke cleared, the Dodgers
actually had gotten cold feet on losing Valdes and offered Hideo
Nomo instead.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle thinks it's too early in the season not to get a lot for
Johnson, who last year was the most dominating pitcher in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   They have to trade him, however. Johnson becomes a free agent
after the season, and he has no plans to return. The Mariners are
still in the division race, so far, at 9 1/2 games out of first and
eight games out of a wild-card spot.
</P>
<P>
   It would be folly not to get something good for one of the best
pitchers in the game. The Marlins, for example, got three good
prospects when they traded Mike Piazza to the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Johnson has not had a good season, compiling
a 5-4 record with a 5.58 ERA. But many baseball people think he is
upset with the club and has had trouble focusing.
</P>
<P>
   When the rumors began that Johnson was close to being traded, he
won two starts in a row, allowing three runs and 10 hits in 17
innings and striking out 25. Then, after Armstrong said Johnson
would remain in Seattle for the rest of the year, the ``Big Unit''
went out Wednesday and got beat 8-1 by the Angels, allowing six
runs in 6 2/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Scouts representing more than 20 clubs were in Seattle to watch
him pitch Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The most intriguing trade could be with the Yankees. The
Mariners would like to get New York right-hander Ramiro Mendoza and
prospects Ricky Ledee and Mike Lowell. But New York thinks the
price is too high. The Padres continue to call, because they don't
want to see the Dodgers get Johnson and would be glad to send
pitcher Joey Hamilton to Seattle. The Orioles also are interested,
which could lead to a Johnson-for-Armando Benitez swap. Both
players could use a change of scenery.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson isn't saying much these days. He continues to mope and
appears unapproachable to teammates and reporters. He said after
Wednesday's game that he is not going to talk to the press anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realize the media has a job to do,'' he said. ``I hope
everyone understands. I'm tired of being a story every day. I'm
tired of talking about what has happened around me.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has become a huge distraction in the clubhouse, but his
teammates say otherwise publicly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does he want to stay?'' asked shortstop Alex Rodriguez, who
didn't answer his own question. ``He's such a great competitor, the
best pitcher in baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not. At least not right now.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
