</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFL-NOTEBOOK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Inside Pro Football: Youth movement on hold as Falcons opt for
veterans
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ On the day he was hired as the Atlanta Falcons
football czar, Dan Reeves talked about the need to rebuild the
moribund franchise with younger players. And there likely will be a
day when the kids he has brought aboard _ cornerback Michael
Booker, linebackers Keith Brooking and Henri Crockett, tailback
Byron Hanspard, tight end O.J. Santiago and others _ will be the
foundation, and not the foundlings, in Suwanee.
</P>
<P>
   Nurturing young players takes time, though, and after 17 months
a certain pragmatism has settled in on Reeves and staff. There is
no better example of what should be dubbed ''Dan's Dilemma'' than
last week's deal for San Diego wide receiver Tony Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Simply defined, it is this: With a dwindling fan base, and
facing a red-ink bath for the second straight season, the Falcons
need to win games now or become a speck on the local sports
landscape. And at any level of the game, enthusiasm can't often
overcome inexperience, a fact that will stunt any well-intentioned
youth movement.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all his rationalizations, Reeves is savvy enough to know
third-rounder Jammi German, who hasn't been on a field since 1995,
isn't apt to quickly assimilate nuances like blitz adjustments. So
to replace Bert Emanuel the club paid a lofty price, at least two
rounds higher than some Chargers coaches felt Martin would fetch.
It is simply the latest example that a move toward youth usually is
a painstaking process. In the era of the salary cap, where NFL
teams pay dearly for veteran mistakes, turning over a roster in
wholesale doses is an impossible task.
</P>
<P>
   The addition of Martin, who turns 33 the day before the regular
season begins, actually continues an offseason trend most observers
failed to discern. The nine veterans added by Atlanta this spring
average 30.5 years of age and 8.0 seasons of experience. Of the key
additions, only free agent Corey Louchiey, 26, has fewer than six
years in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   And since he couldn't fend off a challenge from a player no more
talented than Jerry Ostroski to retain his starter's job in Buffalo
last year, there's no guarantee Louchiey will be an upgrade over
Matt Willig.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other additions, free safety Eugene Robinson, who
bumped a player 10 years his junior (Devin Bush) to the bench, is
35 and will team with 32-year-old William White in the interior
secondary. Backup QB Mark Rypien is 35. Dave Widell and Matt
Elliott, acquired to add depth to the offensive line, are 33 and
29, respectively, and Elliott reportedly failed at least one
physical at a club he visited. Defensive tackle Esera Tuaolo is 30.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the infusion of draft choices and presence of standout
young veterans like offensive tackle Bob Whitfield, tailback Jamal
Anderson, cornerback Ray Buchanan and defensive tackle Travis Hall,
the projected starters for '98 average 28.6 years of age.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a redeeming feature to the graying of the Falcons,
it's that general manager Harold Richardson has done a good job of
keeping the financial investment in the new players low, and only
Martin is signed for more than two years. As temporary as some of
the players may be in Suwanee, however, they are still quick-fix
types. All the good intentions aside, a youth movement is called a
``movement'' because it is a process which takes time and patience.
After 32 seasons of mostly-miserable football, fans here aren't
likely to afford the Falcons much more of either commodity.
</P>
<P>
   Rolling the dice
</P>
<P>
   His age notwithstanding, Martin was a productive player for the
Chargers and his exit leaves the team with a dubious wideout group.
Three of the top five players at the position _ veterans Webster
Slaughter and former Falcons backup Tyrone Brown, along with '98
second-rounder Mikhael Ricks _ weren't in the NFL in 1997.
Incumbents Bryan Still and Charlie Jones combined for one touchdown
last season. So why a trade? Age was one factor. Although he's a
solid citizen, Martin's sour relationship with coach Kevin Gilbride
was another. But general manager Bobby Beathard felt the club
couldn't afford to have a frustrated Martin around again this year.
At the end of 1997, Martin privately apologized to Beathard for
``losing (his) focus'' at times during a quarterback carousel that
included Stan Humphries, Jim Everett, Craig Whelihan and Casey
Weldon. Of the 83 pass attempts to Martin he didn't catch last
year, he had just four drops, but 44 were labeled ``poor throws.''
And while the Chargers drafted Ryan Leaf, it's Whelian, 0-7 as a
starter last year, who figures to open this season No. 1 on the
depth chart.
</P>
<P>
   Limping Lloyd
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh brass won't admit it, but it seems just a matter of
time until the Steelers give up on linebacker Greg Lloyd. The
former league defensive MVP limped through the mini-camp last week
and his right calf was noticeably atrophied from the severe staph
infection he suffered last November. Coach Bill Cowher conceded
Lloyd's recovery was ``taking a lot longer'' than anticipated.
Despite releasing corner Donnell Woolford, the team still needs
salary cap room to sign draft choices. Lloyd, who could be replaced
at the weakside spot by converted defensive end Mike Vrabel, is to
earn $2.8 million. ... As expected, Carnell Lake worked primarily
at cornerback in mini-camp and onetime Georgia Tech standout Lethon
Flowers lined up at strong safety.
</P>
<P>
   Change in the wind?
</P>
<P>
   Tom Modrak, the new director of football operations in
Philadelphia, wasn't pleased last week when starting tailback
Charlie Garner and No. 2 quarterback Rodney Peete missed the first
day of mini-camp. Modrak is finding out fast that not every
franchise runs as smoothly as the Steelers. He's still interested
in running back Raymont Harris, but Green Bay GM Ron Wolf might
beat him to the former Bears 1,000-yard rusher. He is still
rehabbing a broken leg, but Harris looked good in a Thursday
workout in Green Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego might use a second-round pick to take Oklahoma State
defensive tackle Jamal Williams in the July 9 supplemental draft.
Some scouts feel Williams is as good as the late Leon Bender, taken
in the second round this year by the Raiders. ... Former Auburn
safety Martavius Houston hasn't applied for the supplemental draft
yet but is expected to, along with a top-notch offensive tackle
prospect. ... Colts president Bill Polian doesn't expect a deal
before July, but his first session with Tom Condon, the agent for
Peyton Manning, went far better than expected.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
