<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-NET-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SETTING YOUR SIGHTS ON WORLD CUP SITES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By TOMMY CUMMINGS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Got a few days?
</P>
<P>
   That's how long it's going to take to sort through sites
dedicated to the World Cup soccer championships, which start
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The logical starting point is the official site, France 98:
Coupe De Monde (www.france98.com). If it's been a while since those
confusing days in French language class in high school or college,
choose English and go to town.
</P>
<P>
   The framed site has the basics, including history of the World
Cup, news updates, venue information and rosters. It's definitely
official.
</P>
<P>
   FIFA, the official organizing committee for the World Cup, has
detailed World Cup information at its official site (www.fifa.com).
</P>
<P>
   After these official sites, the list of soccer sites is strictly
a fan's preference. Most have rosters, schedules, image galleries,
polls and chat rooms. Many are multilingual.
</P>
<P>
   All of the big-media sites plan extensive coverage. CBS
SportsLine might have the advantage with its affiliation with
Soccernet, regarded as the world's best soccer site.
</P>
<P>
   Kgoal! (www.kgoal.net) promises a free service that allows
soccer fans with Internet access to be informed in real-time _
either in French, Spanish, English or Italian _ about all goals
made during the Cup's 64 games. Every time a goal is scored, an
E-mail is sent to each Kgoal! subscriber.
</P>
<P>
   And for something completely different, access the British
Broadcasting Corp. coverage (www.bbc.co.uk). Included in its vast
features is a debate about and message link to Paul ``Gazza''
Gascoigne, who was kicked off the English team after being found
drunk in a Spanish hotel room.
</P>
<P>
   The tip here is to access your favorite search engine and type
in ``World Cup.'' Don't expect to move from your seat for a while. &QL; 
REVIEW &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pete Rose Cooperstown Countdown (www.scrollsaw.com/peterose)
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati Reds fan Ben Jones of Vandalia, Ohio, thought his
campaign to have Pete Rose considered for the Baseball Hall of Fame
was over.
</P>
<P>
   In September, when he heard that Rose was on the verge of
reinstatement, Jones had his site taken down. Then he read that
acting commissioner Bud Selig might not review Rose's request for
reinstatement after all.
</P>
<P>
   ``If baseball refuses to reinstate Pete, then I decided to
reinstate the Pete Rose Cooperstown Countdown,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Jones rushed his site back online in late April. It features an
online poll on whether to put Rose in the Hall of Fame or keep him
in the ``Hall of Shame.''
</P>
<P>
   From nearly 27,000 respondents, sentiment is running 12-to-1 to
allow Rose, who was suspended for his ties to gambling, in the Hall
of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Jones doesn't know Rose personally, so he can't vouch for his
character. But Jones said he knows baseball talent and there
``never has been any better.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones site doesn't have much depth _ the statistics and
background on Rose were on his previous site. But he is passionate
about this cause.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: (out of five stars). &QL; 
BYTES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NBA.cam on NBA.com: It's kind of like ``The Truman Show'', but
we're not peering in on Jim Carrey; it's the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   For the finals, NBA.com is showing off its NBA.cam, a robotic
camera developed by Chicago-based Perceptual Robotics that fans can
activate through their Web browser.
</P>
<P>
   In another melding of television and the Internet, it's a way to
customize your coverage. Fans can point at or zoom in on their view
of choice. A second NBA.cam also offers interactive, wide-screen
views of all the in-arena action.
</P>
<P>
   Being further interactive, NBA.com is also offering Shockwave
technology to bring play diagrams to life. The software creates
animated diagrams of the Chicago Bulls' triangle offense and the
Utah Jazz's pick-and-roll offense.
</P>
<P>
   Chat highlights: The subject of pitching phenom Kerry Wood of
Irving should come up at 3 p.m. tomorrow when Chicago Cubs general
manager Ed Lynch chats live on CBS SportsLine. ... Nancy
Lieberman-Cline, coach/general manager of the Detroit Shock of the
Women's NBA, 4:30 p.m. Tuesday, ESPN SportsZone. ... Houston Astros
catcher Brad Ausmus, noon Tuesday, Bigleaguers.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
