<HEADER>
A7557 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUTDOORS-LURES-TEX     06-06 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-LURES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTIQUE FISHING TACKLE IS DRAWING MORE COLLECTORS, DRIVING PRICES
UP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By BOB HOOD 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The price of fishing tackle may be on the rise, but if you want
artificial lures worth big bucks, find some that have rusted hooks
and painted bodies that have faded, especially ones in yellowed
boxes with jagged corners.
</P>
<P>
   Some antique lures are worth 20 times more than their original
prices and 10 times more than modern lures. And, if you are lucky,
one old lure could be worth $1,000 or more.
</P>
<P>
   Antique fishing tackle collectors say prices for old lures, rods
and reels are climbing as more collectors become involved, but most
collectors are quick to tell anyone who thinks they may have a
valuable old piece of tackle to not get their hopes too high.
</P>
<P>
   Most antique lures, even many made as far back as the 1920s and
1930s, aren't worth more than $10 to $20, but rare ones can go for
$50 to $100, especially in an original box.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always caution anyone interested in buying an antique lure
to be very careful for what he pays for it,'' said Jeff Winters, a
collector who specializes in Heddon and Creek Chub lures. ``I've
seen a lot of lures priced at $45 to $75 which actually aren't
worth more than $10 or $20, and some aren't even worth more than $5
to $10. But, you should always be on the lookout for those rare
exceptions like the Heddon Punkinseed that sold at Lang's in Maine
a few months ago.''
</P>
<P>
   The Heddon Rainbow Punkinseed was auctioned at Lang's for
$1,320, and a Yellow Musky Rush Tango sold for $1,265.
</P>
<P>
   When searching for rare lures, finding ones that weren't made in
large numbers or have color patterns that weren't highly
distributed is as important as finding ones that date to the turn
of the century or before, collectors say.
</P>
<P>
   Collecting antique lures and other fishing tackle also can be a
rewarding learning experience, both about fishing and about the
people who invented lures. In many cases, a company or person's
name is synonymous with a collectible antique lure, and learning
those names is important for people who are serious about becoming
collectors.
</P>
<P>
   For example, not many people have heard of Bucktail Worden. F.G.
``Bucktail'' Worden founded the South Bend Bait Company in about
1912 and got his nickname after inventing the first bucktail
treble-hook teaser on an artificial lure. Hair and fiber-covered
treble hooks still are popular today.
</P>
<P>
   Some lures were designed after careful planning. Others,
including many of the rarest, came about by accident or
happenstance.
</P>
<P>
   Julio T. Buel, a Vermont furrier, for example, is reported to
have accidentally dropped a spoon overboard while fishing from a
boat in 1830. As he watched the spoon flutter and wobble downwards,
Buel was surprised to see it suddenly snatched by a fish. Buel went
home and made another spoon from his kitchen tableware, attaching
hooks to it. Buel not only caught fish with his spoon, but formed a
tackle company in 1848 and produced high-quality (and collectible)
spoons and spinners until his death in 1870.
</P>
<P>
   If that story sounds familiar, it should. About 53 years later,
in 1883, James Heddon was waiting for a friend on a creek bank in
Dowagiac, Mich., when he tossed a piece of carved wood into the
creek and saw a bass promptly attack it. Heddon went home, carved a
wooden replica of a frog, attached two hooks and thus began the
Heddon Bait Company, credited with being the first manufacturer of
wooden fishing ``plugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Hooking anglers was as important as hooking fish to early lure
manufacturers, just as it is today.
</P>
<P>
   In about 1915, for example, The Detroit Glass Minnow Tube
Company produced a lure that would hold a live minnow in a glass
test tube-like capsule that allowed water circulation. The lure had
four treble hooks, the glass was magnified, and the manufacturer
said the minnow would stay alive all day.
</P>
<P>
   And there was the Booster Bait made in 1915. Its manufacturer
said the lure was ``filled with edible matter and containing a
capsule which, when placed in the water, dissolves, throwing off a
strong taste and smell.''
</P>
<P>
   There are numerous other stories that, like the lures
themselves, are lying there somewhere under the dust, just waiting
to be discovered.
</P>
<P>
   And, about those lures: How does anyone know when they've found
the next $1,000 piece of junk?
</P>
<P>
   Clyde Harbin Sr., perhaps the most well-known Heddon Lure
collector in the United States, offered this advice: ``There ain't
nothing worth anything unless someone is willing to buy it. A lure
is worth whatever someone is willing to pay for it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
