<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-LURES-WHERETO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TACKLING A HOBBY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By BOB HOOD 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
PLACES TO LOOK 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Old tackle stores, fish camps and marinas, drugstores, flea
markets, garage sales, old fishing friends or acquaintances. &QL; 
WHAT TO LOOK FOR &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Old fishing lures, lure boxes, tackle boxes, metal stringers,
reel oil cans, temperature gauges, pliers, publications and
anything else that has to do with fishing. &QL; 
HOW MUCH TO PAY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most lures are overpriced in flea markets and antique stores.
Use prices in collectors' books as guides. Remember that the
majority of antique lures are worth only $10 to $20, some less, but
some rare ones are worth $50 to $100 and more. &QL; 
WHERE TO LEARN MORE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The National Fishing Lure Collectors Club, formed in the
mid-1970s, is a good source for collectors and sellers of fishing
tackle. The club holds regional swap meets and an annual national
meet, and a mailing address is Drew Reese, HRC No. 3, Box 4012,
Reeds Springs, Mo., 65737. &QL; 
PUBLICATIONS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Old Fishing Lures and Tackle,'' by Carl F. Luckey, Books
Americana, Inc., P.O. Box 2326, Florence, Ala., 35630.
</P>
<P>
   ``James Heddon Catalogues,'' Highwood Book Shop, P.O. Box 1246,
Traverse City, Mich., 49685.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Collector's Guide to Antique Fishing Gear,'' by Silvio A.
Calabi, Book Sales, Inc., 110 Enterprise Ave., Secaucus, N.J.,
07094.
</P>
<P>
   ``Collecting Old Fishing Tackle,'' by John Muma, National Child
Publishing Company, P.O. Box 3452 Lubbock, Texas, 79452.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
