<HEADER>
A7560 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-FINALS-COLUMN-HNS     06-06 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-FINALS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Column: Mailman misses his appointed rounds in the Finals
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By FRAN BLINEBURY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ At the rate things are going, the Bulls soon will turn
Utah's Mailman into a commemorative stamp.
</P>
<P>
   After all, they seem to have him licked.
</P>
<P>
   Two games into the NBA Finals and Karl Malone might as well have
his photo back up on the post-office wall with the rest of the
missing persons. Somebody needs to tell him the idea in June is to
get yourself on the front of a Wheaties box, not the side of a milk
carton.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Karl Malone don't play well, we will not win this series,''
Malone said, proving only that his grammar is as bad as his
offense, which says a lot.
</P>
<P>
   After averaging 27 points per game during the regular season,
the Mailman has delivered only 37 total in this series against the
Bulls. He has taken 41 shots and made 14. Friday night, he did not
score a field goal after the midway point of the second quarter. In
short, he's been the Great Salt Fake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Comes at a bleepy time,'' he said, recognizing the aroma of
the obvious.
</P>
<P>
   It also comes at the same time on the calendar when Malone
served up several clunkers last year against the Bulls, which is
one of the reasons the Jazz is trying to prove itself title-worthy.
</P>
<P>
   There was the Game 1 collapse of a year ago, when Malone stood
at the free-throw line in the final seconds with a chance to ice a
Utah win and clunked two foul shots. He misfired on other crucial
occasions during the series. He did not pick up his team and carry
it on his shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Malone entered the Finals as a controversial 1997
Most Valuable Player in the eyes of many. And, if anything, he
added fuel to that debate by looking like a different kind of MVP _
Most Vanishing Person.
</P>
<P>
   All of those monster games in the regular season make nice
highlights for SportsCenter. But this is the time of the year when
reputations _ for better or for worse _ are forged. Michael Jordan
rises to the occasion at this time of the year. Hakeem Olajuwon and
Clyde Drexler did. Magic Johnson and Larry Bird did.
</P>
<P>
   But it seems in June, Malone turns more nervous than a blushing
bride.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Jordan was on a mission to prove the MVP award
rightfully belonged to him and he imposed his will on the series,
lifting the Bulls even on a night when he was ill and dragged them
to another title.
</P>
<P>
   Malone, for all of his muscles and all of his work ethic, looks
like just another 98-pound weakling who is melting under Jordan's
laser-beam glare for the second year in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Malone returned to the big stage, supposedly determined to
redeem himself, and has stood there stage-struck again, forgetting
his lines. The open jumpers on the wing he buried with regularity
in the early rounds of the playoffs against the Rockets, Spurs and
Lakers are not falling. What's worse is when the game is in the
balance late in the fourth quarter, he does not appear comfortable
taking the big shot, or looking for it.
</P>
<P>
   The Mailman's Game 2 line of 5-for-16 and only 16 points looked
like just another night at the dead letter office. And the
crunch-time numbers were worse: Jordan 13 points in the fourth
quarter; Malone one. What's more, he took only two shots in the
final period when the Jazz needed him to step up.
</P>
<P>
   How much of the credit for Malone's troubles should go to Dennis
Rodman, who brought fear and loathing from his Las Vegas trip into
the heart of the Delta Center, bumping Malone and trying to push
him out of his comfort zone?
</P>
<P>
   ``If the referees don't call the small-time stuff, I can play
Karl Malone any day of the week,'' said Rodman, who spent four days
in Salt Lake City and managed to not offend the Mormon community
once. ``I just don't feel comfortable in Utah. It's not my scene.''
</P>
<P>
   Meaning, probably, there aren't enough pierced body parts and
topless dancers for his taste. But it isn't like Rodman has
tattooed himself to Malone, who has had plenty of wide-open looks
at the basket and missed shots.
</P>
<P>
   The result has been the kind of belly-flopping performance that
hasn't been put forth by a superstar in the Finals since 1977, when
George McGinnis built an embarrassing house of bricks for
Philadelphia against Portland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just keep trying,'' Malone said. ``I keep taking
opportunities, if they're there, and I keep trying to do other
things.''
</P>
<P>
   If nobody else, at least the folks who make Rogaine have to be
happy with their celebrity endorser. Sales are going up in Utah,
because the Mailman has a lot of Jazz fans pulling out their hair.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-06-98 1956EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
