<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-JOHNSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON A HAPPY CAMPER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ Golf at The Country Club one day, deep sea fishing
the next. Sometimes life can be tough. And then there is life at a
National Football League minicamp in June.
</P>
<P>
   Meetings, practice, preparation for a season that will be upon
us in a matter of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Give Ted Johnson a choice and he will probably hesitate. Just a
bit. After all, how many times does one get to stroll The Country
Club grounds in Brookline, having your caddie retrieve balls you
slice and hook into the woods. And then there is the deep sea
fishing excursion planned for later in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson, as much as anyone, knows that such activities are
only offshoots and byproducts of what he is, which is the Patriots'
middle linebacker, arguably their best defensive player and
unquestionably a key to a team that hopes to go deep into the
playoffs next season.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, there's one more thing. Johnson is entering the fourth year
of a four-year contract worth $403,000 this season. But another
good season by the former University of Colorado star will earn him
10 times that much in his next contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, nothing's going on,'' said Johnson Saturday as the
Patriots veterans went through their second day of workouts in this
minicamp, which ends Sunday. ``No real talks. There hasn't been any
for a while. But there has been some mutual interest on both sides
to do something.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson took some good-natured ribbing from the media Saturday,
the joke being that if it weren't for his upcoming extension, the
Patriots might have had enough money to keep running back Curtis
Martin around.
</P>
<P>
   ``A business decision,'' was Johnson's explanation as to why
Martin is with the Jets and why he will probably sign a long-term
extension with a big raise in the next several months.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson says he has learned as much about financial aspects of
the NFL these days as he has football the past several months.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a learning experience,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So has his time with the Patriots. A year ago, Johnson and the
rest of the defensive unit were in a state of flux as Bill Parcells
and his staff were replaced by Pete Carroll and his staff. It
wasn't until the end of the season that the defense showed the form
that helped the Patriots get to the Super Bowl two seasons ago.
</P>
<P>
   Now, says Johnson, the expectations are much higher. Johnson
calls it the ``comfortability factor.'' The players know the
coaches and the system, and the coaches know the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is more in sync,'' said Johnson, who has worked
hard on his golf game in the offseason but has worked just as hard
in making himself into what he calls a full-time linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Johnson has been a two-down linebacker, removed on
third and long for defensive backs in nickel and dime coverages.
</P>
<P>
   One knock on him _ and there aren't many _ is that he could
improve his pass coverage. So he has, working hard at getting
quicker, if not faster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to play more,'' he said. ``I want to be full-time. I
don't want to be a two-down-and-out guy.''
</P>
<P>
   As to where he does his playing? Well, there is little doubt
about that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be stupid to want to leave here,'' he said, pointing out
that he has already been to a Super Bowl, he is on a good young
team, the fan base is solid, and he feels very much appreciated.
</P>
<P>
   The flip side of that coin, of course, is that Johnson has
learned that football can come down to business decisions.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, he is in the right place at the right time, and he
will be the first to tell you how good it is.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Will the Patriots be a running team that passes or a passing
team that runs under the guidance of new offensive coordinator
Ernie Zampese? ``The players will dictate that,'' said Zampese
Saturday. Although his inclination is to run the ball more, he will
not be stubborn about it if the offense, minus Martin, cannot
produce.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-06-98 1958EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
