<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-06 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7562 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-COUPLES     06-06 1509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-COUPLES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTHING HOLDS COUPLES BACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; This is Fred Couples. During the 1989 US Open, he invited the
entire crew of the outdoor pro shops at Oak Hill to an Italian
restaurant for dinner at his expense.
</P>
<P>
   This is Fred Couples. He was the best dancer at the calypso
parties during the now defunct Johnnie Walker tournament in Montego
Bay, Jamaica, where he earned a lot of money _ and one victory _
over the years.
</P>
<P>
   This is Fred Couples. He is the PGA Tour's leading money winner
this year, with nearly $1.5 million so far.
</P>
<P>
   Still, people remember how he took an 8 on the 13th at Augusta
National to let the Masters slip out of his grasp and how he landed
in the water on 17 at the Byron Nelson to lose that tournament to
John Cook. Many may have expected to see him let the Memorial get
away last Sunday in Dublin, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't happen. The real Fred Couples stepped to the front of
the pack and stayed there. He won by four shots, a triumph for the
older guys on Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I feel tired and old, but I'm playing as well as I
can play right now,'' says Couples, 38. ``I just don't live and die
golf like I used to. I don't think I'll ever become a bad player.
I'm capable of playing as well at 38 or 39 or 40 as I did at 32.''
</P>
<P>
   Couples has been through a lot _ a divorce, the death of his
father from leukemia last November, and a longtime battle with back
problems. But even though his bad back has limited his competitive
appearances over the years, when Couples walks the fairways, he
walks with a purpose.
</P>
<P>
   How good could Couples have become had his schedule not been
limited by physical problems? Back in 1991 and 1992, he was voted
the Tour's best player by his peers. He won the Masters in 1992, a
year in which he won three times and finished second twice during a
remarkable six-tournament stretch. There were blips in the years
that followed, but when he won his second Players Championship at
Sawgrass in 1996 with a strong finish, he showed he was back.
</P>
<P>
   There was a downturn last season, when he finished outside the
top 30 in earnings for just the second time in 11 years. But now
he's back, in the era of Tiger Woods, Justin Leonard, David Duval,
Davis Love III, and Phil Mickelson. He showed that when he won the
Bob Hope Jan. 18 and then the Memorial.
</P>
<P>
   He has that casual swing, that casual look, that casual way of
expressing himself in conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept the lead and I stayed in the lead,'' he said after last
Sunday's win. ``It was a little easier than I felt it was going to
be.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Don Lyons &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who has been head professional at George Wright GC
in Hyde Park for 16 years, is in his first year as president of the
New England PGA. The 39-year-old Lyons came up in golf the
old-fashioned way, learning the basics as a caddie and bag room
attendant at Salem CC. He later worked in the pro shop under  &UR; Bill
Barclay &LR; , &UR;  &LR; then moved to the Thomson Club, where  &UR; Bill Flynn  &LR; was
head pro. It was Flynn who presided over the restoration of George
Wright and the city's other course, Franklin Park.
</P>
<P>
   The winding road from caddie to bag room to pro shop to head
professional to NEPGA president is one of dedication.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went into the apprentice program,'' says Lyons. ``I never
played much in high school; I played in one amateur tournament. I
didn't start to play until I was 15. I played with friends.''
</P>
<P>
   His golf education came through working with Barclay and Flynn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've only worked for two guys,'' says the Peabody native, who
resides in Danvers with his wife, Peggy, and their four children.
``I learned the basics of the business from both of them _ how to
deal with people. As I got more into it, I grew to love the game of
golf and just being around people who had similar interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day was exciting; different things happen. Everybody
you're dealing with all had the same love. Being able to teach and
help people with their games gave me satisfaction.''
</P>
<P>
   Few are the days when he isn't on the lesson tee at George
Wright, and for things like that he is a four-time recipient of the
NEPGA's Horton Smith Award for dedicated leadership and outstanding
contributions to the education program.
</P>
<P>
   And now he is the leader of the NEPGA. Lyons worked his way up
through the ranks, holding every elective position in the NEPGA
Assistants Association. His term at the helm of the organization
comes with the 1999 Ryder Cup at The Country Club on the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ryder Cup will be one of the biggest events to come to
Boston,'' says Lyons, who will step down when his term ends in
September and be succeeded by  &UR; Steve Napoli  &LR; of Wannamoisett CC.
``We're also seeing the growth of junior golf and we've moved into
a new home site at Cyprian Keys. There's been a rapid growth in our
membership. We have over 600 Class A PGA members and about 300
registered apprentices. Ten years ago, that number was 600, tops.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The national golf media will focus on  &UR; Casey Martin  &LR; again
Monday as he attempts to qualify for the US Open in the sectionals
at Clovernook CC in the Cincinnati suburbs. When Martin won a Nike
event earlier in the year, he gained an exemption that permitted
him to skip a local qualifier. The US Golf Association's executive
committee has agreed to let Martin use a cart. Earlier, Martin won
an injunction in federal court that permits him to ride a cart on
the Nike Tour, and should he make his PGA Tour debut, as expected,
at the Greater Hartford Open this summer, he'll ride in that event
as well. ``The transportation will be a single-rider cart,'' the
USGA's statement read. ``Similar vehicles have been used at recent
USGA national championships for transportation of spectators with
disabilities.'' The statement noted that the USGA was not a party
to the suit Martin brought against the PGA Tour ``and disagrees
with the verdict.'' ... The majority of area pros and amateurs
involved in sectional qualifying this week will play Tuesday at
Canoe Brook CC in Summit, N.J. _ if they can find it. Getting to
the two courses requires intricate moves off Exit 142 of the Garden
State Parkway. Those in the 36-hole test include  &UR; Geoff Sisk  &LR; of
Marshfield and  &UR; Kevin Johnson  &LR; of Halifax and the Nike Tour. Should
Sisk make it to The Olympic Club in San Francisco for the June
18-21 Open and make the cut, he'd have quite a cross-country trip
to make to defend his Massachusetts Open title; the tournament at
Oak Hill CC begins the day after the US Open ends. The 106-player
field at Canoe Brook also includes a few players off the PGA Tour,
including  &UR; Fuzzy Zoeller &LR; , who Monday conducts his annual clinic
for the Boys Clubs of Greater Newark ... Four members of the New
England PGA qualified for the PGA Club Professional Championship
June 25-28 at Pinehurst No. 8 in Pinehurst, N.C., where  &UR; Bruce
Zabriski  &LR; of Rye, N.Y., will defend his title. The area players who
qualified through the regionals last fall are  &UR; Paul Parajeckas  &LR; of
Woburn,  &UR; David Lane  &LR; of Indian Ridge,  &UR; Jeff Stewart  &LR; of North Hill,
and  &UR; Mike Baker  &LR; of Bangor Municipal. There will be 144 competitors
playing for a $300,000 purse. The winner earns $40,000 and earns
exemptions to next year's PGA Championship at Sahalee in Redmond,
Wash., the PGA Cup Matches at the Broadmoor in Colorado Springs,
and three PGA Tour events ... West Roxbury native  &UR; John Hines  &LR; and
 &UR; Jack's  &LR; son  &UR; Steve Nicklaus &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who purchased Executive Sports
International last year, will manage the US Senior Open at Salem CC
in 2001. ESI, a subdivision of the Nicklaus enterprise Golden Bear,
has managed more than 600 tournaments globally since 1971 ...
 &UR; Donald Trump's  &LR; $40 million golf resort in West Palm Beach is
being constructed next door to a boutique named Condoms Galore. ``I
don't think Donald knows about it yet,'' store owner  &UR; Karol Schmick
 &LR; told the Palm Beach Post. ``Maybe the golfers will stop by after
they play to get a little something to bring home to their wives.''
... The soaring popularity of the Ryder Cup has attracted six
prominent clubs to bid for the 2003 matches. The people at Colonial
in Fort Worth brought a video and letters from  &UR; Byron
Nelson &LR; , &UR;  &LR; former President  &UR; George Bush &LR; , &UR;  &LR; Texas Gov.  &UR; George W.
Bush &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and the late  &UR; Ben Hogan  &LR; when they met with the PGA of
America in Palm Beach Gardens, Fla. They also proposed setting up a
corporate village at the Fort Worth Zoo. Colonial and Pinehurst are
considered the leaders, and bids reportedly are in from Medinah,
Congressional, Oakland Hills, and Pebble Beach. Eastern clubs are
thought to have an advantage because of the time difference in
Europe. The matches were at Oak Hill three years ago ...  &UR; Les
Kennedy &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who was a legendary pro at Pawtucket CC from 1944 until
his retirement in 1984 and is still alive and kicking in spite of
recent published reports of his death, will be inducted into the
Pawtucket CC Hall of Fame Friday night. He'll be there.
</P>
</TEXT>
