<HEADLINE>
SANCHEZ VICARIO TOPS SELES FOR TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Monica Seles was the story.
</P>
<P>
   Arantxa Sanchez Vicario was the champion.
</P>
<P>
   Spain was the conquering invader. France provided the ballroom
and Sanchez Vicario, Carlos Moya, and Alex Corretja _ the Barcelona
Brigade _ danced a joyous bolero on the dirt paving of Stade Roland
Garros.
</P>
<P>
   Moya and Corretja, the last of 19 Spaniards crowding the men's
draw, will swing at each other this afternoon, as an afterthought,
but Spain can't lose whatever the score.
</P>
<P>
   Diminutive, perpetually moving Sanchez Vicario made sure of that
Saturday, beating the game and gritty but hard-luck Seles, 7-6
(7-5), 0-6, 6-2, for her third French Open title as Spanish and
Catalan flags of scarlet and gold brightened a dim, rain-heavy sky.
</P>
<P>
   Grieving and underprepared, Seles, the champion of seemingly
long ago, had untold hearts beating for her as she raced improbably
to the final (knocking off Nos. 1 and 3 Martina Hingis and Jana
Novotna on the way), and into a decisive third set against Sanchez
Vicario, whom she'd beaten in 14 of 16 previous encounters. The
death of Seles's father three weeks ago was an immeasurable loss,
and she ``didn't make up my mind to play until the Friday before
the tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Spanish contingent among the sellout gathering of
16,000, it was a Seles crowd. Chorusing, ``Moni-ca! Moni-ca!'' as
she struck the bigger double-fisted blows in the exciting though
unevenly played match, fans sensed success after Seles brilliantly
shut out her opponent in the second set.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't to come because Sanchez Vicario refuses to let a
point die whether she has to climb walls, skin her desperately
reaching arms, careen and skid around corners, risk high-speed
crashes into the net, and almost total herself. Somehow she keeps
the rally breathing, scooping, lofting, overtaking balls that
appear surely to be her foes' points.
</P>
<P>
   Seles was no exception to the mass charitable gestures that made
Sanchez Vicario the United Fund of this tournament. Everybody gave
at the office, particularly in the stretch: Serena Williams 71
unforced errors in three sets, Patty Schnyder 63 in three, No. 2
Lindsay Davenport 56 in two, Seles 47 in three. Her seven victims
contributed a total of 328, but an error-pinching Sanchez Vicario
donated but 187, merely 21 to Seles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arantxa makes you start going for too much to get it past
her,'' sighed Seles. ``She runs down everything and you start
making mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Seles had limited Sanchez Vicario to 6 points in the brief
second set but found an even more determined Sanchez Vicario facing
her as the third set began. Seles failed because she couldn't cash
in five break points: two in the opening game, one in the third,
and two in the fifth where the Spaniard's 3-1 lead jiggled
precariously at 15-40.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first and second games of the third were so important,''
said Sanchez Vicario. ``I kept hanging in there'' to elude two
break points from 15-40 and lead, 1-0. She broke, then boosted it
to 3-0 by escaping a break point with a rocketing backhand, and got
to 4-1 as Seles bungled her openings.
</P>
<P>
   Two points in the first set _ the fifth of the ninth game and
the last of the tie-breaker _ were especially costly to Seles,
playing only her 18th match of this troubled year. Leading, 5-3,
30-30 _ 2 points from the set _ she zinged a serve wide to Sanchez
Vicario's forehand and stood at the net to cream the pop-up return
that her opponent somehow managed. But Seles blew the smash and
also netted the next point, preserving Sanchez Vicario for a
tie-breaker.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez Vicario sprang off to a 5-points-to-1 lead, but for a
moment it was reminiscent of Seles's first of three straight
pre-stabbing titles, as a 16-year-old in 1990. Then, she lagged
behind Steffi Graf, 6-2, in the first-set tie-breaker but reeled
off 6 straight points.
</P>
<P>
   This time she got 4 of them back to 5-5, missed a forehand
return, and became embroiled in a corner-to-corner duel of 15
strokes, her forehand assaulting Sanchez Vicario's backhand. The
Spaniard kept stretching and slicing with one hand, lulling Seles _
until Sanchez Vicario saw a ball she liked and threw herself at it
with both hands, a banger that won the point and set.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the fourth round last Sunday, nobody was talking up the
aging Sanchez Vicario, 26, whose championship days seemed well
behind her (she won the title in 1989 and 1994). Certainly not when
she trailed 16-year-old Williams, 4-6, 2-5 and four times was
within 2 points of losing.
</P>
<P>
   ``That one got me started,'' she said. ``It stung me, hurt me
that Serena show me no respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams had yelled at her during a dispute over an umpire's
call.
</P>
<P>
   Neither she nor Seles figured to get this far. All the attention
was going to the cocksure teen-agers led by Hingis. But Seles and
Sanchez Vicario have plenty of respect now. And Sanchez Vicario has
the championship.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
