<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS PARALLEL A GOOD READ, COVER TO COVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The Last Stand.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine arrived in the mail two days ago, and there was
Michael Jordan on the cover of Sports Illustrated for the millionth
time, looking sweaty and tired, with Scottie Pippen in profile
behind him.
</P>
<P>
   I knew I'd seen this before. Being something of a pack rat, I
didn't have to look far. There's a sports collage on the wall of my
home office _ color magazine photos from the 1960s. I put it
together when I was in high school and it has moved with me.
</P>
<P>
   And there was Bill Russell driving the lane on the Boston Garden
parquet floor next to the headline ``Boston's Old Guard/The Last
Stand.''
</P>
<P>
   Pretty neat. Like Jordan today, Russell was 35 years old (both
born in February) when SI put him on its cover in 1969 to
encapsulate the final quest of a great champion.
</P>
<P>
   There are some obvious differences. For one thing, Sports
Illustrated cost only 50 cents in 1969. Also, Russell made the
cover on April 28, which reminds us that the NBA season lasts two
months longer than it did in the old days. There's no
``www.cnnsi.com'' on the 1969 cover, either, and the old magazine
is slightly larger than today's SI.
</P>
<P>
   But my address is in the same lower left-hand corner of both
magazines and the cover themes haven't changed much in 29 years.
Russell's Celtics in 1969 were going for their second straight
title, their 11th in 13 seasons. They didn't have the home-court
advantage and they had to play the first two games in Los Angeles.
Boston lost the first two games, but recovered to win the series in
seven.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 Bulls are trying to win their third straight title,
their sixth in eight years. Like the '69 Celtics, they are trying
to beat the same team they defeated in the finals the previous
year.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan and Russell have much in common. They are perennial MVPs
(five each) and the undisputed leaders of basketball dynasties.
Russell served as player-coach in his final three seasons. Jordan
is merely the coach on the court, allegedly taking orders from Phil
Jackson. When Jordan won his latest MVP, Russell _ rarely seen away
from the golf course _ was there to present it to Michael.
</P>
<P>
   The 1969 Celtics were tired and got help from spare parts named
Don Nelson and Emmette Bryant. They won Game 7 on the road in the
LA Forum. Red Auerbach has 16 championship rings in his possession,
including nine he won as a head coach, but he wears the ring from
'69. And he still gets a chuckle out of Jack Kent Cooke lining the
Forum ceiling with balloons for the postgame celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are they gonna do with all those damn balloons?'' said a
chuckling, stogie-smoking Auerbach after Boston's 108-106 Game 7
win.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls and Jazz are 1-1 after two games and play three in
Chicago this week. Should the series return to Salt Lake City, and
it undoubtedly will, the Jazz would be smart to put a pin in
anybody who suggests balloons at the Delta Center.
</P>
<P>
   These Bulls have their Don Nelsons and Emmette Bryants. Try
Steve Kerr and Luc Longley. Russell had no running mate equal to
Scottie Pippen, but Sam Jones comes pretty close. Sam was there for
10 of the 11 championships, and he retired with Russell after
winning The Last Stand.
</P>
<P>
   We didn't know Russell was done when he won Title No. 11. He
made the announcement in Sports Illustrated. Similarly, we don't
know whether this is really the end for Michael. He has said he
won't come back if Jackson doesn't return, and Jackson says he's
not coming back. Still, it seems Michael wants to play more ball.
</P>
<P>
   Russell's 1969 Celtics had the hearts of champions. They beat a
Laker team that had Wilt Chamberlain, Jerry West, and Elgin Baylor.
They won on the road, after losing the first two. They won after
fans and rivals counted them out.
</P>
<P>
   There was a lot of stuff about the Bulls being tired and old
after they wheezed to a Game 7 conference final win at home against
Indiana. There's not so much of that talk now. But unless they win
three straight at home, starting tonight, they will have to win
their title out West _ just like the Celtics did in The Last Stand
of 1969.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
