<SLUG> BC-BBO-METS-JONES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMAND PERFORMANCE BY JONES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARVIN PAVE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One week ago in Philadelphia, Mets pitcher Bobby Jones had his
worst outing of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The righthander allowed 10 hits and six earned runs in four
innings, and while the New Yorkers came back for an 8-6 victory to
take Jones off the hook, pitching coach Bob Apodaca wasn't about
to.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had the same pitches like he had today,'' said Apodaca,
after Jones went eight innings and gave up just three hits in a 1-0
victory Saturday at Fenway Park that improved his record to 5-3,
``but he wasn't locating them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why? Well, today you saw a calm Bobby Jones with a rhythm to
his delivery. In Philadelphia, I saw a quick, herky-jerky pitcher,
similar to (Pedro) Martinez Friday night, and that affects your
comand.''
</P>
<P>
   From the moment he started his warmup tosses Saturday, Jones was
eased into his task by Apodaca.
</P>
<P>
   ``He set the tone for his rhythm right from his first pitches in
the bullpen,'' said Apodaca.
</P>
<P>
   Jones not only showed some resiliency in coming back from his
shellacking by the Phillies, but also from his only previous
appearance against the Red Sox. A year ago in Shea Stadium, Jones
was touched for five runs and six hits in just four innings as
Boston romped, 10-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched a lot of tapes from that game last year,'' said
Jones, whose 15 victories in 1997 were the most by a Mets pitcher
since Frank Viola won 20 in 1990. ``Basically, my stuff was a lot
better today against Boston than last year. I had good command of
all my pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   After Troy O'Leary's leadoff single in the second inning, Jones
faced 22 batters without giving up a hit. He was lifted by manager
Bobby Valentine in favor of stopper John Franco to start the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was Bobby's best-pitched game this year,'' said Valentine.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't quite start out that way. Darren Lewis and Reggie
Jefferson opened the Boston first with singles but Jones got Nomar
Garciaparra to hit a ground ball that third baseman Edgardo Alfonzo
turned into a double play.
</P>
<P>
   Jones then got Mo Vaughn on a shallow fly to center and he was
never again in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a big pitch to Nomar, but the big thing all day was
my location,'' said Jones, who said he couldn't afford to worry
about how well his counterpart, Tim Wakefield, was pitching. But he
did have some concern after eyeing the Green Monster from the
pitcher's mound for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, I wanted to get a lot of ground balls,'' said Jones, who
recorded 13 outs on grounders, including two double plays.
</P>
<P>
   And Apodaca knew why.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby had an outstanding game plan and he worked it from the
beginning,'' said Apodaca. ``He established his fastball in the
first couple of innings on both sides of the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Friday night, we played macho ball with Mo Vaughn and tried to
bust him inside and all he did was get the head of the bat out and
hit nothing but shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Bobby forced the hitters to adjust to hitting his hard and
softer pitches on both sides of the plate and then he started
mixing it up with his changeup and curveball.
</P>
<P>
   ``You saw a lot of funky swings on his curveball because he was
coming in with fastballs and sliders all day to those lefthanders
and then he'd break off that curve.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could throw any pitch on any count and get most of them over
for strikes,'' he said. ``It was my best stuff all season.''
</P>
<P>
   And it all started in the bullpen with a pat on the back instead
of a pep talk from his pitching coach.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-06-98 2003EDT &QL; 
