A7568 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-DEATH-PENALTY-NYT &LR;      06-06 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DEATH-PENALTY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK JURY SENTENCES FORMER GUARD TO DEATH FOR TRIPLE KILLING  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the first death penalty trial since New York state
reinstated capital punishment in 1995, a Brooklyn jury sentenced a
former jail guard to death on Saturday for murdering three people
in a robbery.
</P>
<P>
   The former guard, Darrel Harris _ who was given a medal by Mayor
Edward Koch in the 1980s for saving another correction officer's
life during an inmate riot at a Brooklyn jail _ was sentenced to
execution by a jury that rejected his past heroism and other
mitigating factors proposed by the defense as reason enough to
spare his life.
</P>
<P>
   When the sentence was announced in a somber session in state
Supreme Court in Brooklyn, more emotion came from the jury box than
from Harris or his relatives, who appeared to have been informed of
the jury's decision privately before it was announced in court.
</P>
<P>
   One juror began sobbing and nearly collapsed as she left the box
after the panel of seven women and five men was dismissed by Acting
Justice Anne Feldman, who thanked them for performing ``this very
difficult civic obligation.'' Another juror dabbed her eyes.
</P>
<P>
   The jury, which could have instead sentenced the 40-year-old
Harris to life in prison without the possibility of parole, also
rejected as mitigating factors a defense argument that serious
psychological problems and cocaine and alcohol abuse had not only
caused Harris to plunge from hero in 1986 to triple killer a decade
later, but had also fueled his murderous rampage itself.
</P>
<P>
   If Harris is executed by lethal injection, as prescribed under
the 1995 capital punishment law, he will be the first person put to
death in the state since 1963, when the death penalty was carried
out in the electric chair. But years of legal appeals are likely in
the effort to save Harris.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives of his victims, some of whom wept quietly as they left
the courtroom, expressed quiet gratification at what they deemed a
just penalty for the bloodletting at the illegal storefront social
club in Bedford-Stuyvesant, Brooklyn, in the early morning of Dec.
7, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   One of Harris' lawyers, Russell Neufeld, called the death
sentence ``a tragedy for the people of the state of New York and
for all the families involved.'' The victims' families, he said,
``feel this will ease the pain of the loss,'' but the sentence was
``not a solution.''
</P>
<P>
   But Brooklyn District Attorney Charles Hynes said that ``we must
remember that this trial was a search for the truth and an effort
to do justice in the memory'' of the victims.
</P>
<P>
   With no previous criminal record _ and, in fact, as a publicly
honored hero who saved a fellow correction officer from inmates who
were severely beating him in the 1986 jail riot _ Harris had shown
``there's some value in him,'' warranting life in prison, said one
of his lawyers, Colleen Brady, part of a team, with Neufeld and
Timothy Rountree from the Legal Aid Society's capital defense unit.
</P>
<P>
   According to testimony in the trial, Harris' murderous rampage
began when he pulled out a gun in the storefront social club, which
he had previously patronized, and ordered five people to get on the
floor.
</P>
<P>
   He shot three men in the head, two fatally: Michael Harris, 37,
who was not related to him, and Jerome Sims, 58, the manager of the
social club, called Club Happiness. Another shooting victim, Eddie
Brown, 50, survived. And when Harris ran out of bullets, he fatally
stabbed Evelyn Davis, 32, despite her cries to be spared because
``I have five babies,'' according to Brown and a second witness,
Newbry Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   The defense conceded that Harris was the killer, but disagreed
with the prosecution on what had driven him to commit the crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The defense insisted that there had been no robbery and that
rather than killing to eliminate witnesses, as the prosecution
contended, Harris had been a severely disturbed man who had
``snapped.'' A psychiatrist testified about severe childhood
beatings by Harris' mother and, in adulthood, about his job losses,
drug and alcohol abuse, and what he called the traumatic effects of
the 1986 jail disturbance in which Harris saved his colleague.
</P>
<P>
   The defense argued that although this action earned Harris a
medal from New York's mayor, the violence had also left him with
the kind of severe psychological and emotional problems diagnosed
in many war veterans as post-traumatic stress disorder. The city's
Correction Department forced Harris to resign in 1991 because of
his drug use. All this, the defense unsuccessfully argued,
justified a conviction for first-degree manslaughter, punishable by
up to 25 years in prison for each killing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
