<SLUG> BC-BBO-REDSOX-WAKEFIELD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAKEFIELD NOT AT LOSS FOR WORDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Over and over, questions about Boston's 1-0 loss to the New York
Mets Saturday were posed in different ways. But Tim Wakefield kept
repeating himself. It did little to soothe Wakefield's raw nerves
after the knuckleballer's masterful one-hit, one-walk,
three-strikeout performance over eight innings produced only his
third loss of the season.
</P>
<P>
   What made matters worse was that Wakefield (6-3) was charged
with a controversial balk in the sixth inning by home plate umpire
Terry Craft that allowed Brian McRae to score the only run.
</P>
<P>
   Boston hitters, meanwhile, struggled for eight innings against
Bobby Jones (5-3), eking out just three singles against the
righthander, including two in the first inning by leadoff man
Darren Lewis and designated hitter Reggie Jefferson.
</P>
<P>
   So, Tim, what about the balk?
</P>
<P>
   ``The balk shouldn't have mattered,'' he said. ``It shouldn't
have because one run shouldn't have beat us.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's all it took to ruin Wakefield's day.
</P>
<P>
   One hit. One balk. One run.
</P>
<P>
   It added up to one headache for Wakefield, who afterward seethed
over a number of aspects of the loss. First, there was the decision
by manager Jimy Williams to lift Wakefield for Tom Gordon in the
ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was I surprised?'' Wakefield said. ``Yeah, very. But he just
said that Flash needed the work. It's just the way it is. I don't
make the decisions for the club.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the balk. With McRae on third base looking like a
jackrabbit about to sprint for home, Craft said Wakefield balked on
his move toward the plate. But third base umpire Al Clark saw it
differently, saying Wakefield's foot had come off the rubber before
his motion. Craft prevailed, however, and McRae, who had reached on
a walk, stolen second, and advanced to third on a fielder's choice,
came trotting home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want him to steal home. I wanted to keep him honest
and keep him close,'' Wakefield said. ``But I got called for a
balk. I can't even remember having a balk called against me in my
career. If I did have one called against me, it was a long time
ago. But I didn't think one run was going to beat us.''
</P>
<P>
   Which raised another sore subject for Wakefield: Boston's
offensive offense. The Red Sox have been shut out in two of their
last four games. Wakefield couldn't hide his displeasure with the
lack of support, as he kept repeating, ``One run should not beat
this ball club.
</P>
<P>
   ``You throw a one-hitter through eight innings and you come off
the field with an L next to your name. It shouldn't happen. Not
when we're trying to win a championship here. One run shouldn't
beat this ball club, but it did, and it's really hard to swallow.
It really is.''
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield again was asked to expand on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't think one run should beat our ball club,'' he
repeated, ``but it did today, and I don't need to comment on it
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think we've got the offensive power and capability to
come back from one run. It's happened before, and that's what I'm
trying to say.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
