<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-06 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7573 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-BOXNOTES-RIDDICKB     06-06 2197
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXNOTES-RIDDICKBOWE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIGNS THERE BEFORE SAD DETOUR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; NEW YORK _ It is the latest verse of a sad song sung too often
in boxing, and today the melody plays for Riddick Bowe, a
heavyweight champion who always knew how to laugh until boxing made
him cry.
</P>
<P>
   The man who brought laughter back to the sport of tears learned
how far and how fast a champion can fall when he stood up in a
federal courtroom in Charlotte, N.C., Thursday _ barely a year
after leaving boxing behind _ and pleaded guilty to abducting his
estranged wife and five children at knifepoint, unable to do with
those charges what he had been trained to do all his life.
</P>
<P>
   Riddick Bowe, standing in confusion and shame, refused to fight
them.
</P>
<P>
   There was no use anymore and Bowe finally seemed to understand
that. It was knowledge that probably came too late to keep him out
of the same place that his old neighbor from Brownsville, N.Y.,
Mike Tyson, visited a few years back. Bowe is going to prison, it
seems, and while that was a predictable landing place for Tyson, it
was never where Bowe seemed headed.
</P>
<P>
   How did the young boy who used to rise late in the night and
walk to a small factory in Brownsville to meet his mother so she
would not have to walk home alone end up standing before a judge,
accused by his high school sweetheart, Judy Bowe, of carrying a
knife, handcuffs, pepper spray, and duct tape to her new home in
Cornelius, N.C., in February to try to drag his family back
together?
</P>
<P>
   In some demented way, it was typical Bowe, one of the very few
family men in a solitary sport. This was the same Bowe who wore
pictures of his wife and children on his boxing robes, the same
Bowe who talked incessantly to his wife on the phone each night
while held prisoner in the self-imposed exile of training camp.
</P>
<P>
   But something had gone wrong with this Bowe, a fact evident when
he arrived at the annual Boxing Writers Dinner in New York in
April. He came to praise his retiring trainer, old and wise Eddie
Futch.
</P>
<P>
   Bowe, Futch's last heavyweight champion, was to introduce the
trainer that night, but after listening to his slurred speech and
unfathom-able conversational meanderings at an earlier reception,
organizers changed the program. Some will say it was boxing that
silenced him that night, and they probably are correct.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of sad,'' said the man with whom Bowe fought a
stirring trilogy, present champion Evander Holyfield. Sad it was
that last night they sat together in New York, one talking, the
other mumbling back.
</P>
<P>
   ``His demeanor was quite different,'' Holyfield said. ``A guy as
young as him, you kind of wonder what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   If you have fought as long and as hard as Holyfield with no
apparent ill effects, perhaps you wonder. But for so many of us who
watched Bowe get hit in the head again and again by men like
Holyfield and Andrew Golota (who hit him not only high but also low
so often that he pushed Bowe into early retirement), you didn't
have to wonder.
</P>
<P>
   You know what happened to Riddick Bowe.
</P>
<P>
   Boxing happened to Riddick Bowe.
</P>
<P>
   The other way to put it is that Bowe's brain surrendered to his
obsession. It gave up boxing before he did, no longer able to take
the pain.
</P>
<P>
   Your brain was never meant to slam back and forth inside your
skull, although many fighters can take it for years without harm.
Bowe was clearly not among them, especially when he so often taxed
himself with tremendous weight gain followed by withering weight
loss that dried out his body and his soul. Finally one punch too
many dented his face and his brain surrendered, but who can know
which punch it was?
</P>
<P>
   Was it one of Holyfield's hateful shots, perhaps the one that
drove Bowe onto his back in their third fight? How could it be that
one, you say, if he got up the way he did, tottering but brave, to
finish Holyfield the very next round?
</P>
<P>
   Was it one of the ones Golota hit him with that didn't land
below boxing's demilitarized zone? Was it the low blows that twice
left Bowe writhing on the canvas in pain, a victor on his back
because his opponent had less self-control than he did, that did
the real damage?
</P>
<P>
   Or was it one no one will remember and few witnessed? Was it one
of the thousands that hit him during sparring sessions when only
Futch and a handful of hangers-on were there to see it, a lethal
punch left unrecorded by history?
</P>
<P>
   Who can know such things?
</P>
<P>
   All we knew is that Bowe was losing it day by day by day. You
knew it when he would rock back, just a bit off balance, when he
got up too quickly from a chair, his brain unable to readjust
itself quickly enough to keep him on balance. You knew but you kept
silent.
</P>
<P>
   You knew it the first time you talked to him by phone and felt
like you needed a translator to be sure what this funny, funny man
was really saying. You knew but you kept silent.
</P>
<P>
   You knew it when you finally found yourself needing the
translator even when you were face to face with him. You knew for
sure then, but you kept silent.
</P>
<P>
   That's what you do in boxing most of the time. You keep silent.
You let the tragedy play itself out and then you shake your head
and say, ``You kind of wonder what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   You say you wonder, but you know.
</P>
<P>
   You knew it when Golota hit Bowe with a jab and nearly knocked
him out in the first round of their second, terrible confrontation,
the one that ruined both of them for good.
</P>
<P>
   You knew it the day you read that a retired multimillionaire
with five kids named Riddick Bowe had decided to enter the Marine
Corps at an age when he needed special dispensation to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven days later you knew it again when you heard he was
quitting the Corps, drummed out by mutual agreement because he
didn't particularly want to get up early and he missed his family.
</P>
<P>
   You laughed at some of these things and winced at others, but
you kept silent because some people don't survive prizefighting,
and even though Bowe was clearly going to be one of them, he was a
fighter who had earned respect and privacy in his downfall and so
no one spoke about it until Bowe could barely speak himself.
</P>
<P>
   Then you read another headline that his wife of so many years
had accused him of trying to hit her and then you later read she'd
left the man she'd loved since they were kids and then you read
that he'd been arrested for attempted kidnapping in February, the
spiral speeding up with each headline, and you knew why.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the night in New York when you saw Bowe stumbling over
his words the way a drunk trips over a curb. That night two
journalists, professional acquaintances of Bowe and his family,
talked of what they'd seen and what they knew.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you talk to Bowe?'' one says to the other.
</P>
<P>
   A nod.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you gonna write?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothin'. There's nothing to say now.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing to say now about a kid from Brownsville who always
wanted to be Muhammad Ali and now, in his dotage, had become him.
</P>
<P>
   So there it is, and now there's nothing to do but feel a little
guilty because you knew what was coming, but in boxing, as in any
other sport, a guy is free to destroy his body if he wants. He
doesn't have to play. He doesn't have to fight. He doesn't have to
end up like Riddick Bowe, you tell yourself.
</P>
<P>
   That's the justification, and it's true, but when it happens, as
it has now to sad, solitary Riddick Bowe, there's only one thing
left to say about it and a lot of people on all sides of boxing
need to think about it.
</P>
<P>
   We all knew and nobody said a word.
</P>
<P>
   Riddick Bowe will likely live 18 months to two years in a
federal prison, wondering what happened to him.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of us will live a lot longer knowing we don't have to
wonder.
</P>
<P>
   We knew all along.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Don't want to say next weekend's fight between welterweight
champion  &UR; Oscar De La Hoya  &LR; and  &UR; Patrick Charpentier  &LR; is a
mismatch, but word is this is the first time in his career that
Charpentier has sparred in preparation for a match. His old trainer
supposedly was against it. Wonder how he feels about defense? ...
Because of the cancellation of the Holyfield- &UR; Henry Akinwande
 &LR; fight, HBO reportedly granted World Boxing Council champion
 &UR; Lennox Lewis  &LR; an extension on its June 6 deadline to sign a
six-fight, $30 million contract extension because the two sides
will once again try to make a deal for a unification fight in
September.  &UR; Jim Thomas &LR; , &UR;  &LR; Holyfield's lawyer, feels Lewis should
remain a free agent to make a Lewis-Holyfield fight more possible,
as does Showtime executive  &UR; Jay Larkin &LR; , &UR;  &LR; but  &UR; Seth Abraham  &LR; and
 &UR; Lou DiBella &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who run HBO Sports, counter that the deal does not
preclude Lewis from fighting Holyfield on Showtime if it outbids
HBO ... After a complaint from  &UR; Obed Sullivan &LR; , &UR;  &LR; undefeated
heavyweight prospect  &UR; Michael Grant  &LR; nearly had to fight last
weekend while wearing a new protective cup. Sullivan's aides
claimed Grant's gear was so large that it covered half his stomach,
and the New Jersey Athletic Commission agreed, but executive
director  &UR; Larry Hazzard  &LR; finally allowed Grant to wear it. By the
third round it was halfway to his chest, but it made no difference
in the end. Grant KO'd Sullivan in the ninth ... Rumor is Grant
could face former heavy-weight champion  &UR; Michael Moorer  &LR; in
September if anyone can get Moorer's weight down to the heavyweight
limit, which means down to something remotely healthy ...
Featherweight champion  &UR; Naseem Hamed  &LR; claims a sore hand will make
him unavailable for his July 18 fight vs.  &UR; Kennedy
McKinney &LR; , &UR;  &LR; although many in boxing doubt it. Regardless of the
reason, he's out and  &UR; Roy Jones Jr. &LR;  has volunteered to move his
August fight to fill the July date. HBO was hoping to match him
with  &UR; Reggie Johnson  &LR; but Johnson is out with a shoulder problem.
It now appears likely that Jones will end up with World Boxing
Association light heavyweight champion  &UR; Lou Del Valle &LR; , &UR;  &LR; whose
scheduled defense last night disappeared when Holyfield-Akinwande
was canceled ... Don't ask me why, but  &UR; Julio Cesar Chavez  &LR; plans
to train in New York for his June 25 tuneup fight at Foxwoods in
Connecticut ... Promoter  &UR; Bob Arum &LR;  claims ``everything is open
after Sept. 18,'' the night of Chavez's rematch with De La Hoya. He
claims that means they're ready to face  &UR; Felix Trinidad  &LR; or  &UR; Ike
Quartey &LR; . If so, it's because De La Hoya ordered it, not because
Arum is looking for a toughy fight for his meal ticket ... You've
got to hand it to  &UR; Carlos Palomino &LR; . The 48-year-old former
welterweight champion's odd comeback came to an end after five
fights last weekend when he lost a 10-round decision to 30-year-old
 &UR; Wilfredo Rivera &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who is 28-3-1 with his only losses to  &UR; Pernell
Whitaker  &LR; and De La Hoya. ``I gave it all I had,'' said Palomino,
who held the welterweight title from 1976-79. ``I will now
concentrate on my acting career.'' Good idea ... It was mistakenly
reported recently that Main Events' promotional contract with Lewis
had only one fight left to run on it. Fact is, only HBO's deal with
Lewis has one fight left. Main Events has a long-term deal to
promote him ... Lowell's  &UR; Mickey Ward  &LR; looks to play the spoiler
again tonight when he faces young, undefeated  &UR; Zab Judah  &LR; on ESPN2
from Miami. Judah has never lost a round on a judge's card since
turning pro in September 1996 and recently had a no-contest on his
record wiped out by a ruling from the Maryland State Athletic
Commission. Judah is 15-0 with 11 KOs.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   When Holyfield's trainer,  &UR; Don Turner &LR; , was asked Friday if he
would accept a replacement for Akinwande on short notice, he
replied, ``Can't nobody beat him, so what's the big deal? Styles
don't make no difference to Evander. We would take even Tyson again
if he's available.'' ... You may have not gotten to see Holyfield
defend his WBA title against Akinwande, but it seems you'll see him
in the next  &UR; Spike Lee &LR;  film. Holyfield attended a benefit for the
Hale House in New York and made the high bid of $8,000 for a
walk-on part ... Philadelphia fighters stick together.
International Boxing Federation middleweight champion  &UR; Bernard
Hopkins &LR;  has loaned his belt to former US Boxing Association
lightweight champion  &UR; Ivan Robinson &LR;  to gaze at as he prepares for
his June 27 bout with IBF lightweight champion  &UR; Shane Mosley &LR;  at
the Apollo at Temple University ... Arum is going ahead with a
specious libel suit against New York Daily News boxing writer
 &UR; Michael Katz &LR;  for an article critical of Arum's decision to try to
stage a fight between  &UR; Buster Douglas &LR;  and Chelsea's  &UR; John Ruiz  &LR; on
Yom Kippur. Katz's column was published in the International Boxing
Digest yet Arum has demanded a retraction in the Daily News, which
is ludicrous, and claims in his suit that the thrust of Katz's
article ``is that Mr. Arum lacks the integrity to be a fight
promoter.'' If Arum had any integrity, he wouldn't have filed such
a clearly frivolous suit apparently designed to harass and
intimidate one of his harshest critics into silence. If he had any
integrity, by the way, he also wouldn't be a boxing promoter.
</P>
</TEXT>
