<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-GALAXY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION HAVE THEIR HANDS FULL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WELLESLEY _ It's a matter of controlling the ball.
</P>
<P>
   That's something the Los Angeles Galaxy, as well as the
Revolution, like to do. Each wants to dictate the play, so putting
pressure on the ball was something the Revolution stressed in
practice this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing a much better job in being aggressive,'' said
Revolution coach Thomas Rongen before leaving with his team for Los
Angeles, where they play the Galaxy Sunday night. ``It's a team
that can hurt you in different ways, with the through ball, with
good speed up front, and we're going to try to take it away with a
sweeper, like we did against New York-New Jersey.''
</P>
<P>
   Easier said than done. The 11-2 Galaxy happen to be Major League
Soccer's best team, one equally strong on offense and defense.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Revolution are 4-7, with four consecutive losses.
</P>
<P>
   Each team is missing players who have World Cup duty. Forward
Joe-Max Moore and defender Mike Burns are away from the Revolution,
and midfielder Cobi Jones from the Galaxy.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy prefer to move the ball forward with short passes and
once in a while with the long ball. They rarely play the solo game,
preferring to attack with numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can do one of two things,'' Revolution midfielder Edwin
Gorter said. ``You can change your whole system, or you can play
your game, and we're going to do that. We can't chase, we have to
play with possession of the game. When we have the ball, we have to
play with it and not give it back every 15-20 seconds. That would
be very hard on us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy average nearly three goals a game and have the
league's best scorer in Welton, who was traded by the Revolution
for a first-round draft choice last season. A speedy player, he has
11 goals and 8 assists.
</P>
<P>
   Manny Motajo, a Galaxy player in 1996, may play his first game
for the Revolution Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they turn the ball over, they can't attack you, so if we
keep the ball and don't lose it going forward, we should do quite
well for ourselves,'' he said. ``If we can put pressure on them and
make them make mistakes, we'll be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have to match up with Welton man to man,'' said
Rongen, who will have David Nakhid in the middle of the defense.
``We're going to have to make more adjustments than Los Angeles on
the road and try to get a result, that's the bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   There's another new ingredient for the Galaxy in forward Carlos
Hermosillo, Mexico's all-time leading scorer, who, strangely, did
not make that country's World Cup team. He averaged two goals a
game last season for Cruz Azul, a team he's been with since 1991.
Hermosillo, 33, is expected to step in for Clint Mathis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hermosillo is a target player who is actually slow,'' Rongen
said. ``He's a power goal-scorer and he makes them a better team.''
</P>
<P>
   Revolution goalkeeper Ian Feuer, with a 1.90 goals-against
average, should be busy, considering that the Galaxy make good on
44 percent of their shots on net. They are coming off an 8-1 win at
Dallas Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect a little bit of work,'' Feuer said. ``If we can
contain them a bit and get our game going well, we'll be OK. It's a
question of who's going to be able to keep the ball most of the
night. Hopefully, we can pressure them into mistakes and go from
there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
