  (lh) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ITALY
</P>
<P>
   CUP RECORD: 35-14-11 in 13 appearances.
</P>
<P>
   BEST RESULT: Winners in 1934, 1938 and 1982. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PLAYER YOU PROBABLY KNOW: Roberto Baggio, the star striker who
missed the key penalty kick in the 1994 final against Brazil and
may only be a substitute. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PLAYERS YOU SHOULD KNOW: Strikers Alessandro Del Piero and
Christian Vieri, defensive midfielder Demetrio Albertini, left
fullback Paolo Maldini and right fullback Alessandro Nesta.
</P>
<P>
   PROJECTED FINISH: Semifinal. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COMMENT: Cesare Maldini, father of Paolo, took over as coach
after team failure in the 1996 European Championships. Del Piero,
one of the world's best, will help him get Italy into the final
four for the third consecutive time. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHILE
</P>
<P>
   CUP RECORD: 7-3-11 in six appearances. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BEST RESULT: Third in 1962. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PLAYER YOU MIGHT KNOW: Ivan Zamorano, a 31-year-old striker and
the most famous Chilean athlete until Marcelo Rios came of age. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PLAYER YOU SHOULD KNOW: Striker Marcelo Salas, a rising star who
already has signed for mega-lira with Lazio of Rome. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROJECTED FINISH: Second round. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COMMENT: With Zamorano and Salas, Chile has enough firepower to
finish second in a weak group. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AUSTRIA
</P>
<P>
   CUP RECORD: 12-2-12, in six appearances. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Best result: Third in 1954. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PLAYER YOU JUST MIGHT KNOW: Striker Anton ``Toni'' Polster, 34,
who is Austria's all-time leading scorer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PLAYERS YOU SHOULD KNOW: Sweeper Wolfgang Feiersinger and
attacking midfielder Andreas Herzog. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROJECTED FINISH: First round &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COMMENT: Austria's World Cup headquarters is in the wine country
of Bordeaux, but it won't be a very good year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CAMEROON
</P>
<P>
   CUP RECORD: 3-4-4, in three appearances &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BEST RESULT: Quarterfinals in 1990. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PLAYER YOU MIGHT KNOW: Roger Milla, who scored a goal at age 42
in the last World Cup finals but has finally retired. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PLAYERS YOU SHOULD KNOW: Central defender Rigobert Song, the
youngest player to compete in the last World Cup finals at 17, and
goalkeeper Jacques Songo'o. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROJECTED FINISH: First round. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COMMENT: Claude Le Roy is one of four French citizens coaching
African teams in this tournament. He has not had much time to work
miracles.
</P>
</TEXT>
