<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-METS-REDSOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE FALSE MOVE FOILS SOX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One balk call was worth a thousand words Saturday at Fenway
Park. It prompted strong opinions from the Mets and Red Sox. Lusty
echoes by a mixed bag of fans. And a final say by an umpiring crew
who stood by the call even though they seemed to disagree on what
had happened.
</P>
<P>
   When all was said and done, the Red Sox were stuck with a 1-0
loss to the visiting New Yorkers in a hard-fought contest that left
a sellout crowd of 32,545 buzzing long afterward. The victory went
to Bobby Jones (5-3), who outdueled Tim Wakefield (6-3) as they
each worked eight innings. The game was decided in the sixth inning
on a balk call against Wakefield that scored Brian McRae from third
base.
</P>
<P>
   There are 13 ways to balk and Wakefield, who gave up only one
hit, apparently found one of them. According to plate umpire Terry
Craft, who made the call, Wakefield started his motion and then
stepped off the rubber. As it turned out, it didn't matter that
third base umpire Al Clark thought Wakefield had stepped off first.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sucks,'' said an angry Wakefield. ``We're trying to win a
championship here. You hold a ball club to one hit in eight innings
and you walk off the field with a loss. It shouldn't happen like
that. One run shouldn't beat this ball club, and it did. It's hard
to swallow.''
</P>
<P>
   Craft said later that Wakefield had committed the balk long
before stepping off. In his view, the knuckleballer had halted his
windup, broken his hands, then backed off in an attempt to counter
the movement of McRae, who was dancing off third and indeed has the
speed to steal home.
</P>
<P>
   ``A pitcher has to step off the mound before he can move his
hands,'' said Craft. ``He moved his hands and then stepped off.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Who cares which one of us sees it?'' said Clark. ``We're not
out there vying for the call. We're out there to get as many things
correct as we can. Terry saw it. He's looking right at it and can
see his hands move a lot better than I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Funny how things work out. Coming off a 9-2 loss Friday to the
Mets (whose fans filled about half the seats at Fenway Saturday),
the Red Sox were praying for a strong pitching performance.
Wakefield gave them that, allowing only a single by third baseman
Edgardo Alfonzo in the second inning that had nothing to do with
the scoring.
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield walked only one _ but that was McRae leading off the
sixth. With Bernard Gilkey at bat, McRae took second on a delayed
steal. He reached third on a ground out by John Olerud, and the
two-out balk got him home and started the controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clark didn't call anything,'' said Red Sox manager Jimy
Williams. ``He thought Wakefield had stepped off. But the home
plate umpire said he broke his hands. Can they see both? I don't
know. Maybe you can with those friendly eyes always looking at each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield left after eight innings, tired and frustrated. The
Mets got another hit in the ninth off Tom Gordon but did not score.
</P>
<P>
   There will be days like this, said Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never waste a great pitching performance,'' said Williams,
``and that's what Wakefield gave us today. We might have gotten
beat, but credit the other guy, who just pitched better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still, it's just a shame to decide a game on a call like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield did not share the win-some-lose-some philosophy of his
manager. He was angry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen the replays, and truthfully I don't want to
watch it,'' he said. ``I don't know if that's the right call.
</P>
<P>
   ``You had one umpire that said it was, and another who said it
wasn't. It stinks. But stuff happens. I didn't want him to steal
home. I just wanted to keep him honest and keep him close. And I
got called for a balk.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
