<HEADLINE>
WORLD CUP TEAMS: GROUP C 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANCE
</P>
<P>
   CUP RECORD: 15-5-14 in nine appearances. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BEST RESULT: Third in 1958 and 1986. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PLAYER YOU MIGHT KNOW: Zinedine Zidane, playmaker for Juventus
in Italy who is widely considered to be the best creative
midfielder in the game. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PLAYERS YOU SHOULD KNOW: Defensive midfielder Didier Deschamps,
striker Youri Djorkaeff, right fullback Lilian Thuram and central
defender Marcel Desailly. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROJECTED FINISH: Quarterfinals. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COMMENT: Wonderful players, most of whom play in the best
foreign leagues, but pressure and the lack of a game-breaking
striker will conspire against the host country. First appearance in
finals since 1986 in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   DENMARK
</P>
<P>
   CUP RECORD: 3-0-1 in one appearance (1986). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BEST RESULT: Second round. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PLAYERS YOU MIGHT KNOW: Michael and Brian Laudrup, one of the
best brother combinations in the sport's history. The older
brother, Michael (34), is an attacking midfielder who will retire
after the Cup. Brian, a striker who will play for Chelsea in
England next season after playing for Glasgow Rangers in Scotland,
is 29. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PLAYER YOU SHOULD KNOW: Goalkeeper Peter Schmeichel of
Manchester United in England. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROJECTED FINISH: Second round. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COMMENT: Shaky in World Cup warm-up matches but enough
experience and talent to advance in a relatively weak group.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   CUP RECORD: First appearance in the finals. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PLAYER YOU MIGHT KNOW: Shaun Bartlett, the striker who played
for the MetroStars of Major League Soccer last season, but is not
necessarily the biggest man on campus at home. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PLAYERS YOU SHOULD KNOW: Striker Benedict ``Bennie'' McCarthy,
the star of the African Nation's Cup; central defender Mark Fish;
right fullback Willem Jackson. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROJECTED FINISH: First round. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COMMENT: Nelson Mandela's favorite team was a final in the
African Nation's Cup but internal dissension and lack of experience
will tell on a bigger stage. Philippe Troussier, 43, coached Ivory
Coast in the Nation's Cup final versus South Africa and earlier had
been the coach of Nigeria before joining South Africa in March.
</P>
<P>
   SAUDI ARABIA
</P>
<P>
   CUP RECORD: 2-0-2 in one appearance (1994). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BEST RESULT: Second round. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PLAYER YOU MIGHT KNOW: Attacking midfielder Saeed Owairan, who
scored the most spectacular goal of the last World Cup against
Belgium but later spent time in prison for breaking Koranic law. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PLAYERS YOU SHOULD KNOW: Goalkeeper Mohammed Daeya, attacking
midfielder Khalid Muwalid and striker Sami Jaber. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROJECTED FINISH: First round &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COMMENT: Carlos Alberto Parreira coached the MetroStars last
season and didn't qualify for the playoffs. The Saudis won't
either. Parreira, 54, like Bora Milutinovic, is coaching his fourth
national team (Kuwait, United Arab Emirates and Brazil were the
other three). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
