<HEADLINE>
WORLD CUP TEAMS: GROUP D 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPAIN
</P>
<P>
   CUP RECORD: 15-9-13, in nine appearances. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BEST RESULT: Fourth in 1950. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PLAYER YOU MIGHT KNOW: Goalkeeper Andoni Zubizarreta, a
36-year-old Basque who is playing in his fourth World Cup finals
and will retire when this one is over. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PLAYERS YOU SHOULD KNOW: Defensive midfielder Fernando Hierro,
attacking midfielders Luis Enrique and Raul and striker Fernando
Morientes.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROJECTED FINISH: Quarterfinalist. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COMMENT: Spain's coach, Javier Clemente, 48, is a fiery Basque
who once mooned photographers during a practice session but has now
acquired more gravitas. The country itself is one of the world's
most enthusiastic soccer nations, but its results in the World Cup
have not matched the passion. This team won't be better than Brazil
in the quarterfinals. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA
</P>
<P>
   CUP RECORD: 2-0-2, in one appearance in 1994. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BEST RESULT: Second round. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PLAYER YOU MIGHT KNOW: Striker Nwankwo Kanu, one of the stars of
the gold-medal winning Olympic team in Atlanta, who later underwent
heart surgery in the United States in order to avoid retirement.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PLAYERS YOU SHOULD KNOW: Strikers Daniel Amokachi and Daniel
Ikpeba, attacking midfielder Finidi George, defensive midfielder
Sunday Oliseh. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROJECTED FINISH: Second round. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COMMENT: Its stars are stars in the best European leagues, and
Coach Bora Milutinovic _ who coached the United States in 1994, was
fired by Mexico late last year and is now with his fourth Cup team
_ can work wonders. But poor organization and internal dissension
will undermine the Nigerians. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BULGARIA
</P>
<P>
   CUP RECORD: 3-7-13, in six appearances. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BEST RESULT: Fourth place in 1994. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PLAYER YOU MIGHT KNOW: Striker Hristo Stoitchkov, who led the
Bulgarians to the semifinals in 1994, working plenty of left-footed
magic. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PLAYERS YOU SHOULD KNOW: Attacking midfielder Krassimir Balakov,
strikers Luboslav Penev and Emil Kostadinov and right fullback
Radostin Kichichev. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROJECTED FINISH: First round. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COMMENT: Nine members of the team that reached the semifinals in
1994 are back, but these aging veterans seem to have trouble
getting along. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PARAGUAY
</P>
<P>
   CUP RECORD: 3-4-4, in four appearances. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BEST RESULT: Second round in 1986. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PLAYER YOU MIGHT KNOW: Volatile goalkeeper Jose Luis Chilavert,
who has earned a reputation for a volcanic temper and versatility.
With his free-kick ability, he could become the first goalkeeper to
score in the World Cup finals. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PLAYER YOU SHOULD KNOW: Attacking midfielder Roberto Acuna. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROJECTED FINISH: First round. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COMMENT: A surprising second behind Argentina in South American
qualifying, the Paraguayans will create fewer surprises in France.
</P>
</TEXT>
