<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-AUTONOTES-CARTIRL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPLITTING HEADACHES PERSIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The scene was Indianapolis Motor Speedway, home of the Greatest
Spectacle in Racing. Al Unser Jr. was sitting on the wall along pit
row, watching his cousin, Robby Unser, qualify during time trials
for the 82d Indianapolis 500.
</P>
<P>
   A two-time winner of the Indy 500, Al Jr. was rendered nothing
more than a spectator because of the nasty feud between
Championship Auto Racing Teams _ with which Unser is aligned as a
driver for Roger Penske _ and the Indy Racing League, founded by
Indianapolis Motor Speedway president Tony George.
</P>
<P>
   Ostensibly, Unser was at the Brickyard to lend his cousin
support, but it was clear how much he missed being in the race.
When George approached Unser, fans sitting in the stands spotted
them and weighed in with their opinion on the CART-IRL split,
chanting, ``Bring him back, Tony!''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone would love to see it happen. Everyone would love to see
CART and the IRL get together. Everyone, that is, except for CART
and the IRL.
</P>
<P>
   Three years into their rift, CART and the IRL appear to be
growing further apart. Each series has landed title sponsorship for
this season, FedEx signing on with CART and PepBoys with the IRL.
Each has attempted to establish its niche as an open-wheel racing
series, CART on a worldwide circuit of street and road courses, the
IRL on American ovals.
</P>
<P>
   But is there a chance that middle ground can be found at Indy?
It is unlikely, though parties on both sides have expressed concern
about Indy remaining a viable marketing vehicle for the sport.
Television ratings for both series have suffered, enabling NASCAR
to rise as the premier motor sports series.
</P>
<P>
   Last month's Indy 500 drew a 5.5 TV rating nationally; CART's
Motorola 300 at Madison, Ill., which ran the day before, opposite
Game 3 of the Bulls-Pacers NBA Eastern finals, drew a 1.5 rating.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been expressions on both sides they would like to
be here, and we would love to have them feel welcome here, and they
always have been,'' said George, who this year scrapped the
``25-8'' qualifying rule that provided guaranteed starting spots to
the Top 25 IRL drivers and scaled back preparations from a month to
a fortnight to make it more affordable for IRL teams to practice
and qualify at Indy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody tries to characterize this as the IRL keeping the
drivers away. The drivers really don't have a whole lot to say or
do about the situation. I'm sure they miss being here and some
probably don't know what it is like being here so they don't miss
it.''
</P>
<P>
   There remains a constituency of fans who would love nothing more
than to see the return of such CART drivers as Unser and Michael
Andretti. The problem now is that the IRL has implemented its new
chassis and engine formula, which means CART would have to play by
IRL rules at Indy, making it cost-prohibitive for any CART team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's practical,'' said Fred Treadway, an IRL
owner who fields cars for Arie Luyendyk. ``I think (Indy) already
is the Super Bowl for anybody who wants to come here.
Unfortunately, I can't beat anybody who doesn't show up here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there'll be a (CART-IRL) Super Bowl,'' he
continued, ``because if we're running this equipment, we're going
to have an advantage over them, because we'll have been able to
test it and run it and we'll have established relationships with
the engine and chassis manufacturers. So the people in CART or
anyone else coming into this race is going to have the same amount
of expenses, and it's real difficult to find sponsors to give you
enough money to run this one race.''
</P>
<P>
   And this leaves accomplished CART drivers such as Al Unser Jr.,
who will toe the line Sunday at the ITT Detroit Grand Prix, sitting
on the fence at Indy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there are a couple who very much want to come back,''
George said. ``And I hope they have the opportunity to come back,
because they would certainly be welcome.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   After finishing dead last at Indy,  &UR; Tony Stewart  &LR; gained a
measure of redemption by starting on the pole for last night's IRL
True Value 500K at Texas Motor Speedway. Stewart set a track record
during pole qualifications Friday with a lap of 224.448 miles per
hour around the 1.5-mile oval. ``Winning the pole makes us feel
like we're back on track,'' said Stewart, who was bumped from the
front row at Indy by Plano, Texas, native  &UR; Greg Ray  &LR; and then
surrendered the lead to Ray when his engine seized after 22 laps.
``Indy was Indy. That's behind us now and we're ready to look
forward.'' ...  &UR; A.J. Foyt  &LR; said the reason his driver,  &UR; Billy
Boat &LR; , &UR;  &LR; was knocked out of contention early in the Indy 500 was
that Boat's pole-winning car was sabotaged the night before the
race; it was discovered that LocTite, a gluelike substance, had
been poured over the engine. Just a thought, but did anyone check
Luyendyk for fingerprints? Luyendyk, you'll recall, got into a
Victory Lane brouhaha with Foyt last year at Texas Motor Speedway
after blustering into Boat's apparent victory celebration and
claiming he was the rightful winner. Luyendyk was later vindicated
when he was proven correct, but not before he was cuffed around by
Foyt ...  &UR; Davey Hamilton  &LR; once again was carrying the Reebok logo
on his IRL car in last night's race, and he will do so for the
remainder of the season. The Stoughton-based shoe company
originally signed on as sponsor for  &UR; Eliseo Salazar &LR; , &UR;  &LR; but when he
failed to qualify for the Indy 500, Reebok jumped aboard Hamilton's
ride with Neinhouse Motorsports for the race and extended the
sponsorship for the season ... Two-time defending NASCAR Winston
Cup champion  &UR; Jeff Gordon  &LR; won the pole for last night's NASCAR
Winston Cup race at Richmond, the Pontiac Excitement 400, by
setting a track record during qualifications Friday. Gordon broke
his own three-year-old track record at Richmond International
Raceway with a lap of 125.558 ... The Formula One series will make
its lone stop on the North American continent Sunday in Montreal,
where defending series champion and local favorite  &UR; Jacques
Villeneuve  &LR; hopes to acquit himself after last year's debacle.
Villeneuve spoiled a triumphant homecoming to Circuit Gilles
Villeneuve, the track named after his late father, when he crashed
on the second lap ... After winning the Icebreaker in April,  &UR; Mike
Stefanik  &LR; of Coventry, R.I., will go for his second victory of the
season at Thompson (Conn.) Speedway in Sunday's Shaw's 300
Featherlite Modified Series event.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
