<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-06 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7586 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-BELMONT-BAFFERT-B     06-06 1682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-BELMONT-BAFFERT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT RIGHT TIME FOR PEGRAM, BAFFERT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ELMONT, N.Y. _ By 3:15 p.m., when Mike Pegram was into his
fifth Bud Light and Bob Baffert had tapped his foot for the 1,000th
time, the owner and trainer of Real Quiet decided time was moving
too slowly, way too slowly, so they headed away from Real Quiet's
barn, walked across Hempstead Turnpike, and headed for a greasy
spoon diner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Burger and fries,'' wisecracked Baffert. ``Can you imagine the
guy in the diner thinking, `Hey, isn't that Real Quiet's trainer in
here ordering a burger and fries two hours before the race?' But it
was good ... and I finished all the fries, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Time passed, still so slowly. A few minutes before 5, just 45
minutes before the race, Baffert kept asking one and all, ``What
time is it?'' And, ``Anybody got the right time?''
</P>
<P>
   Now Baffert paused outside Real Quiet's barn and said, as he
said last year with Silver Charm, ``the whole experience has been
tremendous. It's great trying to be part of history.''
</P>
<P>
   And then it was 5, and Baffert walked from the barn, took a
right, then headed down into the tunnel that connects the
backstretch to the paddock behind the Belmont Park clubhouse. Real
Quiet was a good furlong behind Baffert and Pegram, and the two
seemed relieved that the time finally had come.
</P>
<P>
   ``Watch out for the horse (expletive),'' Baffert shouted to
Pegram as they avoided the manure there in the darkness of the
tunnel. And when the two emerged back into the light, Baffert began
scaling Real Quiet buttons into the throngs and Pregram stopped for
a fan begging for an autograph.
</P>
<P>
   In the paddock, Chris McCarron, the rider of Thomas Jo, shouted
good luck wishes to Baffert, who was scaling even more Real Quiet
buttons into the thousands in the paddock. Then Baffert gave his
final instructions to jockey Kent Desormeaux and headed up the
steps to the owner's box.
</P>
<P>
   But not before shouting some wisecracks at Gary Stevens, the
jockey aboard Victory Gallop, the one horse Baffert knew he had to
fear in this field of 13 in the Belmont. ``I heard him,'' said
Stevens, ``but I had my game face on and I didn't want him to know
that he could get to me, so I didn't say anything back.''
</P>
<P>
   This was New York, so sentimentality be damned and even if
Baffert was only moments from a Triple Crown, he noticed a band of
hecklers pounding a window that separated the stairs to the owner's
box from the masses. ``They were saying, `Bob, not today,' and I
thought I saw a sign that said that. Then my little 7-year-old son
said to me, `Dad, there's a guy there with a sign that says, `Not
today.'''
</P>
<P>
   Not today.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Baffert had been at the barn in the early morning and went back
to the Garden City Motel to change ... change? He emerged after
noon in his superstitious outfit, the ungodly combination of blue
blazer and green pants and colorful yellow tie that had been given
to him by Australians who had met Baffert in Dubai in March when
Baffert's Silver Charm won the Dubai World Cup. Baffert wore the
outfit in Louisville for the Kentucky Derby, then in Baltimore for
the Preakness, and now here again in New York for the Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   The same underwear, too?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well ... ''
</P>
<P>
   By mid-afternoon, Baffert had gone through his tales of the day
before, of how he had gone to Yankee Stadium Friday night for the
Yankees' game against Florida, of how he had bowed and prostrated
himself at the feet of New York manager Joe Torre, met Yankee
pitcher David Wells (``I asked him who he liked in the race,'' said
Baffert, ``and he told me `Hot Wells.' Figures.'') Then Baffert sat
outside Barn 9 with his brothers and waited and waited, his feet
tapping nervously.
</P>
<P>
   Pegram, meanwhile, was into his fourth beer of the day and
telling his tales, of how he hadn't worn a tie ``in the '90s,'' but
how he was faced with a quandary of all quandaries as he got ready
to gavel open the New York Stock Exchange on Wall Street Friday
morning. Gosh, said Pegram, ``I was really excited about doing that
... it meant a lot to me to open the Exchange, but the limo driver
was telling me I needed to wear a tie.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, said Pegram, ``I just followed the advice my daddy gave me
a long time ago ... `Never make a decision until you have to make
it' ... and my daddy, once again, was right. Nobody asked me to
wear a tie.''
</P>
<P>
   Pegram raised a leg up on the wood fence outside Real Quiet's
barn and talked of how unreal this whole experience had seemed to
him. A reporter mentioned that he had read somewhere that Pegram
had described it as ``an out-of-body experience'' and then Pegram
was asked if he ever had had such an out-of-body event.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many times you been married?'' came back the wisecrack
from the owner. Really, though, he went on, ``an out-of-body
experience is when you know it's happening but it's too good to be
happening to you. It's almost too good to be true. It's like I'm
standing over there watching me do this.''
</P>
<P>
   So much for philosophy. That's because Pegram had some 200 of
his nearest and dearest at the race ``and you know what I did? I
forgot the tickets to the owner's box. I was begging for the
tickets all week and I have 'em for 12 hours and then I lose 'em.
Thirty tickets and I lose 'em. Heck, it's only Belmont Day.''
</P>
<P>
   Worried? Pegram was asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heck, they can't keep me out of the winner's circle so how are
they going to keep us out of our box?'' replied the owner. ``I know
the number of the box ... this is New York, isn't it? You just just
march in, right?''
</P>
<P>
   Pegram had just moved to Seattle back in 1977 to begin amassing
his fortune with McDonald's franchises when Seattle Slew wowed the
racing world with his Triple Crown. ``It really hit me,'' he said.
``I had just moved to Seattle then and Seattle Slew's owners had
paid only $17,000 for him, just like we did, and now here I am. I
mean, the similarities between the two stories are just amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   It was about then, some two hours before the race, that Baffert
stopped tapping his feet enough to get up, move over to Pegram, jab
a phantom microphone under Pegram's chin and say, ``For a guy who
never would talk to the press this guy's come a long way. But thank
God he came around and talked because I ran out of things to say
two weeks ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert then left, walked back over to Real Quiet's barn and
pretended to vomit. Then the trainer sat down, the foot tapping
non-stop once again. Time was moving slowly.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The Belmont clubhouse can be seen from Barn 9, even if it is a
good 10-minute walk. There, the echoes of past greatness in Triple
Crowns watched with mixed feelings. Mrs. Patrice Wolfson, widow of
Louis Wolfson, whose Harbor View Farm owned Affirmed, noted that it
been such a glorious time in 1970s when first Secretariat, then
Seattle Slew, and finally her Affirmed won Triple Crowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the 1970s we were all spoiled,'' said Mrs. Wolfson. ``what
with Secretariat and then Seattle Slew and Affirmed. Maybe it might
be time for a different horse to win the Triple Crown.''
</P>
<P>
   And those who could read between lines and pauses might have
concluded that Mrs. Wolfson meant a lesser horse as much as a
different one.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Penny Chenery, the former Penny Tweedy, is associated with
Triple Crowns as much the memory of Secretariat itself, and she
watched Baffert and Pegram have such a good time leading up to the
race. If she could have done anything different in watching her
Secretariat stride to greatness, Chenery said, it would have been
to enjoy the experience more than she did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Racing people shouldn't be so stiff,'' said Chenery, who
herself was stiff 25 years ago. ``I wish I felt that freedom to
celebrate Secretariat's win. Instead, I felt so much pressure,
particularly at the Belmont.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing could please me more,'' said Chenery of the prospect
of the Triple Crown club having a new member. ``I knew there would
be other Triple Crown winners (after Secretariat's win in 1973),
but when it comes to records, I can get possessive.''
</P>
<P>
   Secretariat, of course, set track records at Churchill Downs,
Pimlico and Belmont in his sweep of the Triple Crown races, a stark
indicator of his greatness. And Saturday ...
</P>
<P>
   No worries for Chenery as the horses ran the Belmont in 2:29,
some five seconds slower than Secretariat's time.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   When Desormeaux moved on the turn, that undulating, gradual but
killing turn that penalizes anyone who wants to go three-wide in a
1 1/2-mile race, ``I thought I had it. For a minute there, I could
taste it.''
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet opened up 5 lengths on the field and seemed home, a
sure Triple Crown winner. Later, Desormeaux said he had moved too
soon, but who knew it then? Baffert watched Victory Gallop gallop
down Real Quiet's flank and mouthed, ``Go, go, go, GO! We got it?
We got it?''
</P>
<P>
   There was a question mark in Baffert's appeal, and long minutes
would pass before the picture worth $5 million would answer that
question. Real Quiet had lost the Belmont by a nose, Victory Gallop
catching him in the absolute final jump of a mile-and-a-half race.
</P>
<P>
   It was the most classic of races, one of indescribable
excitement, and once again it proved that all things in horse
racing must be earned. Baffert, though, kept being himself,
wisecracking to the end, just as he had last year when his Silver
Charm failed to win the Triple Crown by a neck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Real Quiet just ran out of gas,'' said Baffert. ``I'm getting
closer (to winning the Triple Crown). Last year we lost by a neck,
this year by a nose ... maybe next year we'll win by open
daylight.''
</P>
<P>
   And Elliot Walden, the trainer of Victory Gallop, said this when
asked if he had any empathy for Baffert, losing the Triple Crown in
consecutive years by the smallest of margins. ``No,'' said Walden,
``I have no empathy for Bob Baffert. It's not about beating Bob
Baffert.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a classic game, it's a cruel game, horse racing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
