<HEADLINE>
WORLD CUP TEAMS: GROUP E 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NETHERLANDS
</P>
<P>
   CUP RECORD: 11-6-8 in six appearances, 1934, 1938, 1974, 1978,
1990 and 1994. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BEST RESULT: Finalist in 1974 and 1978. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PLAYER YOU MIGHT KNOW: Dennis Bergkamp, blond and elegant
striker who hates to fly but helped Arsenal soar to the Premier
League and FA Cup titles this season. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PLAYERS YOU SHOULD KNOW: Goalkeeper Edwin van der Sar,
midfielder Clarence Seedorf, strikers Patrick Kluivert and Marc
Overmars and the de Boer twins, Frank and Ronald. Frank is a
central defender; Ronald an attacking midfielder.
</P>
<P>
   PROJECTED FINISH: Champion. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COMMENT: The Dutch have often generated huge expectations in the
World Cup and faltered. This team, which has generated fewer
expectations, will not. Coach Guus Hiddink has superb players on
every line and appears to have diffused some of the racial tension
that has caused problems in the past. The key is Bergkamp, who is
nursing a leg injury.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BELGIUM
</P>
<P>
   CUP RECORD: 9-4-16 in nine appearances, 1930, 1934, 1938, 1954,
1970, 1982, 1986, 1990 and 1994. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BEST RESULT: Fourth in 1986. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PLAYER YOU MIGHT KNOW: Midfielder Enzo Scifo, who has played in
three previous World Cups and nearly missed this one after a
dispute with his coach. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PLAYERS YOU SHOULD KNOW: Brazilian-born striker Luis Oliveira
and running mate Luc Nilis; attacking midfielder Marc Wilmots and
defensive midfielder Franky Van der Elst. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROJECTED FINISH: Second round. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COMMENT: The French like to tell Belgian jokes, but while the
French missed the last two World Cup finals, the Belgians are now
in their fifth straight. The bad news is that they are again in the
same group with the Dutch. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO
</P>
<P>
   CUP RECORD: 7-8-18 in 10 appearances, 1930, 1950, 1954, 1958,
1962, 1966, 1970, 1978, 1986 and 1994. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BEST RESULT: Quarterfinalist (as the host) in 1970 and 1986. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PLAYER YOU MIGHT KNOW: Goalkeeper Jorge Campos, who has brought
his technicolor jerseys and striker's instincts to the Major League
Soccer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PLAYERS YOU SHOULD KNOW: Strikers Luis Hernandez and Luis
Garcia, midfielders Alberto Garcia Aspe and Ramon Ramirez and right
fullback Duilio Davino. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROJECTED FINISH: First round. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COMMENT: Winners of the Gold Cup but losers in the World Cup
draw. This is a tough group _ tougher still for a North American
team playing in Europe, especially one with a coach, Manuel
Lapuente, who replaced Bora Milutinovic in last November.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH KOREA
</P>
<P>
   CUP RECORD: 0-3-8 in four appearances, 1954, 1986, 1990 and
1994. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BEST RESULT: First round. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PLAYER YOU MIGHT KNOW: None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PLAYERS YOU SHOULD KNOW: Goalkeeper Kim Byung Ji, sweeper Hong
Myung Bo and strikers Choi Yong Soo and Seo Jung Won. Seo, who is
under contract with Strasbourg in the French First Division, is the
only member of this team who plays outside South Korea or Japan. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROJECTED FINISH: First round. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COMMENT: South Korea has modernized its national team after
failing to win a game in four previous World Cups, but it will have
to wait until it shares home-field advantage in 2002 with Japan
before it can dream of the second round. Coach Cha Bum Kun was the
first Korean to play in Europe, spending a decade in the German
Bundeliga. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
