</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; CUP RECORD: 14-12-7, in eight appearances. &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; BEST RESULT: Semifinals in 1930 and 1962. &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; PLAYER YOU MIGHT KNOW: Dejan Savicevic, longtime attacking
midfielder and creative force for the Italian superclub AC Milan. &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; PLAYERS YOU SHOULD KNOW: Defensive midfielder Slavisa Jokanovic,
midfielders Vladimir Jugovic and Dragan Stojkovic and strikers Savo
Milosevic and Predrag Mijatovic.
 &UR;  &LR; PROJECTED FINISH: Second round. &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; COMMENT: The Yugoslavs missed the last World Cup because of the
U.N. boycott, but they appear intent on making up for lost matches.
They are one of the world's most talented teams, and they have a
coach, Slobodan Santrac, who scored 1,301 goals in 1,359 games as a
player and, thankfully, has never lost his love of offensive,
attractive soccer. &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   UNITED STATES
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; CUP RECORD: 4-9-1 in five appearances.
</P>
<P>
   BEST RESULT: Semifinalist in 1930. &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; PLAYER YOU PROBABLY KNOW Part-time musician Alexi Lalas, who is
not likely to play a major role in this Cup. &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; PLAYERS YOU SHOULD KNOW: Goalkeeper Kasey Keller, defenders Edwin
Pope and Thomas Dooley and midfielder Claudio Reyna. &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; PROJECTED FINISH: First round. &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; COMMENT: Having to share a group with Germany and Yugoslavia
leaves little room for overachievement. &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IRAN
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; CUP RECORD: 0-2-1, in one appearance in 1978. &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; BEST RESULT: First round. &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; PLAYER YOU MIGHT KNOW: Ali Daei, a fluid striker who plays in the
German Bundesliga. &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; PLAYERS YOU SHOULD KNOW: Goalkeeper Ahmad Reza Abedzadeh,
midfielder Mehdi Mahdavikia, attacking midfielder Karim Bagheri and
striker Khodadad Azizi. &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; PROJECTED FINISH: First round. &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; COMMENT: The Iranians have more gifted goal-scorers than the
Americans, but they lack the same rigor further back. If they do
beat the Americans in Lyons, they will consider their World Cup a
success.
</P>
