<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-06 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7589 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-BELMONT-VICTORY-B     06-06 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-BELMONT-VICTORY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL QUIET NOSED OUT BY VICTORY GALLOP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The critics who said that Real Quiet was unworthy of
a Triple Crown championship were right, but only by the length of
an equine's nostril. That was the margin by which Victory Gallop
denied Real Quiet's bid to become the 12th Triple Crown winner in
Saturday's 130th running of the Belmont Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   If Real Quiet's owner Mike Pegram, trainer Bob Baffert, and
jockey Kent Desormeaux, who collectively lost the $5 million Visa
Triple Crown bonus by a nose, were the three unluckiest men at
Belmont Park Saturday, the three luckiest were in the stewards'
stand. Real Quiet came out and bumped Victory Gallop twice, the
second time very soundly, and the stewards announced that they
would have disqualified Real Quiet had the bob of the head gone the
other way. That would have been quite a scene, taking down a 4-5
shot and depriving him of the Triple Crown before a crowd of
80,162, the second largest in the Belmont history. Disqualifying
Real Quiet would have been the correct call, but Belmont might not
be standing today if it had had to be made.
</P>
<P>
   Desormeaux made a move aboard Real Quiet, going to the front
from the outside with 5 furlongs to go in the 1 1/2-mile race. The
Kentucky Derby and Preakness winner moved clear entering the
stretch, opened a 4-length lead passing the eighth-pole, then began
to run out of gas. Meanwhile, Victory Gallop kicked in and came
storming down the middle of the track. The winner, who had run
second in both the Derby and Preakness, survived the bumping and
Real Quiet was beaten at the wire. Thomas Jo, a 28-1 shot ridden by
Chris McCarron, finished third. The race was run in 2:29.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very difficult to sit at the three-eighths pole and not
move, believe me,'' said Gary Stevens, who sat chilly on Victory
Gallop as Real Quiet moved away. ``But I gained so much confidence
riding him in the Preakness that I knew to wait. Real Quiet made an
explosive move but he was tiring coming to the eighth-pole. That's
when we made our move. I thought we'd get to him but he made strong
contact with me. I thought we would have won by a neck but he hit
us hard. It's fortunate that he got up and the stewards didn't have
to go through that decision.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Gary and I talked about tracking Real Quiet,'' said Elliot
Walden, who trains Victory Gallop for Prestonwood Farm. ``The idea
was to stalk him. He let our horse settle and that's because he
felt confident in him. The main thing was to let Real Quiet make
his move, weather the storm, and not go when he goes. We thought we
should stay cool, calm, and collected, and go after him late.''
</P>
<P>
   This was deja vu for Baffert, who lost the Triple Crown and the
$5 million bonus at the wire last year when Touch Gold, ridden by
McCarron, caught Silver Charm, who was ridden by Stevens, nearing
the wire to prevail by a half-length. ``You ran out of horse and
that's my fault,'' Baffert told Desormeaux at the postrace press
conference. ``I don't think so,'' Desormeaux responded. ``I don't
think he saw him coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``The momentum change was too drastic for Real Quiet,''
continued Desormeaux. ``I saw Victory Gallop coming and I tried to
show him to Real Quiet, but it didn't work out. I pulled his head
out a little too hard and he did come out and that's why the
inquiry was posted.
</P>
<P>
   ``To come so far, to get so close, and now it's all gone, it's a
tough pill to swallow. I thought we were in trouble at the
eighth-pole. I knew he was starting to slow down. He was lost on
the lead and I knew if someone aimed at him as a target they might
catch him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a bit premature when I moved. I wish I had it to do
over again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a hard race,'' said Baffert. ``He just got tired at the
end. It was a great run but it's a letdown. It looked like we had
it won.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of pressure on Kent. He thought he was home
free, and nobody's home free.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
