<HEADER>
A7591 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-NEWLEAGU     06-06 1968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-NEWLEAGUE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW LEAGUE PLAN NOT NEWS TO THEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Bob Caporale and Randy Vataha, who run Game Plan Inc. in
Boston, feel good about the new football league proposed by Ted
Turner. They think it validates many of the concepts on which they
based their own venture, the All-American Football League, which
was scheduled to open in the spring of 1999 but is on hold until
Turner and General Electric decide whether to go forward with their
alternative league, which has caused great intrigue around America.
</P>
<P>
   ``It validates all of our research,'' said Caporale, who knows
about alternative leagues from his experience with the New England
Tea Men and the Boston Breakers. ``There's a market there. No
question. The second thing it validates is the concept of single
entity (i.e. the league owning the teams). They've added a new
dimension if they go forward, in that they're making major changes
in the industry in the future in that this would be corporate
ownership of an entire league rather than corporate ownership of
individual teams.''
</P>
<P>
   The concepts that NBC and TNT are talking about are the very
ones that Caporale and Vataha have researched for a couple of
years. But a key difference is that Vataha and Caporale don't
believe they could succeed going head to head with the NFL in the
fall, which the new league intends to do.
</P>
<P>
   Why might it work for the Turner league?
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd have complete control over TV,'' said Vataha. ``They've
got NBC and TNT at night. They don't have to make a TV deal. They
can promote it. They have the marketing thump of Time-Warner. With
NBC and GE, you have a bottomless pit of resources. The biggest
part of a new league is controlling your expenses and having enough
resources to see it through.''
</P>
<P>
   Vataha and Caporale know the problems associated with getting a
TV deal, because it has been a major problem in the launching of
their own league.
</P>
<P>
   With TV taken care of, an obstacle could be securing stadiums.
Vataha and Caporale spent a significant amount of time trying to
secure venues; they were able to get stadiums for most of their
teams, but it wasn't easy. In fact, in Boston, where Turner would
like to market a team, the All-American League has been unable to
find a place to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll have to make decisions on their markets,'' said
Caporale. ``Some of the bigger markets have more than one facility,
but many don't. It's a little less of a problem in New York, and
probably not a problem in LA. In Chicago, there's Soldier Field,
and is there another field they go to there?''
</P>
<P>
   Both men agree that the most compelling issue is competing for
advertising dollars, viewership, and sponsorships. If it's in the
fall, the new league would go head to head not only with the NFL
but also with major college football.
</P>
<P>
   And it's not as simple as playing games at a different time or
on a different day of the week. Vataha says they couldn't pick
Friday because of high school football. They can't play Saturday
because of college football. Sunday and Monday nights are out
because of the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you did it on Wednesday or Thursday night, you couldn't get
the games on NBC because those time slots are too valuable,'' he
said. ``It would have to be on TNT. And if you're doing it on a
weeknight, you're defeating the purpose because a family going to
an NFL game on a weekend is probably paying $200 for tickets. With
kids going back to school, it would be hard to attract families to
attend games.''
</P>
<P>
   While there are compelling reasons for starting up a new league,
Vataha and Caporale figure Turner and NBC head Dick Ebersol will
soon find reasons for not going ahead, or will back off their
original plan to compete head to head.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been there with new leagues,'' said Vataha. ``You just
don't know. There's no guarantees on this thing. What it proves is
that there are some smart people at high levels who feel there is a
market for another professional football league. That's exactly
what our research showed.''
</P>
<P>
   Vataha said no one from Turner or NBC has contacted them
regarding their research. While they would like to see their own
league start up, they wouldn't mind being part of the Turner/NBC
venture if asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that people close to the scene there say it's 75-25
they'll go through with it, but I still think it's 50-50,'' said
Vataha. ``They know the compelling reasons for it, but now the
obstacles are beginning to come into place.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   In assessing players in his strength and conditioning program,
 &UR; Johnny Parker  &LR; was thrilled with linebackers  &UR; Ted Johnson  &LR; and
 &UR; Chris Slade &LR; , center  &UR; Dave Wohlabaugh &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and backup center/guard
 &UR; Heath Irwin &LR; . In addition, he cited great work by the sophomore
class of linemen:  &UR; Ed Ellis &LR; , &UR; Scott Rehberg &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and  &UR; Juan Porter &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Johnson and Slade should be no surprise. Johnson may be the best
middle linebacker in the game and should be in line for the next
 &UR; Willie McGinest &LR; -like contract (or the Patriots' front office
should have its collective head examined).
</P>
<P>
   All of these players participated in more than 80 percent of the
program, which to Parker is just about a guarantee that they will
stay strong and have an injury-free season.
</P>
<P>
   Technically, the program doesn't end until June 26, but players
usually scatter after minicamp. Parker wasn't pleased with the
commitment last year. How about this year?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been OK,'' he said. ``Nothing to get excited about. We
really won't know how successful it was until the players start
performing on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   According to some players, the program was grueling this year,
especially with the introduction of sandbag work, which is designed
to help players with shifting weight they'll encounter during
games.
</P>
<P>
   How did some other big names fare _ say,  &UR; Drew Bledsoe &LR; ?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not enough evidence for this jury to decide,'' said Parker,
who learned about quarterback conditioning from  &UR; Phil Simms &LR;  when
Parker worked for  &UR; Bill Parcells  &LR; with the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Simms taught me that the key for a quarterback is to keep his
entire body strong,'' said Parker. ``A quarterback uses more than
his arm. He's also subject to blind hits, which is a lot different
than the head-to-head contact linemen take.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker said  &UR; Terry Glenn &LR;  ``was severely restricted by his
(clavicle) injury. There's still enough time left for him to have a
productive offseason. The key is consistency, staying with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn left for three weeks on personal business, which set him
back, and also did not participate in the weekend minicamp.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Patriots running back coach  &UR; Kirby Wilson &LR;  inherited  &UR; Curtis
Martin  &LR; in his first year in the job last season, and now he may
have the toughest coaching job on the team: preparing someone to
replace Martin. He wouldn't be surprised if it turns out to be
 &UR; Robert Edwards &LR; . ``I think people are going to be surprised by
him,'' said Wilson. ``He's bigger than Curtis and he appears to be
a step faster. Of course, Curtis was an All-Pro and Robert has a
long way to go before he can be that.'' Wilson on  &UR; Sedrick
Shaw &LR; : &UR;  &LR; ``We saw how he improved during the course of last year
just in practice. That's what you ask for. So far he's been here
every day working out and he's been working hard with Coach Parker.
I can't wait to start working with him.'' Wilson also has two new
fullbacks to break in,  &UR; Tony Carter  &LR; and  &UR; Chris Floyd &LR; , replacing
 &UR; Sam Gash  &LR; and  &UR; Keith Byars &LR; . ``We've upgraded ourselves
tremendously from an athletic point of view,'' said Wilson.
``Obviously we've lost an attitude that Sam and Keith had, the
experience they had, the leadership they had. From what I've seen
of Chris, he's a good blocker and he can catch the ball. But we
won't know much until we see them in pads.'' ... Much of the
running game's success will depend on the offensive line. According
to line coach  &UR; Paul Boudreau &LR; , &UR;  &LR; even though millions have been
earmarked to a unit consisting of tackles  &UR; Bruce Armstrong  &LR; and
 &UR; Zefross Moss &LR; , &UR;  &LR; guards  &UR; Todd Rucci  &LR; and  &UR; Max Lane &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and center
 &UR; Dave Wohlabaugh &LR; , &UR;  &LR; ``I'm going to recommend the best people to
start. If we don't play the best people, regardless of how much
money they make, that's hurting our team.'' Boudreau thinks that
Rehberg, who has been moved to right guard, is ahead of  &UR; Damon
Denson  &LR; (left guard) and Ellis (right tackle). ``I'm pleased with
all three, really,'' said Boudreau. ``Scott picked things up faster
last year, Ed was from a smaller school (Buffalo) and his progress
is like night and day from last year. Damon comes from a big school
(Michigan) and he's played in a million big games. He's got a
guard's body, but this is only the third year he's played the
position because he used to be a defensive tackle.'' Rehberg has
been a workout monster and now has 340 pounds on his 6-foot-8-inch
frame. Ellis, at 6-6, 338, has turned much of his baby fat to
muscle. Denson, who has legs like tree trunks, needed to improve
his foot speed and has done so. He's the little guy in the group at
6-3, 315 ... The only Patriot rookie who is a consensus GTE
Academic All-American and an Associated Press and Walter Camp
All-American is none other than  &UR; Brian Lee &LR; , &UR;  &LR; an undrafted free
safety out of Wyoming. Though Lee was timed at only 4.6 in the 40,
he did win several high school sprint titles. By the way, the only
other academic and football All-American this year was  &UR; Peyton
Manning &LR; , &UR;  &LR; the No. 1 pick in the entire draft.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Parcells said he doesn't have any interest in  &UR; Dave Meggett
 &LR; ``at this time.'' The last three are the key words. Meggett may
not be ready until October anyway because of foot surgery. But he
may be the veteran sparkplug Parcells could use at midseason. ``I
have interest in him as a person,'' said Parcells ... Once again,
Parcells's strength and conditioning program was well-attended.
Most Jets players made their minimum 40 workout dates. One player
still lagging is  &UR; Keyshawn Johnson &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who is more than 10 short ...
Troubled running back  &UR; Lawrence Phillips  &LR; apparently is taking
football seriously again. His minicamp weight was 216 pounds, which
is down from 240 last season with the Dolphins ... One of the
clinchers in the reworking of  &UR; Chris Doleman's  &LR; contract with the
49ers was the team allowing him to skip minicamp ... Having already
tied up many of their key players for the long term, the Jaguars
did the same with receiver  &UR; Keenan McCardell  &LR; last week, inking him
to a four-year, $15.5 million deal ... Veteran receiver  &UR; Alvin
Harper  &LR; has been a no-show at the New Orleans minicamps, giving
rise to speculation that he may retire ... The Bears saved $2.3
million this year and $2.5 million next year by releasing middle
linebacker  &UR; Bryan Cox &LR; , &UR;  &LR; a smart choice for a team going nowhere.
Cox is drawing interest from the Raiders ... The Bengals are said
to be interested in  &UR; Vinny Testaverde &LR; , who was released by the
Ravens. With  &UR; Boomer Esiason  &LR; gone, the Bengals are counting on
 &UR; Jeff Blake  &LR; to get serious about quarterbacking again ...  &UR; Shawn
Lee &LR; , &UR;  &LR; a 10-year defensive tackle with the Chargers, is shopping
for a new home. He plans to visit the Bears ... The Raiders cut
loose Super Bowl XXX hero  &UR; Larry Brown &LR;  and veteran cornerback
 &UR; Terry McDaniel &LR; , who may be a candidate for the Patriots ...
Speedy recovery wishes to  &UR; Michael George &LR; , one of the good guy
agents, who is recovering from a heart attack. George represents
 &UR; Vincent Brisby &LR; , &UR; Troy Brown &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and  &UR; Ben Coates  &LR; on the Patriots
... Sure, the Hartford meeting may be another case of posturing by
Patriots owner  &UR; Bob Kraft &LR; , but at some point he may become serious
about moving the team there. And that point may not be far away.
</P>
</TEXT>
