<HEADLINE>
WORLD CUP TEAMS: GROUP H 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARGENTINA
</P>
<P>
   CUP RECORD: 26-17-9, in 11 appearances.
</P>
<P>
   BEST RESULT: Winner in 1978 and 1986. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PLAYER YOU MIGHT KNOW: Gabriela Batistuta, one of the world's
finest strikers who is known as Batigol but has often had more
success in his Italian club Fiorentina than with Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   PLAYERS YOU SHOULD KNOW: Defender Javier Zanetti, midfielders
Juan Sebastian Veron, Ariel Ortega and Diego Simone and striker
Claudio Lopez. One of Argentina's best, Fernando Redondo, refuses
to play for Coach Daniel Passarella, who once banned his players
from sporting long hair.
 &UR;  &LR; PROJECTED FINISH: Quarterfinals. &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; COMMENT: After beating Brazil in Rio de Janeiro this spring,
Argentina has become the darling of World Cup soothsayers. This one
says the Dutch will beat them in the quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; CROATIA
</P>
<P>
   CUP RECORD: First appearance in the finals. &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; PLAYER YOU MIGHT KNOW: Striker Davor Suker, 30, who is quite
capable of scoring spectacularly in France. &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; PLAYERS YOU SHOULD KNOW: Right fullback Slavan Bilic, midfielders
Robert Jarni, Zvonimir Boban, Robert Prosinecki and striker Goran
Vlaovic. &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; PROJECTED FINISH: Second round. &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; COMMENT: If star striker Alen Boksic were healthy, this
experienced team, with several stars who once played for
Yugoslavia, would be more dangerous. &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN
</P>
<P>
   CUP RECORD: First appearance in the finals. &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; PLAYER YOU MIGHT KNOW: Striker Kazuyosha Miura, the poster boy of
his nation's soccer craze in the mid-1990s. Unfortunately for
Miura, he was cut from the team at the last moment. &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; PLAYERS YOU SHOULD KNOW: Central defender Masami Ihara, defensive
midfielder Motohiro Yamaguchi, attacking midfielder Hidetoshi
Nakata and strikers Masashi Nakayama and Shoji Jo. &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; PROJECTED FINISH: First round &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; COMMENT: The Japanese have not won a friendly since March, and
their best chance for a victory here is against the Jamaicans. &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   JAMAICA
</P>
<P>
   CUP RECORD: No previous appearances. &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; PLAYER YOU MIGHT KNOW: Striker Deon Burton, son of a Jamaican
father and English mother, who bears a certain physical resemblance
to Ronaldo.
</P>
<P>
   PLAYERS YOU SHOULD KNOW: Goalkeeper Warren Barrett, left
fullback Ricardo Gardner, midfielders Steve Malcolm, Theodore
Whitmore and Peter Cargill. &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; PROJECTED FINISH: First round. &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; COMMENT: The Reggae Boyz have the most melodic nickname in France
and have played more preparatory matches than most teams, but there
is no substitute for Cup experience.
</P>
