A7593 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     06-06 1099
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COOKIE FINDS PURPOSE AS MAGIC'S WIFE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ They're calling it a debut. They're saying it's a
career move from out of the blue.
</P>
<P>
   Silly critics.
</P>
<P>
   Earletha ``Cookie'' Johnson knows her husband Earvin has been
setting the stage for ``The Magic Hour,'' the late-night talk show
he'll unveil Monday on Channel 11, for as long as she has known
him.
</P>
<P>
   Before pilot guest Mel Gibson, there was Cookie, who wasn't sure
what to expect when she first sat across from Johnson, not on some
elaborate set but at a no-frills restaurant in Lansing, Michigan,
in early 1978, midway through their freshman year at Michigan
State.
</P>
<P>
   They had met briefly at a party right before the Christmas break
but had exchanged so few words, Cookie was amused when Magic asked
her for her phone number at the end of the night and bemused when
he called her weeks later, on the very first day of the new school
term.
</P>
<P>
   Magic already was living up to his nickname on the basketball
court so Cookie half-expected to spend the evening listening to the
bluster of a big-headed jock. Either that or she worried it would
be one of those excruciating first dates, replete with stilted
conversation and awkward pauses.
</P>
<P>
   The night turned out to be a delight as the Magic mien made
Cookie forget her own shyness. By the time their meals arrived,
Earletha and Earvin were talking and laughing like long lost
friends.
</P>
<P>
   That's Magic's spell, his wife says. Give him five minutes and
he can put anybody at ease.
</P>
<P>
   She doesn't see what difference a few cameras and a studio
audience will make. If ever there was a man who can tune the world
in with his smile, she says, it's her husband, the legendary Lakers
point guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Earvin is so real, he's so comfortable,'' Cookie says. ``From
the very beginning, that's what I found so attractive about him.
I've never seen him try to impress anyone. He just goes about being
himself and (his sway over people) just kind of happens.''
</P>
<P>
   The same could be said of Cookie, who never crumbled when
Johnson fathered a son by someone else a couple of years into their
courtship. Or when he ended their first engagement by phone.
</P>
<P>
   Or when, a few months after they finally were married and only
two days after she discovered she was pregnant with their first
child, he broke the news to her that he had tested positive for the
virus that causes AIDS, an explicit admission of his sexual
wanderings.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout it all she stayed true to herself, her faith, and,
ultimately, her man, who, miracle of miracles, is staring hard at
another beginning instead of the beginning of the end that appeared
so near in the first week of the penultimate month of 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Cookie declares her husband ``cured'' inasmuch as Magic's blood
no longer shows any trace of the deadly virus that hastened his
initial retirement from the Lakers. She credits God, but the daily
medicine cocktails that Magic takes deserve at least an assist.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to make sense of it all now, Magic says, ``God needs a
messenger for HIV and AIDS and sex among young people and he knew I
would enjoy taking on that challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   But imagine being Cookie then, and waking up one glorious
November day to find out your life and that of your unborn child
could be in peril because of your husband's pursuit of carnal
pleasures. You'd need an oxygen tank and fins to plumb the depths
of betrayal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm no dummy,'' says Cookie, 39, who has tested negative for
the AIDS virus. ``I knew he was not a saint (though) I didn't know
to what extent (he was not).''
</P>
<P>
   In the days after Magic's announcement, Cookie was the saintly
one. She could have been forgiven any public displays of anger
toward Johnson yet it was her affection for him that she chose to
show the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it would have been different if we had been married a
long time,'' says Cookie, who had been wed to Johnson less than a
year when a routine physical for an insurance policy spun their
world off its axis. ``To me, our love was more important than the
past. There was no way I was going to leave him to deal with it by
himself.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't matter that he had left her five years earlier, if not
at the altar then on the way to the church.
</P>
<P>
   They had stayed together but lived apart in the early `80s, with
Johnson leaving school for the NBA after his sophomore year and
Cookie staying behind to pursue her degree and then a career as a
department store buyer.
</P>
<P>
   When their long-distance romance led to an engagement in 1986,
it was accorded the kind of headlines you'd expect when one of the
world's most eligible bachelors meets his match. Cookie, who was
working in Toledo, Ohio, at the time, had hand-picked her wedding
party, settled on a ceremony site and narrowed her search for a
dress when the call came from Magic in L.A.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't ready to commit. The wedding was off.
</P>
<P>
   Cookie was crushed. ``Total devastation,'' she remembers
feeling. ``Total embarrassment.''
</P>
<P>
   Hadn't she pursued her own career so her life couldn't be
capsized by a man?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's it,'' Cookie told Magic once she had freed herself from
the sadness pulling her down and fought her way to the surface for
air. ``I can't do this anymore. I'm going to go on with my life.''
</P>
<P>
   And then she did. For more than a year, they exchanged no phone
calls, no letters, nothing. Magic was the one who finally re-opened
the lines of communication and even then it took another year
before Cookie felt she could trust him with her heart.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, she moved out to L.A., but to her own place. It would
take another two years and a temblor that rocked her world for her
to find her niche, away from the Hollywood galas and Showtime's
glare.
</P>
<P>
   Determined to make the best of a bad situation, Magic and Cookie
in 1991 established the Magic Johnson Foundation, which raises
money for, and awareness of, AIDS-related matters, especially where
they concern disenfranchised children.
</P>
<P>
   Cookie, who nearly fainted from nerves the first time she had to
give a speech on behalf of the Foundation, now feels almost as
comfortable talking to people as her husband. She especially enjoys
interacting with children, starting with her own.
</P>
<P>
   Six-year-old E.J., who is HIV-free, and 3-year-old Elisa, whom
the Johnsons adopted when she was three days old, give Cookie joy.
Her life as Magic's wife gives her purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very secure,'' she says, ``I'm a lot more tuned in to
me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
