<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-JAZZ-BULLS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALONE MUST ARRIVE AND DELIVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ Karl Malone knows what people are thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Two games have been played in the NBA Finals and we're still
waiting for the Mailman's A game. Or his B Game. Or his C game.
</P>
<P>
   He conceded Saturday that his two-game performance _ 14 for 41,
more turnovers (6) than jump shots made (3), and only 13 free throw
attempts _ rated a pretty low grade.
</P>
<P>
   ``D minus,'' he said. ``That's an F in some schools.''
</P>
<P>
   It certainly is in the school of public opinion and in Malone's
grading system. He insisted after Utah's 93-88 loss in Game 2 that
the Jazz will not win the series if he doesn't improve. He said he
couldn't remember the last time he played three subpar games ``by
my standards.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming off an uneven performance in last year's championship
series, the Mailman understands he'll be viewed as someone who
doesn't deliver in the Big One unless things change. He insisted
after Saturday's brief workout at Westminster College that he is
unfazed by any criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't have gotten into this profession or stayed in this
profession if I couldn't take criticism,'' he said. ``That's part
of growing up. That's part of the business. You understand that
there are not always going to be good things said about you.''
</P>
<P>
   He was the only player on the Jazz who stayed around to field
queries Saturday. He said he had no plans to change the way he
plays. He did vow not to rush it, which is what he said he did last
year in the Finals.
</P>
<P>
   He was 9 of 25 in the first game, an 88-85 Utah win in overtime.
He made only two jump shots. Game 2 was worse. He went without a
basket in the second half (0 for 4) and made only 5 of 16 shots
overall, including a single spot-up perimeter shot.
</P>
<P>
   In neither game did he lead the Jazz in scoring, a rarity. The
last time Malone did not lead the Jazz in scoring for two straight
playoff games was 1987, in Games 2 (Darrell Griffith) and 3 (Kelly
Tripucka) of the first-round series against Golden State. Utah had
played 124 playoff games before Malone ceded the scoring lead to
John Stockton (Game 1) and Jeff Hornacek (Game 2) in this year's
Finals.
</P>
<P>
   He's clearly struggling with his shot, because all of his 41
attempts have been consistent with the Jazz offensive system. He
said he will continue to keep shooting if the shots are there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to get passive,'' he said. ``But I also don't
think I'm playing relaxed. I have to guard against not trying to do
it all myself. I have to be patient.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what it is,'' he continued, referring to the pressure.
``We played all those other (playoff) games just to get back here.
I know what's at stake. I want to win so bad. But I'm not going to
put any more pressure on myself. I have a hell of a lot already.
All I know is I'll be ready.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufdots &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz watched film for about 40 minutes and then did some
light shooting. Utah coach Jerry Sloan snapped at the reporters
standing outside the coach's office, where the team was meeting.
``It's good you guys got some of it too,'' Malone said, referring
to Sloan's anger. ``He was short with us, too. Then again, we gave
him no reason to be long.'' ... One thing to bear in mind: Since
the 2-3-2 format was introduced in 1985, the home team has never
won all three middle games. The visiting team, however, has twice
swept Games 3-5, in 1990 (Detroit at Portland) and in 1991 (Chicago
at Los Angeles) ... Sloan said he was much more concerned with
``the little things'' than Malone's errant shooting. He cited
Utah's turnovers (20, leading to 33 Chicago points) and the Bulls'
success on the offensive boards (18 rebounds leading to 19
second-chance points) as the two key reasons his team lost Game 2.
He also was unhappy with the team's passivity. ``I just don't think
we came to play basketball in our own building, and that was
shocking to me,'' Sloan said. ``I was upset. But you can't make
them do something they don't want to do. Or at least I can't. Maybe
someone else can.'' ... On the critical play _ Steve Kerr
rebounding his own miss and feeding Michael Jordan for a 3-point
play, Sloan said, ``You look at the film and our guys were just
floating back on defense, like it was a pickup game. It was like,
who cares? How can you walk back up the floor on a play like that?
I told the guys it was like we were all wearing tuxedos out there.
We didn't want to be touched.'' ... Malone was asked for a reaction
to Dennis Rodman's comment that he, Rodman, could guard Malone
``any day of the week'' if the referees let them play. ``Please,''
Malone said with disgust. ``Next question.'' ... The Jazz led the
league in free throw attempts during the season, almost 25 a game.
In the first two Finals games, they've averaged 13.5.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
