<HEADER>
A7598 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-ISLANDER     06-06 2153
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-ISLANDERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISLANDERS FEAR BEING STRANDED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; It would have cost the Islanders a minimum of about $1.5
million to learn whether J.P. Dumont had NHL skill and toughness.
For that kind of money, Gordie Clark didn't think the risk was
worth it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all changed so much, because of the money,'' said Clark,
the former Bruins assistant coach who is now the Islanders'
assistant general manager with an emphasis on player scouting and
development. ``In the old days, you signed your top pick for
$100,000 or $200,000 and said, `What the heck? If it works out, it
works out.' And if it didn't, so what? But, when you're putting out
$1.2 million for just a signing bonus, you want to know it will
work out _ you want to know he'll eventually play in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, the Islanders dished Dumont to the Blackhawks
last weekend, giving up on the forward who this season broke Mario
Lemieux's Quebec League postseason goal-scoring record by potting
31 in the playoffs. In return, the Islanders picked up center
Dmitri Nabokov, a first-round pick (No. 19 overall) in the '95
draft, whom Clark projects as a second-line center. Had the
Islanders not made a deal, and left Dumont unsigned, he would have
been placed back in the amateur draft this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know one thing,'' said Clark. ``I probably shouldn't go to
Quebec in the near future.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark decided that Dumont didn't have the speed or grit that it
takes to play in the NHL. In the two years that he watched him,
Clark didn't see Dumont beat anyone to the outside with speed. He
didn't see him battle for the puck. He saw a kid with some raw
offensive talent, with some genuine upside in scoring, but without
enough fire to battle his way to the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything, say, 10 or 15 feet out, he'd put it in the net,''
said Clark. ``And that's great, if a player can plant himself there
and make those shots. But that's not how the game's played. First
of all, you have to skate to get to the front of the net, and then
you have to have the courage to get there and stay there. I didn't
see it.''
</P>
<P>
   In one brief stretch with the goal-deficient Blackhawks last
season, Nabokov potted five goals in five games. He finished with
seven in about one-third of a season's work. The Islanders don't
figure he'll be a sniper, but he could add 50 or 60 points to their
roster, and that's a far safer and better gamble than laying out
$1.5 million for someone who never wears your uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm wrong, it will be worse than kicking myself in the rear
end,'' said Clark, who was directing the Bruins' draft when they
made Kyle McLaren the No. 9 pick in '95. ``I'll be fired.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Before naming  &UR; Bob Hartley  &LR; as  &UR; Marc Crawford's  &LR; successor
behind the bench, the Avalanche were considering the likes of  &UR; Ted
Nolan &LR; , &UR; Bryan Trottier &LR; , &UR; Jacques Lemaire &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and the  &UR; Dave
Lewis &LR; - &UR; Barry Smith  &LR; 1-2 punch from the Wings. In the end, they
went with Hartley, their coach in Hershey (AHL). Just wondering:
Has anyone been considered for more jobs, only to be left unhired,
than Nolan? He was named Coach of the Year last June just prior to
being fired by the Sabres. A year later, he can't buy a job?
Something just doesn't add up. Nolan recently talked to the Toronto
Star about the perception that he is a ``GM killer'': ``I had
nothing to do with ( &UR; John &LR; ) &UR; Muckler  &LR; getting fired (in Buffalo). I
was a second-year coach _ where would I get that kind of power? But
I keep reading and hearing that. `GM killer.' That's been the
hardest thing to swallow. It hurts, a lot.'' ... Trivia
answer-to-be:  &UR; Marian Cisar &LR; . The 20-year-old Slovak was traded
from Los Angeles to Nashville last week, thus becoming the first
player in Predator history ... Orca Bay Sports and Entertainment,
owner of the Canucks, the Grizzlies, and GM Place in Vancouver,
reports that its hockey team lost a whopping $30 million (Canadian
funds) in 1997-98 (upwards of one-third of that is  &UR; Mark Messier's
 &LR; salary). Beyond that, the Grizzlies lost a little and The Garage
made a little. And beyond that, life goes on for Orca gazillionaire
 &UR; John McCaw &LR; , &UR;  &LR; whose pockets run deeper than the deep blue Pacific
... Former Bruin defenseman  &UR; Glen Wesley &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who would have become a
Group 2 (high compensation) free agent July 1, now will make $12.5
million over the next five years after re-signing with the
Hurricanes. Wesley is still only 29 years old and wouldn't have
become an unrestricted free agent until the summer of 2000. He
might have cashed in much bigger two years from now, but the
guaranteed revenue stream through the spring of '03 _ when he'll be
34 _ made the deal worth taking ... Following his soft performance
in Game 4 of the Eastern finals, Buffalo netminder  &UR; Dominik Hasek
 &LR; slapped a ``Kramer'' sign on his helmet prior to practice the next
day. The joke: Buffalo teammates slapped the ``Kramer'' nickname on
Hasek two years ago, noting how he resembled the character in
``Seinfeld.'' But Hasek didn't think it was so funny originally.
When then-rookie  &UR; Brian Holzinger  &LR; asked him about it during a team
photo shoot, Hasek said little, and was next seen flushing
Holzinger's suit pants down the toilet (we are not making this up).
``That's Dominik,'' said former Bruin defenseman  &UR; Garry
Galley &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who then was one of Hasek's teammates. ``He could snap
just like that. You just never knew.'' The silver lining in the
soggy suit story? ``It was just one of my cheap college suits,''
said the speedy Holzinger, who then was only months removed from
the Bowling Green campus ... According to Canucks play-by-play man
 &UR; Jim Hughson &LR; , &UR;  &LR; coach  &UR; Mike Keenan  &LR; has veto power in regard to the
next general manager. But  &UR; Stephen Bellringer &LR; , &UR;  &LR; president and CEO
of Orca Bay Sports, says such a clause does not exist in Keenan's
three-year contract ... Word around Exit 16W in New Jersey is that
 &UR; Cap Raeder &LR; , &UR;  &LR; the former Boston assistant, is too entrenched in
his new career _ scouting for the Sharks and commentating on
college hockey _ to get back behind a bench with  &UR; Robbie
Ftorek &LR; , &UR;  &LR; his old pal from Needham who recently was named the
Devils' head coach. Ftorek will have to look elsewhere for a top
aide.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Provided  &UR; Art Williams  &LR; is ratified as the Lightning's new owner
(an empty-netter) later this month, he plans to go ahead next
season with one significant management change: GM  &UR; Phil Esposito
 &LR; and head coach  &UR; Jacques Demers &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who recently picked up the title
of director of player personnel, will have equal say in roster
makeup and all related player decisions. A two-headed management
team. Always dicey. Word around the Bolts is that Williams has
become an instant Demers booster, and in a year Demers could be
left running the whole show, with Esposito left without a job ...
Tampa Bay forward  &UR; John Cullen &LR; , &UR;  &LR; recovering from non-Hodgkin's
lymphoma, will join the club for training camp in Austria this
fall, but without a contract. If he remains healthy and can play at
an NHL pace, he'll be signed to a new deal. If his playing days are
over, the former Boston University star will remain with the club
in a front-office capacity ... The oft-injured  &UR; Petr Svoboda
 &LR; recently underwent surgery on his neck, giving him some relief
around a nerve that was irritated as a result of his violent
collision with Buffalo's  &UR; Dixon Ward  &LR; in the opening round of the
playoffs. The night he was hit, Svoboda initially thought he was
paralyzed, but most of the effects of the ``stinger'' soon
diminished ... Ex-Bruins coach  &UR; Rick Bowness &LR; , &UR;  &LR; dismissed from
behind the Islanders bench late last season, is rumored to be
heading to Montreal to join  &UR; Alain Vigneault's  &LR; staff. At the
moment, there is no opening on the Habs' staff, but assistant coach
 &UR; Dave King  &LR; is on the short list of candidates to take over as
Florida's head coach. When Bowness was the Senators' head coach, he
hired Vigneault as an assistant ... Former Bruin  &UR; Sheldon Kennedy
 &LR; began a cross-Canada trek on in-line skates last Saturday, shoving
off from St John's, Newfoundland. His itinerary has him covering
the 5,000 miles to Vancouver in 136 days, about 37 miles a day, in
the hopes of increasing awareness about child abuse. While with the
Bruins in the '96-97 season, Kennedy told a Canadian court that he
was sexually abused hundreds of times as a teenager, all at the
hand of his former junior coach,  &UR; Graham James &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who is serving 3
1/2 years in a Manitoba prison ... By early last week, the Oilers
had sold 13,121 season tickets for next season, triggering a $4
million (Canadian funds) subsidy from the NHL that is earmarked for
small-market Canadian teams ... If  &UR; Doug Gilmour  &LR; gets a serious
look in free agency, it likely will come from the South, either
Tampa Bay or Carolina. Both clubs are desperate for pivots. The
question is: Will either want to meet his $5 million-per-year
asking price? ... Trottier's hiring as Hartley's assistant in
Denver leaves the Portland Pirates without a head coach for the
second time in as many years. It was about this time last year that
Nashville hired away both  &UR; Barry Trotts  &LR; and  &UR; Paul
Gardner &LR; , &UR;  &LR; opening the way for Trottier. Now it's up to Washington
GM  &UR; George McPhee  &LR; to fill the job in Portland, the Capitals' top
minor league affiliate.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Oiler boss  &UR; Glen Sather  &LR; met twice last week with Edmonton's new
ownership group, and by Friday night the former Bruins spare
forward had yet to announce whether he'll stay on as the club's
boss. Complicating the picture: The Canucks were given permission
by the Oilers' new owners to approach Sather about their GM
opening. No one expects Sather to go anywhere, and he likely will
be enticed to stay by being offered an equity position in the
Oilers. If that's the case, the Vancouver job likely would be
offered to NHL VP  &UR; Brian Burke  &LR; (the former assistant GM in
Vancouver) or ex-Boston forward  &UR; Mike Gillis &LR; , &UR;  &LR; now an agent who
represents, among others, Canucks star  &UR; Pavel Bure &LR; . Keep in mind:
Sather is essentially an unrestricted free agent, with untold
leverage handed him by the Vancouver courting. One insider suggests
that his compensation now approaches $2 million a year. He could at
least double that with his new deal, putting him in a position not
unlike that of Oiler goalie  &UR; Curtis Joseph &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who is free to walk
July 1 and likely will command upwards of $7 million a year (a
boost from $2.3 million). Joseph will be using Hasek's new deal as
a bargaining benchmark. Hasek will earn $8 million next season, and
an average of $7.25 million the following two seasons. If the
Sabres so desire, they can retain him for the 2001-02 season at $9
million ...  &UR; Don Sweeney  &LR; will return to Massachusetts General
Hospital this week for another shoulder operation, according to his
agent,  &UR; Mark Witkin &LR; . A small metal plate will be placed over the
crack in Sweeney's shoulder blade, a decision that was made, said
Witkin, after doctors took another look at a recent MRI and weren't
comfortable with how the fracture was healing. Sweeney should be
ready for September training camp ... According to Bruins assistant
GM  &UR; Mike O'Connell &LR; , &UR;  &LR; any player on the Boston roster when the
season ended who is now due to become a free agent July 1 will be
offered a new contract. ``Everyone will be qualified,'' said
O'Connell, making reference to some players who must be offered at
least a 10 percent raise over last season in order for the Bruins
to retain their rights (example:  &UR; Landon Wilson &LR; ) ... Camp Black
'n' Gold, the commune-like voluntary summer camp the Bruins held
last year for their young prospects, will not be in operation this
summer. ``We did it last year because we had so many new faces
coming in,'' said O'Connell. ``It's something we might do again,
but we didn't think there was enough demand to merit it this
summer.'' ... If the Sharks want to pay him,  &UR; Al Iafrate  &LR; has a
deal in place worth $1.85 million for next year. But a bad knee and
painful back again kept The Planet out most of 1997-98, and it's
more likely the Sharks will cut him free, possibly with an eye on
signing him at a much cheaper price, with pay boosts triggered by
the number of games he plays. And of course there is always
Nashville, where Iafrate would be reunited with GM  &UR; David
Poile &LR; , &UR;  &LR; his former boss in Washington ... The Sharks say they'd be
happy to deal their No. 2 pick in the draft, provided someone wants
to send them a core player in his mid or late 20s. Keep in mind:
The Sharks were in the  &UR; Trevor Linden  &LR; hunt before the Canucks
dealt him to the Islanders. He's the kind of player the Sharks
would like to get for the the No. 2 pick. Any chances the Islanders
would dish Linden? ``There's nothing to talk about there,'' said
Clark. ``Trevor brings so much to our team, with his presence on
the ice, and his presence the room.''
</P>
