<HEADER>
A7599 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-OLYNOTES-AMATEURS     06-06 1145
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-OLYNOTES-AMATEURS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME TO REWRITE RULES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Because the Olympic world has changed dramatically since the
Amateur Sports Act was passed 20 years ago (the word ``amateur'' no
longer appears in the International Olympic Committee charter),
Congress soon will be looking at an update. Among other things, the
new Olympic and Amateur Sports Act will strengthen athletes' rights
and give the US Olympic Committee more power to quickly resolve
disputes over team selection (e.g. the Tonya Harding affair). The
amended act would also allow the USOC to send less than a full
Olympic squad if certain athletes don't meet the standard.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Major changes for figure skating will be on the table at next
week's congress in Stockholm. Besides video replay to help judges,
the International Skating Union is also expected to approve a new
placement system (to eliminate the ``wrong'' skater winning by
mathematical fluke) and a new format for ice dancing ...
Splitsville for  &UR; Kyoko Ina  &LR; and  &UR; Jason Dungjen &LR; , &UR;  &LR; the top US
skating pair at Olympus. Ina has hooked up with  &UR; John
Zimmerman &LR; , &UR;  &LR; a former world teamer with  &UR; Stephanie Stiegler &LR; .
They'll be logging lots of frequent-flyer miles, though. Ina trains
in New York, Zimmerman in California ... Predictable, if
disappointing, showing by the rebuilding US women's field hockey
team, which finished eighth last week at the quadrennial World Cup
after winning the bronze medal last time. The Americans, who won
two of seven matches, will now have to qualify for the next Cup.
They can still make it to the 2000 Olympics, though, by winning
next summer's Pan American Games in Winnipeg. As expected, Olympic
champion Australia won the Cup, followed by the Netherlands and
Germany ... No, field hockey isn't in danger of being dropped from
the Olympic program; in fact, the women's field will expand to 12
by 2004. But IOC president  &UR; Juan Antonio Samaranch  &LR; wants the sport
to become more attractive to watch. ``Consider changing some more
rules,'' he urges ... It appears US single sculler  &UR; Jamie Koven's
 &LR; stunning world title last year was no fluke. Koven easily made the
squad again for this year's regatta, beating Olympian  &UR; Cy
Beasley &LR; , &UR;  &LR; then won the opening World Cup event last weekend in
Munich.  &UR; Sally Scovel  &LR; and  &UR; Lianne Bennion Nelson  &LR; took the silver
in the women's pair,  &UR; Sarah Jones  &LR; was fourth in the women's
single, and the US men's eight (with only one member of last year's
gold medal boat aboard) was fifth. Next regatta is two weekends
hence in Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   __ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Besides her lofty goals for the 2000 Olympics (winning an
unprecedented five gold medals in the 100, 200, long jump, and both
relays),  &UR; Marion Jones  &LR; is targeting  &UR; Florence Griffith Joyner's
 &LR; decade-old world record in the 200 (21.34 at Seoul in 1988) at
Sunday's meet in Padua. Jones has already run a 10.71 in the 100
this year, second only to Flo-Jo's 10.49 mark. She'll have a
showdown in the shorter race with Olympic champion  &UR; Gail Devers  &LR; at
next month's Goodwill Games in New York ... Though international
track and field kingpin  &UR; Primo Nebiolo  &LR; is still fuming at the
Atlanta Olympic organizers (``a disaster in the organization and a
strange use of the money''), he says he won't hold it against
Stanford, which is bidding for the 2001 outdoor world
championships. ``It is a good bid from Stanford,'' Nebiolo says.
``We are trying to help them.'' What bothers Nebiolo most about
Atlanta was the post-Games switch of the main stadium into the home
of the Braves. ``They have destroyed the stadium and built a new
stadium in the name of  &UR; Ted Turner &LR; ,'' he says. ``It is shameful.''
... Frenetic tuneup week for the US baseball team (nine games in
nine days against Mexico and Canada) before the regional qualifier
in Nicaragua for this summer's world championships in Italy. The
Americans, who'll be sending their usual squad of college
sophomores and freshmen, need to finish among the top five (with
Cuba already having qualified) to make the 16-team global field ...
Why is USA Swimming holding the trials for next summer's Pan
American Games a year early? Because it has four events in 1999
(the Pan Ams, Pan Pacifics, World University Games, and world
short-course meet), and training schedules won't allow four
multiple trials. So the squads will be chosen at August's summer
nationals in California ... Beach volleyball, the hot new sport on
the Olympic program in Atlanta, is rapidly dropping off the screen.
The AVP men's tour has cut its purses in half, the women's pro tour
has disbanded, and the networks have scaled back coverage
dramatically. Prime reason is the political squabbling among
organizations ...  &UR; Mike Peplinski &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who delayed his kidney
transplant for more than a year so he could be vice skip of the US
men's curling team in Nagano, will get his new organ Thursday.
Since his mother was ruled out as a donor, Peplinski will receive
the transplant from his father-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Lots of New Englanders in the Soling class on this year's US
sailing team: defending champs  &UR; Dave Curtis &LR; , &UR; Moose
McClintock &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and  &UR; Karl Anderson  &LR; (Marblehead, Newport, R.I.,
Barnstable);  &UR; Tony Rey &LR; , &UR; Dean Brenner &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and  &UR; Tom Burnham
 &LR; (Newport, Watch Hill, R.I., and Orange, Conn.), and  &UR; Wally Corwin
 &LR; (Northborough),  &UR; Tom Olsen  &LR; (East Dennis), and  &UR; Bill Fortenberry
 &LR; (Jamestown, R.I.). On the Star class squad is  &UR; George Iverson
 &LR; (Marblehead) ... Walkover for Indianapolis in its quest to host
the 2003 world gymnastics championships. No other city bid. Indy
also hosted the event in 1991, when  &UR; Kim Zmeskal  &LR; won the
all-around in front of 27,000 spectators in the Hoosier Dome. The
2003 event will be the team qualifier for the 2004 Olympics in
Athens ... Mass coaching exit from the US long-track speedskating
team: Program director  &UR; Nick Thometz &LR; , all-around coach  &UR; Gerard
Kemkers &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and sprint coach  &UR; Guy Thibault  &LR; have all moved on.
Thometz will become the sport's project manager for the Salt Lake
City organizing committee. Kemkers is going back to the
Netherlands, and Thibault reportedly was nudged out ... At a time
when some octogenarian sports czars refuse to leave the stage,
international ski president  &UR; Marc Hodler  &LR; is stepping down
gracefully at 79. ``I am going to be 80 soon and there is no
guarantee I would be up to my task,'' says Hodler, the Swiss lawyer
who has run the FIS for an astounding 47 years ... Want a winner's
medal from the 1896 Olympics in Athens? A relay torch from the 1972
Winter Games in Sapporo? A banner from the 1932 Olympics in Los
Angeles? They'll all be auctioned off with tables of other
memorabilia at the US Olympic complex in Colorado Springs June 26.
Bids can be made by mail, phone, fax, or e-mail. Call 719-473-1538
or fax 719-477-0768 for details.
</P>
</TEXT>
