<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-06 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7600 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-USTEAM-REYNA-BOS &LR;      06-06 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-USTEAM-REYNA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN MIDDLE OF US ATTACK, HE'S THE MAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; LYON, France _ Claudio Reyna isn't sure how he feels about all
this ``man in the middle'' hype. After all, there's Kasey Keller
keeping the goal, captain Thomas Dooley prowling the back line,
Eric Wynalda finishing up front.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not my team,'' says Reyna, who'll be the playmaker when
the US men's soccer team takes on the Germans in their crucial
World Cup opener in Paris a week from Monday. ``In soccer, everyone
is important. There's not one guy who can win it. Everyone has to
win it.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Yanks won't win anything here unless Reyna can create
scoring chances out of the midfield in their counterattacking 3-6-1
formation.
</P>
<P>
   When Reyna is in the lineup with freedom to roam, the US is good
for two or three goals a game. When he's sitting out, as he was
with a sore groin in two of the last three Cup tuneups last month,
the Yanks go barren.
</P>
<P>
   With Reyna, they beat Austria, 3-0, and Kuwait, 2-0. Without
him, they played scoreless draws with Macedonia and Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   If it had been the World Cup, Reyna says he would have taken a
pain-killer and pushed himself for 90 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he didn't want to take any risks, nor do I want him to
take any risks,'' says coach Steve Sampson. ``I'm sure we'll see a
phenomenal Claudio Reyna in the World Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   With three-time Cup veteran Tab Ramos still scrambling back into
form after tearing up his right knee twice in less than a year,
Reyna is a priceless commodity. And after viewing the 1994 Cup from
the sidelines with a hamstring injury, the 24-year-old Reyna can't
bear to be among the watching wounded again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was enjoyable just to be with the team and share in their
success,'' says Reyna. ``But obviously, it was disappointing. I
think I would have played. But I knew I'd get my chance _ and here
I am again.''
</P>
<P>
   Reyna has been the man in the middle for a while now, and the
system, which puts him amid five other midfielders, suits him.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many players around him to play off of,'' says
Sampson. ``Claudio is allowed the freedom to come wide or stay
inside or come forward.''
</P>
<P>
   That's one reason why Sampson made the shocking move of dumping
captain John Harkes in April _ because he didn't want Harkes
cramping Reyna's style.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the question is whether Ramos will cramp it. Ramos, a
terrific dribbler with a knack for finding the back of the net, is
used to having the ball. Is there enough of it to go around? Could
both men start?
</P>
<P>
   ``Tab and I are good friends and I love playing with him,'' says
Reyna. ``We can play together. Other countries manage to put their
best players on the field. Why can't we?''
</P>
<P>
   Reyna, seven years junior, was too young to play with Ramos when
they were growing up in New Jersey (they both went to St.
Benedict's Prep in Newark), but most folks thereabouts figured
they'd eventually end up playing for Uncle Sam.
</P>
<P>
   Reyna, whose father played first-division soccer in Argentina,
had both the pedigree and the passion. St. Benedict's, which won 47
straight times, never lost a match when he was on the field. Reyna
led Virginia to three straight NCAA titles, played every minute of
the 1992 Olympics in Barcelona, was the youngest member of the 1994
Cup team, and went directly to Bayer Leverkusen in Germany's
Bundesliga.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he was a bench player there for three seasons, Reyna
never considered playing in the MLS. He figured his time would
come, and when Leverkusen loaned him to VfL Wolfsburg last year,
Reyna blossomed as a playmaker and was named one of the league's
top 25 players by Kicker magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Sampson never sat Reyna down and told him he was making him the
mainspring. ``I read most of it through the papers,'' Reyna says.
</P>
<P>
   Sampson just kept putting him in the middle, surrounding him
with people (like Wolfsburg teammate Chad Deering) who could
shoulder the defensive chores, and letting Reyna improvise.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.5a &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve believes the team should be formed around certain
players,'' Reyna says, ``and he thinks I'm one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.5a &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Last time he was the kid, hoping for a chance but happy to have
the jersey. This time, he's the man in the middle, and he might be
there for a while.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.5a &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I'll be the Thomas Dooley of 2010,'' Claudio Reyna
muses. ``I'll be 37 then, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
