<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-06 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7602 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-FRENCH-COLUMN-HNS     06-06 0351
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-FRENCH-COLUMN </SLUG>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Column: Seles almost all the way back
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By DALE ROBERTSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PARIS _ Athletes mess up all the time, and they do it so
publicly. They get busted for dope or alcohol, or for beating their
significant others, or for tearing up a bar, or for myriad other
nasty crimes and misdemeanors.
</P>
<P>
   But then they apologize, usually shedding a tear or two, and
swear on their mother's grave to improve their behavior. Our
response is to stand and applaud and to keep buying tickets.
</P>
<P>
   To err is human, to forgive is expected, as long as the
offending brute in question can score, tackle or smack the ol'
horsehide over the fence.
</P>
<P>
   Monica Seles, however, adds a unique twist to the familiar
fallen-jock-on-the-rebound saga. She, too, crashed and burned,
going from No. 1 in the world to practically withdrawing from the
world. Except, in her case, she was an innocent bystander, a victim
of somebody else's sick cravings, not her own.
</P>
<P>
   Seles was a goofy, ditzy kid who behaved oddly at times but who
also defied a number of significant shortcomings, namely slow feet
and an ungainly body, to become the best player on the planet while
still a teen-ager. Then one day out of the blue, as it began to
appear she would break all the records, everything was taken from
her. Now, five mostly lost years later, she seems whole again.
</P>
<P>
   Almost.
</P>
<P>
   The tenacity is back. The consistency isn't. Her near perfection
against Martina Hingis in the French Open semifinals gave way to an
alternately brilliant and laughably flawed effort against Arantxa
Sanchez Vicario in Saturday's final, won by the Spaniard 7-6, 0-6,
6-2.
</P>
<P>
   Seles pulverized the ball the same as the old Monica, meaning
the young Monica. She grunted, groaned and grimaced the same as the
old/ young Monica. She took most every ball on her rise, usually
from a good foot inside the baseline. But the old/young Monica
wouldn't have produced the untimely errors, both physical and
mental, that led to her downfall in e.e &QC; e wiC+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-06-98 2022EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980606.0226 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-06 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7603 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBANOTES-VETERANS     06-06 1883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBANOTES-VETERANS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING AN ELDER STATEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; SALT LAKE CITY _ While two of the oldest, most poised, most
fundamentally sound teams fight it out in the NBA Finals, the other
27 are trying to figure out the best way to get there.
</P>
<P>
   The first observation is that they might as well wait until
Michael, Karl, Scottie, and John retire. But the other observation
is that imitation is the sincerest form of flattery and that what
is going on in Utah and Chicago is having its effect.
</P>
<P>
   It's called patience.
</P>
<P>
   These teams have coaches who are 1-2 in seniority in terms of
service with the same club. Utah is a more remarkable story in
that, unlike Chicago, it has been stable and solid despite not
winning a title.
</P>
<P>
   Since Jerry Sloan took over the Jazz 17 games into the 1988-89
season (Utah was 11-6 at the time), the Clippers have had seven
coaches. They'll soon have an eighth.
</P>
<P>
   There were a number of times early in the 1990s when Sloan could
easily have been measured for the hangman's noose. As late as 1995,
Sloan's 60-22 Jazz team lost in the first round, dropping Game 5 at
home to the eventual champion Rockets. The 1993 team also lost in
the first round after taking a 2-0 lead. Management stuck with
Sloan. Management didn't deal Malone or anyone else of importance.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, the Jazz took the vaunted Lakers to seven games in the
conference semifinals. Utah actually led, 2-1, in that series and
almost won Game 5 in the Forum. It seemed inconceivable at that
point that the Jazz would have to wait nine years to get a sniff at
the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   They've got a nice thing going and have for a while. That should
be a valuable lesson for all the wannabes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are a testament to patience,'' says Celtics general
manager Chris Wallace. ``If they had done all those deals over the
years that were rumored or made all the changes they were supposed
to make, they wouldn't have been any better off than they are right
now. Probably not as good.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they also have the perfect situation. They play in a city
where patience is a little easier to come by, too. And ownership is
reflective of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone at times spars with owner Larry Miller or gets on
teammates, but that's what being a veteran leader is all about.
Larry Bird did the same thing, whether it was getting on Kevin
McHale or saying he was insulted with his latest contract. Look at
what the Bulls are going through now, with Scottie Pippen counting
the days until he goes and Michael Jordan drawing a line in the
sand.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Utah had a half-dozen free agents, a few of which
were attractive commodities. Jeff Hornacek and Antoine Carr are in
their dotage, settled here, and were not hard sells. But what about
Howard Eisley, Shandon Anderson, and Bryon Russell? They are all
critical to the Jazz' success, and Utah not only re-signed them but
probably got bargains in all three cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never played anywhere else,'' Anderson said, ``so I don't
know. But I can't imagine it being any better than it is here.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace got the sense this past week at the Chicago predraft
camp that NBA teams are looking to get older. They see the
thirtysomethings still playing and the twenty-somethings wondering
why. They see no dom-inator in the draft and figure someone with an
NBA resume might be preferable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sports is sort of `follow the leader' and the playoffs have
been dominated by the over-30 set,'' Wallace said. ``Everyone now
seems to like the ideas of age and maturity. But you know what'll
happen. The Lakers will win it next year, crush everyone along the
way, and then everyone will be scrambling to get young and
athletic.''
</P>
<P>
   Except in Utah. They don't scramble anything here, except eggs.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The latest big name to appear in trade rumors is Houston fixture
 &UR; Hakeem Olajuwon &LR; . The Dream has three years remaining on his
enormous deal, averaging around $14 million per, and one report had
the Rockets and Orlando talking, with  &UR; Penny Hardaway  &LR; and Olajuwon
as the principals. Wallace said he had not heard specific Olajuwon
rumors, but added that he wouldn't be surprised if something
happened. ``When you're in the position Houston is in, you can go
one of two ways,'' said Wallace. ``You can ride out his career and
then build a statue of the guy in front of the arena. Or you can
see what's out there, make a deal, and try to make another run.
They're basically in a position where they are going to have to
start over soon and they were the eighth seed. So it's tough. In
the era we're in now, if you're a good team, but not good enough to
get there, it's almost like being a bad team.'' Another thing to
bear in mind: Olajuwon has a strong fondness for Vancouver. The
city, not the team ... Interesting sight at a certain Delta gate
two weeks ago at Los Angeles International Airport. On the Sunday
night red-eye to Orlando,  &UR; Shaquille O'Neal  &LR; and his entourage
basically took over the entire first class section. Earlier in the
day, Shaq and the Lakers had been eliminated by the Jazz, which
makes you wonder: Did Shaq have reservations? ... Valparaiso gunner
 &UR; Bryce Drew  &LR; appears to be the consensus winner of the Player Who
Helped Himself The Most Award at the predraft camp. He will help a
team _ say, San Antonio _ that needs a perimeter threat to offset a
solid inside game. ``It helps that there already are players in the
league who do what he does,'' Wallace said. ``Guys like  &UR; Brent
Price  &LR; and  &UR; Matt Maloney &LR; .'' Others who did well, according to
Wallace, include  &UR; Ruben Patterson  &LR; of Cincinnati, a 6-foot-6-inch
tweener who can create havoc on defense, Clemson's  &UR; Greg
Bruckner &LR; , &UR;  &LR; Iowa's  &UR; Ricky Davis &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and Nebraska's  &UR; Tyronn Lue &LR; .
``My feeling is that one of those four will be the first player
taken from the camp,'' Wallace said. ``But they are late teens,
early 20s.'' The one exception is  &UR; Lee Nailon  &LR; of Texas Christian.
He hasn't hired an agent yet and his school is saying he will be
back for another year if he's not a top 15 pick. ``That's a logical
thing to do,'' Wallace said. ``But the more the kid stays away from
the school and the more that the friends and family get involved,
it becomes harder for him. The problem for him is that he's 6-8 but
he's not a rebounder and I don't see him playing small forward.''
... Meanwhile, noted UCLA alumnus  &UR; Bill Walton  &LR; had these
observations on the three Bruins at Chicago,  &UR; Toby Bailey &LR; , &UR; J.R.
Henderson &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and  &UR; Jeelani McCoy &LR; : ``Toby is an incredible athlete,
but he doesn't have a real game. J.R. is going to have trouble in
the NBA playing power forward because that is where the meanest,
nastiest, dirtiest guys play. Jeelani is an incredible talent, but
he hasn't yet shown he can respond to coaching.'' Wallace concurred
on McCoy: ``It's hard to rule him out because of his size and
shot-blocking ability. But with him, you really have no idea what
you're going to get.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The NBA presented its Sportsmanship Award to  &UR; Avery Johnson
 &LR; last week. It was a tough year for the league's image, which took
a beating from  &UR; Latrell Sprewell  &LR; and a few other miscreants. Asked
for his take on sportsmanship in general in the NBA, Johnson said,
``I think overall it's healthy. Naturally, we have some incidents
where guys want to pump their fists in people's faces and when they
make a slam dunk or some of the theatrics that go on with some
players. It's an emotional game. But I think at the same time you
have a lot of young people watching. We are an example for millions
and millions of young people. We have to be an example with our
attitude, with our hard work. We should be an example by the way we
play.'' Someone ought to tell that to  &UR; Antoine Walker  &LR; ... We all
know that  &UR; Rick Pitino  &LR; models himself after  &UR; Pat Riley &LR; ; &UR;  &LR; they are
the only two people in the NBA with the dual titles of president
and head coach. Pitino took another step when he decided not to
attend the predraft camp. Riley hasn't gone for years, although
most coaches do. (A case could be made for Pitino's decision; the
camp is an example of classic management overkill.) ... Seattle GM
 &UR; Wally Walker  &LR; says his assistants, all of whose contracts expire
July 1, are free to talk to other teams. Fired coach  &UR; George Karl
 &LR; contended otherwise. Karl's name continues to surface for the
Clippers' opening, although one LA source said the offer might be
about half of what Karl wants. Meanwhile,  &UR; Lenny Wilkens's  &LR; name is
there for the Seattle opening, with  &UR; Paul &LR;   &UR; Westphal  &LR; in the
on-deck circle ... Can it be true that the IRS is going to drop the
hammer on as many as 15 referees after the playoffs? ... Utah
assistant  &UR; Gordie Chiesa  &LR; says one of the many reasons the Jazz are
successful is that they have two point guards who can shoot the
ball.  &UR; John Stockton  &LR; shot 52.8 percent from the field this season,
the highest percentage of any guard. Eisley was at 44 percent,
which isn't great but still is better than most. ``When your point
guard can make a perimeter shot, your whole team is uplifted,''
Chiesa said. ``It's huge.'' Most starting point guards struggle to
shoot 45 percent. Of the alleged elite in the NBA,  &UR; Allen Iverson
 &LR; (46.1 percent) and  &UR; Gary Payton  &LR; (45.3) were the best. (OK, good
guy Avery Johnson was at 47.8 percent.) But  &UR; Tim Hardaway  &LR; was at
43.1,  &UR; Damon Stoudamire  &LR; at 41.1,  &UR; Rod Strickland  &LR; at 43.4,  &UR; Mark
Jackson  &LR; and  &UR; Jason Kidd  &LR; each at 41.6,  &UR; Nick Van Exel  &LR; at 41.9,
 &UR; Kenny Anderson  &LR; at 39.8,  &UR; Stephon Marbury  &LR; at 41.5, and  &UR; Mookie
Blaylock  &LR; at 39.2 ...  &UR; Ed Pinckney &LR;  was among the members of the
Miami scouting staff at the Chicago camp. Easy Ed was with the
Heat's broadcasting team last season and is hoping to be more
involved in basketball operations ... Don't be surprised if the US
scrambles this month to assemble a backup team for the World
Championships. A roster must be submitted by the end of the month.
With union president  &UR; Patrick Ewing &LR; , &UR;  &LR; Jordan, and  &UR; Charles Barkley
 &LR; all supporting a boycott (if there's a lockout), how easy will it
be for the lads to go and diss the big guys? This group is not a
particularly strong assemblage; it's mostly second-level stars who
are not-rock-the-boat types ( &UR; Vin Baker &LR; , &UR; Allan Houston &LR; , &UR; Terrell
Brandon &LR; , &UR; Tom Gugliotta &LR; ) &UR;  &LR; ... The Indiana Pacers may enter the
Sprewell sweepstakes. President  &UR; Donnie Walsh  &LR; desperately needs
athleticism, which was more than apparent when  &UR; Chris Mullin
 &LR; turned into a cipher in the Bulls series ...  &UR; Chris Webber  &LR; is
already outta there. Is  &UR; Juwan Howard  &LR; next? Wizards GM  &UR; Wes Unseld
 &LR; all but begged to be publicly flogged in a recent letter to season
ticket-holders. The message was that he and everyone else is tired
of the extracurricular garbage, to paraphrase Riley. In one
revealing segment, Unseld apologized to the fans for not fining the
players more, but said he could not do so under league rules.
Howard was a large part of the problem, and the Wizards might not
hesitate to move him. But his ridiculous contract may make him
impossible to trade, and he hasn't done a thing since signing it.
Of course, the Wizards' obsession with doing the right thing will
end as soon as they turn around and sign Strickland for $10 million
a year.
</P>
</TEXT>
