<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-REDSOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS BEAT BOSTON, 1-0  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JACK CURRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Brian McRae was dancing off third base with two outs in
the sixth inning Saturday, hoping that the Mets would find some way
to nudge him the remaining 90 feet to score the game's first run
and hoping that he would distract the Boston pitcher Tim Wakefield
enough to help make that happen. The McRae Boogie worked.
</P>
<P>
   After Wakefield stepped on the pitching rubber and started his
motion, he moved his hands apart and stepped off as McRae dashed
toward home. The third base coach, Cookie Rojas, pointed at
Wakefield, and Umpire Terry Craft called a balk that allowed McRae
to trot in as the Mets stunned the Red Sox, 1-0, at Fenway Park. It
delighted thousands of New Yorkers continually chanting ``Let's Go
Mets'' among the 32,545 fans.
</P>
<P>
   It was a frustrating way for the Red Sox to lose because
Wakefield and Tom Gordon combined for a two-hitter and an off-beat,
yet somewhat routine, way for the pesky Mets to win this
interleague matchup. Bobby Jones provided the impressive pitching
with a three-hitter over eight innings, the Mets played their
usually stingy defense game and the run scored without the benefit
of a hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you're trying to do is distract him and catch him off
guard,'' McRae said. ``Maybe his mind is on other things and you
can get him to balk or do something out of the ordinary. He's not
really concentrating on you and you make that move.''
</P>
<P>
   The move destroyed Wakefield's potential masterpiece because he
allowed only a second-inning single to Edgardo Alfonzo in eight
innings. But Wakefield inexplicably separated his hands and stepped
off the rubber, even if he did not admit to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't remember the last time I balked,'' Wakefield said. ``I
don't know if I did. I don't even want to look at the tape.''
</P>
<P>
   It would show Wakefield opening the sixth by walking McRae on
five pitches. One out later, McRae artfully pulled off a delayed
steal of second base on a 2-1 pitch to John Olerud. Catcher Scott
Hatteberg did not attempt a throw as McRae became the first Met to
reach second. Olerud's grounder to first pushed McRae to third and
brought Butch Huskey up.
</P>
<P>
   After taking a walking lead while timing Wakefield's motion on
his first pitch to Huskey, McRae sprinted 20 feet down the line
just as the right-hander initiated his motion. Wakefield flinched
at the fake.
</P>
<P>
   ``He fooled me,'' Valentine said. ``I thought he was going.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, so did Wakefield.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty simple,'' Craft said. ``He started upward in his
motion and then he separated his hands and then he stepped off.
Either one would have been a balk.''
</P>
<P>
   Because McRae diverted Wakefield's attention, Jones' effort was
not wasted. Jones (5-3), who won his fourth straight decision, did
not surrender a hit after the second, retiring 17 of the last 21
batters he faced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby Jones pitched as good a game as I've ever seen him
pitch,'' Valentine said. Jones added: ``I think this was one of my
best. I've had games where I've pitched seven or eight innings and
allowed one or two hits. As far as my stuff, tonight was one of
those days.''
</P>
<P>
   John Franco worked the ninth for his 13th save.
</P>
<P>
   Even after adding Mike Piazza, who did not play again Saturday
because of a bruised hand, the Mets win with pitching, defense and
fundamentals, and this game epitomized that style. McRae stole
second, convinced Wakefield he might steal home and helped the Mets
steal a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to just sit there,'' McRae said. ``Nothing was
going on in the game. I just thought it might be our only chance to
score.'' It worked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
