</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATTACK-ADS-PAYOFF-2takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOING NEGATIVE YIELDS POSITIVES AS ATTACK ADS PAY OFF AT POLLS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL HEFNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. -- Assemblywoman Barbara Alby was portrayed
as a wind-up hula dancer. Richard Katz was smeared as anti-Latino.
Orange County conservative Jim Lacy saw himself described as an
ally of Willie Brown Jr., San Francisco's liberal mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Voters may think they sent politicians a message against
negative campaigning Tuesday by rejecting Al Checchi, who spent
millions on attack ads in the gubernatorial primary. But the
political road kill left in the trail of legislative races across
the state tells a different story.
</P>
<P>
   Republican or Democrat, from Sacramento to San Fernando to San
Juan Capistrano, going negative paid off at the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Alby, a Sacramento-area Republican, lost her primary bid for a
seat in Congress to Doug Ose, whose negative advertising centered
on votes and floor sessions Alby missed while in office.
</P>
<P>
   One television spot featured a grass-skirted toy to highlight a
trip Alby made to Maui last fall. The ad didn't bother to mention
that she was there to attend a meeting of the National Foundation
for Women Legislators, or that she serves on the group's board. Nor
did it acknowledge that some of Alby's other absences came on
``check-in'' days when no floor sessions were held.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money made a new truth. It rewrote the truth,'' she said.
``Money makes a new truth, which isn't true at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Ose defended his campaign tactics and said voters have a right
to expect that elected officials will be on the job. The hula
dancer may not have been flattering, but it conveyed an important
message, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was our attempt to portray, with some degree of
humor, the obligation that elected officials have,'' Ose said. ``We
can back up everything we said in that piece.''
</P>
<P>
   In Orange County, Lacy headed into the Republican primary for an
Assembly seat with what he thought was an impeccable conservative
pedigree.
</P>
<P>
   A consultant to the Howard Jarvis Taxpayers Association, Lacy
serves on the American Conservative Union's board of directors. He
was once national chairman of the Young Americans for Freedom and
in 1976 was a Republican delegate for Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine his surprise when an opponent's mailer carried a picture
of Brown, the famously liberal former Assembly speaker, and
suggested Lacy was supported by trial lawyers, a group long
affiliated almost exclusively with Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``To link me to Willie Brown was just about as far-fetched as
anything I've seen in politics,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lacy said his campaign did receive donations from attorneys but
that they came from a new, conservative political action committee.
He said his opponent didn't bother to draw the distinction.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lesson in all this,'' he said. ``The lesson is that
our political system has become, our method of campaigning has
become, a dirty, win-at-all-costs business which does absolutely
nothing to inspire integrity and confidence in our political
leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Patricia Bates, who defeated Lacy in Tuesday's primary,
nor her campaign consultant returned calls for comment.
</P>
<P>
   This year's primary brought plenty of negative campaigning to
the San Fernando Valley area of Los Angeles as well, where Katz, a
former member of the state Assembly, and Councilman Richard Alarcon
battled for the state Senate seat being vacated by Sen. Herschel
Rosenthal, D-Van Nuys, because of term limits.
</P>
<P>
   Each says the other went overboard. Alarcon claimed Katz's
mailers reprinted his Social Security number and unfairly portrayed
a dispute he had with the Internal Revenue Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``The IRS made a mistake on my income taxes,'' Alarcon said.
``They owed me money; it wasn't the other way around. He just
assumed that I failed to pay my taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   Katz had complaints of his own, including a mailer that noted
the state Legislature last year cut funding for prenatal care. The
vote came after Katz left office.
</P>
<P>
   But if the campaign had a ``daisy spot'' -- the name political
strategists have given to devastatingly negative ads since a 1964
commercial against Sen. Barry Goldwater juxtaposed a girl picking
flowers with a nuclear-bomb blast -- it didn't come from either of
the candidates.
</P>
<P>
   In a last-minute mailer, state Sen. Richard Polanco, D-Los
Angeles, sought to link Katz to Gov. Pete Wilson and, by extension,
to a 1988 incident in Orange County in which some Republicans hired
guards to question Latinos as they went to the polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Polanco mail had the distinction of both being full of
lies and an appeal to race,'' Katz said.
</P>
<P>
   Polanco did not return calls for comment. But Alarcon, who holds
a narrow lead in the race with some ballots still being counted,
disavowed the racial overtones made against Katz.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't have used it in my campaign,'' he said. ``I'm not
going to defend that. I had nothing to do with that.''
</P>
<P>
   But he also said there was nothing wrong with Polanco urging
Latinos to assert their right to vote and including a ``voting
rights identification card'' in the mailer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Latinos are often hassled when they go to the polls,'' Alarcon
said. ``It's perfectly appropriate for Richard Polanco to do this,
when we've seen egregious civil rights violations with regard to
Latinos voting.''
</P>
<P>
   Katz said it's no secret why negative campaigning is used so
often -- it works, even if voters say they don't like it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They still remember and believe parts of it while they're
complaining about it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (2ND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
</TEXT>
