A7611 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATTACK-ADS-PAYOFF-2nd     06-06 0323
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATTACK-ADS-PAYOFF-2ndtake-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOING NEGATIVE YIELDS POSITIVES AS ATTACK ADS PAY OFF AT POLLS
</HEADLINE>
 Los Angeles:   about it,'' he said. 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are other benefits as well. A candidate who spends his
time attacking an opponent doesn't have to talk about his own
qualifications or describe what he will do in office.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are limits to the power of negative campaigning,
experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Slinging mud tends to lower the standing of the candidate who
throws it, as well as the target. And attacks seem to have less
effect on candidates who voters think they know and like.
</P>
<P>
   ``It works far better against candidates that have not yet
defined themselves,'' said Sherry Bebitch Jeffe, a political
analyst at Claremont Graduate University in Claremont, a Los
Angeles suburb.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffe noted that the ads showing Assemblyman Kevin Murray, D-Los
Angeles, behind the wheel of his Corvette didn't seem to hurt him
at the polls. He bested Marguerite Archie-Hudson in the primary for
a state Senate district in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   But the effects of a negative campaign don't always end on
Election Day. They drive some people right out of politics.
</P>
<P>
   Toy maker Richard Sybert of Ventura County, which borders Los
Angeles County to the west, ran unsuccessfully for Congress in 1994
and 1996, then saw his election hopes dashed this year after he was
videotaped tearing down an opponent's campaign signs. The deed was
broadcast on television and publicized in campaign mailers.
</P>
<P>
   Sybert wants nothing more to do with running for office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking back at the last six years, politics have given me and
my family nothing but heartache,'' he said. ``I'm done.''
</P>
<P>
   For others like Alby, it means rethinking her high-road
political strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had it to do over again, I would have gone negative,''
she said. ``I would have unloaded on him.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
