<HEADER>
A7612 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-McHALE-COLUMN-LAD     06-06 1495
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-McHALE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCOUTS SEE PROBLEMS WITH NOMO 
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Although Hideo Nomo got his wish by being traded to
the New York Mets, scouts watching him this season say he has to
make some major adjustments if he ever is going recapture any of
his past glory.
</P>
<P>
   Nomo's 2-7 record and 5.05 earned-run average with the Dodgers
illustrate only part of his problems this season. He had a dramatic
loss in velocity on his fastball that made his nasty forkball
vulnerable. He has only tinkered with a breaking pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're a two-pitch pitcher and you don't have one of
them, you are in trouble,'' said an AL scout. ``He is out of sync
in a lot of areas, but the fastball sets up everything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the pop on the fastball might be gone forever, even
though he is only 29. In his first four seasons in Japan, all
before the age of 24, Nomo averaged almost 240 innings.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, when Nomo went 18-8 for the Kintetsu Buffaloes, he also
threw 21 complete games. At the age of 21. The next year he threw
22. Most pitchers aren't even in the big leagues at that age, much
less carrying a team.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry Wood of the Chicago Cubs is 20 and never has thrown more
than 150 innings in a minor-league season.
</P>
<P>
   Fernando Valenzuela , once the Dodgers' workhorse, was never the
same after throwing 20 complete games in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   But it's more than just stats. Nomo's reputation as a warrior on
the mound might have come back to haunt him. He welcomed the role
of ace in Japan and never wanted to come out of games. But when
Nomo signed with the Dodgers in 1995, there were reports that pitch
counts of 170 and even 180 were not uncommon.
</P>
<P>
   Many think Nomo might also have to tone down or even discard the
famous ``Tornado'' windup that made him so endearing to fans.
Keeping the mechanics consistent throughout a game was a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Just last Saturday, Nomo slightly lost his balance several times
during the delivery.
</P>
<P>
   With more walks and hits allowed, Nomo found himself pitching
more out of the stretch. There were some who thought Nomo should
pitch out of the stretch all the time, the way he did that night in
1996 when he threw a no-hitter on a rainy mound at Coors Field.
</P>
<P>
   But even that delivery has become a problem. This season he has
spread his legs wide apart, meaning the lead leg has to come a much
greater distance before it heads toward the plate. That has cost
him several mph on his fastball.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Dave Wallace, the former Dodgers pitching coach now with
the Mets, can sort it all out. But it seems the future is all up to
Nomo.
</P>
<P>
   What's wrong with Pettitte? Nomo isn't the only front-line
pitcher with problems. Yankees left-hander Andy Pettitte is not
enjoying the team's best start in 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees privately are worried about Pettitte's season-long
slump, especially after he allowed eight of the 11 runs Boston
scored in the third inning last Sunday. It was the most the Yankees
had allowed in one inning since July 2, 1943, when they surrendered
12 in the fourth inning to the Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Against Boston, Pettitte lasted only 2.2 innings _ the shortest,
non-injury workday of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte says he can't explain the problem, but there are
several theories.
</P>
<P>
   _ He has been distracted by complications in the birth of his
second child, which was delivered last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   _ In the past two years, Pettitte has suffered injuries to his
back and elbow. He says nothing is wrong, but his walks are up
almost 50 percent over last year.
</P>
<P>
   _ Use of the cut-fastball, similar to the one that robbed Jim
Abbott of his fastball before he turned 30. Pettitte has won 42 in
his first three seasons. But because he uses a pitch that's
generally considered taxing to his arm, he might already be paying
the price at age 25. Against Boston, Pettitte threw 70 pitches, and
the Sox swung and missed a total of three times.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the reason, the numbers are glaring: In Pettitte's
first three seasons, opponents batted .266 and averaged 1.3 hits
and walks an inning. This year, they are hitting .310 and averaging
1.7 hits and walks an inning. He has a 4.88 ERA. His career ERA was
3.58 coming into this season.
</P>
<P>
   Interleague reunion: Fans like interleague play, which began
this weekend, more than the players. Except in Cincinnati and
Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds' roster includes six players who used to play for the
Indians or in their minor league system: pitchers Jeff Shaw, Danny
Graves and Scott Winchester, catcher Eddie Taubensee, outfielder
Jon Nunnally and pitcher David Weathers. It would be seven but
first baseman Sean Casey is in the minors right now working on his
swing.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland has three players with ties to the Reds: pitcher Dave
Burba (traded there the day before Opening Day for Casey), pitcher
John Smiley (injured) and reserve infielder Jeff Branson. Burba is
scheduled to pitch today against Winchester.
</P>
<P>
   It's also big because the three-game series could challenge the
Reds' all-time three-game attendance record (152,565 vs. Dodgers in
1974). Not bad for a team averaging around 20,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been waiting for this, big-time,'' said Graves, who spent
some time with the Indians last year.``I was talking to my wife
before the season started, and I told her, `I just hope I'm in the
big leagues for the Cleveland series. That's all I want to do.' I
don't look at it like they shouldn't have traded me. But I want to
show them, `Here's what you had, and here's what Cincinnati has
now.'''
</P>
<P>
   Reminded that the Reds took two of three from the Tribe last
year, Taubensee joked, ``We're still defending state champions.
They were almost defending world champions, but we won the state.''
</P>
<P>
   Rockies rubble: Just when it appeared as if the Colorado Rockies
were beginning to play well at home by beating Houston two of three
last weekend, they flopped against the expansion Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, they lost 6-4 to Andy Benes, who was hit by Darryl Kile
after Kelly Stinnett hit a home run. Benes' 1997 season ended last
September when he was struck on the hand by the Rockies' Pedro
Astacio.
</P>
<P>
   Benes has had a grudge against the Rockies since 1996, when
Colorado manager Don Baylor implied during a postgame TV interview
Benes would find a way to lose if the game is close in the late
innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``This didn't hurt as bad as them taking a loss,'' Benes said
``I'll leave it at that.'' The following night, the Rockies lost
9-3, falling to 8-18 in Coors.
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Mike Lansing has turned into a serious
disappointment after getting a four-year, $23.75-million contract,
which almost was the exact same money they wouldn't give to Andres
Galarraga. Lansing says he's not hurting anymore (leg and back
problems early), but that might be cause for more concern.
</P>
<P>
   When he played for Montreal, Lansing used to beat up the Rockies
at Coors Field. Now, he is in a prolonged slump, batting .244 with
only two homers and three steals. He also has seven errors.
</P>
<P>
   Drew trickle down: As expected, the Phillies took the University
of Miami's Pat Burrell with the first overall pick in Tuesday's
draft. For their next trick, they'll attempt to sign him.
</P>
<P>
   As much as the Phillies don't want to talk about J.D. Drew _
upper management wouldn't even refer to him by name Tuesday _ the
hard truth is Drew could still have a major impact in the team's
attempts to sign Burrell.
</P>
<P>
   Drafted fifth by the Cardinals, Drew's $11-million demand
remains intact. The difference this time could be that the
Cardinals are willing to meet it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drew was the No.1 guy on our draft board,'' Cardinals GM Walt
Jocketty said. ``We knew he'd be tough to sign, but we feel we have
a lot to sell him on in St. Louis. We're just going to give it our
best shot.''
</P>
<P>
   There are several reasons to believe the Cardinals' best shot
will be good enough. In last year's draft, Rick Ankiel, a highly
regarded high school pitcher, slipped to the second round of the
draft and was selected by the Cardinals. Ankiel signed for $2.5
million, just $50,000 less than the Tigers paid Matt Anderson as
the first overall pick.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to drafting Drew Tuesday, the Cardinals took
Stanford pitcher Chad Hutchinson in the second round. Like Drew and
Ankiel, Hutchinson is a Scott Boras client.
</P>
<P>
   If the Cardinals meet Drew's demands before Burrell signs with
the Phillies, then the entire financial landscape will change.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question we're in a business where comparables are
important,'' Phillies president Dave Montgomery said. ``If they do
something quickly (with Drew), it obviously could impact us.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Burrell doesn't officially have an agent, he is being
advised by Jeff Moorad, who represents Eric Karros and Raul
Mondesi.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always had a good working relationship with Jeff
Moorad,'' GM Ed Wade said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
