<SLUG> BC-SHUTTLE-MIR-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASTRONAUTS UNABLE TO SPOT MIR HULL BREACH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By MARK CARREAU &QL; 
c. 1998 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cosmonauts aboard Russia's Mir space station injected a green,
glowing gas into their crash-damaged Spektr module Saturday, hoping
that visiting U.S. shuttle astronauts could spot it flowing from an
elusive hull breach.
</P>
<P>
   The experiment didn't work.
</P>
<P>
   A more elaborate attempt is planned for Monday as the crew of
the shuttle Discovery departs the Russian orbital outpost after a
four-day visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hope is that there will be a jet of gas visible,'' said
Jim Van Lak, the deputy director of NASA's cooperative human
spaceflight program with the Russians. He characterized Saturday's
test while the two spacecraft were joined in orbit as a dress
rehearsal.
</P>
<P>
   Mir was struck by an out-of-control Russian Progress cargo
capsule last June 25 in a near-disastrous collision. The force of
the impact breached the hull of the Spektr. The Russian-American
crew survived by quickly sealing off the leaking module.
</P>
<P>
   Several previous attempts to pinpoint the location of the breach
have failed, though engineers believe it is near the base of a long
solar array that was mangled by the collision.
</P>
<P>
   Though the odds of recovering Spektr are low, experts from the
United States and Russia believe the accident has presented them
with an opportunity to develop a harmless marker gas. It could be
used to find a leak if a similar incident occurred on the
international space station.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, cosmonauts Talgat Musabayev and Nikolai Budarin
injected a combination of nitrogen, acetone and biacetyl gases into
the lifeless Spektr while Discovery commander Charles Precourt and
his crewmates stationed themselves with cameras at different
windows in their spacecraft to observe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw a couple of crystals of ice come from the area of the
solar array but nothing from the base,'' Precourt informed mission
control as the 30-minute exercise got under way.
</P>
<P>
   As the test drew to a close, their luck had not changed. The two
crews, however, had several suggestions to improve their viewing
odds during Monday's attempt.
</P>
<P>
   When Discovery backs away from Mir, shuttle pilot Dominic Gorie
plans to maneuver his spacecraft to a point 240 feet from the
station and then hold position. With the shuttle positioned between
the rising sun and Mir, the cosmonauts will discharge the glowing
gas again. They hope the gas will be fluorescent against the black
background of deep space as it is struck by sunlight.
</P>
<P>
   In August, spacewalking cosmonauts Anatoly Solovyev and Pavel
Vinogradov entered the darkened Spektr with search lamps in a bid
to find the breach.
</P>
<P>
   In September, U.S. astronaut Mike Foale joined Solovyev on an
spacewalk in which they probed around the base of the solar array
and a radiator.
</P>
<P>
   In October, a gas without a tracer was pumped into Spektr while
the crew of the U.S. shuttle Atlantis waited nearby. About 10
crystals of ice emerged from the base of the solar array, but it
was not clear from precisely where.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, astronaut Andy Thomas spoke wistfully of returning to
Earth after his almost five-month stay on Mir, the last by an
American.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I look forward to is free time,'' said Thomas, who
trained for nearly two years in Russia. ``Every moment I'm here is
committed and planned. I'm looking forward to not having anything
to do for a while. That will be a great pleasure.``
</P>
<P>
   He is scheduled to return to Earth aboard Discovery on Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
