<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-06 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7617 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-HNS &LR;      06-06 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLD </SLUG>
 CUP-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Talented U.S. has bad luck of the draw
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JOHN P. LOPEZ &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
Ask the soccer experts of the world and most of them likely would
agree: This probably is the best team the United States ever has
sent to a World Cup championship.
</P>
<P>
   But that and a few thousand francs might only get the Americans
a caf au lait and an early ticket home.
</P>
<P>
   Such is life at the highest level of the game, where merely
being good rarely is good enough.
</P>
<P>
   And such was the luck of the World Cup draw for the Americans,
who drew the unenviable task of facing the machine-like Germans,
the skilled Yugoslavs and an Iranian team whose players will
compete as if their lives depended on the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Interesting only begins to describe the possibilities for Group
F of the World Cup championship.
</P>
<P>
   For the Americans, coach Steve Sampson and his 1998 team
continue to prove that not only do they belong among the world's
elite, but on any given day the United States is capable of beating
the best.
</P>
<P>
   In the past three years, the U.S. national team has defeated
Chile, Mexico, Ireland and Nigeria among other notables. And this
year came the shocker of shockers, a 1-0 victory over World Cup
favorite Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Young, world-class American talents such as superb goalkeeper
Kasey Keller, midfielder Claudio Reyna and defender Eddie Pope seem
to be laying the groundwork for future success. U.S. Soccer's
stated goal of winning the World Cup by the year 2010 does not seem
so unrealistic anymore.
</P>
<P>
   But if the talented U.S. team is going to have any chance of
advancing past the first round of this World Cup, it needs to
improve _ and fast.
</P>
<P>
   Germany, a three-time World Cup champion and probably the most
consistent team in history, is heavily favored to win Group F.
</P>
<P>
   Considering Brazil's recent struggles, few would argue against
picking Germany to win the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran striker Juergen Klinsmann, 33, who was brilliant in the
1990 and 1994 Cup tournaments, returns to lead the Germans again.
He has not lost a step. He paced Italy's Sampdoria in goals for the
third consecutive year this season.
</P>
<P>
   Behind Klinsmann is a defense that strangles opponents with its
efficiency and near-flawless offensive execution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying we will become world champions, but I think we
are capable,'' said Berti Vogts, Germany's coach. ``Other teams
have more talent, but we could still beat them. I believe we're
heading in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   The same could be said for Yugoslavia, a perennial World Cup
power before civil war ripped apart the nation, forcing Yugoslavia
to miss the 1994 tournament and the 1992 and 1996 European
championships.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslavs supposedly were struggling to regain form and were
considered on the decline before World Cup qualifying began in
1997. But the story of Yugoslavia's soccer demise was greatly
exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia has shown steady improvement over the past year, even
rolling to 14 goals in its final three World Cup qualifiers last
year. Strikers Predrag Mijatovic and Dragan Stojkovic are world
class.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Slobodan Santrac told reporters after the draw into Group
F that ``anyone who underestimates us will be making a big
mistake,'' which could be prophetic considering the U.S. team is
counting on making it to the second round.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there is Iran. If you do nothing else this summer, set
the VCR for the June 21 U.S.-Iran match in Lyon.
</P>
<P>
   The Iranian team on paper is not nearly as strong as the
Americans. Its defense is considered a huge weak point.
</P>
<P>
   But with so many political ramifications on the line and a
dangerous scorer in Ali Daei at the front, Iran will play the match
of its life against the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it seems Iran will finish at the bottom of this group and
Germany at the top, with the United States and Yugoslavia battling
for the second invitation to the second round.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
