r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-T     06-06 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE THE EARLY CELEBRATION, STARS' REAL CUP RUNNETH EMPTY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ It seemed like such a shiny trophy, but it sat there,
alone and mostly ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, a TV cameraman would pause in front of the big
silver bowl, tape a few seconds of it, then move on.
</P>
<P>
   The Detroit Red Wings, more than anything, had the right
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our sights are set higher,'' winger Darren McCarty said. ``Not
to downplay what we've done or anything, but we've done all this
before.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Stars flew home to four months of golf and mending
from injuries, the Red Wings fixed their sights yesterday on the
next trophy. The only one that counts, once you've sipped champagne
from it like the Red Wings.
</P>
<P>
   Their placid reaction at winning the Western Conference final
series against the Stars on Friday _ and the Clarence Campbell
Trophy that came with it _ was conspicuous. Nobody sloshed around
the locker room, pouring bubbly over the owner's head or puffing on
foot-long cigars. Nobody cried tears of joy or dedicated the
victory to their mothers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have some business to finish,'' explained Martin
Lapointe.
</P>
<P>
   Now that we've mentioned it, the stupidest thing the Stars did
was the banners. Maybe the T-shirts. Or maybe the ball caps.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars had the best record in the NHL during the regular
season, 49-22-11. They earned the Presidents' Trophy that
symbolizes it.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, for some reason, within a day of the regular season-ending
victory against Chicago, banners and T-shirts could be found around
town, celebrating the Stars as ``Western Conference Champions.''
</P>
<P>
   Wrong. Dead wrong.
</P>
<P>
   You don't win anything on paper in the NHL. Otherwise, why would
we have what seem like nine months of playoffs?
</P>
<P>
   The Red Wings media noticed the banners before Game 1 and the
premature coronation made all the Detroit papers. Since this is the
self-proclaimed ``Hockeytown'' and apparently the place where the
game was invented, Red Wings fans duly noted and responded.
</P>
<P>
   ``You haven't won anything yet,'' read one memorable, R-rated
e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   I knew he was right. The banners were a rookie mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Not that they affected anything that happened in this tensely
played series. On the contrary, the way that Detroit goaltender
Chris Osgood performed in Game 6 made one think he had canceled his
newspaper subscriptions months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The banner faux pas is mentioned only to elaborate on how the
Red Wings know better. In the winning locker room Friday, they had
new ``Western Conference Champions'' T-shirts and caps, too.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody was wearing them.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Wings have done all this before.
</P>
<P>
   It looked like a unanimous decision, if you watched only the six
games on TV or in person. The Red Wings were faster, deeper _
better in almost every way.
</P>
<P>
   But they were also healthier. And to ignore that would
exaggerate the true measurable difference between the two
conference rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Inches, it says here. And a lot of it was between the ears.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, when the Red Wings drink again from the Stanley Cup _
and surely, they will _ they might save a sip for Brian Marchment.
The San Jose punk took Joe Nieuwendyk out of the Stars' lineup and,
in so doing, altered the script of the ensuing 16 playoff games.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars really aren't as bad as they looked on the power play.
``Au contraire,'' during the regular season they were as efficient
as any unit in the league, thanks mostly to Nieuwendyk being able
to team with Mike Modano. Also, in losing Nieuwendyk, the Stars
lost the NHL's second-best player at winning faceoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars can't look back. They can only look to the future. And
when you factor in Nieuwendyk and a healthy Richard Matvichuk,
Shawn Chambers and Greg Adams, the talent base is closer than the
six games would have some people believe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this was a once-every-four-years deal,'' Modano
said. ``I see us as maybe where Detroit was four or five years ago.
They have a lot of champions on that team now. And they play like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   A well-earned off-season lies ahead for the Stars. They have
golf to play. They have wounds to mend. They have some roster
tinkering to do.
</P>
<P>
   For the champion Red Wings, there is ``some business to
finish.''
</P>
<P>
   Some cups you drink from. Some just sit and shine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
