<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Stars take step up NHL ladder
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By BILL SULLIVAN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
DETROIT _ It isn't easy. It isn't supposed to be. For most, there
is a rite of passage before they can drink from the Cup, a price to
be paid before even the most talented of players and teams can have
their names etched on hockey's most cherished prize.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, the Dallas Stars would like to think they made
a sizable down payment, even in a season that ended a little
earlier than they had hoped.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've come a long way, and we've still got a long way to go,''
center Mike Modano said after Friday night's 2-0 loss to the
Detroit Red Wings closed out both the NHL Western Conference final
and a memorable year for Dallas. ``But I see us being in this
position next year and for a long time to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a continual thing. We're in the same boat
Detroit was four or five years ago _ a couple of appearances in the
conference finals, a couple of appearances in the (Stanley Cup)
finals and you learn to go over that edge, to get that little extra
that puts you in a championship mode.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars believe they moved in that direction this year. Their
performance in the postseason would seem to support their case.
</P>
<P>
   First, they overcame the loss of center Joe Nieuwendyk (torn
anterior cruciate ligament) in the first playoff game against San
Jose. Next, they exorcised the ghosts of last spring by eliminating
Edmonton (a first-round upset winner over Dallas a year ago) in the
second round.
</P>
<P>
   Even after losing Game 1 of this Western Conference final, the
Stars extended the defending Stanley Cup champions to six tough
games before bowing out.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were the toughest team we played, because they could shut
you down,'' Red Wings coach Scotty Bowman said. ``We didn't get
many scoring chances against them. They're an extremely
well-coached team.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had that chemistry of real hard-nosed players. If you can
get good, hard-nosed players who don't take a lot of penalties,
that's a tough combination.''
</P>
<P>
   Dallas rode that combination, plus the work of goal-tender Ed
Belfour, to 109 regular-season points and the President's Trophy,
awarded to the team with the best regular-season record. All of
that would have been meaningless, the Stars knew, if it had been
followed by another first-round knockout. But 10 postseason wins _
particularly in the face of mounting physical problems _ proved
that this team was no flash in the pan.
</P>
<P>
   By Friday night, Nieuwendyk was a spectator. Defensemen Sergei
Zubov (leg) and Richard Matvichuk (knee and shoulder) were more
game than able. Modano (shoulder) was playing at less than 100
percent and so were several others.
</P>
<P>
   Even Detroit players conceded a grudging admiration for Dallas'
grit. Against the gifted Red Wings, however, grit wasn't enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our group sustained a lot of injuries to key personnel, and
yet our people battled through it and never made excuses,'' Stars
coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``But in the end, it really started to
catch up with us.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, a resulting lack of firepower proved to be Dallas'
undoing. The Stars gave up just 15 goals in the six-game series,
but scored only 11. A woefully inept power play produced just one
goal in 30 attempts and yielded two shorthanded goals to the Wings.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you play against good skilled teams like Detroit, you
can't go in expecting to win 1-0 or 2-1,'' Hitchcock said. ``You
have to expect to score three and maybe four goals to win. If you
expect your goaltender to be your first star every night, you're
not realistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting Nieuwendyk and Modano healthy will be part of improving
offensively. Deep-pocketed owner Tom Hicks isn't likely to be shy
about letting Hitchcock and general manager Bob Gainey mine the
free-agent market, either. So this should still be a team on the
rise. Even in the wake of Friday night's disappointment, several
players sounded ready to get right back to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news is that it's not that long a summer now,'' Pat
Verbeek said. ``We get back at it pretty quickly and start all
over.''
</P>
<P>
   Modano indicated that the race for this year's Cup was over,
dismissing Washington's chances of winning the Stanley Cup series
that begins Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're going to be pretty much a whipping boy,'' he
said. ``I think (Detroit and Dallas) are the best two teams in the
league. Detroit has to feel good about their chances.''
</P>
<P>
   Modano thinks the Stars do, too, even if it may take a while to
get over the current disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The season comes to an end so fast,'' he said. ``It's tough to
sit back and enjoy what you did for the past eight months.
Everything is so magnified in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Both the good and the bad. After last year's first-round
shocker, Dallas at least can look back on a postseason that was
more good than not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'll take a big lesson from this experience,'' Modano
said. ``It's disappointing, but we've got some guys who are going
to be around here a long time. If that's the case, I think we'll be
pretty good for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday night's growing pains may simply be part of the process.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
