</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC WINS COLLEGE WORLD SERIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GORDON VERRELL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OMAHA, Neb. _ USC bashed its way back to the top of the college
baseball world Saturday with a College World Series-record five
home runs - and a ``book''-defying maneuver by the coach, Mike
Gillespie, that even he said would have people thinking he'd taken
a few too many spills off of Traveler.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans beat back persistent Arizona State, 21-14, in the
championship game of the CWS, a heavyweight slugfest that The Old
Coach, Rod Dedeaux, said ``reminded me of the SC-Notre Dame game in
1931.''
</P>
<P>
   Except there probably wasn't as much hitting in that one.
</P>
<P>
   USC (49-17), which climbed through the loser's bracket after
losing its first game here, to LSU, 12-10, and ASU (41-23), which
came into the championship unbeaten after ousting Long Beach State
on Thursday night, 14-4, battered out 39 hits between them. Each
club used five pitchers, few with much success at all in the
highest-scoring and, surprisingly, one of the most entertaining
games in the 52 years of the CWS.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game had everything in it,'' said Gillespie.
</P>
<P>
   What was in it for Gillespie, who played on USC's 1961 CWS title
team, was his first national championship in his 12 years as the
Trojans' coach, and SC's record 12th.
</P>
<P>
   ``But almost all of that tradition,'' Gillespie was quick to
note, ``was between 1948 and 1978. Since then we've been good,
we've had a lot of success, but we had not won a national
championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Not since 1978.
</P>
<P>
   This one will be remembered mostly for the record 62 home runs
in the 14 games, a record, and the nine hit on Saturday, another
record - among the 23 that fell in the championship game alone.
</P>
<P>
   It will also be recalled for a steal of home by Morgan Ensberg
in the seventh inning, a play of which Gillespie said, ``In spite
of the fact it makes no sense, and there's not one baseball person
who thinks there's a place for that play, we know that it works.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Pat Murphy, the ASU coach, also knows it works.
</P>
<P>
   ``The steal of home was a big momentum change,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   USC rocketed out of the gate for an 8-0 lead its first two
at-bats, driving ASU starter Ryan Mills, the sixth player taken in
last week's draft, off the mound in just the second inning. First
baseman Robb Gorr homered in the first and second innings, and
second baseman Wes Rachels - who was selected the Most Outstanding
Player after driving in seven runs on Saturday, another record -
crashed a three-run homer in the second.
</P>
<P>
   ASU then knocked out the Trojans' starter, freshman Rik Currier,
with a five-run second that included a grand slam by shortstop
Michael Collins.
</P>
<P>
   And it was that way the rest of the long afternoon, in a game
one minute short of four hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those guys battled, they fought to the end,'' Rachels said,
respectfully, of ASU. ``No lead was safe . . . one run, three runs,
eight runs.''
</P>
<P>
   ASU got to within a run at 9-8 in the fourth, and still had the
Trojans well within sight after six innings, trailing, 11-8.
</P>
<P>
   That's when, with the bases loaded, two outs and the hot-hitting
Rachels at the plate, Gillespie ``decided to roll the dice,'' as he
explained his daring theft of home.
</P>
<P>
   Ensberg bluffed from third base three times, once racing nearly
halfway down the line before stopping. Then, on Chad Pennington's
1-2 pitch to Rachels, Ensberg came all the way, sliding under the
tag of catcher Greg Halvorson and touching a wild celebration in
front of the Trojans' first base dugout.
</P>
<P>
   Rachels then followed with a two-run single for a 14-8 lead.
</P>
<P>
   But the Sun Devils weren't through even then. A two-run single
by Rudy Arguelles off of Steve Immel, the former Lakewood High
hurler making his first appearance in the CWS, a run-scoring double
by Mikel Moreno and then a two-run homer by Andrew Beinbrink off of
Mike Weibling got ASU right back in it, trailing only, 14-13, after
seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``That tells you something about our team, the way we kept
battling back,'' Murphy said.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans weren't done either. Right fielder Brad Ticehurst
broke an 0-for-10 with a two-run homer in the eighth inning, his
fourth home run of the series, and in the ninth designated hitter
Jason Lane, who led the CWS in hits with 15, hit his fourth homer
of the series - a grand slam - in the top of the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a feeling that might finally get it done,'' said Lane,
who hit .517 (15 for 29) in the Series.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Krawczyk came out of the bullpen in the bottom of the
eighth and retired the only five batters he faced to earn his 23rd
save of the season and the 49th of his career, both NCAA records.
</P>
<P>
   Lane, who was the second Trojan to take the mound, was awarded
the win, although it could have gone to Immel, mostly because Immel
was the only USC pitcher, outside of Krawczyk, not to allow a
homer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a team win, it doesn't matter who got it,'' said Immel,
who last pitched on May 21 in USC's opening game in the East
Regional. ``I hadn't gotten into a game here, but what better one
to get into than the championship game.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, an emotional Rachels said, ``In 1995 (when USC lost
in the championship game to Cal State Fullerton, 11-5) I sat on the
bench, crying like a baby. It was horrible. Now I'm crying again .
. . tears of joy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
