u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BABY-KIDNAPPED-COX     06-06 0327
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BABY-KIDNAPPED-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    5-month-old taken to Canada is returned to mother
 &HT;    By Joshua B. Good
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Five-month-old Samuel Smith smiled as soon as he saw
his mom.
</P>
<P>
   That was all it took for Amanda Smith, 18, to burst into tears
as FBI Special Agent Alan Sosebee handed the baby to her Saturday
evening.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel's cheeks soon were wet with Amanda's tears and kisses.
Samuel kept on smiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looks real good, still cute and chubby,'' Smith said as
cameras, reporters and FBI agents crowded around the reunited pair
at Atlanta's Hartsfield International Airport, where a Delta flight
from Montreal brought Samuel back home.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, a single mother from Carroll County, Ga. had gone five
days without seeing her son. On Monday, a woman she thought was her
friend took Samuel, using the excuse that she wanted to show the
boy to her husband, police said. Samuel's brother, Randy, 2, went,
too. But a jogger found Randy abandoned at a nearby church Monday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Wanting a baby of her own, Dayna Nicole Dunn, 20, called the
baby her's and named him Billy, said Dunn's brother-in-law, Patrick
Dunn, who saw her with Samuel on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Although Samuel wore a hospital wrist band and a belly-button
clip, Dunn wasn't able to convince her family she had just given
birth to the hefty 5-month-old, Patrick Dunn said.
</P>
<P>
   So Monday night she fled north, driving to Canada in a beat-up
pickup truck with her husband, Glenn, and the baby, accordinig to
the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn's family helped the FBI catch them. The couple ran out of
cash and on Thursday were expecting to receive money at a Western
Union branch in Quebec City when Quebec police arrested them, the
FBI said. The Dunns face kidnapping charges in Carroll County, Ga.
Canadian authorities expect the couple to be extradited back to the
U.S. on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
