</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-BAFFERT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAFFERT TRIES TO ENJOY MOMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DEBBIE ARRINGTON  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ On the longest day of his life, Bob Baffert tried
to stay loose. He joked around, talked baseball with friends, even
went out for burgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honest, I'm much more relaxed this year,'' said the trainer of
Real Quiet. ``I figured this day would take forever, but I haven't
even had time to look at a Racing Form. Who's running?''
</P>
<P>
   His horse had a date with destiny, but Baffert couldn't let the
pressure get to him. ``I've done everything I can do,'' said the
former Long Beach resident. ``Why worry?''
</P>
<P>
   For the second straight year, Baffert had come to New York with
a potential Triple Crown champion. No one had ever been in that
position before.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just enjoying the moment,'' he said during the almost
endless afternoon. ``You never know when you'll be back again.''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert's day started extra early by his laid-back standards. He
arrived at Barn 9 before 6 a.m. after a late night at Yankee
Stadium, spent with his three sons and best friend, Mike Pegram,
Real Quiet's owner. On the eve of the Belmont Stakes and a
potential $5.6 million payday, Baffert relaxed watching baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert and company were scheduled to throw out the first pitch,
part of a whirlwind week of Big Apple photo opportunities. Instead,
Yankee owner George Steinbrenner starred them in Triple Crown
Night, presenting them with a van-load of mementos and hosting them
in his private box. Steinbrenner, a long-time thoroughbred owner,
wanted to talk horses the entire game.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot believe all the stuff my kids got,'' said Baffert.
The highlight: A baseball autographed by the Yankees' legendary
slugger, Joe DiMaggio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told George this story: When I was training quarter horses,
I was up at Bay Meadows (in San Francisco) for a race and I met Joe
DiMaggio,'' Baffert continued. ``I told DiMaggio, `Wow, you were a
heck of a pitcher!' He looked at me like I was nuts. I didn't know
any better; I wasn't a big baseball fan when I was growing up. All
I knew is that he could make a great cup of coffee (from Dimaggio's
Mr. Coffee commercials).
</P>
<P>
   ``So, I say to George, `Tell DiMaggio that idiot in the cowboy
hat from Bay Meadows says hi.''' Steinbrenner quickly fetched the
autographed ball, telling Baffert, ``This will help you remember
who he is next time.''
</P>
<P>
   After a morning packed with TV and radio interviews, Baffert
drove back to his New Jersey hotel room to maybe take a nap and
pick up his wife Sherry, four kids and assorted relations. Although
there are several hotels closer to Belmont Park on Long Island,
Team Baffert and Pegram could only find the 66 rooms they needed
together in Newark.
</P>
<P>
   His trip back was delayed two hours by heavy traffic with 80,000
racing fans all headed to Belmont, too. ``I'm happy my horse can
bring so many people out,'' said Baffert.
</P>
<P>
   Pegram, meanwhile, had problems convincing Belmont clubhouse
ushers to let him in. He lost tickets for some 30 box seats. ``When
I said just give us some other seats, they laughed at me,'' he
said. So, he came on over to the barn to hang out.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert's crew had delivered 15 cases of light beer (``We're all
on a diet,'' joked Pegram) for a post-race party. Pegram quickly
downed two brews and called to Baffert to ``make yourself useful''
and fetch him some more.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been like Disneyland, Magic Mountain and Knott's
Berry Farm all rolled into one,'' said Pegram of his Triple Crown
trip. ``Win or lose, we've had one great time. What more could you
ask?''
</P>
<P>
   ABC and ESPN TV crews converged on Barn 9 for more pre-race
interviews. But just 90 minutes before post-time, Baffert and a
couple of cohorts disappeared in a van, arriving back only five
minutes before going on the air during ABC's live Belmont coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were hungry!'' explained Baffert. ``So, we drove over to
this little diner that's across the street from the track. They
were definitely surprised to see me and said, `Shouldn't you be at
the Belmont?' I asked them if they had a TV so we could watch the
race.''
</P>
<P>
   Time finally arrived to take Real Quiet to the paddock for
saddling. The champ napped and snacked on hay most of the
afternoon, more relaxed than his boss.
</P>
<P>
   On the way to the track, Real Quiet gawked at fans as much as
they did at him. Gleaming in the sun, the bay colt pranced to loud
applause in the post parade.
</P>
<P>
   The next few minutes blurred by. After saddling his horse,
Baffert could barely squeeze through the crowd to his family in the
clubhouse terrace. He could see little of the 1{-mile race except
the home stretch.
</P>
<P>
   In the test of the champion, Real Quiet failed by a whisker to
rival Victory Gallop. The finish so close, Baffert thought he had
won.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they turned for home, I wanted to cry. Everyone around me
was telling me we got it,'' said Baffert. ``For a moment, I knew
what it was like to win the Triple Crown. I could see the
headlines. But The Fish floundered.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting closer. Silver Charm lost by a half-length; this
time it was a nose. We still had a great run. I won't look back and
second guess what we did. Eventually, I'm going to win this
thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-06-98 2141EDT &QL; 
