<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-06 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7641 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-STARS-TEX     06-06 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS NOT ANTICIPATING MAJOR CHANGES TO ROSTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tom Hicks stood in the visitors locker room at Joe Louis Arena
on Friday night, consoling the Stars hockey team that he owns but
not getting too caught up in the sorrow of a 2-0 Detroit Red Wings
victory that eliminated his team from the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, there was time for reflection, but Hicks is a man who
likes to think big and plan big.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what I would have hoped was going to happen last
year,'' Hicks said of an appearance in the Western Conference
finals.
</P>
<P>
   If the Stars have a schedule, they're likely one year behind.
Last season, the Edmonton Oilers pulled off a first-round upset of
the Stars. This year, the Stars dispatched the San Jose Sharks and
Oilers before falling to the defending Stanley Cup champion Red
Wings. The Stars were Presidents' Trophy winners for best
regular-season record. They were among the final four teams
remaining in the NHL playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Red Wings coach Scotty Bowman called the Stars his toughest
playoff opponent in the past two years _ a span of seven series.
Popular opinion says the Stars are ``this close'' to beating the
Red Wings. The only problem is that the Red Wings aren't quite
ready to give up the Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a message in what they've done,'' Hicks said of
Detroit. ``They've progressed a little bit more each year, and
that's what we have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars have the best regular-season record in the NHL during
the past two seasons, so they have closed in on setting a Stanley
Cup on Hicks' mantel. But what more can the team do during the
summer to bring that goal closer?
</P>
<P>
   Relatively little, considering the Stars have 13 regulars under
contract. But they also have nine players of whom they have to make
a decision concerning free agency, and another seven players
fighting to get into the lineup. While there will be a few
interesting negotiations with key restricted free agents such as
Richard Matvichuk, Darryl Sydor and Jamie Langenbrunner, the Stars
already have the core of their team in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as contracts go, it won't be near as busy as last
summer,'' said Doug Armstrong, who as an assistant to Stars general
manager Bob Gainey is the man responsible for negotiating player
contracts. ``Last summer, we had our captain (Derian Hatcher) and
our premier center (Mike Modano) not under contract. This summer,
we have some important components, but we're in pretty good
shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the key signings for the Stars are Sydor, Matvichuk,
Langenbrunner and restricted free agent Juha Lind. Matvichuk is
scheduled to have major knee surgery and will likely miss the next
six months, so his contract negotiations could be sticky.
Langenbrunner expects to get his $500,000 salary more than doubled
and Sydor will probably get a small raise from his $1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   As for unrestricted free agents, the Stars have some tough
decisions to make. They'll likely ask 38-year-old center Guy
Carbonneau back. He was magnificent in the playoffs. Not so certain
is the role of 37-year-old defenseman Craig Ludwig, who played well
in the playoffs but might not be able to hold off young defensemen
such as Sergey Gusev, Brad Lukowich or Petr Buzek.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars also have to ponder the future of wingers Greg Adams
and Benoit Hogue. Do the Stars make room for younger players such
as Jamie Wright and Jason Botterill? Do they keep the skilled Hogue
and Adams? Or do they venture out into the free-agent market as
they have done the previous three summers to find a winger who can
add some scoring?
</P>
<P>
   Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said it's too early to make personnel
decisions. He wants to reflect on the season and have a clear mind
before addressing key moves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know whether we can clearly evaluate right now,'' he
said. ``What you find out is that once you get a taste of this,
once it gets in your blood, for me anyway, it becomes everything
that you want. And now you have to decide how as an organization do
you get to that next step.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you have enough horses? Do you change things? When you
reach this level, you can't afford to gloss anything over. You have
to be truthful and realistic with the coaching staff, with the
players, with all the personnel. You need to spend a lot of time
looking at everything.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars will likely do that. The expansion draft to stock the
new Nashville franchise will be on a date yet to be set in late
June _ and the Stars will likely lose one player. Free agency
begins July 1 and the bidding will begin on available players.
</P>
<P>
   There are key decisions looming for the Stars. But if you listen
to those closest to the team, they don't believe much change is
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys will come away disappointed, but it's still a great
season,'' Modano said. ``I really see ourselves being in this
position next year and for a long time to come. I don't think it's
a once-every-four-year deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a continual thing. We're in the same boat
that Detroit was four or five years ago. A couple of appearances in
the conference finals, a couple of appearances in the finals, and
you learn to go over that edge, to give that little extra that puts
you into that championship mode. That's where we are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-06-98 2153EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980606.0244 </DOCNO>
