<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-06 22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7852 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-FRENCH-HNS &LR;      06-06 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-FRENCH-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Sanchez Vicario outduels Seles
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By DALE ROBERTSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
PARIS _ At 17, Arantxa Sanchez Vicario surprised herself and
everyone else by winning the 1989 French Open. Steffi Graf was
tennis' ranking whiz kid back then, already a two-time teen-age
champion at Roland Garros coming off her Golden Grand Slam year, so
Sanchez Vicario's victory over Graf in the final would be a most
shocking of upsets.
</P>
<P>
   What's an Arantxa, we asked? Some kind of spider? The world
could hardly spell, or pronounce, her name.
</P>
<P>
   Five Junes later, the stocky little Spaniard won a second French
title, but that one carried an asterisk. Graf was hurt and Monica
Seles was gone from the scene, left a recluse by a knife-wielding
maniac. With a new wave of teen terrors beginning to rattle the
gates as well, the counter-punching Sanchez Vicario seemed unlikely
to add any more major pelts to her collection.
</P>
<P>
   But there she stood Saturday, stained with red mud and soaked
with sweat, a 26-year-old afterthought when the tournament began,
holding the Suzanne Lenglen Trophy aloft for a third time as the
French fans grudgingly gave Sanchez Vicario her due.
</P>
<P>
   Seles, 24 and going on middle age after everything she has had
to endure, was their dame, with good reason. But you had to admire
how Sanchez Vicario fought back here, too, shrugging off wrist and
leg injuries that had plagued her preparations to ultimately
survive three consecutive draining matches.
</P>
<P>
   Having managed this do-over of the 1991 final against Seles,
Sanchez Vicario also battled hard enough and played well enough for
two sets to reverse the result, producing a victory more startling
perhaps than the original one nine years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been hard because I have to be realistic that I was not
winning much,'' she said after the 7-6 (7-5), 0-6, 6-2 victory that
secured only her second championship of any kind over the last 26
months. ``But I work harder, I push myself to be a better tennis
player. It paid off, I think.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez Vicario's third Roland Garros title, tying her for third
with Seles among the post-Open era players behind Chris Evert
(seven) and Graf (five), ensures Spain of its second clean sweep at
the French in five years. Alex Corretja and Carlos Moya, both
friends and countrymen of hers, play in the men's final today.
</P>
<P>
   After Sanchez Vicario won in 1994, Sergi Bruguera then defeated
fellow Spaniard Alberto Berasategui for the men's title.
</P>
<P>
   While the Seles comeback, stalled again of late because of her
father's long illness and recent death from stomach cancer, was the
hotter story of this day going in, Sanchez Vicario was determined
not to let it overshadow her own desires. If there was going to be
a fairy-tale finish to the French fortnight, she intended for it to
be her fairy tale.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had pretty similar years,'' she said. ``It's been very
tough for both of us, in different situations. This was good for
women's tennis because it shows that we can still make unbelievable
matches.''
</P>
<P>
   The match was indeed unbelievable on several levels, not the
least of which was how radically it kept swinging back and forth.
Seles got up a break straight away, but Sanchez Vicario broke right
back. When Seles' second break set her up to serve for the first
set, the Spaniard answered in kind again.
</P>
<P>
   In the tiebreaker, Sanchez Vicario held on despite dropping four
points in a row, watching a 5-1 lead disappear in a matter of
seconds. And then Seles blew her off the court in the second set,
losing only six points total and apparently, once she quickly
gained a break point in the first game of the third set, securing
the momentum for keeps.
</P>
<P>
   Nope. Sanchez Vicario saved the game by digging out three
consecutive winners and then broke Seles easily for a 2-0 lead.
When Seles was unable to capitalize on break points in the next two
service games, blowing two in the latter with horrible errors, the
day was lost for her.
</P>
<P>
   During the changeover, trailing 1-4, she sat with her eyes
closed, breathing deeply, apparently trying to block out the
opportunities squandered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arantxa is such a great player, she just ran down
everything,'' Seles said. ``I had to work very hard. At the end,
she just made less errors than I did. I was up in so many games on
her serve in the third set. They just slipped away.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't expect to have that happen and win the match against
someone like Arantxa.''
</P>
<P>
   Seles got a break when rain delayed the match 45 minutes,
leaving the courts slower than she would have liked given the foot
speed of her opponent. Sanchez Vicario, the consummate
counter-puncher, will chase down pretty much any ball that isn't
hit into the stands.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez Vicario's determination made her play more offense than
normal, at least when circumstances dictated. And, while she hit
only half as many winners as did Seles, she also made 19 fewer
errors. The fact that Seles would win 10 more points in the match
proved irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question, she puts a lot of pressure on a person who has a
hitting style like myself,'' Seles said. ``Sometimes you go for too
much and you make errors.''
</P>
<P>
   She conceded the defeat ``disappointed'' her, but she has felt
worse in her life. Lots worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a very different two weeks,'' Seles said, ``just
because I was able to concentrate on tennis, which was a very nice
feeling. I haven't been able to do that in a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   In defeat then, she won.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-06-98 2230EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
