<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-06 22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7853 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-BELMONT-TEX     06-06 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-BELMONT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VICTORY GALLOP DENIES REAL QUIET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By RANDY MOSS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ The record books will show only that Real Quiet
came agonizingly close to sweeping the Triple Crown, missing by a
nose in the Belmont Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   But he was destined to lose, by heartbreak or controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Victory Gallop, second in the Kentucky Derby and Preakness
Stakes, finally caught ``The Fish'' yesterday, turning the tables
on Real Quiet in the mile-and-a-half Belmont Stakes by the closest
possible margin.
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet blew a four-length stretch advantage as onrushing
Victory Gallop emerged as the photo-finish winner of a dramatic,
head-bobbing conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hate to lose like that,'' said trainer Bob Baffert, who
also missed a Triple Crown bid last year when Silver Charm lost the
Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   But the alternative might have been worse. If Real Quiet had won
the photo, the three Belmont Park stewards said that because of
stretch interference he ``probably'' would have been the first
horse in 130 years to face Belmont disqualification.
</P>
<P>
   The incident occurred as Real Quiet weakened and jockey Kent
Desormeaux saw Victory Gallop gaining fast. Desormeaux tugged on
the right rein, hoping to intimidate Victory Gallop or turn Real
Quiet's head in Victory Gallop's direction to elicit a competitive
surge.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Real Quiet veered toward Victory Gallop and bumped him
twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a desperation measure,'' Desormeaux said.
</P>
<P>
   The finish was so close that jockey Gary Stevens, aboard Victory
Gallop, didn't know which horse had won. While pulling up, Stevens
told an outrider that he intended to claim foul if necessary, but
the result of the photo made that academic.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Stevens rode Silver Charm last year for Baffert.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is bittersweet,'' Stevens said. ``The whole country was
watching that other horse. I know what it feels like to come up
short like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The owners of Victory Gallop _ Houston brothers Art, Jack and
J.R. Preston _ also know how it feels to narrowly lose.
</P>
<P>
   In the Kentucky Derby, Victory Gallop's late charge came up a
half-length short. Stevens, selected to replace Alex Solis, changed
tactics in the Preakness and hustled Victory Gallop to stay in
front of Real Quiet, but that resulted in a 21/4-length loss.
</P>
<P>
   Recovering quickly from a skin rash in the week after the
Preakness, Victory Gallop was permitted to keep his pace in the
Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   He was next to last in the 11-horse field before getting into
gear. But even as Victory Gallop was advancing, Stevens was worried
that Real Quiet's quick move to leaders Chilito and Grand Slam
around the second turn would be too much to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was getting away from us,'' Stevens said. ``I really didn't
know if we could get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Desormeaux moved Real Quiet too early. Perhaps Baffert's
decision to give Real Quiet a week off after the Preakness made a
difference in the closing furlong. Maybe Real Quiet doesn't want a
mile-and-a-half.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, Real Quiet suddenly became rubber-legged in
the last 200 yards as Victory Gallop poured it on.
</P>
<P>
   ``We split horses at the eighth-pole and this colt saw
daylight,'' said Stevens, who twice moved Victory Gallop between
horses for room in the lane. ``I was very confident we were going
to pick (Real Quiet) up.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the closing few strides, Real Quiet made serious contact
with us. I felt like (Victory Gallop) was going to win by a neck or
more and all of a sudden he hit me and it broke this colt's
momentum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortunately, we got up. The stewards didn't have to go into
that decision. That would have been a bad situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas-bred gelding Thomas Jo, partly owned by breeder Larry
Smith of Pilot Point, finished third, six lengths back.
</P>
<P>
   Victory Gallop, the 9-to-2 second betting choice behind 4-to-5
favorite Real Quiet, paid $11 to win and completed the distance in
2:29, five full seconds slower than Secretariat's race and track
record.
</P>
<P>
   First place in the Belmont was worth $600,000 to the Prestons,
but that pales in comparison with the first-place prize that would
have awaited Real Quiet's owner, Mike Pegram.
</P>
<P>
   Pegram made $200,000 for finishing second, but missed out on a
$5 million Visa Triple Crown Challenge bonus. More disappointing,
he said, is that Real Quiet is not the 12th horse to sweep the
classics. Now he is the 14th horse to capture the first two legs
and fail in the third.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the famous horses on the list of Triple Crown
near-misses, Real Quiet _ a crooked-legged $17,000 bargain
nicknamed ``The Fish'' by Baffert _ came the closest to glory.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had it,'' Baffert said. ``I could just see the headlines
tomorrow: `The Fish Does It.'''
</P>
<P>
   But with yet another failed Triple Crown assault on the books,
the morning papers will read differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fish floundered,'' Baffert said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
