r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-IRL-TMS-TEX     06-06 0490
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-IRL-TMS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRL LIKELY TO REWARD TMS WITH TWO RACE WEEKENDS NEXT YEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Texas Motor Speedway is likely to retain its
distinction as the only venue with two race dates on the Pep Boys
Indy Racing League's 1999 schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Leo Mehl, the IRL's executive director, said he is working on
next year's lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be a while before we have a schedule for next year,''
Mehl said after the drivers' meeting for the True Value 500K
yesterday. ``But there's no reason not to come back to Texas twice.
I mean, we've got a night race and a day race _ and they like us
down here.''
</P>
<P>
   The IRL's second 1998 visit to North Texas, for the Lone Star
500K, is booked for the afternoon of Sept. 20. It is the 10th of 11
races on a schedule highlighted, as usual, by the Indianapolis 500.
</P>
<P>
   IRL officials added the fall race at TMS, a July 19 event at
Dover (Del.) Downs International Speedway and Atlanta Motor
Speedway on Aug. 29 to this year's lineup. Those venues fit the
IRL's all-oval criteria.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to have an oval facility that's got a place for us
on the schedule. That's what we're looking for,'' Mehl said. ``I
think our schedule will grow in 2000. There are some things
happening, but they're not going to happen in 1999.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month at the Indianapolis Motor Speedway, IRL founder Tony
George said he hoped to grow the league ``in a managed way so that
we can run 16 or 18 races. That would be my guess.''
</P>
<P>
   Mehl and George, who also is president of the IMS, declined to
name specific markets for expansion. But an IRL source says the new
oval planned by International Speedway Corp. in Kansas City, Mo.,
another new oval planned as a joint venture between ISC and the
Indianapolis Motor Speedway Corp. for the Chicago area and even the
high-banked Daytona International Speedway in Daytona Beach, Fla.,
are candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to grow the schedule, and it's tough right now because
there aren't a lot of options available to us,'' George said. ``We
still have hopes of expanding into other major markets in the next
year or two. I hope we have the same number of races, if not more
(in 1999). We've got a few irons in the fire and with the simple
nod of the head we could add a couple. Teams need to know, because
they're trying to put their sponsorship packages together. And TV
obviously wants to know what dates are on so they can give us
primary consideration.''
</P>
<P>
   George said he has enjoyed both of the IRL's June visits for
night races here, and working with developer Bruton Smith and his
Speedway Motorsports Inc. staffs at Atlanta and Charlotte motor
speedways.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a beautiful facility, it's a big market and it's sort
of been starved for racing,'' George said. ``Right now, Speedway
Motorsports has been very good to work with. Plus, Bruton is just
relentless.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-06-98 2237EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
