<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-06 22:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7856 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPEECH-COX     06-06 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPEECH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gingrich renews his attacks on Clinton 'defendant-in-chief'
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. _ House Speaker Newt Gingrich gave President
Clinton a new title Saturday, ``defendant-in-chief.''
</P>
<P>
   Ending a brief cease-fire in his war of words on Clinton, the
speaker, in a play on the president's role as commander-in-chief of
U.S. armed forces, said Clinton was erecting barriers to
independent counsel Kenneth Starr's investigation of alleged
wrongdoing in the White House and to congressional probes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the spectacle in Washington today of the president
frankly as defendant-in-chief,'' Gingrich said at a Heritage
Foundation dinner for nearly 400 people in this western Michigan
city. ``It would have been inconceivable for (George) Washington or
(Benjamin) Franklin or (Thomas) Jefferson or (Alexander) Hamilton
to have the person sworn to uphold the Constitution as the chief
law-enforcement officer using every defense item he can find from
every defense lawyer in town.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich came to former President Gerald Ford's hometown to talk
about the concept of responsibility as part of Heritage's 25th
anniversary celebration. Previous speakers in the conservative
think tank's lecture series include Supreme Court Justice Clarence
Thomas and Lady Margaret Thatcher, the former British prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
   He never mentioned Clinton's name, but talked at length about
two of Clinton's predecessors, George Washington and Dwight
Eisenhower, returning to the same themes he has used repeatedly to
criticize the president.
</P>
<P>
   Washington, he said, knew that ``the being is more important
than the talking. ... You can talk about the country being under
the law, but if you break the law, in fact others will break the
law, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Remarking on the 54th anniversary Saturday of the D-Day landings
in Normandy, Gingrich said, ``Eisenhower said the greatest of all
the lessons of Normandy was the courage and idealism of young
Americans. That goes to the heart of responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Saturday in Marietta, Gingrich spoke at a drug awareness
seminar sponsored by U.S. Sen. Paul Coverdell (R-Ga.).
</P>
<P>
   The federal government needs to set a tough zero-tolerance
policy for violence in all public schools, one that would prohibit
schools from readmitting students who have brought a weapon to
school, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich said that while many school districts expel students
who bring weapons on school grounds, there needs to be a
further-reaching federal law that mandates all of them to do so.
``We need to change the federal law,'' Gingrich said, outside
Wheeler High School in Marietta.
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell's ``Operation Drug Free Georgia'' organization hosted
the morning seminar, which drew about 50 people. Parents were
encouraged to talk to their children about the danger of drugs,
before the kids are offered marijuana, LSD or another illegal
substance.
</P>
<P>
   ``If necessary, we need to test kids, and that should be a
condition of going to school,'' Gingrich told them. ``If you want
your child to be in school and that child behaves in a way that is
suspicious, they should have the right to test him or immediately
send him home.'' Before his Michigan speech, Gingrich heard several
calls for Clinton's impeachment from the people who waited in line
at a suburban book store to get an autographed copy of ``Lessons
Learned the Hard Way,'' his new book.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker was noncommittal, saying any decision about
impeachment hearings would await a report from Starr, if he decides
to send one to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Brigle, a real estate appraiser, said he welcomed
Gingrich's more aggressive approach, but said he hasn't gone far
enough. ``I still don't see the leadership I'd like.''
</P>
<P>
   Seven-year-old Taylor Niebor also had kind words for the
speaker. ``Thank you for telling the truth,'' she told Gingrich as
he signed books for her father and grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Journal-Constitution staff writer Kelly Simmons and The
Associated Press contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-06-98 2245EDT &QL; 
