<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-06 22:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7859 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-FINALS-HNS &LR;      06-06 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-FINALS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Bulls want to make most of upper hand
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By EDDIE SEFKO &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
CHICAGO _ The Bulls are in the NBA Finals, but they aren't even the
hottest team in their city. Just ask the Astros about the Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   But there's no denying Michael Jordan and friends are the new
sizzling team of the Finals, having cooled off the Utah Jazz in
Game 2 on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes the hard part for the Bulls. It's so hard nobody has
done it. And even though these Bulls have made a habit of doing
uprecedented things, this undertaking was too much for people such
as Larry Bird, Magic Johnson and a lot of other legends.
</P>
<P>
   They embark this evening on a quest to become the first team to
win the middle three games of the NBA Finals on its home floor.
After the way the Bulls handled themselves in the first two games
at Utah, who would bet against them?
</P>
<P>
   With the series knotted at a win apiece, the Bulls return to the
United Center tonight for Game 3 knowing if they can sweep the
middle three games of the best-of-seven Finals, they can win title
No. 6 of the '90s without having to return to Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   Bear in mind the Bulls have swept the three middle games before
_ as the visiting team. They did so at Los Angeles against the
Lakers in 1991 after splitting the opening two games at home.
</P>
<P>
   If the Bulls can do it on the road, who's to say they can't do
it at home?
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe their coach. Phil Jackson doesn't exactly sound
overconfident about a sweep of the next three games.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a long playoff (series),'' Jackson said. ``I can see
it in the making. It's going to be one of those playoffs that are
going to be very difficult. So I think disregard for either team in
this situation is (unwise).''
</P>
<P>
   But the Bulls have nothing about which to be upset. They lost
the opener against the Jazz, but had an excellent chance to win.
Then they made all the right plays in Game 2 to grab the home-court
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   As far as Scottie Pippen is concerned, things have gone right on
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time we lose a game, Chicagoans worry,'' Pippen said.
``But we have a good feel for where we are. We knew we needed to
win one game in Utah and we did. People should just relax and enjoy
the show. We're very confident.''
</P>
<P>
   And why not? The Bulls stopped Utah's seven-game playoff winning
streak Friday. Jerry Sloan's forces looked tentative in both games
at Utah.
</P>
<P>
   But the difficulty home teams have had in the middle games since
the Finals went to a 2-3-2 format in 1985 is cause for the Bulls to
recognize they are vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to go there and steal one or two,'' said the Jazz's
Bryon Russell. ``So it's not over. It's one loss. We ran off seven
in a row, so we have to lose one sometime. This wasn't a good time,
but we lost it, so now we have to regroup.''
</P>
<P>
   This series has followed the same path as the Rockets' 1994
Finals with New York. The Rockets won the opener, then lost Game 2
at The Summit. They then won Game 3 in New York to regain the
home-court advantage. Still, they needed seven games to close out
the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the pressure of protecting their home floor, the
Bulls face several other interesting subplots today:
</P>
<P>
   Can the Bulls duplicate the impressive job they have done
defensively, particularly against Karl Malone?
</P>
<P>
   It's clear the Jazz is having doubts because of the way the
Bulls are choking off scoring opportunities for Malone. Dennis
Rodman did a wonderful job in Game 2 and for the series Malone is
shooting only 14-for-41 (34 pecent).
</P>
<P>
   Malone must play better if Utah is to have more success in the
series.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's will to win still seems stronger than anybody else's in
the game, including Malone's.
</P>
<P>
   After five NBA championships, it would be understandable if
Jordan's hunger is not as great as earlier in the decade. But he's
shown he isn't satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   Sloan's return to Chicago always creates a sideshow. He had his
No. 4 retired by the Bulls and, even though Sloan likes to say,
``They think I've been dead for 10 years,'' there's still an
attachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Bulls' dynasty is to end, I couldn't think of a better
coach to end it than Jerry,'' Orlando president Pat Williams said
recently.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was general manager of the Bulls when Sloan played for
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry was the Bulls' first franchise player,'' Williams said.
``So it would be sweet consolation to Chicago because Jerry is one
of its all-time sports greats _ Bobby Hull, Dick Butkus, Gale
Sayers and Ernie Banks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dick Motta used to say that what people underestimated most
about Jerry was the size of his heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, we'll find out if he can will some of that heart to his
troops.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Sloan was unhappy after sleeping on the Game 2 loss.
His team watched film at its practice facility, then, as they
exited the locker room and headed to the court, Sloan lashed out at
the media for not being in their assigned waiting area.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Malone was asked if Sloan was as short with the Jazz as
he was with the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, but we expect that,'' Malone said. ``He's always short
with us, especially when we don't give him a reason to be long with
us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls, meanwhile, seem to have an inner confidence that they
can become the first team to win all three of the middle games of
the Finals at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very hard to beat a good team three times in a row,''
Jordan said. ``We may very well have to win another one in Utah.
But right now, we're just taking it one game at a time. If we do
that, we'll be fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've beaten some good teams to get here. So if that's what
they consider to be dead, I don't mind being dead for a little
while longer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-06-98 2259EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980606.0251 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-06 23:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7865 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OZONE-AZR &LR;      06-06 1593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OZONE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKY HARBOR AIRCRAFT UNDER CLOUD IN OZONE FIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY JO PITZL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ They pollute. They're virtually unregulated. And
they're one of the reasons the Valley is losing its battle against
summer ozone pollution.
</P>
<P>
   Airplanes take off or land at Sky Harbor International Airport
more than 1,400 times a day, leaving nearly invisible trails of
ozone-causing chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   But local regulators are powerless to rein in the emissions.
It's a power that belongs to federal authorities _ and they rarely
exercise it.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a disparity in the air-pollution wars that
frustrates local authorities and fuels charges of double standards.
As Phoenix area officials are being pressured by the federal
government to improve air quality, a major source of pollution
can't be touched.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want everybody to play by the same rules,'' said Rep.
Marilyn Jarrett, R-Mesa. At the state Legislature, she's griped
about aircraft emissions being outside her reach while she is asked
to tighten restrictions on cars or to consider whether to ban leaf
blowers.
</P>
<P>
   Max Shauck, chairman of the Aviation Sciences Department at
Baylor University, said airlines' unregulated nature deepens the
rift.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're getting off scot-free,'' he said. ``It's such an
inequitable situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The local rumblings about aircraft emissions echo those of other
areas, most notably Los Angeles. There, in the nation's smog
capital, regulators are pressuring for something to be done to curb
airport emissions.
</P>
<P>
   A national environmental group complains that aircraft are
getting off easy when it comes to contaminating the skies. In a
1996 report, the Natural Resources Defense Council spotlighted
airports _ and aircraft in particular _ as unchecked pollution
sources.
</P>
<P>
   Aircraft can produce as much ground-level ozone as power plants
or smokestacks, the NRDC stated. And while those industrial sources
have to hew to clean-air guidelines, it's different at the local
airfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``The aviation industry is being given a free ride,'' stated the
NRDC report, ``Flying Off Course.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither airports nor the airlines are held accountable for the
aggregate impacts of their ground-level aircraft emissions.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The takeoffs, landings and idling times of aircraft Valleywide
make them the number-one industrial source of nitrogen-oxide
pollution in the region. They're the third-biggest offender for
industrial hydrocarbon pollution, statistics show. &UR; Those two
chemicals combine to form ozone, a pollutant that has kept the
Valley from meeting federal clean-air standards.
</P>
<P>
   At Sky Harbor alone, aircraft emissions contribute nearly 25
percent of the total pollution _ almost double their emissions from
1990.
</P>
<P>
   Spread across the entire region, aircraft at Sky Harbor and a
dozen smaller airports are responsible for 3 to 5 percent of the
Valley's air pollution, local studies show. That's much less than
motor vehicles but substantially more than most other contributors
to bad air _ lawn mowers, leaf blowers and wood-burning fireplaces,
for example.
</P>
<P>
   But representatives of airlines and airports say curbing
aircraft emissions is outside of their control. The problem, they
say, lies in the crazy quilt of agencies and groups that use and
regulate airport activities. There are many sources of pollution,
but no one with control over the whole picture.
</P>
<P>
   For example, federal authorities are in charge of aircraft
emissions. But rather than exercise their power, they conform to
less rigid international standards, fearful of disrupting
international commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Airport officials say that for all the focus on aircraft, the
main source of the problem is something that airports and airlines
can't do much about: The automobile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing we can do can force passengers into using public
transportation or a shuttle,'' said Bonnie Wilson of the North
American branch of the Airports Council International.
</P>
<P>
   At Sky Harbor, emissions from all the cars coming and going
outstrip those from planes by a factor of 3-1, according to the
airport's most recent environmental impact statement.
</P>
<P>
   Add the motor vehicle exhaust and plane emissions to byproducts
of plane engine combustion, such as benzene and formaldehyde, and
airports add up to one big pollution headache. That's a good reason
to reduce jet emissions while cutting back on car trips at
airports, the NRDC reported.
</P>
<P>
   Left unregulated, airplanes' share of pollution at Sky Harbor is
likely to increase as cars and trucks face even more restrictions
and as airports shift their service vehicles to alternative fuels.
The airport expects air travel to grow 30 to 50 percent over the
next 17 years.
</P>
<P>
   Sky Harbor's environmental statement bears this out: In just
seven years, the pollution balance between cars and planes has
shifted from 7-1 to 3-1. During this time, car engines have gotten
cleaner and aircraft engines have remained virtually unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   Aircraft pour five to seven tons of nitrogen oxides into the
Valley's atmosphere daily, according to two local 1996 studies.
Airplanes are responsible for 1.4 tons to 2.2 tons a day of
hydrocarbons.
</P>
<P>
   Measured against fixed pollution sources, such as microchip
plants or electrical generators, airplane exhaust is sizable.
Aircraft produce 19 percent more nitrogen oxides, the second source
in that category, according to the Maricopa County Environmental
Services Department. &UR; Airplane exhaust ranks third behind
wood-furniture manufacturers and industrial solvent use as a source
of hydrocarbons.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, plane engines are being built cleaner today than
before, said Shauck of Baylor. Since 1981, standards have aimed at
cleaning up smoke, hydrocarbons and carbon monoxide. Just this
spring, standards were tightened again, for nitrogen oxides.
</P>
<P>
   The rub, Shauck said, is that airplanes last a long time.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't just junk these (existing) engines,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That's where cleaner-burning aviation fuel comes into play, said
Shauck, who is researching alternative fuels. He predicts such
fuels are four to five years away from being certified for use by
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, most attempts to cut emissions at airports are
occurring on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   At Sky Harbor, SuperShuttle vans and most cabs run on
alternative fuels. In August, a fleet of 16 buses powered by
compressed natural gas will replace diesel-powered shuttle buses.
To city Aviation Director Dutch Bertholf Jr., such moves are part
of the airport's effort to be a good neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   But the changes also show how little sway airport officials have
over Sky Harbor's pollution. Ground vehicles and operations make up
only a sliver of the picture, according to local and national
studies.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines are also trying to help out: Since last fall, Southwest
Airlines has been experimenting with 22 electrically powered
baggage tugs, about half of its fleet. The tugs whirr across the
tarmac, ferrying bags from airplanes to terminals.
</P>
<P>
   But the effect of such strategies is so small that some
clean-air advocates have offered a more drastic solution: Build a
new airport outside Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say that plan would only make things worse. An airport
in a city such as Casa Grande would add to pollution by increasing
the number of miles driven by most travelers, said Gaye Knight,
environmental-program specialist for the city of Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   The construction of a third runway at Sky Harbor, currently
under way, is a more practical solution, Sky Harbor officials
argue. That's because it will reduce the time aircraft idle waiting
to take off.
</P>
<P>
   Some who favor a new airport have seen a link between Denver's
clean-air victories and the closing of centrally located Stapleton
International Airport. But the achievements came prior to Denver
International Airport opening 24 miles northeast of downtown Denver
in February 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado officials attribute their recent clean air record to
tighter restrictions on cars and trucks. The airport's move
probably helped, but it's not the reason for the cleaner skies,
said Christopher Dann of the Colorado Department of Public Health
and Environment.
</P>
<P>
   In the Los Angeles region, some are preaching decentralized air
travel. As Los Angeles International Airport contemplates yet
another expansion, neighboring El Segundo is promoting the idea of
beefing up surrounding airports instead. That way, travelers would
have shorter commutes and pollution would not be concentrated.
</P>
<P>
   But for such a proposal to have much effect, airlines would need
numerous locations within a single metro area _ a costly prospect
they are not likely to embrace.
</P>
<P>
   In Phoenix, some degree of decentralization is being
contemplated as Sky Harbor grapples with restraints on its
geographic growth. Planners already are talking about using
Williams Gateway Airport in Mesa for cargo and passenger operations
as air travel grows.
</P>
<P>
   Airport pollution is likely to get some attention in local
debates as regulators scramble for ways to improve the Valley's air
quality.
</P>
<P>
   It's already happened in California, said Sid Greenwald, an
airport consultant with the firm of Landrum and Brown of
Cincinnati. &UR; Communities should promote mass transit to get people
to and from airports, she said. &UR; And they should take aim at the
federal government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell them to hop up and down and get on the feds' backs to do
more about (airplane) engine emissions,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
