<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY YOU RUN WITH THE BULLS
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI 
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
You can't help it _ and you won't admit it _ but you want the
Chicago Bulls to win the NBA title. 
You're not from Chicago. You don't even like Chicago, its office
build ings set like tombstones at the edge a frigid lake, like
blocks of ice stacked outside an open freezer.
<TEXT>
<P>
   You're not a Bulls fan, and never have been a Bulls fan, and
don't want to be a Bulls fan. You've seen how sanctimonious and
smug Bulls' fans have become.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, here you are, rooting for the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   Not out loud, of course, because that would be like admitting
you en joy a grilled porterhouse now and then, or the occasional
cigar, or Cadillac automobiles, or the novels of Hemingway.
</P>
<P>
   You don't like any of those things _ not really, not much _ but
you still like the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   It worries you.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls have won five champi onships, while the team from Utah
has none. Five championships is enough. One is enough. That's what
you believe. That's what you say, the whole time secretly wanting
Chi cago to get a sixth.
</P>
<P>
   You wonder if there's something wrong with you.
</P>
<P>
   There must be something wrong with you. &QL; 
END OF MILLENNIUM &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is something wrong with you.
</P>
<P>
   You don't belong in these times. It's the end of the millennium
and you live in the United States of America and you, somehow,
haven't lost your soul.
</P>
<P>
   You want the Chicago Bulls to win because you know it's more
than basketball you're watching when Michael Jordan and Scottie
Pippen are on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   It's something special, like fire works bursting in a night sky.
Wish ing for them to fade is like wanting to hurry a sunset, like
rubbing off a kiss.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees won more champi onships than they needed to or de
served, but only a fool would have looked forward to a lineup
without Ruth and Gehrig.
</P>
<P>
   Without Mantle and Maris.
</P>
<P>
   What seems like forever is only a blink of the eye.
</P>
<P>
   Starr handing off to Hornung.
</P>
<P>
   Montana going long to Rice.
</P>
<P>
   Magic flipping behind his back to Kareem.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen throwing full-court to Jor dan.
</P>
<P>
   What the columnist Jimmy Can non said a generation ago about Di
Maggio could be said today of Jordan:
</P>
<P>
   ``Doing what he had to do when the time came. . . . Standing up
and proving his greatness every time there was a crisis. . . .
Winning sometimes with his presence alone because the other people
knew how good he was and choked up a lit tle.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, if you follow the game I play, you know Cannon was the
Jordan of his time. And Grantland Rice the Ruth. And Red Smith the
DiMaggio.
</P>
<P>
   And the great Shirley Povich, who died at 92 last week after 75
years on the job, the Gehrig.
</P>
<P>
   And nobody is left on the field who comes close. &QL; 
FINDING THE WORDS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nobody who could put into words the glorious tragedy of being
great on a team with someone greater. Of being Pippen on a team
with Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   When Gehrig played with Ruth, the writer Franklin P. Adams
(F.P.A.) explained it all in a sen tence.
</P>
<P>
   Of Gehrig he wrote, ``He was the guy who hit all those home runs
the year Ruth broke the record.''
</P>
<P>
   Even without an Adams or a Rice or a Smith or a Povich to spell
it out, you know why you're backing the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just about sports. Memo ries are great, and the
highlights are on film. But something in you still longs for a new
movie from Jimmy Stewart. A new bit from the Marx Brothers. It's
not selfish. It has more to do with self-preservation than with
greed.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls will break up at the end of this season and you'll be
left among those who ``saw them when.''
</P>
<P>
   You've been around long enough to appreciate all the great ones
give you. And long enough to understand that when they go, they
take a piece of you with them. &QL; 
 &UR; E.J. Montini can be reached at 444-8978 or at ed.montini &LR; pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
