<HEADER>
A7872 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-BELMONT-LADN     06-06 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-BELMONT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL QUIET JUST MISSES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ In the end, the critics were correct. Real Quiet
didn't fit the picture of a Triple Crown winner.
</P>
<P>
   By a photo-finish margin, officially termed a nose but actually
the width of your hand, Real Quiet and jockey Kent Desormeaux
didn't measure up Saturday, losing the 130th Belmont Stakes to
Victory Gallop and Gary Stevens in front of 80,167 tortured fans.
</P>
<P>
   Had the finish line arrived a stride earlier or a stride later,
Real Quiet would be hailed today as the 12th horse to sweep the
Kentucky Derby, the Preakness and the Belmont. Or, at least, he
would be hailed as a tough and tenacious overachiever.
</P>
<P>
   Had the result been different, Desormeaux and trainer Bob
Baffert would go back to work at Hollywood Park as conquering
heroes, and owner Mike Pegram might never have to pay for another
beer despite having a $5 million Triple Crown bonus in his pocket.
</P>
<P>
   But after watching Real Quiet lose a race he had led by four
lengths in the middle of the quarter-mile Belmont Park homestretch,
his team can only play the ``woulda, coulda, shoulda'' game with
which horseplayers are so familiar.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my fault,'' Baffert offered minutes after the race,
saying Real Quiet lost simply because he lacked the stamina for the
1{-mile marathon. ``The Fish (Real Quiet's nickname) floundered and
that was it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to do it again, I can tell you that,'' Desormeaux
said, trying to take the blame, saying he sent Real Quiet to a
commanding lead too early, squandering the colt's dwindling energy,
and was too aggressive about trying to let Real Quiet ``see''
Victory Gallop coming, turning the colt's head so hard he veered to
the right in the final yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not his fault,'' Baffert responded. ``Today, we just got
beat. That's all there is to it. It wasn't (Desormeaux), the horse
just got beat.''
</P>
<P>
   That slight swerve in deep stretch _ actually two swerves
strides apart _ put Real Quiet in the path of Victory Gallop and
briefly stopped the latter's momentum.
</P>
<P>
   If Real Quiet had won on the track, he might have lost the
Triple Crown in the stewards' stand, a chilling thought that must
have haunted the Belmont Park officials overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens, unsure he'd won the head-bobbing finish, immediately
asked an official outrider to put a ``hold'' on the result so he
could claim foul. The stewards posted the ``inquiry'' sign and it
was eight minutes before they announced that the result would stand
_ Victory Gallop first, Real Quiet second, Thomas Jo and Chris
McCarron six lengths back in third. (Disappointment of the day was
Grand Slam, who finished seventh as the 7-1 third choice.)
</P>
<P>
   Victory Gallop, who was timed in 2:29.16, one of the slower
recent Belmonts, paid $11 as the 9-2 second choice of the track's
second biggest crowd ever. Real Quiet was 4-5 _ the heaviest
Belmont favorite since Alysheba 11 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The videotape showed that the bumping between the two horses was
all Real Quiet's fault, whether because of his staggering fatigue
or because of Desormeaux's work with the reins.
</P>
<P>
   In a printed statement, the stewards said that had Real Quiet
won the photo, he ``probably'' would have been disqualified for
interference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad he got beat, then. That would have been worse,'' said
Baffert, who kept his famous sense of humor after watching Real
Quiet lose the Belmont and the Triple Crown in even more dramatic
fashion than Baffert-trained Silver Charm did in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet is the fifth Triple Crown hopeful to fail in the
Belmont since Affirmed accomplished the last sweep 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, it was Stevens who rode Silver Charm last year, and
thought he had the Belmont won until Touch Gold rallied on the
outside.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, in the race whose sheer length makes it a classic
jockeys' race, Stevens rode brilliantly to win the Belmont for the
second time. (He teamed up with Thunder Gulch in 1995.)
</P>
<P>
   He had to thread Victory Gallop through traffic several times
before finally seeing daylight in the shadow of the grandstand.
Stevens' performance was a triumph of patience.
</P>
<P>
   The day before, he had a chalk talk with Elliott Walden, who
trains the son of Cryptoclearance for the Preston brothers, Texas
oilmen who breed horses at Prestonwood Farm in Kentucky. Stevens
was urged not to chase Real Quiet if the favorite made the same
mid-race move toward the leaders that won him the Derby and
Preakness. It was a rope-a-dope strategy _ let Real Quiet tire
himself out.
</P>
<P>
   Victory Gallop was 10th, eight lengths behind early leader
Chilito, as they ran up the backstretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very, very difficult to hit the three-eighths pole and
see Real Quiet opening up on me and not hit the button,'' Stevens
said. ``But that's the way you ride when you have confidence in
your horse.''
</P>
<P>
   Victory Gallop lost the Derby by half a length after a sweeping
rally, and Walden thought his horse had deserved to win. After
Saturday's race, maybe Walden was right.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the Real Quiet bashers were right, though not by much.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
