<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILWAUKEE-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: DOWNTOWN MILWAUKEE HOUSING PICKS UP  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JILL SCHACHNER CHANEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE, Wis. _ The recently completed conversion of three
historic manufacturing and warehouse buildings into a mixed-use
downtown development is considered an early success story in this
city's effort to build a full-time residential population in the
heart of its business and financial district.
</P>
<P>
   Called City Hall Square, the $17-million, 135-unit mixed-income
rental complex is the first large downtown residential project in
10 years. It also contains 32,000 square feet of ground-floor
commercial space.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 75 percent of the apartments have been leased since the
developer _ Housing Horizons LLC, a wholly owned company of the
Kimberly-Clark Corp., based in Dallas _ began renting the units in
December.
</P>
<P>
   Market-rate rents range from $780 a month for a one-bedroom unit
to $1,200 for a two-bedroom. Half of the apartments are set aside
for moderate-income tenants. For a household of four with an income
of no more than $32,340 a year, a one-bedroom rents for $450 a
month, a two-bedroom for $650.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, two apartment buildings were developed downtown with a
total of 322 units, but the recession quashed hopes at the time of
creating a residential component there. It is only in the last
three years that developers have found a renewed interest among
young professionals and empty-nesters in moving out of the suburbs
and into the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured it was senseless for me to live in the suburbs,''
said Jose Yamat, who rented a two-bedroom, two-bath apartment in
City Hall Square.
</P>
<P>
   Yamat, a 34-year-old stockbroker, had previously lived in the
suburbs and planned to rent another suburban apartment with his new
wife, Stephanie. That was until he began thinking about the
benefits of living downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Giving up his 20-minute commute would give him more time to
enjoy the city, including summer jazz concerts and boating on Lake
Michigan, whose downtown shoreline is peppered with marinas.
</P>
<P>
   ``For someone in my age group with no kids, living downtown is
more desirable,'' Mr. Yamat said. ``Everything is happening
downtown.''
</P>
<P>
   He has found the downtown to be surprisingly friendly for
living, offering nearly everything he needs within walking distance
with the exception of a supermarket.
</P>
<P>
   Both developers and residents say the renewed interest in
downtown Milwaukee is due in large part to public and private
efforts to make it more livable, including a variety of year-round
cultural events like art exhibitions, concerts and a $15-million
pedestrian walkway along the banks of the now clean Milwaukee
River, which snakes through the area.
</P>
<P>
   Several upscale restaurants, cafes, and microbreweries have
opened along the riverwalk, with outdoor seating when weather
permits. In addition, the three-year-old Betty Brinn Children's
Museum on the lakefront is drawing more families downtown, and
plans have been completed to expand the nearby Milwaukee Art
Museum.
</P>
<P>
   City officials say they also are streamlining the zoning and
approval process to encourage more residential and commercial
development downtown. According to Peter Park, the city's planning
director, the current downtown zoning permits residential uses only
by special approval. But, he said, the city is changing its
regulations to allow such uses by right to encourage developers to
convert more of the older, low-rise commercial buildings into
residences.
</P>
<P>
   The city also is completing a downtown plan to encourage an
organized development of the square-mile area, rather than allowing
it to occur on a piecemeal basis, Park said. Part of the plan
includes the addition of some 5,000 units of downtown housing, said
Daniel McCarthy, urban development coordinator for the Department
of City Development.
</P>
<P>
   To help accomplish this goal, the city is in limited instances
providing loans, infrastructure and other assistance to developers
whose projects have the potential to spur other development in the
area.
</P>
<P>
   For example, about eight blocks west and across the river from
City Hall Square, the city condemned at a total cost of $4 million
a half block of blighted property for the benefit of a
not-for-profit developer, who took over the property for $1.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy said the city took the unusual step of condemning the
property for the developer because of a large amount of investment
in the area, including the city's new convention center, a new IMAX
theater and its main library.
</P>
<P>
   A further consideration was that because the project would be
testing the waters for more residential development there rents
might not be able to support the construction debt, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Plans for the $10.5-million project, called Library Hill
Apartments, call for 140 units with rents for one-bedrooms to
two-bedrooms-with-den ranging from $800 to $1,100 for said Jon
Wellhoefer, executive vice president of the Milwaukee Redevelopment
Corp., its developer. Construction is scheduled to begin this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Wellhoefer said the project already had received a great amount
of interest from Marquette University students, whose campus is
less than a mile west of downtown Milwaukee, and from employees of
many of the businesses in the west side of downtown.
</P>
<P>
   These projects and the riverwalk already are helping to spur
additional development of market-rate rental and condominium
apartments in the downtown.
</P>
<P>
   One of those spin-off projects, called Riverfront Lofts,
originally was intended to be a small commercial development. But
David Zazove, president of Tandem Realty Corp., of Chicago, its
developer, said he had received so many inquiries about whether he
would use his 80-year-old warehouse on the Milwaukee River for loft
apartments that he jettisoned his original plans and began
construction of Riverfront Lofts four months ago.
</P>
<P>
   So far, 17 of the planned 36 condominium apartments almost
directly across the river from City Hall Square have been sold. The
lofts, which will include three duplex penthouse apartments, range
in price from $170,000 to $795,000 and in size from 1,800 to 5,000
square feet, Zazove said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we first started this project, we were going to make
small units and price them as inexpensively as possible,'' he said.
``But when we started to market the building we found out there was
enough of a market for luxury lofts.''
</P>
<P>
   The depth of the market also has begun to spark development in
neighborhoods adjacent to the downtown.
</P>
<P>
   In the city's historic Third Ward, a one-time produce market on
the Milwaukee River on the southeast edge of downtown, two former
warehouses are being converted to condominiums and a 12-year-old
rental apartment building is being converted to condominiums, said
Peter Ogden, president of Ogden &AMP; Co., a Milwaukee real estate
brokerage.
</P>
<P>
   Ogden said that half of the 103 apartments in the building,
called The Broadway, sold in the first month of sales with prices
ranging from $61,000 for a 750-square-foot one bedroom, one-bath
unit to $144,000 for a nearly 1,200-square-foot two-bedroom, two
bath unit with den.
</P>
<P>
   Ogden reports a variety of purchasers including an unexpected
number of older couples who are selling spacious suburban homes to
buy downtown apartments.
</P>
<P>
   One of the buyers was Charles Cain, who recently signed a
contract for one- bedroom with den.
</P>
<P>
   Cain, who is 49 and lives in the suburb of Lake Geneva with his
wife, Lorraine, has commuted nearly an hour to his downtown
construction equipment supply company for 15 years. Now that his
three children are grown, he says he is looking forward to enjoying
the city's offerings without facing a long commute.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was tired of driving,'' he said. ``We do a lot of things
downtown, and we just made the decision to move and not commute
anymore.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
