<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980606.0262 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-06 23:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7885 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHELTERS-AZR &LR;      06-06 1199
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHELTERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIFE IN A SHELTER: DAYS OF QUIET TEARS AND TIMID SMILES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSIE STECKNER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The rambling, ranch-style house is full, again. Two over
capacity. But two more are on their way _ a mother and her toddler
who have had a rough night.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, the staff has found room. While they wait for the new
arrivals, they turn to other problems, other decisions.
</P>
<P>
   By 9 a.m., there's plenty to deal with. Most are not dramatic
scenes of screams and blood _ that happens elsewhere. Here in one
of the Valley's eight domestic-violence shelters, the day passes in
moments marked by working and waiting, by quiet tears and timid
smiles. Sometimes, even by laughter.
</P>
<P>
   The phone is ringing. Donations need sorting. A job applicant
wants the nickel tour. A young boy wants a ride to finish his
community service. Volunteers have to organize the latest
fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the ground chuck for lunch is thawing on the counter
top.
</P>
<P>
   And someone has to keep an eye on Anna's kids.
</P>
<P>
   There's been a death in her family, and she needs to be with her
sister. It's too hard to take along the girls, an infant and a
1-year-old who's learned to walk and likes to explore. So they need
watching.
</P>
<P>
   With each hour come more challenges and tasks, both tiny and
monumental. The day is really no worse, or better, than any other.
</P>
<P>
   By 5 p.m., the woman and her toddler will have arrived, hot and
a little shaky, but safe. Three other moms, with 14 children among
them, will have been turned away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cook, clean, counsel, sort those donations, solve
problems,'' the shelter director said.
</P>
<P>
   Then, joking, she added, ``We just try to save the world.''
</P>
<P>
   10:20 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The 10-year-old boy is sweating outside, working off his
community service, his punishment for misbehaving at school, by
pulling weeds and watering plants. He lived here not too long ago
when his mother was a resident, so he knows the place _ the house
that's been expanded and remodeled so many times, the backyard play
area, the shade trees, the bright potted flowers.
</P>
<P>
   A second round of donations comes through the door. More
clothes, a coffeemaker, coffee mugs. They are put outside on the
back patio, next to the other bags and the donated mattresses. The
women will go through them later and take what they need.
</P>
<P>
   10:45 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Maria is chopping tomatoes and onions and lettuce in the
kitchen. The women's lunch will be tacos, with Maria's leftover
rice and stuffed peppers. Maria enjoys the cooking, and the other
women would gladly let her do it all. But chores are shared by
everyone in the house. She works and smiles as her four children
play with toys and watch a Winnie-the-Pooh video in the living
room. She speaks little English, and no one here right now speaks
Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   Maria arrived last month, the same day as another resident, a
single working woman named Donna, a counselor says: ``Both with
black eyes on Cinco de Mayo.''
</P>
<P>
   11:40 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   It's lunch time, and Anna is back. The staff gathers in the
kitchen and listens patiently. Her voice cracking, Anna slowly
describes the accident that has left her young nephew dead, the
last thing Anna needs.
</P>
<P>
   She's been in and out of doctors' offices, trying to figure out
what happened when her boyfriend slugged her in the eye _ something
called a blowout fracture that has left her face numb. She has two
kids with her at the shelter and three others staying with her
ex-husband. She recently went to a job interview and has been
sorting through the donations to furnish her future home. She's
eager to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Anna rocks her baby in her lap and watches her toddler take
uncertain steps. The little girl's soft brown hair is gathered on
top of her head, and it bobs up and down with each move.
</P>
<P>
   ``She learned to walk here,'' Anna said.
</P>
<P>
   12:50 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The newest residents arrive. Mother and son, two pale blondes,
faces flushed from the early afternoon heat. The mother wears a
T-shirt bearing a large smiley face. Her own expression shows only
sadness and confusion. The other women in the house are asked to
introduce themselves and make the pair feel at home.
</P>
<P>
   She's Ruthie, and the baby is Michael.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was my nephew's name,'' Anna says quietly. She fights
back tears.
</P>
<P>
   1:10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money, money, money,'' said the shelter director, carrying the
day's mail into the kitchen. Welfare checks are in. ``I tell them
to save their money. They want to spend it, but I tell them they
gotta save.''
</P>
<P>
   Maria's face brightens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money,'' she said. ``That's English.''
</P>
<P>
   She laughs loudly at the joke. All the women do. For one quick
moment, the shelter, with all its pain and desperation, sounds like
a dormitory full of giggling students.
</P>
<P>
   Maria returns to her chores, humming as she clears the table and
washes the lunch dishes.
</P>
<P>
   1:45 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Dawn keeps one eye on her golden-haired toddler and the other on
the TV. ``Next, on Sally Jessy Raphael,'' the announcer's voice
booms. ``My husband controls me!''
</P>
<P>
   Dawn smirks. ``That sounds familiar. When he came home, dinner
had to be ready, the house had to be spotless,'' she says, shaking
her head. ``If it wasn't, he'd hit me.''
</P>
<P>
   Dawn has battled drugs and suffers from a mental illness. She
wants work, maybe a career in cosmetology, but for now she collects
disability and tries to care for her son. She admits that she's
called her abusive husband a few times from the shelter. Still, she
thinks she'll make it.
</P>
<P>
   1:55 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Ruthie meets with the counselor, recounting a life of failed
relationships, heartache and abuse. She's ready for a change.
Michael, a chunky toddler wearing a red t-shirt and red shoelaces
in his sneakers, doesn't stray far from her side.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not used to being away from me,'' she says, plopping down
on the floor with him.
</P>
<P>
   Ruthie could use a cigarette. So could Dawn. ``Show me where to
go,'' says Ruthie, and the pair retreat outside, cigarettes in
hand.
</P>
<P>
   2:45 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   More donations arrive. More phone calls come in. More work is
done by volunteers. A local beauty-pageant winner helps clean the
kitchen; an 89-year-old grandmother sorts brochures. ``I came in
one day to drop off a donation. The next day I was working,'' says
the grandmother, her young eyes twinkling.
</P>
<P>
   4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Staff meeting. The counselor briefs the others on Ruthie. One
son is in trouble with police, another is leaving town for a while,
the third, the baby, might need to see the doctor. What would make
her happy is to see son No. 2 one more time. There is no safety
risk, the staff agrees, so she can go.
</P>
<P>
   Ruthie walks in, studying a bus schedule and smoothing back her
long blonde hair. She has just $1.25. The shelter director gives
her a bus pass and handful of quarters for the phone. ``I'm
shaking,'' Ruthie says, and tears run down her pale face. The
counselor offers a hug before Ruthie leaves.
</P>
<P>
   The phone rings. A long-ago client is having problems with
another man. This time, her husband has tried to burn down her
home, with her still inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the beat goes on,'' the counselor ays. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
